  cont({
    id: "europe", name: "Europe", emoji: "🏛️", color: "#3a6ea5",
    blurb: "Greece to the Cold War",
    intro: "From the first democracy to two world wars and back to peace — Europe's story shaped governments, science, and ideas all over the planet.",
    badge: { name: "European Historian", emoji: "🏛️" },
    lessons: ["eu1", "eu2", "eu3", "eu4", "eu5", "eu6", "eu7", "eu8", "eu9", "eu10"],
    sectionQuiz: [
      { q: "Put these in order — which came <b>first</b>?", type: "mc", options: ["The Roman Empire", "Ancient Greek democracy", "The Industrial Revolution", "World War I"], answer: 1, explain: "Greek democracy (~508 BC) came first, then Rome, then the Industrial Revolution (1760s), then WWI (1914)." },
      { q: "Athens gave the world the idea of democracy. Which empire later spread law and engineering across Europe?", type: "mc", options: ["The Aztec Empire", "The Roman Empire", "The Ottoman Empire", "The British Empire"], answer: 1, explain: "Rome spread roads, law, and engineering far and wide." },
      { q: "Feudalism traded land for loyalty and service.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Lords gave land/protection in exchange for loyalty and labor." },
      { q: "Which invention from the Renaissance helped Enlightenment ideas spread quickly?", type: "mc", options: ["The printing press", "The telephone", "The car", "The internet"], answer: 0, explain: "Gutenberg's printing press (~1440) made books cheap and ideas fast-moving." },
      { q: "The Industrial Revolution moved millions of people from farms to…", type: "mc", options: ["Castles", "Factories and cities", "Monasteries", "Ships"], answer: 1, explain: "Factory work in growing cities replaced farm life for millions." },
      { q: "The harsh peace after WWI helped lead to…", type: "mc", options: ["The Renaissance", "World War II", "The fall of Rome", "The Cold War ending"], answer: 1, explain: "Resentment after WWI's treaty helped extremists rise, leading to WWII." },
      { q: "Fascism is the opposite of democracy because it…", type: "mc", options: ["Holds many fair elections", "Puts total power in one leader and crushes dissent", "Has no leader at all", "Lets everyone vote daily"], answer: 1, explain: "Fascism concentrates power and silences opposition." },
      { q: "During the Cold War, the USA and USSR mostly…", type: "mc", options: ["Fought each other directly in huge battles", "Competed without fighting each other directly", "Were close allies", "Shared one government"], answer: 1, explain: "They competed in spies, space, and influence but avoided direct war." },
      { q: "The fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989 symbolized…", type: "mc", options: ["The start of WWI", "The end of the Cold War", "The birth of Rome", "The Renaissance"], answer: 1, explain: "It marked the Cold War's end and the decline of communism in Europe." },
      { q: "Which big idea did ancient Greece, the Enlightenment, and modern democracies share?", type: "mc", options: ["Kings should have absolute power", "Government should answer to the people", "Only soldiers should rule", "Ideas should be kept secret"], answer: 1, explain: "The thread from Athens to today is government answerable to its people." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({"id": "eu1", "continent": "europe", "n": 1, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏛️", "title": "Ancient Greece & the Birth of Democracy", "hook": "Around 2,500 years ago, in a hot, rocky corner of Europe, ordinary people did something almost no one had ever tried before: <b>they ruled themselves</b>.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Imagine a land of sun-baked hills, blue sea, and olive trees, broken up by mountains so steep that travel between towns was slow and hard. That land is <b>Greece</b>, and those mountains shaped its whole story. Because it was so difficult to unite everyone under one ruler, the Greeks instead built dozens of small, independent towns-with-territory called <b>city-states</b>. Each had its own laws, its own army, its own gods to honour, and its own fierce pride."}, {"t": "p", "html": "A city-state was called a <i>polis</i> (that is where we get the word \"politics\"). Each polis usually had a high, defensible hill called an <b>acropolis</b> where people could shelter in danger, and an open marketplace called an <b>agora</b> where they traded goods, swapped news, and argued about ideas. The two most famous city-states were <b>Athens</b> and <b>Sparta</b>, and they could hardly have been more different. Sparta was a city built around its army, where boys were taken from home and trained as fearsome soldiers from childhood, and where toughness mattered above all. Athens, by contrast, became famous for art, philosophy, theatre, and a daring new idea about who should hold power."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Around 508 BC, the Athenians began building a system they called <b>demokratia</b> — from <i>demos</i>, meaning \"the people,\" and <i>kratos</i>, meaning \"power\" or \"rule.\" Power by the people. Instead of a king deciding everything, free Athenian men would gather on a hillside called the Pnyx, listen to speeches, debate the great questions of the day — should we go to war? how should we spend the city's money? — and then vote by a show of hands. A simple farmer could stand up and argue against a wealthy general, and his single vote counted just as much. Some important jobs were even filled by drawing lots, like picking names from a hat, because the Athenians believed almost any citizen should be able to take a turn at running the city."}, {"t": "p", "html": "But here is the honest part, and it matters: this democracy was not for everyone. Only free adult men born in Athens could vote — perhaps one in ten people who actually lived there. Women, however clever or capable, could not vote or hold office. Enslaved people, who did much of the hard labour that kept the city running, had no say at all. Foreigners, even those who had lived and worked in Athens for many years, were shut out too. So Athenian democracy was genuinely real and revolutionary for its time, and also far narrower than the democracies we know today. Both of those things are true at once, and a good historian holds them together rather than picking just one."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> To vote someone <i>out</i> of the city for ten years, Athenians scratched the person's name onto broken pieces of pottery called <i>ostraka</i>. If 6,000 shards carried your name, you were banished. That is where we get the word <b>ostracise</b>."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Athens was also home to three thinkers whose questions still echo in classrooms today. <b>Socrates</b> wandered the marketplace asking people to explain what they really meant by \"justice\" or \"goodness\" — and gently showing, question after question, that they often could not. He believed that a good life began with admitting how much you do not know. His student <b>Plato</b> wrote down those conversations and founded a school called the Academy, where students explored big ideas about truth and fairness. And Plato's own student <b>Aristotle</b> studied almost everything — animals, stars, weather, logic, and government — sorting the world into careful categories, and later tutored a boy who grew up to become Alexander the Great, conqueror of a vast empire."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "columns", "file": "The Parthenon in Athens.jpg", "caption": "The Parthenon, a marble temple crowning the Acropolis of Athens.", "credit": "Photo: Steve Swayne, CC BY 2.0"}, {"t": "p", "html": "High above the city stood the <b>Acropolis</b>, a rocky hill topped by gleaming marble temples. The grandest, the <b>Parthenon</b>, was built in the 440s and 430s BC to honour Athena, the goddess the city was named after. Its columns were built with a clever optical trick: they bulge very slightly in the middle, because perfectly straight columns would actually look thin and pinched to the human eye. The whole building leans and curves in tiny, carefully calculated ways to <i>appear</i> perfectly straight and balanced. The Greeks understood that how something seems can differ from how it truly is — a very Greek idea, and the same kind of careful thinking their philosophers brought to questions about life and justice."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Greeks loved competition, and not only in war. Every four years, the city-states paused their quarrels for the <b>Olympic Games</b>, held at Olympia in honour of Zeus. Athletes ran, wrestled, boxed, and raced chariots. The first recorded games date to <b>776 BC</b>, and the truce that protected travelling athletes was taken so seriously that even enemy cities allowed them to pass."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you meet a new idea in history, ask two questions at once — \"What was new and brave here?\" <i>and</i> \"Who was still left out?\" Holding both answers together is how you understand the past honestly, without either worshipping it or sneering at it."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Put the Greek story in order", "sub": "Drag earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "776 BC", "label": "First recorded Olympic Games at Olympia"}, {"yr": "508 BC", "label": "Athens begins building democracy"}, {"yr": "447 BC", "label": "Construction of the Parthenon begins"}, {"yr": "399 BC", "label": "Socrates is put on trial in Athens"}, {"yr": "335 BC", "label": "Aristotle founds his school, the Lyceum"}]}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Almost every word we use for self-government — <i>democracy, politics, citizen</i> — was minted in ancient Greece. When you vote for a class representative, debate the rules of a game, or insist on being heard, you are using a tool the Athenians invented. They did not get everyone included; later generations had to widen the circle, and that work continues. But the daring first move — the idea that ordinary people, not just kings, can rule — began on a hillside in Athens."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What do the two Greek words behind \"democracy\" mean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["City and law", "People and power", "Wealth and war", "Gods and temples", "Land and sea"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Demos means \"the people\" and kratos means \"power\" or \"rule\" — power by the people.", "hint": "Think demos + kratos."}, {"q": "Why did Greece develop into many separate city-states instead of one kingdom?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A law forbade large kingdoms", "Steep mountains made travel and unity hard", "They had no roads at all", "Each city spoke a different language", "The sea froze every winter"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Greece's rugged mountains made it difficult to unite everyone, so independent city-states formed instead.", "hint": "Think about the landscape."}, {"q": "A Greek city-state was called a...", "type": "mc", "options": ["polis", "demos", "forum", "agora", "ostrakon"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A city-state was a polis, the root of our word \"politics.\""}, {"q": "In Athenian democracy, who was allowed to vote?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Everyone who lived in Athens", "Only the king and nobles", "Free adult men born in Athens", "Women and men equally", "Anyone over the age of ten"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Only free adult men born in Athens could vote — perhaps one in ten residents. Women, enslaved people, and foreigners were excluded.", "hint": "It was revolutionary but narrow."}, {"q": "Match the thinker to the fact: who tutored Alexander the Great?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Socrates", "Plato", "Aristotle", "Zeus", "Pericles"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Aristotle, Plato's student, later tutored the young Alexander the Great.", "hint": "He was the last of the three famous thinkers."}, {"q": "What were ostraka used for?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Cooking food", "Recording Olympic scores", "Writing names to banish someone", "Paying taxes", "Building temples"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Athenians scratched names onto pottery shards (ostraka) to vote someone into exile — the origin of \"ostracise.\""}, {"q": "The Parthenon was a temple built to honour which goddess?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Hera", "Aphrodite", "Athena", "Artemis", "Demeter"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Parthenon on the Acropolis honoured Athena, the goddess after whom Athens was named."}, {"q": "Sparta and Athens were very similar cities with the same values.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Sparta centred on its army and soldier training, while Athens became famous for art, philosophy, and democracy."}, {"q": "In what year were the first Olympic Games recorded?", "type": "mc", "options": ["776 BC", "508 BC", "447 BC", "1 AD", "1896"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The first recorded Olympic Games at Olympia date to 776 BC.", "hint": "It is the earliest date in the lesson."}, {"q": "Athenian democracy included every person living in the city.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. It was real and bold, but women, enslaved people, and foreigners could not vote — only free Athenian-born men."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu2", "continent": "europe", "n": 2, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏟️", "title": "The Roman Empire: Rise & Fall", "hook": "From a few huts on seven hills, Rome grew into an empire so vast that a single set of roads, laws, and coins reached from Britain to the deserts of the Middle East — and then, slowly, <b>it came apart</b>.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Legend says Rome was founded in <b>753 BC</b> by twin brothers, Romulus and Remus, raised by a wolf. The legend is a story, but the city was real, and it began as a small town on hills beside the River Tiber in Italy. Over the next thousand years, Rome would pass through three great stages — <b>kingdom</b>, then <b>republic</b>, then <b>empire</b> — and each one changed how it was ruled."}, {"t": "p", "html": "At first, Rome was ruled by kings. But around <b>509 BC</b>, the Romans threw out their last king — remembered as a cruel tyrant — and swore a solemn oath never to be ruled by one man again. In his place they created a <b>republic</b>, a word from the Latin <i>res publica</i> — \"the public thing,\" meaning the state belonged to its people, not to a single ruler. Power was deliberately shared and balanced. Elected officials called <b>consuls</b> led the state, but only two of them at a time, and only for one year each, so that no individual could grab too much for too long. Guiding the biggest decisions was the <b>Senate</b>, a council of experienced men, many from Rome's oldest and most respected families, whose advice carried great weight."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Republic was not perfect — power still leaned toward wealthy families — but it lasted nearly 500 years and conquered first all of Italy and then lands far beyond. Yet that very success brought trouble. Victorious generals returned home rich, famous, and commanding armies loyal to them personally rather than to Rome, and the Senate struggled to control them. One such general, <b>Julius Caesar</b>, won dazzling victories in Gaul (modern France) and became so powerful that fearful senators, worried he would crown himself king, stabbed him to death in the Senate in 44 BC. But his murder did not save the Republic — instead it plunged Rome into years of civil war, and the chaos that followed ended the Republic for good."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Out of that chaos rose Caesar's adopted heir, a young man named Octavian who took the title <b>Augustus</b>, meaning \"the revered one.\" In 27 BC he became Rome's first <b>emperor</b> — though cleverly, he never used the hated word \"king,\" and kept the Senate and old offices in place so that, on the surface, the Republic seemed to continue. In truth, he held the real power. Under Augustus and the emperors who followed, Rome entered a long stretch of relative peace and prosperity called the <b>Pax Romana</b>, the \"Roman Peace,\" which lasted roughly 200 years and let trade, building, and culture flourish across three continents."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> The Romans built so many roads — over 80,000 km of them — that the saying \"all roads lead to Rome\" was almost literally true. Some, like parts of the Appian Way, can still be walked on today, nearly 2,000 years later."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Rome's true genius was engineering and organisation. <b>Aqueducts</b> — long stone channels, sometimes carried high on graceful rows of arches — brought fresh water from distant hills into the cities by the gentle pull of gravity alone, feeding public fountains and even heated baths. Straight, paved <b>roads</b> let armies, traders, and messages move quickly across the whole empire in almost any weather. The Romans also perfected a kind of concrete so strong that some of their structures still stand today. And Roman <b>law</b> was written down and displayed in public so that, in principle, the same rules applied to everyone, everywhere — the powerful idea that you should be judged by clear, known laws rather than the whim of a ruler, an idea courts still build on today."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "colosseum", "file": "Colosseo 2020.jpg", "caption": "The Colosseum in Rome, where crowds of 50,000 once gathered.", "credit": "Photo: Diliff, CC BY-SA 2.5"}, {"t": "p", "html": "The most famous Roman building of all is the <b>Colosseum</b>, a vast oval arena finished around 80 AD that could hold roughly 50,000 spectators. There, crowds watched gladiator contests and staged hunts. It was thrilling and, by our standards, brutal — a reminder that a civilisation can be brilliantly advanced in some ways and harsh in others."}, {"t": "p", "html": "No empire lasts forever. Over centuries Rome grew too large to defend, money problems mounted, and groups from beyond the frontiers pushed in. In <b>476 AD</b>, the last emperor in the West was removed, and historians often mark that year as the \"fall\" of the Western Roman Empire. But the eastern half did not fall. Centred on the city of Constantinople, it carried on as the <b>Byzantine Empire</b> for nearly another thousand years."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> \"The fall of Rome\" sounds like a single dramatic crash, but it was really a slow unravelling over centuries — and only half the empire ever fell. When history gives you a tidy date, ask: was it a sudden event, or a long process someone later boxed into one year?"}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Republic vs Empire", "a": {"title": "Roman Republic", "items": ["Power shared among many", "Two consuls, elected yearly", "Senate guided decisions", "No single ruler for life"]}, "b": {"title": "Roman Empire", "items": ["Power held by one emperor", "Emperor ruled until death", "Senate became less powerful", "Began with Augustus, 27 BC"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Rome is all around you. The language of law and government still uses Latin words like <i>senate</i>, <i>republic</i>, and <i>justice</i>. The arches and concrete the Romans perfected hold up bridges and buildings today. The calendar months July and August are named for Julius Caesar and Augustus. Even the alphabet you are reading is the Roman one. Empires can fall — but the good ideas they leave behind keep travelling those long, straight roads into our own time."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What were Rome's three great stages of government, in order?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Empire, republic, kingdom", "Kingdom, republic, empire", "Republic, kingdom, empire", "Empire, kingdom, republic", "Kingdom, empire, republic"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Rome moved from kingdom to republic (509 BC) to empire (27 BC).", "hint": "It started with a king and ended with an emperor."}, {"q": "What does the Latin phrase res publica, behind \"republic,\" mean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The royal palace", "The public thing", "The great army", "The seven hills", "The Roman peace"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Res publica means \"the public thing\" — the state belonging to the people rather than a king."}, {"q": "How did the Romans limit the power of their consuls?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They served for life", "There were two, each serving one year", "They were chosen by the king", "There were ten of them", "They could never lead armies"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Two consuls ruled at a time for only one year each, so no single person could seize total control."}, {"q": "Who became Rome's first emperor?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Romulus", "Julius Caesar", "Augustus", "Nero", "Constantine"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Augustus, Caesar's adopted heir, became the first emperor in 27 BC.", "hint": "He avoided ever calling himself \"king.\""}, {"q": "What was the Pax Romana?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A famous Roman road", "A type of aqueduct", "About 200 years of relative peace", "The Roman Senate building", "A gladiator school"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Pax Romana, or \"Roman Peace,\" was roughly two centuries of relative stability beginning under Augustus."}, {"q": "How did Roman aqueducts move water across long distances?", "type": "mc", "options": ["With electric pumps", "By the gentle pull of gravity", "Carried in barrels by horse", "Using steam engines", "Through underground rivers only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Aqueducts used a slight downward slope so gravity pulled fresh water from distant hills into the cities."}, {"q": "Roughly how many people could the Colosseum hold?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 500", "About 5,000", "About 50,000", "About 500,000", "About 5 million"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Colosseum could hold roughly 50,000 spectators."}, {"q": "Historians often mark the \"fall\" of the Western Roman Empire in which year?", "type": "mc", "options": ["753 BC", "44 BC", "80 AD", "476 AD", "1453 AD"], "answer": 3, "explain": "In 476 AD the last emperor in the West was removed, a date often used to mark the fall.", "hint": "It is the latest AD date among the early choices."}, {"q": "When the Western Empire fell, the whole Roman world ended immediately.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. The eastern half continued as the Byzantine Empire, centred on Constantinople, for nearly another thousand years."}, {"q": "The saying \"all roads lead to Rome\" reflects the Romans' huge road network.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Rome built over 80,000 km of roads, and many genuinely connected back toward the capital."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu3", "continent": "europe", "n": 3, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏰", "title": "The Middle Ages: Knights, Lords & the Church", "hook": "After Rome's protection vanished, Europe rebuilt itself around a new bargain — <b>land in exchange for loyalty</b> — and crowned it all with stone castles and soaring churches.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "The thousand years between the fall of Rome (around 476 AD) and roughly 1500 are called the <b>Middle Ages</b>, or the medieval period — \"middle\" because they sit between the ancient world and the modern one. With no single empire to keep order, people needed a new way to feel safe. The answer that spread across much of Europe was a system we now call <b>feudalism</b>."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Feudalism worked like a pyramid of promises. At the top sat the <b>king</b>, who owned all the land. He granted large estates to powerful <b>lords</b> (or nobles) in return for their loyalty and soldiers. Those lords granted smaller pieces to <b>knights</b>, armoured warriors who fought on horseback. At the bottom were the <b>peasants</b>, most of them <b>serfs</b>, who farmed the land. Serfs were not enslaved, but they were not free to leave; in exchange for protection and a place to live, they owed their lord work, crops, and obedience."}, {"t": "p", "html": "It was an exchange running in both directions. A peasant gave labour and got protection and a place to live. A knight gave military service and got land to support himself. A lord gave loyalty and soldiers and got the king's backing. Almost everyone owed something to someone above them — and owed something to those below them too. Becoming a knight was itself a long journey: a boy might start as a <b>page</b> serving in a noble household, grow into a <b>squire</b> who looked after a knight's horse and armour, and only after years of training be \"knighted\" with a tap of a sword on each shoulder. Knights were expected to follow a code of honour called <b>chivalry</b> — to be brave, loyal, and to protect the weak — though, being human, they did not always live up to it."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> A full suit of plate armour could weigh around 20–25 kg, spread cleverly across the body. A fit, trained knight could still run, mount a horse, and even do a cartwheel in it — it was far less clumsy than films often suggest."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Towering over this whole world was the <b>Church</b>. In medieval western Europe, almost everyone shared the same Christian faith, and the Church touched every part of daily life from birth to death. It ran the schools, cared for the sick and the poor, and recorded history, since monks living quietly in monasteries were often the only people who could read and write. People marked the passing year by religious festivals and feast days. And the grandest, costliest buildings of the age were not palaces but <b>cathedrals</b> — vast stone churches with soaring ceilings and glowing stained-glass windows, so enormous that they often took a hundred years or more to build, passing from one generation of stonemasons to the next."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "castle", "file": "Castle of Coca 02.jpg", "caption": "A medieval castle's thick walls and towers were built for defence.", "credit": "Photo: Daniel Villafruela, CC BY-SA 3.0"}, {"t": "p", "html": "When danger came, people sheltered behind the <b>castle</b>. The earliest castles were simple mounds of earth topped with a wooden tower, called \"motte-and-bailey\" castles, but because wood burned easily, over time they grew into mighty fortresses of stone. Thick, high walls, narrow slit windows just wide enough for an archer to shoot through, a deep ditch or water-filled <b>moat</b>, a drawbridge, and a heavy iron-and-wood gate called a <b>portcullis</b> that could be dropped in an instant all made a well-built castle very hard to attack. A castle was a home, a military fort, and a bold statement of power all at once — visible proof, for miles around, of who controlled the land."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Then, in the middle of the 1300s, came a catastrophe. A disease known as the <b>Black Death</b>, a terrible plague, swept along trade routes into Europe. Between roughly 1347 and 1351, it may have killed a third or more of all the people on the continent. Whole villages emptied. No one understood what caused it — and there was no cure."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The horror was immense, and people searched desperately for explanations — some blamed bad air, some prayed harder, and some cruelly blamed innocent groups for the suffering. We now know the plague was spread largely by fleas carried on rats that travelled aboard trading ships and wagons. Yet its aftermath quietly reshaped society in ways no one intended. With so many workers dead, the survivors suddenly mattered more. Peasants could demand better pay, or simply walk to a different lord who would treat them better. The old feudal bargain, which depended on people staying put on their lord's land, began to loosen. Out of one of history's darkest moments came the slow, unplanned beginnings of a freer world for ordinary working people."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Big disasters often change history in two layers — the immediate suffering, and the surprising long-term ripples. When you study a catastrophe, ask not only \"what was lost?\" but also \"what shifted afterwards that no one planned?\""}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You are a serf after the Black Death", "prompt": "Half your village has died, and your lord still demands the same old work for the same low pay. Nearby, a different lord is offering wages to anyone who will farm his empty fields. What do you do?", "opts": [{"label": "Quietly accept the old terms and stay", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Safe but unrewarded. Many did this out of habit and fear — yet across Europe, more and more chose otherwise, and the old system weakened."}, {"label": "Bargain with your lord for better pay first", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Smart. With workers now scarce, your labour is valuable. Many peasants really did win better terms this way as bargaining power shifted toward them."}, {"label": "Leave secretly for the lord offering wages", "tag": "Watch out", "outcome": "Tempting, and many did flee — but lords and even kings tried to ban it with new laws. Bold, risky, and part of why the old order cracked."}]}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> The Middle Ages still shape your world. Words like <i>loyalty</i>, <i>service</i>, and <i>noble</i> carry their echo. Castles and cathedrals still stand across Europe, drawing millions of visitors. And the idea that workers can bargain when their skills are scarce — that you are not simply stuck where you were born — gathered real force in the wake of the Black Death. History's hardest chapters sometimes plant the seeds of the freedoms we now take for granted."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Why are the Middle Ages called \"middle\"?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They happened in the middle of Europe", "They sit between the ancient and modern worlds", "Most people were middle-aged", "They lasted only the middle of a century", "They were ruled from a central city"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The medieval period sits between the ancient world and the modern one — in the \"middle.\""}, {"q": "In the feudal system, what did lords give the king in return for land?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Gold coins only", "Loyalty and soldiers", "Stained-glass windows", "Their castles", "Nothing at all"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Lords received land and gave the king loyalty and soldiers in return."}, {"q": "Who sat at the bottom of the feudal pyramid?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Knights", "Lords", "Peasants and serfs", "Bishops", "Consuls"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Peasants, most of them serfs who farmed the land, were at the base of the feudal pyramid."}, {"q": "Were serfs the same as enslaved people?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Yes, exactly the same", "No — not free to leave, but not enslaved either", "Yes, but only in winter", "No — they were wealthy nobles", "No — they ruled the knights"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Serfs were not enslaved, but they were not free to leave; they owed their lord work and obedience in exchange for protection.", "hint": "It was an in-between status."}, {"q": "Why were monks often the keepers of records and history?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They were the best fighters", "They were often the only people who could read and write", "They owned all the castles", "The king ordered only monks to travel", "They invented the printing press"], "answer": 1, "explain": "In the medieval Church, monks were frequently the only literate people, so they ran schools and recorded history."}, {"q": "What was a portcullis?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A water channel", "A heavy castle gate", "A knight's helmet", "A church festival", "A type of plague"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A portcullis was a heavy gate that could be dropped to defend a castle's entrance."}, {"q": "Roughly when did the Black Death sweep through Europe?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 476 AD", "About 800 AD", "About 1347–1351", "About 1500", "About 1760"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Black Death struck Europe around 1347 to 1351."}, {"q": "About how much of Europe's population may the Black Death have killed?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 1 in 100", "A third or more", "Almost no one", "Exactly half of children only", "About 5 percent"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The plague may have killed a third or more of all people in Europe."}, {"q": "After the Black Death, surviving peasants gained more bargaining power.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. With workers scarce, survivors could demand better pay or move to better lords, loosening the feudal system."}, {"q": "Medieval castles were mainly built as comfortable holiday homes.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Castles were fortresses for defence and statements of power — with thick walls, moats, and gates — though lords did live in them."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu4", "continent": "europe", "n": 4, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🎨", "title": "Renaissance & Enlightenment: New Ways of Thinking", "hook": "Two great waves of curiosity swept across Europe — one reviving the beauty of the ancient world, the other daring to ask whether <b>reason itself</b> could reshape how people live.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Around 1400, in the wealthy cities of Italy, something stirred. Scholars and artists rediscovered the writings, art, and ideas of ancient Greece and Rome, and felt inspired to match them. This burst of creativity is called the <b>Renaissance</b>, a French word meaning \"rebirth.\" It was not that everyone had forgotten the ancients — but now people studied them with fresh excitement and began to believe that human beings could achieve extraordinary things in this world, not only the next."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Renaissance needed money as well as genius, and much of it flowed from a single banking family in the Italian city of Florence: the <b>Medici</b>. They grew immensely rich by lending money and managing it for others, and they spent some of that wealth as <b>patrons</b> — paying artists, architects, and thinkers to create great works, partly out of love of beauty and partly to win fame and influence for their family. This pattern spread to other rich families, the Church, and city governments across Italy. Without such wealthy patrons funding their work, many of the masterpieces we treasure today would simply never have been made — a reminder that art and money have always been quietly connected."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Renaissance artists also discovered new techniques that made their work startlingly lifelike. They mastered <b>perspective</b> — a way of drawing so that a flat picture seems to have real depth, with distant objects shrinking toward a vanishing point — and they studied the human body closely to paint it accurately. Two artists tower over the age. <b>Leonardo da Vinci</b> was a true \"Renaissance man\" — painter, scientist, and inventor all at once — who filled notebooks with studies of muscles, swirling water, birds in flight, and imagined flying machines, and who painted the famous <i>Mona Lisa</i> with her mysterious half-smile. <b>Michelangelo</b> carved the towering marble statue of <i>David</i> from a single block of stone, and, lying on his back high on wooden scaffolding for years, painted the vast ceiling of the Sistine Chapel in Rome."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Mona Lisa, by Leonardo da Vinci, from C2RMF retouched.jpg", "caption": "Leonardo da Vinci's Mona Lisa, painted in the early 1500s.", "credit": "Photo: Leonardo da Vinci, Public Domain"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Then came an invention that spread ideas faster than ever before. Around 1440, a German named <b>Johannes Gutenberg</b> built a printing press that used movable metal letters. Before this, books were copied by hand, one at a time, and were rare and costly. Now identical books could be printed quickly and cheaply. Knowledge — once locked in a few monasteries and palaces — began to reach ordinary people, and ideas could no longer be easily controlled."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> A scribe might take months or even years to copy a single large book by hand. With Gutenberg's press, a workshop could produce hundreds of copies in the same time — a leap as world-changing in its day as the internet was in ours."}, {"t": "p", "html": "As printed ideas spread, people began testing old beliefs against careful observation. <b>Galileo Galilei</b> pointed a new invention, the telescope, at the night sky and saw moons circling Jupiter — evidence that not everything revolved around the Earth. <b>Isaac Newton</b> later showed that the same force, <b>gravity</b>, that makes an apple fall also keeps the Moon in its orbit, binding heaven and Earth under one set of laws. This method — observe, measure, test — became the heart of modern <b>science</b>."}, {"t": "p", "html": "This spirit of questioning grew into a second great wave, the <b>Enlightenment</b> of the 1600s and 1700s. Thinkers asked: if reason can unlock the secrets of the stars, can it also improve how we govern ourselves? The English philosopher <b>John Locke</b> argued that people are born with natural <b>rights</b> — to life, liberty, and property — and that a government's job is to protect them. If a government fails, he said, the people may change it."}, {"t": "p", "html": "These were daring claims. They suggested that kings did not rule by the will of God alone, and that ordinary people had rights no ruler could rightly take away. Other Enlightenment thinkers pushed further still: some argued for splitting up government's powers so no single person could grow too strong, others for freedom of speech and religion, and a few brave voices began to question slavery and to argue that women, too, deserved education and rights. Not everyone agreed, and change came slowly. But Locke's ideas, and those of his fellow thinkers, were printed, translated, and carried far — and would later echo through revolutions and written constitutions on continents far beyond Europe's shores."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Notice the chain of cause and effect: rediscovered learning fed the printing press, the press spread science, science encouraged questioning, and questioning produced new ideas about rights. Big changes in history rarely stand alone — each one hands a tool to the next."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Order the age of new ideas", "sub": "Drag earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "c. 1400", "label": "The Renaissance begins in Italy"}, {"yr": "c. 1440", "label": "Gutenberg builds his printing press"}, {"yr": "1503", "label": "Leonardo begins painting the Mona Lisa"}, {"yr": "1610", "label": "Galileo observes Jupiter's moons"}, {"yr": "1687", "label": "Newton publishes his laws of gravity"}]}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> The way you learn science today — observe, measure, test, and question — was forged by Galileo and Newton. The belief that you have rights simply because you are human traces back to thinkers like Locke. And every time information races around the world in seconds, you are living out Gutenberg's revolution at full speed. The Renaissance and Enlightenment taught Europe, and eventually the world, a powerful habit: to look closely, think for yourself, and ask why."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What does the word \"Renaissance\" mean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Revolution", "Rebirth", "Reason", "Reform", "Republic"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Renaissance is French for \"rebirth\" — a renewed interest in ancient Greek and Roman ideas.", "hint": "It is about something coming back to life."}, {"q": "Which wealthy family were famous patrons of Renaissance art in Florence?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Medici", "The Tudors", "The Habsburgs", "The Caesars", "The Bourbons"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The Medici banking family paid artists and thinkers, funding much of the Renaissance."}, {"q": "What does it mean to be a \"patron\" of the arts?", "type": "mc", "options": ["To paint pictures", "To pay for and support artists' work", "To copy books by hand", "To rule a city-state", "To invent machines"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A patron provides money and support so artists and thinkers can create.", "hint": "Think about who funds the work."}, {"q": "Which artist painted the Mona Lisa and filled notebooks with inventions?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Michelangelo", "Galileo", "Leonardo da Vinci", "Gutenberg", "Newton"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Leonardo da Vinci, the classic \"Renaissance man,\" painted the Mona Lisa and studied science and invention."}, {"q": "Around 1440, what did Johannes Gutenberg create?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The telescope", "The printing press with movable metal letters", "The first cathedral", "The law of gravity", "The Sistine Chapel"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Gutenberg built a printing press with movable metal type, making books cheap and widespread."}, {"q": "Why was the printing press so important?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It made armour lighter", "It let knowledge spread quickly and cheaply", "It cured the plague", "It funded the Medici", "It powered factories"], "answer": 1, "explain": "By replacing slow hand-copying, the press spread knowledge to ordinary people and made ideas hard to control."}, {"q": "What did Galileo see through his telescope that challenged old beliefs?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The surface of the Sun up close", "Moons circling Jupiter", "A new continent", "Gutenberg's press", "The city of Rome"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Galileo saw moons orbiting Jupiter — evidence that not everything circled the Earth."}, {"q": "Isaac Newton showed that the force pulling an apple down is the same one that...", "type": "mc", "options": ["Lights the stars", "Keeps the Moon in orbit", "Spreads the plague", "Powers the printing press", "Builds cathedrals"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Newton showed gravity both makes apples fall and keeps the Moon in orbit — one law for heaven and Earth."}, {"q": "John Locke argued that people are born with natural rights a government should protect.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Locke claimed people have natural rights to life, liberty, and property, and that government exists to protect them."}, {"q": "The Enlightenment taught that only kings, not ordinary people, could reason about government.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. The Enlightenment encouraged everyone to use reason, and argued ordinary people had rights rulers could not rightly take away."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu5", "continent": "europe", "n": 5, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "⚙️", "title": "The Industrial Revolution", "hook": "In a single lifetime, machines began doing work that had always needed human muscle or animal strength — and the way people lived, worked, and even <b>told the time</b> changed forever.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "For thousands of years, almost everything people used was made slowly by hand or with simple tools, and most people lived on the land as farmers. Then, beginning around <b>1760 in Britain</b>, a transformation now called the <b>Industrial Revolution</b> changed all of that. New machines, powered by new sources of energy, started producing goods faster and in far greater quantities than ever before — and the change spread across Europe and the world."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Why Britain, and why then? The country had plenty of <b>coal</b> to burn for energy and <b>iron</b> to build machines, rivers and ports for trade, and inventors eager to solve problems. The key breakthrough was the improved <b>steam engine</b>, refined by <b>James Watt</b> in the 1760s and 1770s. By burning coal to boil water into steam, it created powerful motion that could drive machinery — energy on demand, day or night, rain or shine."}, {"t": "p", "html": "This power gave rise to the <b>factory</b>. In the old way, a weaver worked at home on a single loom, making cloth slowly with the whole family helping — a system sometimes called \"cottage industry.\" Now, instead, hundreds of workers gathered in one large building, tending long rows of powered machines that spun thread and wove cloth at astonishing speed. The textile (cloth) trade led the way, and one machine could now do the work of many hands. Towns swelled into crowded, smoky industrial cities as people left the countryside seeking work and wages. Britain, with its mills and ironworks roaring day and night, became known as \"the workshop of the world.\""}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> Before the railways, a journey that takes an hour by train today might have taken a whole day by horse-drawn coach. Steam trains were so much faster that some early doctors worried — wrongly — that the human body could not safely travel at such speeds."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Steam did not stay still — it learned to move. The <b>railway</b> arrived when engineers put steam engines on wheels and ran them along iron rails. In 1825 the first public steam railway opened in north-east England, and in 1830 a famous line linked the cities of Liverpool and Manchester, carrying passengers as well as goods. The engineer <b>George Stephenson</b> and his son Robert built some of the most successful early locomotives, including the speedy <i>Rocket</i>. Suddenly people and goods could travel quickly and cheaply over long distances. Coal, cloth, food, newspapers, and letters moved across whole countries in hours instead of days, knitting communities — and eventually the wider world — far more tightly together."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "factory", "file": "Stephensons Rocket.jpg", "caption": "Stephenson's Rocket, a famous early steam locomotive of 1829.", "credit": "Photo: William M. Connolley, CC BY-SA 3.0"}, {"t": "p", "html": "But this new world had a harsh side that we must not look away from. Early factories were often dangerous, deafening, and dirty, the air thick with cotton dust or coal smoke, and the working day could stretch to twelve hours or more, six days a week. Fast-moving machines had no safety guards, and accidents were common. Worst of all, many factories and coal mines employed <b>children</b>, some as young as five or six, because they were small enough to crawl under machines to clear jams or squeeze into narrow mine tunnels, and because they could be paid far less than adults. It was exhausting, frightening, and perilous work, and it robbed many children of school and play."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Over time, people fought to make things better, and this part of the story matters just as much as the machines. Reformers, writers like Charles Dickens whose novels exposed the misery of the poor, doctors, campaigners, and the workers themselves all spoke out against the worst abuses. Governments slowly passed <b>laws</b> — known in Britain as the Factory Acts — that limited working hours, banned the youngest children from the most dangerous jobs, set basic safety rules, and later required children to attend school instead of toiling all day. Workers also began joining together in <b>trade unions</b>, pooling their voices to bargain for fairer pay and safer conditions. Progress was slow and hard-won, often resisted at first, but step by step it was real."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Even the way people kept time changed. In the old days, each town set its clocks by the local position of the Sun, so noon in one place differed from noon in another. That did not matter when travel was slow — but fast trains needed exact, shared schedules. So countries adopted standard <b>time zones</b>, with everyone in a region keeping the same official time. The next time you check a train timetable, you are using a system the railways made necessary."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Powerful new technology almost always brings benefits and harms tangled together. The wise question is not \"is it good or bad?\" but \"who gains, who is hurt, and how do we fix the harms while keeping the gains?\" People answered that question, imperfectly, throughout the Industrial Revolution."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You are a factory owner in 1840", "prompt": "Your mill is profitable, but you employ young children for long hours in unsafe conditions. A new law proposes limiting child labour and shortening the working day. How do you respond?", "opts": [{"label": "Resist the law to protect short-term profits", "tag": "Watch out", "outcome": "Common at the time, but short-sighted. Many owners fought reform — yet public anger grew, and the laws came anyway. History remembers the reformers more kindly."}, {"label": "Support reform and improve conditions", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Forward-thinking. Some owners did invest in safer mills and schooling, earning loyalty and respect. Treating workers well proved good for society and, often, for business too."}, {"label": "Do only the minimum the law forces", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Understandable and very common — most owners did just enough to comply. It still meant real, if slow, improvement for workers over time."}]}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Nearly every machine-made thing around you — your clothes, your phone, the train or bus you ride — descends from the Industrial Revolution. So do the protections you may take for granted: limits on working hours, the right to school instead of labour, and laws keeping workplaces safe. It was an age of dazzling progress and real suffering, side by side. Learning to chase the progress while fixing the harm is a challenge every new technology, right up to today's, still hands us."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Where and roughly when did the Industrial Revolution begin?", "type": "mc", "options": ["France, around 1500", "Britain, around 1760", "Italy, around 1400", "Greece, around 776 BC", "Germany, around 1440"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Industrial Revolution began in Britain around 1760.", "hint": "Think coal, iron, and an island nation."}, {"q": "Which fuel powered the steam engines of the Industrial Revolution?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Oil", "Coal", "Wind", "Wood only", "Electricity"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Coal was burned to boil water into steam, powering the engines and factories."}, {"q": "Who refined the steam engine into a powerful, practical machine?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Isaac Newton", "James Watt", "Johannes Gutenberg", "Galileo Galilei", "John Locke"], "answer": 1, "explain": "James Watt improved the steam engine in the 1760s and 1770s, making it far more useful."}, {"q": "What was a factory's main difference from older ways of making goods?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It used no machines at all", "Many workers and machines gathered in one large building", "Only one person worked there", "It ran only on horse power", "It made goods more slowly"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Factories brought many workers and powered machines together in one place, producing goods far faster."}, {"q": "What major change did putting steam engines on wheels create?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The telescope", "The printing press", "The railway", "The aqueduct", "The castle"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Steam engines on wheels created the railway, letting people and goods travel quickly over long distances."}, {"q": "Why were very young children often employed in factories and mines?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They were the strongest workers", "They were small, could reach tight spaces, and were paid little", "Laws required children to work", "Adults refused all factory jobs", "They owned the machines"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Children were small enough to crawl under machines or into narrow tunnels, and could be paid very little."}, {"q": "What did Britain's Factory Acts do?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Banned all factories", "Limited working hours and protected children", "Built more coal mines", "Created the steam engine", "Ended the railways"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Factory Acts limited working hours, restricted child labour, and later required schooling — slow but real reform."}, {"q": "Why did countries adopt standard time zones?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Sun stopped shining", "Fast trains needed exact, shared schedules", "Clocks were banned", "Factories closed at night", "Locke demanded it"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Local Sun-based time varied from town to town; fast railways needed everyone to share the same official time."}, {"q": "The Industrial Revolution brought both great progress and real suffering at the same time.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. It produced dazzling new goods and travel alongside dangerous, harsh working conditions — both at once."}, {"q": "Trade unions were groups of workers joining together to demand fairer pay and safer conditions.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Workers formed trade unions to push for better wages and safer workplaces during the Industrial Revolution."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu6", "continent": "europe", "n": 6, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🌍", "title": "World War I: Causes & Consequences", "hook": "In the summer of 1914, one pistol shot in a city most Europeans had never visited pulled an <b>entire continent</b> into the deadliest war it had ever known.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Picture Europe in 1914 as a row of climbers roped together on a cliff. The ropes are called <b>alliances</b> — promises that if one country is attacked, its friends will fight too. Roped together, the climbers feel safe. But ropes work both ways: if one person slips, everyone is yanked over the edge. That is almost exactly what happened."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Historians use four letters to remember the deep causes: <b>M-A-I-N</b>. <b>Militarism</b> meant countries had spent years building huge armies and navies, drawing up detailed battle plans, and treating war as a normal tool of statecraft; many generals were quietly itching to use the forces they had built. <b>Alliances</b> were the ropes — two rival teams, with Germany and Austria-Hungary on one side and France, Russia, and Britain on the other, each promising to defend the others. <b>Imperialism</b> meant European powers competed greedily for colonies and resources around the world, and every rivalry overseas bred fresh jealousy back home. <b>Nationalism</b> meant intense pride in one's own nation — and, among smaller peoples ruled by big empires, a burning hunger to break free and govern themselves."}, {"t": "p", "html": "These tensions were like dry firewood stacked for years. All it needed was a spark. The spark came on 28 June 1914 in Sarajevo, a city in the Balkans, when a young nationalist named Gavrilo Princip shot <b>Archduke Franz Ferdinand</b>, heir to the throne of Austria-Hungary, along with his wife. Austria-Hungary blamed neighboring Serbia and, after weeks of angry demands, declared war. Because of the alliance ropes, the yank traveled fast: Russia stepped in to protect Serbia, Germany stood by Austria-Hungary, France was bound to Russia, and when Germany marched its troops through neutral Belgium to attack France, Britain joined the war too. In barely a month, a quarrel between two countries had become a war involving the whole continent and its overseas empires."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Soldiers on both sides expected to be <b>home by Christmas</b> 1914. Instead the war ground on for more than four years, until November 1918."}, {"t": "p", "html": "What made it so terrible was a deadly mismatch: <b>old tactics meeting new weapons</b>. Armies still tried marching in lines across open fields, the way they had for centuries, but now machine guns could fire hundreds of bullets a minute and heavy artillery could shred whole regiments from miles away. To survive, soldiers dug into the earth. Soon two facing lines of <b>trenches</b> — muddy ditches reinforced with wood and sandbags — stretched for hundreds of miles across France and Belgium, separated by a cratered, barbed-wire wasteland called No Man's Land. Life in the trenches was wet, freezing, and infested with rats and lice. For years the front lines barely moved more than a few miles, even as artillery, poison gas, and disease killed millions on both sides."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "trench", "file": "Cheshire_Regiment_trench_Somme_1916.jpg", "caption": "British soldiers in a frontline Somme trench, 1916.", "credit": "Photo: Ernest Brooks, Public domain"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you read that a war had a single \"cause,\" be a little skeptical. The assassination was the trigger, but the M-A-I-N pressures were the loaded gun. Big events usually have a <i>spark</i> and a pile of slow-building <i>fuel</i> — and the fuel is often the more important half of the story."}, {"t": "order", "title": "How the war unfolded", "sub": "Drag earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1914", "label": "Franz Ferdinand is assassinated in Sarajevo"}, {"yr": "1914", "label": "Alliances drag Europe's powers into war"}, {"yr": "1916", "label": "The Battle of the Somme — months of trench fighting"}, {"yr": "1918", "label": "Germany surrenders; the fighting ends"}, {"yr": "1919", "label": "The Treaty of Versailles is signed"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "When the guns finally fell silent on 11 November 1918, the victorious nations met near Paris to write the <b>Treaty of Versailles</b>. They forced Germany to accept the blame for the war, give up territory, shrink its army to a fraction of its former size, and pay enormous sums of money called reparations. Many Germans, who had not felt defeated on their own soil, were left feeling humiliated and cheated. Meanwhile the war shattered old empires entirely: the German, Austro-Hungarian, Russian, and Ottoman empires all collapsed, and brand-new countries such as Poland and Czechoslovakia appeared on the redrawn map of Europe. The treaty was meant to guarantee a lasting peace."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Around <b>nine million soldiers</b> died in World War I, plus millions of civilians — a loss so vast that nearly every town in Europe still has a memorial listing local names."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> The way World War I ended helped plant the seeds of the next one, just twenty years later — proof that how you make peace matters as much as how you win. The alliance lesson still shapes our world: today's defense pacts, like NATO, are built by people who studied 1914 and asked how to keep ropes from dragging everyone off the cliff again."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What do the letters M-A-I-N stand for as causes of World War I?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Money, Armies, Islands, Nations", "Militarism, Alliances, Imperialism, Nationalism", "Maps, Allies, Industry, News", "Monarchy, Anger, Ideas, Navies", "Markets, Air power, Iron, Nuclear weapons"], "answer": 1, "explain": "M-A-I-N stands for Militarism, Alliances, Imperialism, and Nationalism — the four long-building pressures behind the war.", "hint": "The first word means a love of building up armies."}, {"q": "Whose assassination in Sarajevo helped trigger the war?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Kaiser Wilhelm of Germany", "Tsar Nicholas of Russia", "Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary", "King George of Britain", "President Wilson of the United States"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Archduke Franz Ferdinand, heir to Austria-Hungary's throne, was shot in Sarajevo on 28 June 1914.", "hint": "He was the heir to Austria-Hungary."}, {"q": "Why did one assassination grow into a war across all of Europe?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A volcano blocked the roads", "Alliances pulled friend after friend into the fight", "Everyone ran out of food at once", "A single king ruled all of Europe", "The countries shared one army"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The alliance system acted like ropes: when one country went to war, its allies were pulled in too.", "hint": "Think of climbers roped together."}, {"q": "Soldiers in 1914 expected to be home by Christmas.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Many believed the war would be short, but it lasted more than four years."}, {"q": "What was the main reason trench warfare developed?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Soldiers liked living underground", "New weapons like machine guns made open attacks deadly", "There was no flat ground in Europe", "Trenches were warmer in summer", "Generals had run out of bullets"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Machine guns and artillery made crossing open ground suicidal, so armies dug in for protection.", "hint": "It was about surviving new weapons."}, {"q": "What was the strip of dangerous ground between the trenches called?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Green Belt", "The Iron Curtain", "No Man's Land", "The Free Zone", "The Front Garden"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The cratered, barbed-wire space between opposing trenches was called No Man's Land.", "hint": "It belonged to neither side."}, {"q": "In which year did the fighting of World War I end?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1916", "1917", "1918", "1919", "1920"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Germany surrendered and the fighting stopped in November 1918.", "hint": "It is the year before the Treaty of Versailles."}, {"q": "What did the Treaty of Versailles do to Germany?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Gave it new colonies", "Made it the leader of Europe", "Blamed it, shrank its army, and demanded payments", "Joined it with Austria-Hungary", "Excused it from all responsibility"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The treaty assigned Germany blame, cut its military, took land, and demanded large reparations.", "hint": "Many Germans felt it was harsh and humiliating."}, {"q": "The Treaty of Versailles guaranteed lasting peace in Europe.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Its harsh terms left resentment that helped lead to World War II just twenty years later."}, {"q": "Which modern alliance was shaped partly by the lessons of 1914?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Olympics", "NATO", "The Hanseatic League", "The Roman Senate", "The Silk Road"], "answer": 1, "explain": "NATO is a modern defense alliance built by leaders who studied how 1914's ropes dragged everyone into war.", "hint": "It is a defense pact with a four-letter name."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu7", "continent": "europe", "n": 7, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "⚔️", "title": "World War II & the Rise of Fascism", "hook": "Out of the anger and hunger of the 1930s rose leaders who promised glory — and led the world into its most destructive war, and one of history's darkest crimes.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "If World War I left Europe wounded, the <b>Great Depression</b> of the 1930s knocked it flat. Starting with a stock market crash in America, the disaster spread across the world: banks collapsed, factories fell silent, and millions of ordinary people lost their jobs, their savings, and sometimes their homes almost overnight. Frightened, hungry, and desperate, many began listening to anyone who promised to make their nation proud and great again — and that fear and anger is the soil in which a dangerous idea called <b>fascism</b> took root and grew."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Fascism is a way of running a country built on total obedience to one strong leader and one nation. It treats disagreement as betrayal, glorifies the military, and casts other groups of people as enemies to be feared and blamed. In Italy, Benito Mussolini seized power first, in the 1920s. But the most dangerous fascist of all was <b>Adolf Hitler</b>, who took control of Germany in 1933. Hitler blamed Germany's troubles on others — above all on Jewish people — promised to tear up the hated Treaty of Versailles and restore German greatness, and quickly built a brutal dictatorship. He banned other political parties, controlled the newspapers and radio, and crushed, jailed, or killed anyone who dared to oppose him."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Hitler then began grabbing neighboring lands, gambling that no one would stop him. At first, other countries hoped that giving in to his demands would satisfy him and avoid another war — a policy called appeasement. But each time he was given something, he simply demanded more. When Germany invaded <b>Poland in September 1939</b>, Britain and France finally drew the line and declared war. World War II had begun, and within a year much of Europe was under threat."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Germany's early attacks used a tactic nicknamed <b>blitzkrieg</b>, meaning \"lightning war\" — fast tanks and aircraft striking together to overwhelm defenders before they could react."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Blitzkrieg let Germany conquer much of Europe with frightening speed. But Hitler's regime did something far worse than conquest. The Nazis carried out the <b>Holocaust</b>: the deliberate, organized murder of six million Jewish people, along with millions of others they hated, including Roma people, disabled people, and political opponents. It is important to face this soberly. These were not numbers — they were families, children, neighbors, and friends, killed simply for who they were. Remembering them honestly is how we honor them and guard against such hatred ever returning."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "star", "file": "Into_the_Jaws_of_Death_23-0455M_edit.jpg", "caption": "American troops wade ashore on D-Day, 6 June 1944, in Normandy, France.", "credit": "Photo: Robert F. Sargent, U.S. Coast Guard, Public domain"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Watch for leaders who blame all of a country's problems on one group of people. That pattern — finding a scapegoat — is one of history's oldest and most dangerous tricks. Real problems almost always have many causes, and a leader who offers a single enemy is usually hiding something."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Slowly, though, the tide turned against Hitler. The Soviet Union, which Hitler invaded in 1941, fought back at a terrible cost in lives and gradually pushed the Germans back from the east. The United States, drawn into the war after being attacked, brought enormous industrial power, building ships, tanks, and planes faster than the Axis could destroy them. The turning point in Western Europe came on <b>D-Day, 6 June 1944</b>, when Allied forces launched the largest seaborne invasion in history, landing tens of thousands of troops on the beaches of Normandy in France under heavy fire. From there they fought their way east toward Germany, while Soviet armies pressed in from the west, squeezing Hitler's shrinking empire from both sides."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two sides of World War II in Europe", "a": {"title": "The Axis", "items": ["Germany under Hitler", "Italy under Mussolini", "Built on fascism and conquest", "Used blitzkrieg tactics"]}, "b": {"title": "The Allies", "items": ["Britain and France", "The Soviet Union", "The United States", "Landed at Normandy on D-Day"]}}, {"t": "p", "html": "Caught between the closing Allied and Soviet armies, Germany finally collapsed. Hitler took his own life as enemy soldiers reached Berlin, and in <b>May 1945</b> Germany surrendered, ending the war in Europe at last. The cost was almost unimaginable: tens of millions of soldiers and civilians dead, great cities flattened to rubble by bombing, and a once-proud continent left exhausted and in ruins. People everywhere were determined that such horror must never be allowed to happen again."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "World War II killed an estimated <b>70 to 85 million people</b> worldwide — the deadliest conflict in human history."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> After 1945, Europeans built memorials, museums, and laws so that the Holocaust would never be forgotten — coining the phrase \"Never again.\" The horror of those years also pushed nations to create the United Nations and, later, the European Union, choosing cooperation over conquest. When you hear leaders today warn against hatred and scapegoating, they are drawing on the hardest lesson Europe ever learned."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What economic disaster helped fascism rise in the 1930s?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Industrial Revolution", "The Great Depression", "The Gold Rush", "The Space Race", "The Renaissance"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Great Depression threw millions out of work, making people desperate enough to follow extreme leaders.", "hint": "It was a worldwide collapse of jobs and banks."}, {"q": "What is a key feature of fascism?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Sharing power equally among everyone", "Total obedience to one strong leader, treating disagreement as betrayal", "Letting citizens vote out any leader easily", "Avoiding all armies and weapons", "Welcoming every group of people equally"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Fascism demands obedience to one leader and one nation and treats disagreement and outsiders as enemies.", "hint": "It is the opposite of sharing power."}, {"q": "Which event in 1939 finally caused Britain and France to declare war?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Germany's invasion of Poland", "The sinking of a cruise ship", "A volcano in Italy", "The Berlin Olympics", "The fall of the Berlin Wall"], "answer": 0, "explain": "When Germany invaded Poland in September 1939, Britain and France declared war, starting World War II.", "hint": "It was an invasion of a country to Germany's east."}, {"q": "What does the tactic 'blitzkrieg' mean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Slow siege", "Lightning war", "Sea battle", "Night march", "Peace treaty"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Blitzkrieg means 'lightning war' — fast strikes by tanks and aircraft together.", "hint": "Think of something fast and electric in the sky."}, {"q": "What was the Holocaust?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A famous European festival", "The Nazis' deliberate murder of six million Jewish people and millions of others", "A type of fast tank", "A peace conference in Paris", "A scientific discovery"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Holocaust was the Nazis' organized murder of six million Jewish people, along with millions of others they targeted.", "hint": "It is the war's gravest crime against innocent people."}, {"q": "On D-Day, the Allies launched the largest seaborne invasion in history.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "On 6 June 1944, Allied forces landed on the beaches of Normandy in the largest seaborne invasion ever."}, {"q": "Where did the D-Day landings take place?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The coast of Italy", "The beaches of Normandy in France", "The shores of Greece", "The Russian border", "The cliffs of Dover"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The D-Day landings happened on the beaches of Normandy, in northern France.", "hint": "It is a region of northern France."}, {"q": "In which year did the war in Europe end with Germany's surrender?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1941", "1943", "1944", "1945", "1948"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Germany surrendered in May 1945, ending World War II in Europe.", "hint": "It is the year after D-Day."}, {"q": "Which two countries' huge resources helped turn the war against Germany?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Spain and Portugal", "The Soviet Union and the United States", "Sweden and Norway", "Greece and Turkey", "Ireland and Iceland"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Soviet Union's manpower and the United States' industry both proved decisive against Germany.", "hint": "One was in the east, one across the Atlantic."}, {"q": "What phrase did Europeans adopt to remember the Holocaust?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Home by Christmas", "Never again", "Better late than never", "All for one", "Peace in our time"], "answer": 1, "explain": "'Never again' became the promise to remember the Holocaust and prevent such hatred from returning.", "hint": "It is a two-word vow about the future."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu8", "continent": "europe", "n": 8, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🧱", "title": "The Cold War & the Fall of Communism", "hook": "After 1945 the two strongest victors became <b>rivals</b>, and for forty years a wall of fear divided Europe — until ordinary people tore it down.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "When World War II ended in 1945, two giants stood tall above the ruins of the old world: the <b>United States</b> in the West and the <b>Soviet Union</b> in the East. They had fought Hitler side by side as allies, but they believed in almost completely opposite ideas about how a country and its economy should work. Once their common enemy was gone, that deep disagreement hardened into a tense, suspicious, decades-long standoff that became known as the <b>Cold War</b>."}, {"t": "p", "html": "It was called \"cold\" because the two superpowers never fought each other directly with their armies; both now had nuclear weapons, and a \"hot\" war between them could have destroyed the world, so neither dared start one. Instead they competed in every other way they could imagine: building ever bigger arsenals of weapons, backing rival governments and rebels around the globe, spying on each other, and racing to prove that their way of life was best. The United States championed <b>capitalism and democracy</b>, where people own their own businesses and choose their leaders in free elections. The Soviet Union championed <b>communism</b>, where the government owned and controlled the economy and a single party held all political power, allowing no real opposition."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Europe itself was split down the middle. The Soviet Union controlled the countries of Eastern Europe, while the West stayed tied to America. Winston Churchill gave the divide its famous name, saying an <b>\"Iron Curtain\"</b> had descended across the continent. It was not a real curtain but a heavily guarded border of fences, watchtowers, and soldiers that you could not freely cross."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "The rivalry even reached space. When the Soviets launched <b>Sputnik</b>, the first satellite, in 1957, a stunned America poured money into science — a contest that ended with Americans walking on the Moon in 1969."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Nowhere was the divide sharper than in <b>Berlin</b>, Germany's old capital. The city sat deep inside Soviet-controlled East Germany, but the city itself was split between a communist East and a free West. Because life was so much freer and richer in the West, so many people slipped out of communist East Germany through West Berlin that the country was losing many of its brightest workers. To stop them, in 1961 the government suddenly built the <b>Berlin Wall</b> — concrete, watchtowers, and barbed wire slicing right through the middle of the city, in some places separating families and even neighbors literally overnight. For nearly thirty years that wall became the world's most famous symbol of a divided Europe."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "wall", "file": "Thefalloftheberlinwall1989.JPG", "caption": "Crowds celebrate atop the Berlin Wall as it falls in November 1989.", "credit": "Photo: Lear 21, CC BY-SA 3.0"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Notice that the Cold War's biggest weapon was often <i>information</i> — what people were allowed to know, read, and say. When a government has to build a wall to keep its own people in, that tells you something important about how free they really feel inside it."}, {"t": "p", "html": "By the 1980s, the communist system was struggling badly. The economies of the East had fallen far behind the booming West, shops often ran short of basic goods, and people were tired of being told what they could read, say, and think. A reform-minded Soviet leader named Mikhail Gorbachev began loosening the old tight controls, hoping to save the system. But once people sensed that change was possible, there was no stopping them. Across Eastern Europe in 1989, huge peaceful crowds poured into the streets demanding freedom. On the night of <b>9 November 1989</b>, with the border guards overwhelmed and unsure of their orders, East Berliners simply walked up to the Wall — and then began climbing over it. People attacked the hated concrete with hammers and chisels while the whole world watched on television and wept with joy."}, {"t": "order", "title": "The Cold War, start to finish", "sub": "Drag earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1945", "label": "World War II ends; US and USSR become rivals"}, {"yr": "1957", "label": "The Soviets launch Sputnik, the first satellite"}, {"yr": "1961", "label": "The Berlin Wall is built across the city"}, {"yr": "1989", "label": "The Berlin Wall falls"}, {"yr": "1991", "label": "The Soviet Union breaks apart"}]}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Within two years of the Wall falling, the <b>Soviet Union itself dissolved</b> in 1991, splitting into fifteen separate countries and ending the Cold War."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Many countries that were trapped behind the Iron Curtain — like Poland, Hungary, and the Baltic states — are now free democracies and members of the European Union. Pieces of the Berlin Wall stand in museums around the world as a reminder that even the most fearsome barriers can fall when ordinary people decide they have had enough. The questions the Cold War raised — about freedom, information, and how much power a government should have — are still argued about today."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Which two superpowers were the main rivals in the Cold War?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Britain and France", "The United States and the Soviet Union", "Germany and Italy", "China and Japan", "Spain and Portugal"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The United States and the Soviet Union were the two superpowers at the heart of the Cold War.", "hint": "One led the West, one led the East."}, {"q": "Why was the Cold War called 'cold'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It was fought mostly in winter", "The two superpowers never fought each other directly with armies", "It took place near the Arctic", "No weapons were ever built", "It lasted only a few weeks"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It was 'cold' because the superpowers competed fiercely but never fought each other directly — a direct war was too dangerous.", "hint": "Think about what they avoided doing to each other."}, {"q": "What economic and political system did the Soviet Union champion?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Capitalism", "Communism", "Feudalism", "Fascism", "Monarchy"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Soviet Union championed communism, where the government controlled the economy and one party held power.", "hint": "It is the opposite of capitalism."}, {"q": "Who described the divide in Europe as an 'Iron Curtain'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Mikhail Gorbachev", "Winston Churchill", "Adolf Hitler", "Franz Ferdinand", "Benito Mussolini"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Winston Churchill famously said an 'Iron Curtain' had descended across Europe.", "hint": "He was a British wartime leader."}, {"q": "The Sputnik launch in 1957 helped spark the space race.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Sputnik, the first satellite, shocked the United States into pouring money into its own space program."}, {"q": "Why was the Berlin Wall built in 1961?", "type": "mc", "options": ["To stop floods from a nearby river", "To stop people fleeing communist East Germany to the West", "To protect the city from invasion", "To celebrate the end of the war", "To mark the border of France"], "answer": 1, "explain": "So many people were fleeing East Germany through West Berlin that the government built the Wall to stop them.", "hint": "It was meant to keep people in, not out."}, {"q": "In which year did the Berlin Wall fall?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1961", "1969", "1979", "1989", "1991"], "answer": 3, "explain": "The Berlin Wall fell on 9 November 1989, as crowds climbed over and tore at it.", "hint": "It is two years before the Soviet Union dissolved."}, {"q": "What largely brought down the Berlin Wall?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A powerful bomb", "Huge peaceful crowds demanding freedom", "A natural earthquake", "An American invasion", "A vote in the United Nations"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Peaceful crowds and loosened controls, not weapons, brought the Wall down in 1989.", "hint": "It was the people, not an army."}, {"q": "What happened to the Soviet Union in 1991?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It conquered Western Europe", "It broke apart into fifteen separate countries", "It joined the United States", "It built a second wall", "It launched another satellite"], "answer": 1, "explain": "In 1991 the Soviet Union dissolved into fifteen independent countries, ending the Cold War.", "hint": "It split into many smaller nations."}, {"q": "Many former Iron Curtain countries are now members of which organization?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Axis", "The European Union", "The Soviet Union", "The Hanseatic League", "The Roman Empire"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Countries once behind the Iron Curtain, like Poland and Hungary, are now free members of the European Union.", "hint": "It is a peaceful union of European nations."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu9", "continent": "europe", "n": 9, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🗺️", "title": "Europe Today: Lands, Borders & the European Union", "hook": "A continent once carved up by centuries of war now lets you cross from <b>Portugal to Poland</b> without ever showing a passport. How did that happen?", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Europe is one of the world's smaller continents, yet it is astonishingly varied. Its shape is jagged and broken, full of <b>peninsulas</b> — fingers of land reaching into the sea — like Italy, Spain, Scandinavia, and Greece. All that coastline meant that for thousands of years, nearly everyone in Europe lived close to the water, which made trade, fishing, and exploration central to European life."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The land itself shaped where people settled and how they lived. The <b>Alps</b>, Europe's greatest mountain range, curve through the heart of the continent like a spine, their snowy peaks feeding rivers and for centuries acting as a natural wall that separated the cooler north from the warmer south. To the south lies the warm <b>Mediterranean Sea</b>, ringed by sunny coasts where olives, grapes, and lemons have grown since ancient times, and whose calm waters once carried Greek and Roman ships between distant ports. And threading through the whole continent are great rivers — above all the <b>Rhine</b> and the <b>Danube</b> — which work like natural highways, carrying boats, trade goods, travelers, and ideas across many different countries and connecting peoples who speak entirely different languages."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "The <b>Danube</b> flows through or past <b>ten countries</b> — more than any other river in the world — linking places as different as Germany, Austria, Hungary, Serbia, and Romania."}, {"t": "p", "html": "These rivers and seas explain something important: Europe's geography naturally connects its peoples, even though for most of history its many nations spent their energy fighting one another over land, religion, and pride. After the horrors of two world wars, which you read about in earlier lessons, a few far-sighted leaders had a daring idea. What if countries that traded closely together, openly sharing the very coal and steel they once fought over, would find that going to war had become both pointless and impossible? They started small, with just a handful of countries pooling their heavy industry. That idea grew, step by step over the following decades, into the <b>European Union</b>, or EU — today a partnership of around <b>27 nations</b> stretching from Ireland to the edge of Asia."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Matterhorn_from_Domhütte_-_2.jpg", "caption": "The Matterhorn, one of the most famous peaks in the European Alps.", "credit": "Photo: Zacharie Grossen, CC BY-SA 3.0"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you look at a map, don't just memorize borders — ask <i>why</i> they are where they are. Mountains, rivers, and coastlines often explain a border far better than any politician could. Geography is the quiet author of much of history."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The EU does some genuinely remarkable things. Most of its members share a single currency, the <b>euro</b>, so a shopkeeper in France, a baker in Greece, and a student in Germany all reach into their pockets and pull out the very same coins and banknotes. Many members also agreed to <b>open borders</b>, meaning you can drive or take a train from one country straight into the next without ever stopping to show a passport — something that would have astonished Europeans a century ago, when those same borders bristled with soldiers and checkpoints. Citizens of any member country are free to live, work, and study in any other member country they choose, so a young person from Spain can build a life in Sweden as easily as moving to the next town."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Europe before and after the EU", "a": {"title": "Europe in 1914", "items": ["Rival empires and armies", "Borders guarded by soldiers", "Different money in every land", "Centuries of repeated wars"]}, "b": {"title": "The EU today", "items": ["Around 27 cooperating nations", "Many open, passport-free borders", "A shared currency, the euro", "Decades of peace between members"]}}, {"t": "p", "html": "The EU is not a single country, and it is not perfect — its members still argue, keep their own languages and traditions, and sometimes disagree sharply about money and rules. Some nations, like the United Kingdom, have even chosen to leave. But the bigger picture is striking: lands that spent <b>centuries at war</b> now settle their differences by talking around a table instead of fighting on a battlefield."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "In 2012 the European Union was awarded the <b>Nobel Peace Prize</b> for helping turn a war-torn continent into a peaceful one."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> The EU is one of history's boldest experiments — an attempt to answer the question this whole course keeps raising: how do you stop neighbors from going to war? Whether you think it has fully succeeded or not, the fact that millions of young Europeans now grow up able to cross old battlefields freely, with the same coins in their pockets, is one of the most hopeful changes in all of European history."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What is a peninsula?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A tall mountain", "A finger of land reaching into the sea", "A deep underground cave", "A type of river boat", "A large desert"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A peninsula is land that juts out into the sea, like Italy or Greece — Europe has many.", "hint": "Think of Italy's boot shape sticking into the water."}, {"q": "Which mountain range curves through the heart of Europe?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Andes", "The Himalayas", "The Alps", "The Rockies", "The Urals"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Alps are Europe's greatest mountain range, long acting as a natural divide between north and south.", "hint": "The Matterhorn is one of its peaks."}, {"q": "Why were Europe's rivers like the Rhine and Danube so important?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They were good for skiing", "They acted as natural highways for boats, goods, and ideas", "They kept armies out", "They were full of gold", "They never froze"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Great rivers carried boats, trade, and ideas across many countries, connecting Europe's peoples.", "hint": "Think about how goods moved before roads and trains."}, {"q": "The Danube flows through or past more countries than any other river in the world.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The Danube touches ten countries, more than any other river on Earth."}, {"q": "What daring idea led to the creation of the European Union?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Building one giant army", "That nations who trade and share resources would no longer want to fight", "Making everyone speak one language", "Removing all mountains", "Crowning a single emperor"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Leaders hoped that sharing the resources nations once fought over would make war unthinkable.", "hint": "It is about trading instead of fighting."}, {"q": "Roughly how many nations are members of the European Union?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 5", "About 12", "About 27", "About 50", "About 100"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The European Union is a partnership of around 27 member nations.", "hint": "It is fewer than 30 but more than 20."}, {"q": "What is the shared currency used by many EU countries called?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The dollar", "The pound", "The euro", "The franc", "The mark"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Many EU members share a single currency called the euro.", "hint": "Its name sounds like the continent."}, {"q": "What does 'open borders' mean within much of the EU?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Borders are removed by mountains", "You can cross between countries without a passport check", "Only soldiers may cross", "Borders close at night", "Each border has a giant gate"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Open borders mean people can travel between many EU countries without stopping for passport checks.", "hint": "It makes train trips between countries simple."}, {"q": "The EU is a single united country with one government.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The EU is a partnership of separate nations that keep their own languages, traditions, and governments."}, {"q": "Why did the EU receive the Nobel Peace Prize in 2012?", "type": "mc", "options": ["For inventing the euro", "For helping turn a war-torn continent into a peaceful one", "For winning a war", "For building the tallest tower", "For exploring space"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The EU was honored for helping transform a continent once torn by war into a largely peaceful one.", "hint": "It is about peace, not money or science."}]});

  lesson({"id": "eu10", "continent": "europe", "n": 10, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🎻", "title": "Great Minds & Masterpieces: Europe's Science, Art & Music", "hook": "From the laws of gravity to the swirl of <b>The Starry Night</b>, a great many ideas that shaped the whole world were first dreamed up on this one small continent.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "For its modest size, Europe has produced a remarkable number of the ideas, paintings, and pieces of music that people everywhere still treasure. This is not because Europeans were smarter than anyone else — brilliant minds have lived on every continent — but because, for several centuries, conditions in Europe lined up to let curiosity flourish and spread: universities, printing presses, wealthy patrons, and busy trade routes carrying ideas from city to city."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In <b>science</b>, a long chain of European thinkers slowly transformed how all of humanity understands the universe. <b>Isaac Newton</b>, in England, explained with a single set of ideas why apples fall to the ground and why planets stay in orbit around the Sun, setting out his famous laws of gravity and motion that engineers still use today. Nearly two centuries later, another Englishman, <b>Charles Darwin</b>, proposed the theory of evolution, showing how living things gradually change and adapt over countless generations — an idea that reshaped how we understand every plant and animal on Earth, including ourselves. And <b>Marie Curie</b>, a Polish-born scientist working in France, discovered new chemical elements and pioneered the study of radioactivity, working with materials so dangerous they eventually harmed her health, and became the first person ever to win two Nobel Prizes."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Marie Curie remains the only person to win Nobel Prizes in <b>two different sciences</b> — physics and chemistry — a record unbroken for over a century."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In <b>art</b>, Europe gave the world painters whose works still draw millions of visitors to museums every year. <b>Leonardo da Vinci</b>, a towering genius of the Italian Renaissance, painted the famously mysterious <i>Mona Lisa</i>, with her faint, unreadable smile, and filled private notebooks with sketches of flying machines and inventions centuries ahead of his time. Much later, the Dutch painter <b>Vincent van Gogh</b> painted swirling, glowing, emotional scenes like <i>The Starry Night</i>, using thick, bold strokes of color unlike anything before him. He struggled with poverty and ill health and barely sold a single picture in his lifetime — yet today he is one of the most beloved and recognizable artists in all of history."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Van_Gogh_-_Starry_Night_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg", "caption": "Vincent van Gogh's The Starry Night, painted in 1889.", "credit": "Photo: Vincent van Gogh, Public domain"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Genius is rarely lonely. Newton said he saw far because he stood \"on the shoulders of giants.\" Almost every great mind borrowed, built on, and argued with the people who came before. When you admire a discovery, remember the long chain of curious people behind it."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In <b>music</b>, three German-speaking composers shaped the very sound of Western music for centuries to come. <b>Johann Sebastian Bach</b> wove many melodies together at once with such breathtaking mathematical precision that musicians still study his work to learn how harmony itself fits together. <b>Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart</b> was a dazzling child prodigy, performing for kings and composing music by the age of five, and he poured out hundreds of works of astonishing beauty before dying tragically young. And <b>Ludwig van Beethoven</b> bridged the old, orderly style and a powerful new emotional one — and most astonishing of all, he composed some of his greatest symphonies after he had gone completely <b>deaf</b>, hearing every note only in his own mind."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "Which European mind made this mark?", "prompt": "You read that someone discovered new elements and won two Nobel Prizes in different sciences. Who is it most likely to be?", "opts": [{"label": "Marie Curie", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Correct! Curie's work on radioactivity earned her Nobel Prizes in both physics and chemistry."}, {"label": "Wolfgang Mozart", "tag": "Watch out", "outcome": "Mozart was a brilliant composer, not a scientist — and Nobel Prizes did not exist in his lifetime."}, {"label": "Leonardo da Vinci", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "A reasonable guess, since da Vinci was a genius — but he was a Renaissance artist and inventor, not a discoverer of elements."}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "What truly made these achievements world-changing was that they did not stay put in Europe. The printing press let books and discoveries spread faster than ever before, while ships, universities, and later Europe's vast empires carried these ideas and artworks to every corner of the globe — for better and sometimes for worse. The result is that this knowledge now belongs to everyone. Today a student in Japan can study Newton's laws of motion, an orchestra in Brazil can fill a concert hall with Beethoven, scientists everywhere build on Curie's work, and visitors from every nation on Earth line up patiently inside the <b>Louvre</b> in Paris just to glimpse the small, smiling face of the <i>Mona Lisa</i>."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "The <b>Louvre</b> in Paris is the world's most-visited art museum, drawing millions of people every year to see masterpieces gathered over centuries."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> The ideas born in Europe — gravity, evolution, the symphony, the great museum — have become a shared inheritance for all of humanity, no longer European alone. They remind us that a single curious mind, building on those before it, can change how billions of people see the universe, hear beauty, or understand life itself. The next giant whose shoulders someone stands on could be anyone, anywhere — perhaps even you."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What did Isaac Newton famously explain?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The theory of evolution", "The laws of gravity and motion", "Radioactivity", "How to paint the Mona Lisa", "The structure of music"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Newton explained gravity and the laws of motion, describing why apples fall and planets orbit.", "hint": "Think of an apple falling from a tree."}, {"q": "Which scientist proposed the theory of evolution?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Isaac Newton", "Marie Curie", "Charles Darwin", "Ludwig van Beethoven", "Leonardo da Vinci"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Charles Darwin proposed evolution, explaining how living things change over many generations.", "hint": "His name is linked to natural selection."}, {"q": "Marie Curie was the first person to win two Nobel Prizes.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Curie won Nobel Prizes in both physics and chemistry — still the only person to win in two different sciences."}, {"q": "Who painted the mysterious Mona Lisa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Vincent van Gogh", "Leonardo da Vinci", "Wolfgang Mozart", "Charles Darwin", "Johann Sebastian Bach"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Leonardo da Vinci, a genius of the Italian Renaissance, painted the Mona Lisa.", "hint": "He was also a famous inventor."}, {"q": "Which painter created The Starry Night?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Leonardo da Vinci", "Marie Curie", "Vincent van Gogh", "Isaac Newton", "Wolfgang Mozart"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Vincent van Gogh painted the swirling, glowing The Starry Night in 1889.", "hint": "He was a Dutch painter who sold little in his lifetime."}, {"q": "Which composer kept creating great symphonies even after going deaf?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Johann Sebastian Bach", "Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart", "Ludwig van Beethoven", "Vincent van Gogh", "Isaac Newton"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Beethoven composed some of his greatest works after losing his hearing completely.", "hint": "He heard the music only in his mind."}, {"q": "Which composer was a famous child prodigy, composing at age five?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Charles Darwin", "Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart", "Marie Curie", "Leonardo da Vinci", "Isaac Newton"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Mozart was composing music by age five and produced hundreds of works before dying young.", "hint": "His full name includes 'Amadeus'."}, {"q": "According to the lesson, why did Europe produce so many famous ideas?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Europeans were smarter than everyone else", "Conditions like universities, printing, and trade let curiosity flourish and spread", "It had the most gold", "Other continents had no thinkers", "It was the largest continent"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The lesson stresses it was favorable conditions — not greater intelligence — that helped ideas flourish and spread.", "hint": "The lesson is careful to say it was NOT about being smarter."}, {"q": "What did Newton mean by standing 'on the shoulders of giants'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["He was very tall", "He built on the work of earlier thinkers", "He lived on a mountain", "He carried heavy weights", "He worked completely alone"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Newton meant that his discoveries built on the work of the curious people who came before him.", "hint": "Genius is rarely lonely."}, {"q": "Which famous Paris museum houses the Mona Lisa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The British Museum", "The Louvre", "The Prado", "The Hermitage", "The Vatican Museum"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Mona Lisa hangs in the Louvre in Paris, the world's most-visited art museum.", "hint": "It is the world's most-visited art museum."}]});

