  cont({
    id: "asia", name: "Asia", emoji: "🐉", color: "#c0392b",
    blurb: "China, India, Japan & more",
    intro: "The world's largest continent and home to its oldest civilizations, biggest populations, and many of history's greatest inventions.",
    badge: { name: "Asian Explorer", emoji: "🐉" },
    lessons: ["as1", "as2", "as3", "as4", "as5", "as6", "as7", "as8", "as9", "as10"],
    sectionQuiz: [
      { q: "Which of these was invented in ancient China?", type: "mc", options: ["The steam engine", "Paper", "The telescope", "The car"], answer: 1, explain: "China invented paper, printing, gunpowder, and the compass." },
      { q: "Gandhi led India's independence movement using…", type: "mc", options: ["A huge army", "Nonviolent resistance", "Pirate ships", "Castle sieges"], answer: 1, explain: "Gandhi's nonviolent resistance inspired movements worldwide." },
      { q: "Japan stayed exactly the same for all of history and never modernized.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 1, explain: "Japan rapidly modernized during the Meiji era (late 1800s)." },
      { q: "The Silk Road was…", type: "mc", options: ["A type of cloth", "Trade routes linking Asia, the Middle East, and Europe", "A Japanese castle", "A Chinese river"], answer: 1, explain: "It was a network of trade routes carrying goods and ideas across continents." },
      { q: "Colonialism in Asia means…", type: "mc", options: ["Asian countries colonizing Europe", "European powers controlling Asian lands", "A trade festival", "A religion"], answer: 1, explain: "European powers controlled large parts of Asia for resources and trade." },
      { q: "Which is the world's most populous region?", type: "mc", options: ["Asia", "Europe", "Africa", "Oceania"], answer: 0, explain: "Asia has more people than any other continent — over half the world." },
      { q: "After WWII, several Asian economies grew so fast they were nicknamed the…", type: "mc", options: ["Asian Tigers", "Asian Lions", "Asian Eagles", "Asian Bears"], answer: 0, explain: "South Korea, Taiwan, Singapore, and Hong Kong were the 'Asian Tigers.'" },
      { q: "India is home to several major world religions, including Hinduism and Buddhism.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Both Hinduism and Buddhism began in ancient India." },
      { q: "The Taj Mahal was built as a…", type: "mc", options: ["Fortress", "Tomb of love by a Mughal emperor", "Train station", "School"], answer: 1, explain: "Emperor Shah Jahan built it as a tomb for his beloved wife." },
      { q: "Why did the Silk Road matter beyond trade?", type: "mc", options: ["It only moved silk", "It spread ideas, religions, and technology between cultures", "It was never used", "It connected only two cities"], answer: 1, explain: "Ideas, faiths, and inventions traveled the Silk Road along with goods." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({"id": "as1", "continent": "asia", "n": 1, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🐉", "title": "Ancient China: Dynasties & Great Inventions", "hook": "<b>For thousands of years, China was a world of its own — building walls you can see from space and inventing things the whole planet still uses.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Imagine a country so old that its history is measured not in centuries but in <i>dynasties</i> — long families of rulers, each lasting hundreds of years. That country is China, one of the oldest continuous civilizations on Earth."}, {"t": "p", "html": "A <b>dynasty</b> is a line of rulers from the same family. When one family lost power, another took over and started a new dynasty. The Chinese had a famous idea about this called the <b>Mandate of Heaven</b>: rulers were allowed to rule only as long as they ruled well. Floods, famine, or defeat were taken as signs that heaven had withdrawn its blessing — and that it was time for a new family to take charge. The early dynasties, the <b>Shang</b> and the <b>Zhou</b>, gave China writing, bronze, and deep traditions. Shang priests scratched questions to the gods onto bones and turtle shells, then heated them until they cracked and read the answers in the cracks; those carved marks are the ancestors of Chinese writing. During the long Zhou dynasty, a wise teacher named <b>Confucius</b> taught that a good society depends on respect, honesty, and treating others well — ideas that shaped Chinese life for the next 2,000 years."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Then in 221 BC a ruler named <b>Qin Shi Huang</b> conquered the warring kingdoms and joined them into a single empire, calling himself the <i>First Emperor</i>. He was ruthless, but he was also an organizer. He standardized the money everyone used, the way words were written, and even the width of cart axles, so that wheels would fit the same ruts in roads all across the land. He linked older walls in the north into one long defensive barrier — the first version of the Great Wall. The word \"China\" itself may come from his dynasty's name, Qin."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Qin Shi Huang was buried with an army of more than <b>8,000 life-sized clay soldiers</b> — the Terracotta Army — each with a different face. It lay hidden underground for over 2,000 years until farmers digging a well found it in 1974."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Later came the <b>Han dynasty</b>, so important that most Chinese people today still call themselves the \"Han.\" The Han ruled for about 400 years — roughly as long as from Shakespeare's day to ours — and it was a golden age of peace, invention, and learning. Officials were chosen partly through tough written exams, so that clever people, not just wealthy ones, could help run the empire. Under the Han, a trade route called the <b>Silk Road</b> stretched thousands of miles westward across deserts and mountains, carrying Chinese silk, spices, and ideas all the way to Rome — while camels brought back glass, gold, and new foods in return. Few traders walked the whole route; goods passed from hand to hand across the world."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "greatwall", "file": "The Great Wall of China at Jinshanling-edit.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Jakub Hałun, CC BY-SA 4.0", "caption": "The Great Wall winding over mountains near Beijing."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The <b>Great Wall</b> was not built all at once. Different dynasties added to it over more than a thousand years to keep out raiders from the north. Stretched end to end, all its branches together run over <b>13,000 miles</b> — longer than the distance across the United States and back."}, {"t": "p", "html": "China gave the world four inventions so important they're often called the <b>Four Great Inventions</b>: <b>paper</b>, the <b>compass</b>, <b>gunpowder</b>, and <b>printing</b>. Before paper, people wrote on heavy bamboo strips or costly silk; a single long book could weigh as much as a child and needed a cart to move it. Cheap, light paper changed everything, because suddenly ideas could be written down and shared easily. Before the compass, sailors risked losing their way the moment land slipped out of sight; a sliver of magnetized iron that always pointed the same direction let ships travel far from shore with confidence. Printing meant a book could be copied hundreds of times without a tired hand writing out every word — spreading knowledge faster than ever before."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Gunpowder was discovered by accident by alchemists who were actually searching for a potion to make people <i>live forever</i>. Instead, they found something that went bang."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Chinese dynasties through time", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~1600 BC", "label": "Shang dynasty — early writing & bronze"}, {"yr": "~1046 BC", "label": "Zhou dynasty — Mandate of Heaven"}, {"yr": "221 BC", "label": "Qin — China united by First Emperor"}, {"yr": "206 BC", "label": "Han dynasty — Silk Road opens"}, {"yr": "1368 AD", "label": "Ming dynasty — Great Wall rebuilt"}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When something lasts a very long time, ask <i>why</i>. China's writing, its respect for scholars, and ideas like the Mandate of Heaven helped tie the country together across thousands of years — even when ruling families changed."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Every time you read a book, use a phone's compass, or send a message that started as ink on paper, you're using ideas first developed in ancient China. And the Great Wall still draws millions of visitors who walk where soldiers once stood watch."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What is a \"dynasty\"?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A type of wall", "A line of rulers from the same family", "A trade route", "A kind of money", "A Chinese festival"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A dynasty is a series of rulers who come from the same family.", "hint": "Think about families passing power down."}, {"q": "The Mandate of Heaven said a ruler could keep power only as long as they ruled well.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Disasters were seen as signs that heaven had withdrawn its blessing, justifying a new dynasty."}, {"q": "Who united many kingdoms and became China's First Emperor in 221 BC?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Han emperor", "Qin Shi Huang", "Confucius", "Genghis Khan", "Marco Polo"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Qin Shi Huang unified China and called himself the First Emperor.", "hint": "His name sounds like the dynasty he founded."}, {"q": "What famous thing was found buried near Qin Shi Huang's tomb?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A library of gold books", "An army of clay soldiers", "A fleet of ships", "A mountain of silk", "A hidden city of glass"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Terracotta Army of over 8,000 clay soldiers guarded his tomb.", "hint": "It was made of baked earth."}, {"q": "The Silk Road was mainly a route for sailing across the ocean.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Silk Road was an overland trade route stretching west across Asia."}, {"q": "Which of these is NOT one of China's Four Great Inventions?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Paper", "The compass", "Gunpowder", "The telescope", "Printing"], "answer": 3, "explain": "The telescope was developed later in Europe; the four were paper, compass, gunpowder, and printing.", "hint": "Three help you write, find your way, or make a bang."}, {"q": "Why did the Chinese keep adding to the Great Wall over the centuries?", "type": "mc", "options": ["To mark farmland", "To keep out raiders from the north", "To hold back floods", "To store grain", "To race horses on top"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The wall was built and rebuilt to defend against northern invaders.", "hint": "Think about defense."}, {"q": "Gunpowder was discovered by people searching for what?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A faster horse", "A potion for eternal life", "A new color of silk", "A cure for hunger", "A way to fly"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Alchemists seeking an immortality potion stumbled onto gunpowder instead.", "hint": "They wanted to live forever."}, {"q": "Most people in China today identify with which dynasty's name?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Shang", "Qin", "Han", "Ming", "Zhou"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Han dynasty was so influential that most Chinese still call themselves Han.", "hint": "It opened the Silk Road."}, {"q": "China is one of the oldest continuous civilizations on Earth.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Its history of writing, culture, and dynasties stretches back thousands of years without a break."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as2", "continent": "asia", "n": 2, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🕌", "title": "India: Empires, Religion & Independence", "hook": "<b>India gave the world the number zero, the game of chess, and one of history's most famous peaceful revolutions.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "India is a land of astonishing variety — hundreds of languages, snow-capped mountains, steaming jungles, and a history that reaches back more than 4,000 years to one of the world's first great cities."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Along the Indus River, the <b>Indus Valley Civilization</b> built brick cities with straight streets, public wells, and covered drains long before most of the world had figured out plumbing. Their cities were so carefully planned that the bricks were all made to the same size, and homes had bathrooms with water that drained away — comforts that vanished from much of the world for thousands of years afterward. Curiously, we still cannot read their writing, so much about them remains a mystery. Later, powerful empires rose. The <b>Maurya Empire</b> united most of India under one ruler, and its greatest emperor, <b>Ashoka</b>, was a fierce conqueror — until a single terrible war changed him. After winning the bloody battle of Kalinga, where tens of thousands died, Ashoka was so sickened by the suffering he had caused that he gave up conquest entirely, embraced the gentle teachings of <b>Buddhism</b>, and had messages about kindness and honesty carved onto stone pillars across his empire. Some of those pillars still stand today."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "The numbers you use every day — 0, 1, 2, 3 — are often called \"Arabic numerals,\" but they were actually invented in <b>India</b>. Arab traders carried them to Europe, which is how they got the name."}, {"t": "p", "html": "India is also a birthplace of religions. <b>Hinduism</b>, one of the world's oldest faiths, grew here, along with <b>Buddhism</b> and <b>Jainism</b>. Later, <b>Islam</b> arrived through traders and rulers. India became home to people of many beliefs living side by side."}, {"t": "p", "html": "From the 1500s, the <b>Mughal Empire</b> ruled much of India. The Mughals were Muslim rulers, but India's population was mostly Hindu, and one of their wisest emperors, <b>Akbar</b>, became famous for trying to treat people of all faiths fairly. He removed unfair taxes on non-Muslims and invited scholars of many religions to debate in his court. The Mughals loved art, poetry, gardens laid out in perfect patterns, and grand buildings. Their most famous builder was Akbar's grandson <b>Shah Jahan</b>, who created a wonder of the world out of marble and grief."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "taj", "file": "Taj Mahal in March 2004.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Dhirad, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "The Taj Mahal, a tomb built out of love."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The <b>Taj Mahal</b> is a tomb of white marble that Shah Jahan built for his beloved wife, Mumtaz Mahal, after she died. It took around 20,000 workers more than 20 years to finish. Its dome and gardens are so perfectly balanced that it's considered one of the most beautiful buildings ever made."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In the 1700s and 1800s, Britain gradually took control of India — first through a powerful trading company, then directly as a colony of the British Empire. For nearly 200 years, this vast and ancient land was ruled from an island thousands of miles away. The British built railways and telegraph lines, but the wealth and the decisions mostly flowed back to Britain, and Indians had little say over their own country. Over time, more and more Indians began to ask a simple question: why should our home be governed by strangers from far away?"}, {"t": "p", "html": "A lawyer named <b>Mohandas Gandhi</b>, often called the <i>Mahatma</i> or \"great soul,\" led the fight for independence in an unusual way: <b>without violence</b>. He urged Indians to peacefully refuse to cooperate with unfair laws — to march, to boycott British cloth and spin their own, to resist openly, but never to strike back even when struck. In one famous protest, the <b>Salt March</b>, he walked 240 miles to the sea to make salt himself, defying a law that forced Indians to buy taxed British salt. Millions joined movements like it. After decades of patient struggle, in 1947 India finally became independent."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two ways to seek change", "a": {"title": "Gandhi's nonviolence", "items": ["Peaceful marches and protests", "Refusing to obey unjust laws", "Boycotting British goods", "Accepting punishment without fighting back"]}, "b": {"title": "Violent revolt", "items": ["Armed uprising", "Fighting soldiers directly", "Risk of huge loss of life", "Often answered with harsher force"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Gandhi believed that <i>how</i> you win matters as much as <i>whether</i> you win. Nonviolence aimed to change opponents' minds rather than simply defeat them — a strategy that later inspired leaders around the world."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> India is now the most populous country on Earth and the world's largest democracy. Gandhi's idea of peaceful protest shaped movements far beyond India, including the American civil rights movement led by Martin Luther King Jr."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Along which river did one of India's earliest great civilizations build brick cities?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Ganges", "The Indus", "The Nile", "The Amazon", "The Yangtze"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Indus Valley Civilization built advanced cities along the Indus River.", "hint": "The civilization is named after it."}, {"q": "The numbers 0, 1, 2, 3 were actually invented in India.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "They are called 'Arabic numerals' only because Arab traders carried them from India to Europe."}, {"q": "Why did Emperor Ashoka turn to peace and Buddhism?", "type": "mc", "options": ["He lost a war and was forced to", "He was sickened by the suffering of a war he won", "A foreign king ordered him to", "He wanted to build the Taj Mahal", "He was never a warrior at all"], "answer": 1, "explain": "After a bloody victory, Ashoka was horrified by the suffering and embraced peace.", "hint": "He won the war but was changed by it."}, {"q": "Who built the Taj Mahal, and for whom?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Ashoka, for his army", "Shah Jahan, for his late wife", "Gandhi, for his followers", "A British governor, for a queen", "Akbar, for his father"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Shah Jahan built it as a tomb for his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal.", "hint": "It was an act of love and mourning."}, {"q": "The Taj Mahal was built in just a few months.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It took roughly 20,000 workers more than 20 years to complete."}, {"q": "Which religion is NOT one that began in India?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Hinduism", "Buddhism", "Jainism", "Christianity", "All of these began in India"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Hinduism, Buddhism, and Jainism began in India; Christianity began in the Middle East.", "hint": "Three grew in India; one came from elsewhere."}, {"q": "How did Gandhi lead the fight for India's independence?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Through nonviolent resistance", "By raising a huge army", "By bribing British officials", "By moving to Britain", "By starting a navy"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Gandhi championed nonviolence — peaceful protest and refusing to cooperate with unjust laws.", "hint": "He refused to fight back."}, {"q": "In what year did India become independent?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1857", "1901", "1947", "1969", "1991"], "answer": 2, "explain": "India gained independence from Britain in 1947.", "hint": "Just after World War II."}, {"q": "The Mughal emperors were known for loving art, gardens, and grand buildings.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The Mughals were famous patrons of art and architecture, including the Taj Mahal."}, {"q": "Gandhi's methods later inspired which famous movement?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The space race", "The American civil rights movement", "The Industrial Revolution", "The Silk Road trade", "The building of the Great Wall"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Martin Luther King Jr. drew on Gandhi's nonviolent ideas in the U.S. civil rights movement.", "hint": "Think of a leader named King."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as3", "continent": "asia", "n": 3, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "⛩️", "title": "Japan: From Samurai to Modern Power", "hook": "<b>Japan spent centuries as a closed island of samurai and castles — then transformed itself into a modern nation faster than almost any country in history.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Japan is a chain of islands off the eastern coast of Asia, shaped by mountains, the surrounding sea, frequent earthquakes, and a deep love of tradition. Cut off from the mainland by water, it grew a culture all its own — and for much of its history, real power lay not with the emperor in his palace but with warriors who carried swords."}, {"t": "p", "html": "For hundreds of years, Japan was ruled by a <b>shogun</b> — a top military commander — while the emperor stayed in his palace as a respected but mostly ceremonial figure. It was a little like having a king who wore the crown while a general actually made the decisions. Beneath the shogun were powerful lords called <i>daimyo</i>, each with their own lands and castles. Serving these lords were the <b>samurai</b>, skilled warriors who followed a strict code of honor called <b>bushido</b>, meaning \"the way of the warrior.\" A samurai was expected to be brave, loyal, and disciplined, and to value honor more than his own life."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "A samurai's sword, the <b>katana</b>, was folded and hammered thousands of times during forging to make the steel both razor-sharp and tough enough not to snap. Samurai believed their very soul lived in the blade, and a fine sword could be treasured and passed down through a family for many generations."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Samurai didn't just fight — many were poets, calligraphers, and students of philosophy. A great warrior was admired for writing a beautiful poem as much as for winning a duel. Bushido valued loyalty, courage, and self-control as much as skill in battle, and these ideals shaped the way Japanese people thought about duty and honor for centuries. Even the famous tea ceremony, a slow and graceful ritual of preparing and serving tea, grew out of this culture of calm, focus, and respect."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "torii", "file": "080103 hakkai-san toumei-san and mount fuji.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Σ64, CC BY 3.0", "caption": "Mount Fuji, Japan's sacred snow-capped peak."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Towering over the landscape is <b>Mount Fuji</b>, a near-perfect volcanic cone that the Japanese have considered sacred for centuries. Standing more than 12,000 feet tall and capped with snow for much of the year, it can be seen from far away on a clear day, including from the city of Tokyo. Artists painted it again and again — one famous series of woodblock prints shows \"thirty-six views\" of the mountain — poets wrote about it, and pilgrims climbed its slopes as an act of devotion. Over time it became more than a mountain; it became a symbol of Japan itself, calm and enduring."}, {"t": "p", "html": "For more than 200 years, Japan chose to <b>close itself off</b> from the outside world, a policy known as <i>sakoku</i>, or \"closed country.\" Foreign ships were turned away, foreigners were mostly forbidden to enter, and Japanese people were not allowed to leave. Only a tiny trickle of trade was permitted through a single port. During this long, peaceful time, Japan developed its own art, theatre, and crafts in rich detail — but it also fell behind in the science and machinery that were transforming Europe and the rest of the world."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Then in 1853, American warships under <b>Commodore Perry</b> sailed into a Japanese harbor — huge black steamships belching smoke, unlike anything most Japanese had ever seen — and demanded that Japan open to trade. The shock was enormous. It was clear that Japan's swords and traditions could not match foreign cannons. Soon after, in the <b>Meiji Restoration</b> of 1868, power returned to the young emperor, and Japan made a bold choice: rather than be conquered, it would learn. In just a few decades it built railways, factories, modern schools, and a powerful navy, sending students abroad to study and inviting experts in. The samurai class faded away, but the nation that emerged was strong, modern, and proudly its own."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Japan's journey", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~1192", "label": "First shogun rules; samurai era begins"}, {"yr": "~1600s", "label": "Japan closes itself to the outside world"}, {"yr": "1853", "label": "Perry's ships demand Japan open up"}, {"yr": "1868", "label": "Meiji Restoration — rapid modernization"}, {"yr": "1900s", "label": "Japan becomes a modern industrial power"}]}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You advise the emperor in 1868", "prompt": "Foreign powers are far ahead in technology and weapons. What should Japan do?", "opts": [{"label": "Learn from the world and modernize quickly", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Japan adopts new technology while keeping its culture — and becomes a major power within decades."}, {"label": "Refuse all change and stay closed forever", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Other nations had already forced China to give up trade and land; staying weak could mean the same fate."}, {"label": "Copy other countries exactly and forget all tradition", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Japan instead blended the new with the old, keeping its identity while gaining modern strength."}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Japan's leaders showed that a society can change quickly <i>and</i> keep its identity. They borrowed technology without throwing away their culture — a balance many countries struggle to strike."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Today Japan is one of the world's leading nations in technology and design, from bullet trains to robots and video games. Yet temples, tea ceremonies, and respect for Mount Fuji still sit comfortably beside the neon and the skyscrapers."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Who held the real military power in old Japan while the emperor was mostly ceremonial?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The pope", "The merchants", "The farmers", "The shogun", "The samurai class as a whole"], "answer": 3, "explain": "The shogun was the top military ruler; the emperor remained a respected figurehead.", "hint": "It's a single commander, not the whole warrior class."}, {"q": "What was 'bushido'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A type of castle", "The samurai code of honor", "A Japanese coin", "A sacred mountain", "A kind of ship"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Bushido, 'the way of the warrior,' was the samurai's code of honor.", "hint": "It guided how warriors should live."}, {"q": "Samurai were only fighters and had no interest in art or learning.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Many samurai were also poets, calligraphers, and students of philosophy."}, {"q": "What is Mount Fuji?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A samurai sword", "An ancient emperor", "A sacred volcanic mountain", "A type of temple", "A Japanese city"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Mount Fuji is a sacred volcanic cone and a symbol of Japan.", "hint": "Artists and pilgrims have honored it for centuries."}, {"q": "For over 200 years, Japan deliberately closed itself off from the outside world.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Japan barred most foreigners and forbade its own people from leaving for over two centuries."}, {"q": "Who arrived in 1853 and pushed Japan to open to trade?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Genghis Khan", "Commodore Perry", "Marco Polo", "Shah Jahan", "Captain Cook"], "answer": 1, "explain": "American Commodore Perry's warships forced Japan to consider opening up.", "hint": "He was an American naval officer."}, {"q": "What happened in the Meiji Restoration of 1868?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Japan closed its borders", "Power returned to the emperor and Japan modernized rapidly", "The samurai conquered China", "The Great Wall was built", "Japan stopped all trade"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Power returned to the emperor and Japan swiftly modernized.", "hint": "It opened a new, modern era."}, {"q": "A samurai's katana sword was made quickly with little effort.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The katana was folded and hammered thousands of times — a long, careful process."}, {"q": "How long did Japan take to become a modern industrial power after the Meiji Restoration?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A few decades", "About a thousand years", "Just one year", "Five hundred years", "It never did"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Japan industrialized remarkably fast, within just a few decades.", "hint": "It was surprisingly quick."}, {"q": "What did Japan manage to keep even as it modernized?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Its old weapons only", "Its closed borders", "Its lack of railways", "Nothing at all", "Its culture and traditions"], "answer": 4, "explain": "Japan blended new technology with its traditional culture and identity.", "hint": "Temples and tea ceremonies survive today."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as4", "continent": "asia", "n": 4, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🕌", "title": "The Ottoman Empire & the Spread of Islam", "hook": "<b>An empire that bridged Europe, Asia, and Africa lasted 600 years — and helped a young religion grow into one followed by nearly two billion people.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "In the early 600s, a new religion called <b>Islam</b> began in the deserts of Arabia. Within a few centuries it had spread across three continents — and one empire would carry its influence further than almost any other."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Islam was founded by the Prophet <b>Muhammad</b> in the city of Mecca, in what is now Saudi Arabia. Muslims believe in one God — called <b>Allah</b>, the Arabic word for God — and follow a holy book called the <b>Quran</b>. They share many figures with Judaism and Christianity, honoring prophets such as Abraham, Moses, and Jesus. Muslims try to live by five core duties known as the Five Pillars, which include daily prayer, giving to the poor, and, if able, making a pilgrimage to Mecca at least once in a lifetime. The faith spread remarkably quickly through trade, teaching, and travel along well-worn routes, reaching from Spain in the west to India in the east within a single century."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "During Europe's Middle Ages, the Islamic world was a center of learning. Scholars preserved ancient Greek books, advanced <b>algebra</b> (an Arabic word!), and made discoveries in astronomy and medicine that the whole world later built upon."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Centuries later, a Turkish people founded the <b>Ottoman Empire</b>, named after an early leader called Osman. Starting from a small kingdom, it grew over generations until it ruled lands across southeastern Europe, the Middle East, and North Africa — a span of three continents. In 1453, after a long siege, the young Ottoman sultan <b>Mehmed II</b> captured the great walled city of <b>Constantinople</b>, today called Istanbul. Its mighty walls had protected it for a thousand years, but Ottoman cannons finally broke through, ending the long-lived Byzantine Empire and giving the Ottomans a magnificent new capital that sat right where Europe meets Asia."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Süleymaniye Mosque 2007 Dincdurmaz.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Dincdurmaz, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "The Süleymaniye Mosque rising over Istanbul."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Ottomans built magnificent <b>mosques</b> — places of worship crowned with great domes and slender towers called <b>minarets</b>. The Süleymaniye Mosque in Istanbul, designed by the master architect <b>Sinan</b>, still stands as a marvel of engineering and beauty."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The empire reached its height under <b>Suleiman the Magnificent</b> in the 1500s, who ruled for nearly 50 years. Europeans gave him the name \"the Magnificent\" for his power and splendor, but at home Turks called him \"the Lawgiver\" because he reorganized the empire's laws to be clearer and fairer. The Ottoman lands were home to many peoples and religions, and the empire ran a system in which Christians and Jews were often allowed to keep their own faiths, run their own community courts, and worship freely, in return for paying a special tax. It was not equality as we'd think of it today, but in an age of harsh religious conflict, it allowed very different communities to live side by side."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Ottoman cities buzzed with life. Istanbul's Grand Bazaar grew into one of the largest covered markets in the world, with thousands of shops selling spices, carpets, gold, and silk. The empire welcomed people of many backgrounds, and when Jewish families were expelled from Spain in 1492, many found a new home in Ottoman lands. Skilled cooks, builders, and craftworkers from across three continents mixed their traditions, shaping the food, music, and art of the region in ways you can still taste and hear today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Ottomans controlled key crossroads of trade between Europe and Asia, sitting astride the routes that carried silk and spices westward. This was so important — and the goods were taxed so heavily as they passed through — that it helped push European explorers to search for new sea routes to reach Asia directly. That hunger for a way around the Ottoman lands is one reason Columbus ended up sailing west across the Atlantic in 1492, stumbling instead upon the Americas."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two great empires meet", "a": {"title": "Byzantine Empire", "items": ["Christian", "Capital: Constantinople", "Lasted about 1,000 years", "Ended in 1453"]}, "b": {"title": "Ottoman Empire", "items": ["Muslim", "Made Constantinople its capital", "Lasted about 600 years", "Ended after World War I"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Empires often spread ideas as much as armies do. Trade routes, scholars, and shared laws carried language, science, and faith across thousands of miles — sometimes more powerfully than any conquest."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Islam is now the second-largest religion in the world, followed by nearly two billion people on every continent. Istanbul, once the Ottoman capital, is still one of the world's great cities — a place where Europe and Asia literally meet across a single strait."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Where and when did Islam begin?", "type": "mc", "options": ["In Europe in the 1400s", "In Arabia in the early 600s", "In India in 1000 BC", "In China in the 600s", "In Egypt in 200 AD"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Islam began in Arabia in the early 600s with the Prophet Muhammad.", "hint": "It started in the deserts of Arabia."}, {"q": "What is the holy book of Islam?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Torah", "The Quran", "The Bible", "The Vedas", "The Analects"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Muslims follow the Quran as their holy book.", "hint": "Its name starts with Q."}, {"q": "During Europe's Middle Ages, the Islamic world was an important center of learning.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Islamic scholars preserved ancient texts and advanced math, astronomy, and medicine."}, {"q": "The word 'algebra' comes from which language?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Latin", "Greek", "Arabic", "Chinese", "Hindi"], "answer": 2, "explain": "'Algebra' is an Arabic word, reflecting Islamic scholars' work in mathematics.", "hint": "Think about who advanced the math."}, {"q": "What great city did the Ottomans capture in 1453?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Constantinople", "Rome", "Cairo", "Baghdad", "Athens"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The Ottomans captured Constantinople (now Istanbul) in 1453.", "hint": "It is now called Istanbul."}, {"q": "Tall, slender towers on a mosque are called minarets.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Minarets are the slender towers that are a feature of mosques."}, {"q": "Why was Suleiman called 'the Lawgiver' by the Turks?", "type": "mc", "options": ["He built the Great Wall", "He invented gunpowder", "He sailed to America", "He created a respected system of fair laws", "He banned all trade"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Suleiman was admired for his organized, fair system of laws.", "hint": "The title is about rules, not battles."}, {"q": "Under the Ottomans, Christians and Jews were never allowed to keep their own religions.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "They were often allowed to keep their faiths, usually in exchange for paying a special tax."}, {"q": "How did Ottoman control of trade routes affect Europe?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It ended all European travel", "It pushed Europeans to seek new sea routes", "It had no effect at all", "It made Europe close its ports", "It stopped the printing press"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Ottoman control of land routes encouraged Europeans to search for sea routes to Asia.", "hint": "Think of why Columbus sailed west."}, {"q": "Islam is today one of the world's largest religions.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Islam is the second-largest religion, with nearly two billion followers worldwide."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as5", "continent": "asia", "n": 5, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🚢", "title": "Colonialism in Asia", "hook": "<b>For centuries, far-off European countries ruled much of Asia — sometimes through a single company more powerful than a nation.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Asia is home to ancient civilizations and great wealth. From the 1500s onward, European nations sailed across the world to trade with Asia — and gradually ended up controlling much of it. This is the story of <b>colonialism</b>."}, {"t": "p", "html": "A <b>colony</b> is a land ruled by a country far away. European powers — Britain, France, the Netherlands, Portugal, and others — wanted Asia's spices, silk, tea, cotton, and other goods, which sold for huge profits back home. In an age before refrigerators, spices like pepper and cloves were so valuable they were almost worth their weight in silver. At first the Europeans simply traded, setting up small ports and warehouses on the coast. But over time, by making deals, taking sides in local quarrels, and using their powerful ships and guns, they took control of land, ports, and eventually whole countries with millions of people."}, {"t": "p", "html": "One of the strangest rulers in all of history was not a king at all, but a <b>company</b>. The <b>British East India Company</b> began in 1600 as a group of London merchants who simply wanted to trade. But over the next two centuries it grew so powerful that it raised its own armies, minted its own coins, collected taxes, and governed much of India on behalf of Britain. Imagine a single business with the power of a government, making war and ruling over millions of people, all to earn money for its owners. Eventually it grew so large and caused so many problems that the British government stepped in and took over its territories directly."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "At its height, the British East India Company commanded an army <b>larger than Britain's own</b> — controlled not by a government, but by a board of businessmen seeking profit."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "ship", "file": "East Indiaman.jpg", "credit": "Photo: National Maritime Museum, Public Domain", "caption": "A trading ship of the East India Company era."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Colonial powers reached across nearly all of Asia. Britain ruled India, Burma, Malaya, and beyond. The Dutch controlled the thousands of islands of Indonesia. France held Vietnam, Cambodia, and Laos, which together it called French Indochina. Each colonial power built ports, railways, telegraph lines, and huge plantations growing tea, rubber, and spices. Some of these things were genuinely useful and still exist today. But they were built mainly to move valuable goods out of Asia, and the profits flowed back to Europe rather than to the farmers and workers who actually grew and made everything. Local people often had to work long hours for very little, on land their families had once owned."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Daily life under colonial rule varied, but it was rarely equal. The rulers and their officials usually lived comfortably in fine houses, while the people whose land it was did the hardest work for the least reward. Decisions about taxes, schools, and laws were made by foreigners, often without asking those who would have to live by them. Sometimes harsh policies and the loss of local control even worsened terrible famines, in which millions of people went hungry."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Colonialism is part of <b>hard history</b> — the kind we study carefully and honestly. It did bring some railways, schools, and new ideas, and many people on all sides lived ordinary lives, raised families, and did their best. But the system itself was built on taking control of other people's lands and labor, often unfairly and sometimes with great cruelty, and the people under colonial rule frequently had little say in their own futures. Studying it isn't about blaming individuals today; it's about understanding how power worked and why so many people longed to be free."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You lead a region under colonial rule", "prompt": "Foreign rulers control your country's trade and government. The people want change. What path do you choose?", "opts": [{"label": "Organize peaceful protests and demand self-rule", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Across Asia, peaceful and persistent movements eventually won independence for many nations."}, {"label": "Do nothing and accept it forever", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Without action, foreign control and unfair trade are likely to simply continue."}, {"label": "Launch an immediate armed revolt", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Some revolts happened, but they were often crushed by stronger forces; lasting change usually needed organized, broad movements too."}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "In the 1900s, especially after the two World Wars left European powers weakened, colonies across Asia fought for and won their freedom. India became independent in 1947. Indonesia, Vietnam, and many others followed. The map of Asia filled with new, self-governing nations."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you study colonialism, ask <i>who benefited</i> and <i>who decided</i>. Following the flow of money and power — rather than just the buildings left behind — reveals the real story."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> The borders, languages, and economies of many Asian nations today were shaped by their colonial past. Understanding that history helps us understand the world's present — and why independence is so deeply valued by the people who won it."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What is a 'colony'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A type of ship", "A land ruled by a country far away", "A trading spice", "A kind of railway", "A religious building"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A colony is a territory controlled by a distant ruling country.", "hint": "Think about who is in charge from afar."}, {"q": "Which goods did European powers want from Asia?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Spices, silk, and tea", "Snow and ice", "Sand and stone", "Nothing at all", "Only soldiers"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Asia's spices, silk, tea, and other goods were extremely valuable in Europe.", "hint": "These sold for big profits back home."}, {"q": "The British East India Company was actually a business, not a government.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "It began as a merchant company yet grew powerful enough to govern much of India."}, {"q": "How large was the British East India Company's army at its height?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Smaller than a single village", "Larger than Britain's own army", "Just ten soldiers", "Exactly the same as today's", "It had no army"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Remarkably, the Company's army grew larger than Britain's own national army.", "hint": "It was bigger than you'd expect."}, {"q": "Which European country controlled the islands of Indonesia?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Britain", "France", "The Netherlands", "Portugal", "Spain"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Dutch (the Netherlands) controlled the islands of Indonesia.", "hint": "They are also called the Dutch."}, {"q": "Under colonialism, most of the profits flowed back to the European ruling countries.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Goods and profits mostly flowed to Europe rather than to the people of the colonies."}, {"q": "France controlled which part of Asia?", "type": "mc", "options": ["India", "Vietnam and its neighbors", "China", "Japan", "Saudi Arabia"], "answer": 1, "explain": "France controlled Vietnam and neighboring lands in Southeast Asia.", "hint": "Think of Southeast Asia."}, {"q": "Colonialism brought only good things and harmed no one.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It built some infrastructure but was based on controlling others' land and labor, often unfairly and cruelly."}, {"q": "When did India become independent?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1776", "1857", "1947", "1989", "2001"], "answer": 2, "explain": "India gained independence in 1947, after which many other Asian nations followed.", "hint": "Just after World War II."}, {"q": "What weakened European powers and helped Asian colonies win freedom in the 1900s?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The building of the Great Wall", "The two World Wars", "The Silk Road", "The invention of paper", "The Meiji Restoration"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The two World Wars left European powers weakened, opening the way for independence movements.", "hint": "Two huge global conflicts."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as6", "continent": "asia", "n": 6, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "✊", "title": "Asia Wins Its Freedom", "hook": "<b>For centuries, much of Asia was ruled by faraway empires.</b> Then, in a single remarkable generation, hundreds of millions of people <i>became free</i>.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Imagine being told that the most important decisions about your village, your school, and even your salt were made by people who had never seen your country. For a long time, that was life across much of Asia under European empires. The story of the 20th century is how that changed."}, {"t": "p", "html": "By the early 1900s, Britain ruled India, the Netherlands ruled what is now Indonesia, France ruled Vietnam, Portugal held tiny coastal colonies, and other powers held pieces of the map. This kind of rule, where one country governs another from far away, is called <b>colonialism</b>. These rulers built railways, ports, and grand government buildings, and some of them lasted so long that people could not remember a time before them. But the empires also shipped wealth back home and made the biggest decisions themselves — what crops to grow, who could go to which school, even what could be sold. Slowly, more and more Asians began to ask a powerful question: <i>why shouldn't we govern ourselves?</i>"}, {"t": "p", "html": "In India, a lawyer named <b>Mohandas Gandhi</b> — later called the Mahatma, meaning 'great soul' — offered a surprising answer. Instead of fighting with weapons, he taught <b>satyagraha</b>: peaceful resistance. Refuse to cooperate with unjust laws, he said, hold marches and boycotts, accept being arrested calmly — but never hate the person enforcing the law. Hatred, he believed, only fed more violence. It was a slow and demanding kind of courage, because it meant staying gentle even when treated harshly. Yet millions of ordinary people — farmers, weavers, students, and shopkeepers — joined him, and the movement grew too large for any empire to ignore."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Did you know? In 1930 Gandhi led a 240-mile (385 km) walk to the sea — the <b>Salt March</b> — simply to make salt from seawater. British law said only the government could do that. By breaking one small rule, he turned a whole empire's attention to the unfairness of the whole system."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "star", "file": "Mahatma-Gandhi, studio, 1931.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Elliott & Fry, public domain", "caption": "Gandhi, who led India with peaceful resistance"}, {"t": "p", "html": "World War II shook the empires badly. The war drained their treasuries, destroyed their cities, and exhausted their armies, and afterward they simply could no longer hold on to distant lands. The years right after the war became a great wave of freedom. In <b>1945</b>, Indonesia declared independence. In <b>1947</b>, British India became free — though it was painfully split into two countries, <b>India and Pakistan</b>, and millions of families had to leave their homes and move, sometimes overnight. In <b>1948</b>, Burma (now Myanmar) and Ceylon (now Sri Lanka) followed. Country after country raised a new flag."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Freedom did not always come quietly. Vietnam fought a long and bloody war, first against France and then against the United States, before becoming fully independent in 1975. Some nations argued for years over what kind of country they would build, and a few new borders were drawn in ways that caused lasting tension. Each nation's path was different — some peaceful, some violent, some smooth and some heartbreaking — but across the continent the direction was the same. The age of empires was ending, and the age of independent Asian nations had begun."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Asia gains its freedom", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1945", "label": "Indonesia declares independence"}, {"yr": "1947", "label": "India and Pakistan become independent"}, {"yr": "1948", "label": "Burma and Ceylon become independent"}, {"yr": "1954", "label": "France withdraws from Vietnam"}, {"yr": "1957", "label": "Malaya gains independence"}]}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two roads to freedom", "a": {"title": "Peaceful resistance (India)", "items": ["Marches, boycotts, strikes", "Refusing unjust laws", "Trying not to hate opponents", "Won independence in 1947"]}, "b": {"title": "Armed struggle (Vietnam)", "items": ["Long guerrilla warfare", "Decades of fighting", "Huge loss of life", "Won full independence in 1975"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: When you read 'independence,' ask <i>three</i> questions — Who ruled before? How did the change happen, peacefully or by war? And what was it like the day after? The 'day after' is often the hardest and most interesting part."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Why it still matters: Gandhi's idea — that ordinary people, acting together without violence, can change powerful systems — inspired leaders around the world, including Martin Luther King Jr. in the United States. Today, more than half of all humans live in Asian countries that govern themselves, a change that mostly happened within living memory of some people's great-grandparents."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What did Gandhi mean by satyagraha?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Armed rebellion", "Peaceful resistance to unjust laws", "Paying higher taxes", "Voting in British elections", "Building railways"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Satyagraha meant refusing to cooperate with unjust laws while never hating the opponent.", "hint": "It was the opposite of fighting with weapons."}, {"q": "In what year did India become independent?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1930", "1939", "1945", "1947", "1957"], "answer": 3, "explain": "British India became independent in 1947, splitting into India and Pakistan.", "hint": "It came shortly after World War II ended."}, {"q": "What was the Salt March a protest against?", "type": "mc", "options": ["High food prices", "A law that only the government could make salt", "A new railway", "A school closure", "A tax on tea"], "answer": 1, "explain": "British law forbade Indians from making their own salt, so Gandhi walked to the sea to make some.", "hint": "It involved walking to the ocean."}, {"q": "When British India became independent, it split into which two countries?", "type": "mc", "options": ["India and Bangladesh", "India and Nepal", "India and Pakistan", "India and Sri Lanka", "India and Burma"], "answer": 2, "explain": "In 1947 it became India and Pakistan, and millions of people had to move.", "hint": "One name starts with 'P'."}, {"q": "Which event left Europe's empires exhausted and unable to hold their colonies?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Industrial Revolution", "World War II", "The Cold War", "The Salt March", "The fall of Rome"], "answer": 1, "explain": "After World War II the empires were broke and worn out, speeding up independence.", "hint": "It ended in 1945."}, {"q": "Which country won independence through a long armed struggle rather than peaceful marches?", "type": "mc", "options": ["India", "Vietnam", "Ceylon", "Malaya", "Burma"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Vietnam fought decades of war against France and then the United States.", "hint": "It is in Southeast Asia and fought for decades."}, {"q": "Gandhi's title 'Mahatma' means what?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Great soul", "Wise king", "Strong warrior", "Holy river", "First leader"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Mahatma means 'great soul.'", "hint": "It describes his spirit, not his power."}, {"q": "Indonesia declared its independence in 1945.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Indonesia declared independence in 1945, right at the end of World War II."}, {"q": "Gandhi's methods influenced Martin Luther King Jr. in the United States.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "King studied Gandhi's nonviolent resistance and used similar methods in the U.S. civil rights movement."}, {"q": "Every Asian country won independence peacefully and without any hardship.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Some paths were peaceful, but others involved war, and even India's freedom came with painful division."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as7", "continent": "asia", "n": 7, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🚩", "title": "China's Revolution & Transformation", "hook": "<b>In one lifetime, China went from a struggling, divided land to one of the most powerful economies on Earth.</b> It is one of the great <i>turnarounds</i> in human history.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "If you could fast-forward through 100 years of China, you would see farmland turn into glittering cities, bicycles turn into high-speed trains, and a country that was often poor become a place that builds skyscrapers faster than almost anywhere on Earth. How did that happen?"}, {"t": "p", "html": "For more than two thousand years China was ruled by emperors, in a long line of ruling families called dynasties. But in <b>1912</b> the last emperor — a small boy named Puyi, who was crowned when he was not even three years old — gave up the throne, and China became a republic. The decades that followed were some of the hardest in the country's history. Warlords with private armies carved up the land and fought one another. Japan invaded in the 1930s, bringing terrible destruction. And all the while a civil war simmered between two groups with very different visions for what China should become."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In <b>1949</b>, after years of fighting, the Communist Party, led by <b>Mao Zedong</b>, won that civil war and founded the People's Republic of China. Mao stood in Beijing and declared that the Chinese people had 'stood up.' He promised to lift up the poorest farmers, end foreign interference, and make China strong and united again after what many called a 'century of humiliation.' For a war-weary country, those promises carried enormous hope."}, {"t": "p", "html": "But hope and harm can live in the same chapter. Some of Mao's biggest plans caused great suffering. The <b>Great Leap Forward</b> (begun in 1958) tried to turn China into an industrial power almost overnight, pulling farmers off their fields to make steel in backyard furnaces. Crops went unharvested, and a terrible famine followed in which many millions died. Later campaigns shut schools and turned neighbors against one another. These were painful, frightening years, and China studies them carefully today. The lesson is a hard one: enormous change, even when it begins with good intentions, can be both hopeful and harmful at once."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Did you know? In 1980 the Chinese city of Shenzhen was a small fishing town of about 30,000 people. Today it is a high-tech megacity of over 17 million — one of the fastest urban transformations in all of human history."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "star", "file": "Pudong Shanghai November 2017 panorama.jpg", "credit": "Photo: King of Hearts, CC BY-SA", "caption": "Shanghai's Pudong skyline today"}, {"t": "p", "html": "The great turnaround came after 1978, when a practical leader named <b>Deng Xiaoping</b> took charge and opened China to foreign trade and private business. Farmers were allowed to sell extra crops, families could start their own small companies, and foreign firms were invited to build factories. Deng famously suggested it didn't matter whether a cat was black or white, as long as it caught mice — his way of saying: use whatever works, and stop arguing about labels. Factories sprang up along the coast by the thousands, and China became known as 'the world's workshop,' making everything from toys and shoes to phones and solar panels."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The results were staggering. Over just a few decades, <b>hundreds of millions</b> of people rose out of poverty — one of the largest and fastest reductions in poverty ever recorded anywhere. Sleepy towns swelled into vast cities, a huge new middle class appeared with money to spend, and China built the longest high-speed rail network on the planet, with sleek trains gliding between cities at over 300 kilometers per hour. Not every part of this boom was easy — pollution, crowded cities, and a gap between rich and poor all grew too — but the scale of the change was almost without parallel in human history."}, {"t": "order", "title": "China's modern journey", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1912", "label": "The last emperor abdicates; China becomes a republic"}, {"yr": "1949", "label": "The People's Republic of China is founded"}, {"yr": "1978", "label": "Deng Xiaoping begins economic reforms"}, {"yr": "2001", "label": "China joins the World Trade Organization"}, {"yr": "2008", "label": "Beijing hosts the Summer Olympics"}]}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You lead a country that is very poor", "prompt": "Most people are farmers and there is little industry. What do you try?", "opts": [{"label": "Open up to foreign trade and let people start businesses", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "This is roughly what China did after 1978 — growth was fast, though it brought new challenges like pollution and inequality."}, {"label": "Force everyone to industrialize instantly with strict targets", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "The Great Leap Forward tried this and caused a tragic famine. Rushing huge change can backfire badly."}, {"label": "Invest patiently in schools, roads, and steady trade", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Slower but sturdier. Many successful economies grew this way, building foundations before booming."}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: A country's story is rarely all triumph or all tragedy. Good thinkers hold two ideas at once — China's rise lifted hundreds of millions out of poverty, <i>and</i> some chapters caused real suffering. Both are true."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Why it still matters: China is now the world's second-largest economy and a major force in technology, manufacturing, and trade. The phone or toy in your hand may well have been made there. Understanding China's transformation helps explain the world you are growing up in."}], "quiz": [{"q": "In what year did China's last emperor give up the throne?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1899", "1912", "1949", "1978", "2001"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The last emperor abdicated in 1912 and China became a republic.", "hint": "It was early in the 20th century."}, {"q": "Who founded the People's Republic of China in 1949?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Deng Xiaoping", "Puyi", "Mao Zedong", "Sun Yat-sen", "Chiang Kai-shek"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Mao Zedong's Communist Party won the civil war and founded the People's Republic in 1949.", "hint": "His surname is Mao."}, {"q": "Which leader opened China to trade and private business after 1978?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Mao Zedong", "Deng Xiaoping", "Puyi", "Sun Yat-sen", "Confucius"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Deng Xiaoping launched the reforms that made China 'the world's workshop.'", "hint": "He talked about a cat catching mice."}, {"q": "What did the Great Leap Forward tragically cause?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A great famine", "A new dynasty", "An Olympic Games", "A space program", "A peace treaty"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The rushed industrialization led to a terrible famine.", "hint": "It was about food shortages."}, {"q": "What nickname did China earn as it produced goods for the whole world?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The world's library", "The world's workshop", "The world's garden", "The world's bank", "The world's stage"], "answer": 1, "explain": "China became known as 'the world's workshop' for its huge manufacturing.", "hint": "It is where things are built."}, {"q": "The city of Shenzhen grew from a small town into a megacity of millions.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Shenzhen went from about 30,000 people in 1980 to over 17 million today."}, {"q": "China's reforms lifted hundreds of millions of people out of poverty.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "It was one of the largest reductions in poverty ever recorded."}, {"q": "Deng Xiaoping's famous saying was about which animal?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A cat", "A dragon", "A tiger", "An ox", "A horse"], "answer": 0, "explain": "He said it didn't matter if a cat was black or white as long as it caught mice — meaning use whatever works.", "hint": "It catches mice."}, {"q": "China today has the world's longest high-speed rail network.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "China built the planet's longest high-speed rail network during its transformation."}, {"q": "China is currently the world's second-largest economy.", "type": "mc", "options": ["First-largest", "Second-largest", "Tenth-largest", "Smallest", "It has no economy"], "answer": 1, "explain": "China is the world's second-largest economy and a major force in trade and technology.", "hint": "It ranks just behind one other country."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as8", "continent": "asia", "n": 8, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏙️", "title": "Modern Asia: Tigers & Rising Powers", "hook": "<b>How did countries with almost no natural riches become some of the wealthiest on Earth?</b> Their secret weapons were <i>schools, ports, and hard work</i>.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Picture a tiny island with no oil, no farmland to speak of, and not even enough fresh water. In 1965 it was poor and unsure of its future. Today that island — Singapore — is one of the richest places in the world. How is that possible?"}, {"t": "p", "html": "In the decades after World War II, several Asian economies grew so fast and so steadily that people gave them a fierce nickname: the <b>Four Asian Tigers</b>. They were <b>South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Singapore</b>. None of them had much in the way of natural resources — no great oil fields, no endless farmland, no mountains full of gold. By the old rules, places like these were supposed to stay poor. Instead, they bet on something different: educating their people and selling clever, well-made products to the entire world. The bet paid off spectacularly."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The recipe was strikingly similar in each place. First, invest heavily in <b>schools</b>, so that ordinary workers become skilled and capable. Second, build <b>ports, roads, and factories</b>, then export goods to foreign customers — starting with simple things like clothes and toys, then climbing the ladder to complex, valuable ones like ships, televisions, cars, and tiny microchips. Third, never stop improving; this year's product should be better than last year's. Do this patiently, and within a single generation a family could go from a poor village to a comfortable city apartment. Children grew up in a completely different world from their grandparents."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Did you know? South Korea was poorer than many African countries in the 1950s. Today it is the home of Samsung and Hyundai, makes many of the world's most advanced computer chips, and its pop music and films are loved worldwide."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "1 singapore city skyline dusk panorama 2011.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Chensiyuan, CC BY-SA", "caption": "Singapore's skyline at dusk"}, {"t": "p", "html": "<b>Japan</b> showed the way first. Its cities had been devastated in World War II, yet within a few decades Japan rebuilt with astonishing speed and discipline, becoming famous around the globe for reliable cars and beautifully engineered electronics. Names like Toyota, Sony, and Honda became household words on every continent. By the 1980s Japan was the world's second-largest economy. Its recovery proved something hopeful and important: a country could rise from ruin to riches through industry, careful craftsmanship, and education, even with almost no natural resources of its own."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Now a new set of giants is rising. <b>India</b>, with well over a billion people, has become a world center for software and technology — many of the engineers behind the apps and websites you use every day were trained in Indian universities. Across Southeast Asia, fast-growing countries like Vietnam and Indonesia are building their own factories and attracting businesses from around the world. Even China, which we met in an earlier lesson, followed a version of this same path. Taken together, these economies mean Asia is no longer simply 'catching up' to the rest of the world. In many fields — from smartphones to shipbuilding to film — it now leads."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two paths to wealth", "a": {"title": "Resource-rich countries", "items": ["Sell oil, gas, or minerals", "Wealth from the ground", "Can struggle if prices fall"]}, "b": {"title": "The Asian Tigers", "items": ["Few natural resources", "Sell skills and products", "Invest in schools and ports", "Built lasting industries"]}}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "Your nation is small with no oil", "prompt": "You want your people to prosper. Where do you put your money first?", "opts": [{"label": "Build great schools and universities", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "This was the Tigers' core bet. Skilled people can make valuable things for decades, far longer than any one resource lasts."}, {"label": "Borrow heavily to look rich quickly", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Debt without real industry behind it can lead to a crash. Looking wealthy isn't the same as being productive."}, {"label": "Build ports and invite factories to export goods", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "A proven Tiger strategy. Trade connects a small country to the whole world's customers."}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: When a country gets rich, ask <i>what is it selling?</i> Selling things dug from the ground is one path; selling skills, ideas, and manufactured goods is another. The second kind tends to last longer because it doesn't run out."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Why it still matters: Many of the gadgets, cars, and films in your life come from these rising Asian economies. And their story carries a hopeful message: with education and effort, even a place with no natural riches can build a bright future within a single lifetime."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Which four economies were called the 'Four Asian Tigers'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["China, Japan, India, Russia", "South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, Singapore", "Vietnam, Thailand, Laos, Cambodia", "India, Pakistan, Nepal, Bhutan", "Indonesia, Malaysia, Brunei, Philippines"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Four Tigers were South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Singapore.", "hint": "One is a tiny island city-state, one is a former British port."}, {"q": "What did the Asian Tigers rely on, since they lacked natural resources?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Oil reserves", "Education and exporting products", "Large farmlands", "Gold mines", "Diamond deposits"], "answer": 1, "explain": "They invested in schools and sold clever products to the world.", "hint": "It starts in classrooms and ends in ports."}, {"q": "Which country rebuilt after World War II to become the world's second-largest economy by the 1980s?", "type": "mc", "options": ["China", "India", "Japan", "Singapore", "Vietnam"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Japan rose from wartime ruin to economic powerhouse, famous for cars and electronics.", "hint": "It is known for reliable cars and electronics."}, {"q": "South Korea is now home to which famous companies?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Toyota and Sony", "Samsung and Hyundai", "Apple and Google", "Tata and Infosys", "Nokia and Volvo"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Samsung and Hyundai are South Korean, and the country makes advanced computer chips.", "hint": "One makes phones, one makes cars."}, {"q": "Which country has become a world center for software and technology with over a billion people?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Japan", "India", "Taiwan", "Singapore", "South Korea"], "answer": 1, "explain": "India became a global hub for software and trained many of the world's engineers.", "hint": "It is the most populous democracy."}, {"q": "South Korea was wealthier than most of the world in the 1950s.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It was actually quite poor in the 1950s, poorer than many countries, before its rapid rise."}, {"q": "Singapore had abundant oil and farmland, which made it rich.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Singapore had almost no natural resources; it grew rich through trade, ports, and education."}, {"q": "Selling skills and manufactured goods tends to last longer than selling a single natural resource.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Resources can run out or drop in price, while skills and industries can keep producing value."}, {"q": "A key shared strategy of the Tigers was building ports and exporting goods.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Ports and exports connected these economies to customers around the world."}, {"q": "Which is a fair lesson from the Asian Tigers' success?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Only countries with oil can get rich", "Education and effort can build wealth even without resources", "Big size is the only thing that matters", "Geography decides everything", "Trade is unimportant"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Their story shows that schooling and hard work can create prosperity without natural riches.", "hint": "Think about what the Tigers all chose to invest in."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as9", "continent": "asia", "n": 9, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏔️", "title": "The Roof of the World: Asia's Geography & Monsoons", "hook": "<b>Asia holds the tallest mountains, the mightiest rivers, and more people than any other continent.</b> To understand why, look <i>up</i> — and then follow the water down.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Stand in northern India and look north, and you'll see a wall of white peaks so high that airplanes fly beside them. This is the Himalaya, the 'roof of the world.' Almost everything about how Asia lives — where its people farm, drink, and gather — begins with these mountains."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The <b>Himalayas</b> were born from one of the slowest, mightiest collisions on Earth. Tens of millions of years ago, the great slab of land carrying India began drifting north and crashed — extremely slowly — into the rest of Asia. With nowhere to go, the ground between them crumpled upward, like a rug shoved against a wall, folding into ridge after ridge of soaring rock. The two slabs are still pressing together today, so the mountains keep rising a little every year. Here stands <b>Mount Everest</b>, at about 8,849 meters (29,032 feet) the highest point on the entire planet, its summit so high that climbers must carry bottled oxygen to breathe."}, {"t": "p", "html": "From these mountains and the high <b>Tibetan Plateau</b> behind them pour many of Asia's greatest <b>rivers</b>. Melting snow and slow-moving glaciers release water that feeds the sacred <b>Ganges</b> as it flows across northern India, the <b>Yangtze</b> sweeping across China (the longest river in all of Asia), the <b>Indus</b> in Pakistan, and the <b>Mekong</b>, which winds for thousands of kilometers through six countries in Southeast Asia. Wherever these rivers flow, farms and cities follow close behind — because a river means three precious things at once: water to drink, water to grow food, and a natural road for boats to carry people and goods."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Did you know? The rivers born in the Himalayas and nearby Tibetan Plateau supply water to roughly <b>two billion</b> people. That's why the region is sometimes called the 'water tower of Asia.'"}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Everest North Face toward Base Camp Tibet Luca Galuzzi 2006.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Luca Galuzzi, CC BY-SA", "caption": "Mount Everest, the planet's highest peak"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Now meet the force that rules the calendar across much of Asia: the <b>monsoon</b>. It works like a giant breath the continent takes once a year. In summer, the vast land of Asia heats up faster than the surrounding ocean. The hot air over the land rises, and cooler, moisture-soaked winds rush in from the sea to take its place — and as that wet air climbs over the land and mountains, it dumps heavy, drenching rains for months on end. Then in winter the whole pattern reverses: the land cools, the winds blow the other way, from land out to sea, and the weather turns dry and clear. Billions of farmers across India and Southeast Asia plant, water, and harvest their crops by the steady rhythm of these rains. A monsoon that comes late or weak can mean a hungry year."}, {"t": "p", "html": "But Asia isn't all green and wet. To the north and west lie vast, dramatic <b>deserts</b>. The <b>Gobi</b>, sprawling across Mongolia and northern China, is a cold desert — a place that bakes under the summer sun yet freezes hard in winter, very different from the hot sandy deserts you might first imagine. Deserts often form where tall mountains block the rain-carrying winds, leaving the land behind them in a dry 'rain shadow.' Add it all up and a single continent ends up holding steamy tropical jungles, frozen mountain peaks, windswept grasslands, and bone-dry sands, sometimes only a few hundred kilometers apart. Few places on Earth are so varied."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Summer monsoon vs winter monsoon", "a": {"title": "Summer monsoon", "items": ["Land heats up", "Winds blow from sea to land", "Heavy rains for months", "Crops are planted"]}, "b": {"title": "Winter monsoon", "items": ["Land cools down", "Winds blow from land to sea", "Dry, clearer weather", "Harvest and rest"]}}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You farm rice in monsoon Asia", "prompt": "The rains are due any week now. What do you do?", "opts": [{"label": "Prepare the fields and plant just before the rains arrive", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Perfect timing. The monsoon will water your young rice. Generations of farmers have read the skies this way."}, {"label": "Plant in the dry season and hope for the best", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Without the rains, young plants can wither. In monsoon lands, timing is everything."}, {"label": "Build channels to store some rain for the dry months", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Smart and ancient. Irrigation lets farmers stretch the monsoon's gift across the year."}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: When you wonder why so many people live in a place, follow the <i>water</i>. Rivers and reliable rains let lots of people grow lots of food in a small area — and where there's food, there are people. Asia's geography is a food-making machine."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Why it still matters: More than half of all humans live in Asia, largely thanks to these rivers and rains. But a warming planet is changing the monsoon and melting Himalayan glaciers faster. Understanding this geography helps us understand the future of billions of people — and the planet."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What is the highest mountain on Earth?", "type": "mc", "options": ["K2", "Mount Fuji", "Mount Everest", "Kilimanjaro", "Mont Blanc"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Mount Everest, about 8,849 meters tall, is in the Himalayas.", "hint": "It's in the Himalayas."}, {"q": "How were the Himalayas formed?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A giant volcano", "Two landmasses colliding and crumpling upward", "A meteor impact", "Wind piling up sand", "A river carving rock"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Indian landmass slowly crashed into Asia, pushing the ground up like a crumpled rug.", "hint": "Think of two pieces of crust pushing together."}, {"q": "Which is the longest river in Asia?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Ganges", "The Mekong", "The Yangtze", "The Indus", "The Amur"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Yangtze, flowing across China, is Asia's longest river.", "hint": "It flows across China."}, {"q": "What causes the summer monsoon rains?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The land heats up and pulls moist sea winds inland", "The ocean freezes", "Volcanoes erupt", "The moon's gravity", "Melting deserts"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Hot air rises over the heated land and draws in wet winds from the sea, bringing rain.", "hint": "It has to do with land heating faster than the sea."}, {"q": "The Gobi Desert is best described as what kind of desert?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A hot, sandy desert", "A cold desert with freezing winters", "An underwater desert", "A jungle", "A frozen ocean"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Gobi is a cold desert where summers bake but winters freeze.", "hint": "It's in Mongolia and northern China."}, {"q": "Why do so many people live in Asia?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It has the most gold", "Rivers and reliable monsoon rains allow huge amounts of food to be grown", "It has the fewest mountains", "It has no deserts", "It is the smallest continent"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Plentiful water from rivers and rains lets many people grow food in a small area.", "hint": "Follow the water and the food."}, {"q": "The Himalayas are still slowly rising each year.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The collision that built them continues, so they rise a little every year."}, {"q": "The winter monsoon is usually wetter than the summer monsoon.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It's the reverse: the summer monsoon brings the heavy rains, while winter is dry."}, {"q": "More than half of all humans live on the continent of Asia.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Asia is home to more than half the world's people, thanks largely to its rivers and rains."}, {"q": "The Mekong River passes through several Southeast Asian countries.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The Mekong winds through six countries in Southeast Asia."}]});

  lesson({"id": "as10", "continent": "asia", "n": 10, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🐫", "title": "The Silk Road: A Highway of Goods & Ideas", "hook": "<b>Long before the internet, a network of dusty roads carried treasures and ideas across the whole of Asia.</b> It moved <i>silk, paper, and even religions</i> between worlds.", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Imagine an information superhighway made not of cables but of camels, deserts, and mountain passes — stretching over 6,000 kilometers from China all the way to the Mediterranean. For more than a thousand years, this was how the East and West learned about each other."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The <b>Silk Road</b> wasn't a single paved road at all — that name was actually invented much later by a European scholar. It was really a sprawling web of overland routes, with sea routes too, threading across China, Central Asia, India, Persia (today's Iran), and on to Europe and the Mediterranean. Very few traders ever traveled the whole enormous distance themselves. Instead, goods passed hand to hand, merchant to merchant, town to town, like a relay race stretching across half the world. A bolt of cloth might change owners a dozen times before it reached its final buyer, with each trader taking a small profit along the way."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The network got its name from <b>silk</b>, the smooth, shimmering, featherlight cloth that, for a very long time, only China knew how to make. The Chinese guarded the secret of the silkworm — a caterpillar that spins the fine thread — so carefully that smuggling silkworm eggs out of the country could be punished by death. People in faraway Rome paid small fortunes for silk robes without having any idea where the cloth came from or how it was made; some even believed it grew on trees. But silk, precious as it was, turned out to be only the beginning of what these roads would carry."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Did you know? <b>Paper</b> was invented in China and traveled west along the Silk Road. It took centuries, but eventually paper reached Europe — and changed everything, making books and learning far cheaper than before."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Registan square, Samarkand.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Ekrem Canli, CC BY-SA", "caption": "The Registan in Samarkand, a Silk Road jewel"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Crossing the deserts was dangerous and slow, so the routes were dotted with <b>oasis cities</b> — green havens fed by springs or rivers, where exhausted caravans of camels could finally rest, water their animals, trade their wares, and swap news from distant lands. <b>Samarkand</b>, in what is now Uzbekistan, became one of the most dazzlingly rich and beautiful of all, its markets piled high with goods and its squares ringed by tiled buildings that glowed turquoise and gold. These oasis cities worked rather like ancient airports: bustling crossroads where languages, coins, recipes, songs, and faces from a dozen different lands all mixed together in one place."}, {"t": "p", "html": "And here is the deepest magic of the Silk Road: it carried <b>ideas</b>, not just goods. The religion of <b>Buddhism</b>, born in India, spread along these very routes into Central Asia, China, Korea, and Japan, carried by monks and merchants until it reshaped the beliefs of hundreds of millions of people. Skills traveled too — how to make glass, how to weave fine carpets, how to play new instruments and cook new dishes. Later, the explosive Chinese invention of <b>gunpowder</b> made its way westward and would eventually change warfare across the world. This is the great lesson of the Silk Road: whenever people trade things, they end up trading thoughts as well — and trading thoughts changes the world far more than trading goods ever could."}, {"t": "order", "title": "What traveled the Silk Road", "sub": "Drag these into order, from China westward to Europe by origin.", "items": [{"yr": "China", "label": "Silk and paper"}, {"yr": "India", "label": "Buddhism and spices"}, {"yr": "Persia", "label": "Carpets and glass"}, {"yr": "Arabia", "label": "Incense and traders' maps"}, {"yr": "Europe", "label": "Gold, wool, and silver"}]}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Goods vs ideas on the Silk Road", "a": {"title": "Goods that traveled", "items": ["Silk and paper", "Spices and tea", "Glass and carpets", "Gunpowder"]}, "b": {"title": "Ideas that traveled", "items": ["Buddhism and other faiths", "Ways of making paper", "New foods and recipes", "Music, art, and stories"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: Trade is never <i>only</i> about stuff. Whenever goods move between peoples, ideas, words, foods, and beliefs sneak along for the ride. Watching what a society buys and sells tells you who it's talking to."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Why it still matters: The Silk Road was an early version of <b>globalization</b> — the way distant places connect and shape each other. Today ships, planes, and the internet do what camels once did. The noodles, numbers, and inventions in your life often traveled their own 'silk roads' to reach you."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What was the Silk Road?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A single paved highway", "A network of trade routes linking Asia and Europe", "A river in China", "A famous mountain range", "A type of ship"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It was a web of overland and sea routes connecting China, Central Asia, India, Persia, and Europe.", "hint": "It was many routes, not one road."}, {"q": "Which prized cloth gave the Silk Road its name?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Cotton", "Wool", "Silk", "Linen", "Velvet"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Silk, which only China knew how to make, gave the route its name.", "hint": "It's in the name."}, {"q": "Which important invention traveled west from China and made books cheaper?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The wheel", "Paper", "The clock", "Glass", "The compass"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Paper was invented in China and eventually reached Europe, transforming learning.", "hint": "You write on it."}, {"q": "Which religion spread from India into China along the Silk Road?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Buddhism", "Christianity", "Judaism", "Shinto", "Hinduism"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Buddhism traveled from India into China and beyond along these routes.", "hint": "It began in India."}, {"q": "What were the green resting places between deserts called?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Harbors", "Oasis cities", "Castles", "Glaciers", "Forts"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Oasis cities like Samarkand had water and became rich trading crossroads.", "hint": "They had precious water."}, {"q": "Which Central Asian city became famous and wealthy as a Silk Road hub?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Tokyo", "Samarkand", "Mumbai", "Shanghai", "Hong Kong"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Samarkand grew dazzlingly rich and beautiful from Silk Road trade.", "hint": "Its Registan square is pictured in the lesson."}, {"q": "Most traders traveled the entire length of the Silk Road themselves.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Goods usually passed hand to hand, town to town, like a relay, rather than one trader going the whole way."}, {"q": "The Silk Road carried ideas as well as goods.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Religions, inventions, foods, and music all traveled along with the merchandise."}, {"q": "China kept the method of making silk a closely guarded secret for a long time.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "For centuries China guarded the secret of silkworms, so others had to buy silk without knowing how it was made."}, {"q": "The Silk Road can be seen as an early form of what modern idea?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Globalization", "Democracy", "Industrialization", "Photography", "Space travel"], "answer": 0, "explain": "It connected distant places and let them shape each other, much like today's globalization.", "hint": "It's about distant places connecting and trading."}]});

  /* ============================================================
     AFRICA
     ============================================================ */
  cont({
    id: "africa", name: "Africa", emoji: "🦁", color: "#d68910",
    blurb: "Kingdoms, trade & rebirth",
    intro: "The birthplace of humanity, home to mighty kingdoms and golden trade routes — and a continent that won back its freedom and is now young, fast-growing, and full of energy.",
    badge: { name: "Africa Pathfinder", emoji: "🦁" },
    lessons: ["af1", "af2", "af3", "af4", "af5", "af6", "af7", "af8", "af9", "af10"],
    sectionQuiz: [
      { q: "Africa is often called the birthplace of…", type: "mc", options: ["The car", "Humanity", "The printing press", "Democracy"], answer: 1, explain: "The earliest humans lived in Africa — it's where our species began." },
      { q: "The kingdom of Mali was famous for its huge wealth in…", type: "mc", options: ["Ice", "Gold and salt", "Oil", "Silk"], answer: 1, explain: "Mali grew rich from the gold and salt trade across the Sahara." },
      { q: "The Atlantic slave trade forcibly took millions of Africans across the ocean.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Over 12 million Africans were enslaved and shipped to the Americas — a great tragedy." },
      { q: "During the “Scramble for Africa,” European powers…", type: "mc", options: ["Left Africa alone", "Divided up almost the whole continent among themselves", "Asked Africans to rule Europe", "Built the pyramids"], answer: 1, explain: "By 1914, Europeans controlled almost all of Africa." },
      { q: "Most African nations became independent…", type: "mc", options: ["In ancient times", "Around the 1950s–60s", "Never", "In the year 2020"], answer: 1, explain: "A wave of independence swept Africa in the mid-1900s." },
      { q: "Timbuktu was famous as a center of…", type: "mc", options: ["War", "Trade and learning, with great libraries", "Ice fishing", "Car making"], answer: 1, explain: "Timbuktu was a renowned center of trade, books, and scholarship." },
      { q: "Nelson Mandela is celebrated for…", type: "mc", options: ["Inventing the telephone", "Helping end apartheid and uniting South Africa", "Building the Great Wall", "Discovering gold"], answer: 1, explain: "Mandela helped end racial segregation (apartheid) and became South Africa's first Black president." },
      { q: "Africa today has the world's youngest and fastest-growing population.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Africa is young and rapidly growing — full of future potential." },
      { q: "Ancient Egypt, in northern Africa, is famous for building…", type: "mc", options: ["Skyscrapers", "The pyramids", "Railways", "The Colosseum"], answer: 1, explain: "Egypt built the pyramids over 4,000 years ago." },
      { q: "Why does understanding colonialism help explain modern Africa?", type: "mc", options: ["It doesn't", "Colonial borders and choices still shape today's countries", "Africa was never colonized", "It only affected Europe"], answer: 1, explain: "Borders drawn by colonizers still influence African nations today." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({"id": "af1", "continent": "africa", "n": 1, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏺", "title": "Ancient Africa: Mighty Kingdoms & Golden Trade", "hook": "<b>Imagine a king so rich that when he traveled across the desert, he gave away so much gold that prices changed for years afterward.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Long before many famous cities existed, Africa was home to some of the wealthiest and most learned kingdoms on Earth. Across grasslands, deserts, and great rivers, traders, scholars, and builders created empires whose names still shimmer with gold."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In West Africa, three great empires rose one after another, each larger than the last: <b>Ghana</b>, then <b>Mali</b>, then <b>Songhai</b>. (The old empire of Ghana was not in the same place as the modern country named Ghana — it borrowed the proud name later.) Each grew powerful by controlling trade across the Sahara Desert, the vast sea of sand that separates West Africa from the lands to the north. Whoever ruled the trade routes ruled the gold, and whoever ruled the gold grew mighty."}, {"t": "p", "html": "What did they trade? Mostly <b>gold and salt</b>. It sounds surprising, but salt was once as precious as gold. People needed salt to stay healthy and to keep food from spoiling, and it was rare in the south. Gold was plentiful in the south but rare in the north. So great caravans — sometimes thousands of camels long — carried slabs of salt south and gold north across the burning Sahara. The journey could take months, and a single mistake could cost lives, so guides who knew the desert's hidden wells were treasured. The kingdoms in the middle taxed every load that passed and grew enormously rich."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The most famous ruler of Mali was <b>Mansa Musa</b>, who reigned in the 1300s. In 1324 he made a long journey to Mecca, traveling with thousands of people, soldiers, and camels loaded with gold. Along the way he handed out gold to the poor and built mosques in the cities he passed. Stories say he gave away so much gold in Egypt that its value dropped there for years afterward. Whether every tale is exact or not, the world certainly noticed Mali — soon mapmakers in faraway Europe drew Mansa Musa seated on his throne, holding a glittering golden nugget, the richest man they had ever heard of."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Mali's empire included <b>Timbuktu</b>, a city that became a glowing center of learning. Scholars there studied astronomy, mathematics, medicine, and law, and they collected tens of thousands of handwritten books. Students traveled great distances to study at its mosques and schools, and a single rare book could cost more than a house. Booksellers were among the richest people in the city. Timbuktu showed that Africa was a place of ideas and libraries, not only of trade."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> Many of Timbuktu's old manuscripts still survive today. Families guarded them for centuries, and people have worked hard to protect and restore them so the words of long-ago scholars are not lost."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Great Mosque of Djenné 3.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Ruud Zwart, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "The great mud-brick mosque of Djenné, West Africa"}, {"t": "p", "html": "How did these empires keep order across such enormous distances, with no telephones and no cars? They built networks of officials, judges, and messengers, and used a shared system of weights for measuring gold. Markets ran on trust and reputation, and travelers from far away wrote home in amazement at how safe the roads were and how fairly disputes were settled — strong signs of well-governed states. And Africa's greatness was not only in the west. In the east, the kingdom of <b>Aksum</b> (in today's Ethiopia and Eritrea) traded ivory and gold across the Red Sea, minted its own coins, and built towering stone pillars carved from single blocks of rock. Far to the south stood <b>Great Zimbabwe</b>, a city of massive stone walls built without any mortar to hold them — just carefully fitted stones, still standing after 700 years, whose people worked gold and traded goods that reached the Indian Ocean coast."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Order the West African empires", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~700s", "label": "Empire of Ghana rises in West Africa"}, {"yr": "~1235", "label": "Empire of Mali is founded"}, {"yr": "~1324", "label": "Mansa Musa makes his famous journey to Mecca"}, {"yr": "~1460s", "label": "Songhai Empire grows to its greatest size"}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When a story sounds amazing — like a king giving away mountains of gold — ask, \"How do we know this?\" Historians compare different writers, coins, ruins, and maps. When many separate clues agree, we can trust the story more."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> These kingdoms remind us that history's centers of wealth and learning have shifted around the world many times. Knowing that Africa held proud empires and great libraries helps everyone tell a fuller, fairer story of the human past."}, {"t": "p", "html": "From the golden caravans of Mali to the stone towers of Zimbabwe, ancient Africa was busy, brilliant, and connected to the wider world — a continent of kings, scholars, and builders whose work still amazes us today."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What two goods were most important in the Saharan trade?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Gold and salt", "Silk and spices", "Iron and wood", "Cotton and tea", "Copper and glass"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Gold from the south and salt from the north were traded across the desert, and the kingdoms in between grew rich by taxing them.", "hint": "One kept food fresh; the other was a precious metal."}, {"q": "Which ruler became famous for his journey to Mecca in 1324?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Sundiata", "Mansa Musa", "Sunni Ali", "Aksum", "Ezana"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Mansa Musa of Mali traveled with so much gold that the world took notice and mapmakers later drew him holding gold.", "hint": "His name begins with the title 'Mansa.'"}, {"q": "Timbuktu was best known as a center of what?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Shipbuilding", "Volcanoes", "Learning and books", "Gold mining", "Sea fishing"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Timbuktu had mosques, schools, and tens of thousands of manuscripts, drawing scholars from far away.", "hint": "Think libraries and students."}, {"q": "The old empire of Ghana was in the same place as the modern country of Ghana.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. The ancient empire was farther northwest; the modern country borrowed the proud old name later.", "hint": "Names can travel even when places do not."}, {"q": "Which order is correct, earliest to latest?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Mali, Ghana, Songhai", "Songhai, Mali, Ghana", "Ghana, Mali, Songhai", "Mali, Songhai, Ghana", "Ghana, Songhai, Mali"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The empire of Ghana rose first, then Mali, then Songhai.", "hint": "Ghana came first; Songhai was the last of the three."}, {"q": "Great Zimbabwe is famous for stone walls built without mortar.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Its huge walls were made of carefully fitted stones with nothing gluing them together, and they still stand.", "hint": "Think of stones stacked so precisely they need no glue."}, {"q": "The kingdom of Aksum was located in which part of Africa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The far west", "The deep Sahara", "The southern tip", "The eastern region (today's Ethiopia and Eritrea)", "An island in the Atlantic"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Aksum traded across the Red Sea and lay in what is now Ethiopia and Eritrea.", "hint": "It traded across the Red Sea."}, {"q": "Why was salt so valuable in this trade?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It was used to make jewelry", "People needed it for health and to preserve food", "It could be burned as fuel", "It was used to write books", "It was rare gold"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Salt kept people healthy and preserved food, and it was scarce in the south, making it extremely valuable.", "hint": "Think about staying healthy and keeping food from spoiling."}, {"q": "Aksum was advanced enough to make its own coins.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Aksum minted its own coins, a sign of a wealthy and organized kingdom.", "hint": "Minting coins shows a strong economy."}, {"q": "What is the best reason historians trust the stories about these kingdoms?", "type": "mc", "options": ["One writer said so", "Many different clues — coins, ruins, maps, and writers — agree", "They sound exciting", "A king wrote them down", "Movies showed them"], "answer": 1, "explain": "When separate sources like coins, ruins, maps, and many writers agree, the story becomes much more trustworthy.", "hint": "More agreeing clues means more confidence."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af2", "continent": "africa", "n": 2, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "⛓️", "title": "The Atlantic Slave Trade", "hook": "<b>For more than 300 years, ships crossed the Atlantic Ocean carrying people who had been taken from their homes — one of the saddest journeys in human history, and one we must understand with care and respect.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "This lesson is about a hard part of history: the Atlantic slave trade. We will tell it honestly but gently. It is a story of great wrong, but also of the strength, courage, and dignity of millions of people who never gave up their humanity."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Slavery — forcing people to work without freedom or pay — has sadly existed in many places and times throughout history, on every continent. But the <b>Atlantic slave trade</b>, which grew from the 1500s to the 1800s, was especially large, organized, and cruel. European traders carried captured Africans across the Atlantic Ocean to the Americas, where they were forced to labor for the rest of their lives on huge farms, called plantations, growing sugar, cotton, coffee, and tobacco. The crops they grew were shipped back across the ocean and sold for great profit, while the people who grew them received nothing for their work."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Historians estimate that around <b>12 million Africans</b> were taken across the ocean over these centuries. They came from many different peoples, languages, and homelands stretching across West and Central Africa. It is hard to picture a number that large, so it helps to remember this: each one was a person with a family who missed them, a name spoken by those who loved them, and a story of their own. They were not a number. They were people, every single one."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Captives were often held first in stone forts along the African coast, then forced onto crowded ships for a long, terrible ocean voyage called the <b>Middle Passage</b>. The conditions were harsh and frightening, and many did not survive the crossing. We remember this with sorrow and respect, without dwelling on painful details. It is important to know, too, that the people taken were not strangers to civilization — they came from rich cultures with their own farming, crafts, religions, music, and skilled trades. Some had been kings, weavers, farmers, healers, and storytellers. The trade tore them from full and meaningful lives."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "ship", "file": "Cape Coast Castle 02.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Erik Kristensen, CC BY 2.0", "caption": "Cape Coast Castle in Ghana, now a place of remembrance"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Why did this happen? It was driven by money. Plantations in the Americas wanted cheap labor to make huge profits, and traders ignored the humanity of the people they bought and sold. Wealth and greed, not any fault of the captured people, drove this trade. Yet through all of it, enslaved Africans showed remarkable <b>resilience</b>. They held on to their music, their stories, their faith, and their cooking. They built families and communities. Many resisted — some by quietly keeping their culture alive, others through escapes and uprisings. Their strength shaped the music, food, and culture of the entire Americas, from spirituals and blues to dishes eaten today."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> Much of the music the world loves — including jazz, blues, gospel, and rock and roll — grew from the songs and rhythms that enslaved Africans and their descendants kept alive. Their resilience gave a gift to the whole world."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Over time, more and more people came to see slavery as deeply wrong. Formerly enslaved people who escaped wrote books and gave speeches about their lives, and their powerful words changed minds. Free Black communities, church groups, and many others joined the cause. Movements to end slavery — called <b>abolition</b> — grew on both sides of the Atlantic. Slowly, country by country, the trade and then slavery itself were outlawed during the 1800s, though the struggle for full equality and dignity continued long afterward."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two truths to hold together", "a": {"title": "The wrong that happened", "items": ["Millions taken from their homes", "Families separated by force", "Driven by greed for profit"]}, "b": {"title": "The dignity that endured", "items": ["Cultures, music, and faith kept alive", "Communities and families rebuilt", "Courage and the long fight for freedom"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When studying a painful history, it helps to ask two questions: \"What was the wrong?\" and \"Where do we see courage and strength?\" Honest history holds both — it never hides the harm, and it never forgets the dignity of the people."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> The descendants of enslaved Africans live across the Americas today and have shaped its music, language, food, science, and ideas of freedom. Places like Cape Coast Castle are now memorials where people from around the world come to remember, learn, and honor those who suffered."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Remembering this history is not about shame or blame for anyone alive today. It is about respect — making sure that millions of people are not forgotten, and learning to treat every human being as someone with dignity, a name, and a story."}], "quiz": [{"q": "The Atlantic slave trade mainly carried people across which ocean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Pacific", "The Atlantic", "The Indian", "The Arctic", "The Red Sea"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The trade carried captured Africans across the Atlantic Ocean to the Americas.", "hint": "It is named after the ocean."}, {"q": "About how many Africans do historians estimate were taken across the ocean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 1 thousand", "About 10 thousand", "About 1 million", "About 12 million", "About 500 million"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Historians estimate around 12 million people were taken over more than three centuries.", "hint": "It was a number in the millions — a very large one."}, {"q": "What was the long ocean crossing called?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Middle Passage", "The Silk Road", "The Great Trek", "The Gold Route", "The Long March"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The terrible voyage across the Atlantic was called the Middle Passage.", "hint": "Its name has the word 'Middle' in it."}, {"q": "The slave trade was driven mainly by greed for money and profit.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Plantations wanted cheap labor for profit, and traders ignored the humanity of the people they sold.", "hint": "Think about who profited from the plantations."}, {"q": "Which of these grew from the music kept alive by enslaved Africans and their descendants?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Only classical opera", "Jazz, blues, and gospel", "Medieval chants", "None at all", "Silent films"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Jazz, blues, gospel, and later rock and roll all grew from these musical roots.", "hint": "Think of American music styles with deep rhythm and soul."}, {"q": "The movement to end slavery was called abolition.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Abolition was the movement that worked to outlaw the slave trade and slavery itself.", "hint": "It sounds like 'abolish.'"}, {"q": "What does 'resilience' mean in this lesson?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Giving up easily", "Strength to endure hardship and keep going", "Forgetting the past", "Becoming wealthy", "Traveling far"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Resilience is the strength to endure great hardship and keep one's dignity, culture, and hope alive.", "hint": "Think of bouncing back and staying strong."}, {"q": "Cape Coast Castle today is used as a place of remembrance and learning.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. The fort is now a memorial where people come to remember and honor those who suffered.", "hint": "Old forts can become memorials."}, {"q": "Which two things does honest history try to hold together?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Blame and shame", "The wrong that happened and the dignity of the people", "Only the good parts", "Only dates", "Profit and loss"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Honest history names the wrong clearly while also remembering the courage and dignity of the people.", "hint": "One is about harm; the other is about strength."}, {"q": "Remembering this history is mainly about shaming people alive today.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. It is about respect and remembrance, so that millions are not forgotten — not about shame or blame for anyone today.", "hint": "Think respect and memory, not blame."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af3", "continent": "africa", "n": 3, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🗺️", "title": "The Scramble for Africa", "hook": "<b>Imagine grown-ups sitting around a table in Europe, drawing lines on a map of a continent they had barely visited — deciding the borders of lands where millions of people already lived.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "In the late 1800s, several European countries rushed to take control of nearly all of Africa in just a few decades. Historians call this fast, competitive grab the \"Scramble for Africa.\" To understand today's world, it helps to understand how it happened."}, {"t": "p", "html": "For most of history, Europeans had stayed mostly along Africa's coasts, trading at ports but rarely venturing inland. But new inventions changed that. Steamships could travel up rivers, railways could cross great distances, fast-firing guns gave armies a powerful advantage, and new medicines helped Europeans survive diseases that had once kept them away. Above all, the factories of Europe's Industrial Revolution were hungry for <b>raw materials</b> — rubber for tires, copper for wires, gold, palm oil, cotton, and more — and Africa had them in abundance. Greed for these riches turned a trickle of explorers into a flood of competing empires."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In 1884 and 1885, leaders of European nations met at the <b>Berlin Conference</b>, a grand gathering in the German capital, to agree on rules for dividing Africa among themselves so they would not go to war with one another over it. Here is the striking part: <b>almost no Africans were invited</b>. The people whose homes and futures were being decided had no seat at the table. Powerful outsiders drew borders on a map of a continent most of them had never visited, often using straight lines and rulers that ignored the real homelands, languages, rivers, and kingdoms of the people who actually lived there."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Afrikakonferenz 1884.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Adalbert von Rößler, Public domain", "caption": "The Berlin Conference of 1884, dividing Africa"}, {"t": "p", "html": "By around 1914, almost the entire continent was claimed by a handful of European powers. Only <b>Ethiopia</b> stayed independent — under Emperor Menelik II it famously defended itself and defeated a much larger invading army at the Battle of Adwa in 1896, a victory celebrated across Africa and beyond — and Liberia remained largely on its own. Everywhere else, the old kingdoms and councils were pushed aside, and decisions about African lives were now made in distant European capitals."}, {"t": "p", "html": "This control is called <b>colonialism</b>: when one country rules over another land and its people. Colonial rulers took resources, made local people work for them, often for little or no pay, and treated African cultures, languages, and leaders as if they did not matter. They drew taxes from villages and sent the profits overseas. Many Africans resisted — through wars, protests, strikes, and by keeping their own traditions, faiths, and languages alive — but the powerful weapons and money of the colonizers were hard to overcome. Resistance never fully stopped, and it would grow into the freedom movements of the next century."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> The straight-line borders drawn in Europe are still visible on the map of Africa today. Some split a single people across two or three countries, while others forced groups who had never lived together into one. Many of today's challenges trace back to those lines."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Borders: real homelands vs. drawn lines", "a": {"title": "Before the Scramble", "items": ["Borders followed rivers, languages, and kingdoms", "Communities shaped their own lands", "Many different states and peoples"]}, "b": {"title": "After the Berlin Conference", "items": ["Straight lines drawn by outsiders", "One people split across countries", "Different peoples forced together"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you see a decision being made, ask: \"Who was in the room — and who was left out?\" At the Berlin Conference, the people most affected had almost no voice. Noticing who is missing from a decision helps you understand whether it was fair."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You lead a community in 1885", "prompt": "Outsiders have claimed your homeland and demand your people's labor and resources. What do you do? (There were no easy choices.)", "opts": [{"label": "Organize peaceful protest and keep your culture and language strong", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Hard and slow, but preserving identity and unity helped many communities survive and later fight for freedom."}, {"label": "Fight back immediately against far stronger weapons", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Brave, and sometimes successful — but the colonizers' guns and resources often made open war very costly."}, {"label": "Give up your traditions to please the rulers", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Understandable under pressure, but losing language and culture made it harder for communities to stay united."}]}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Most of Africa's modern borders were set during this period, not by Africans themselves. Understanding the Scramble helps explain why some countries contain many different language groups, and why building unity has sometimes been a challenge. It is a key to reading the map of the world today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Scramble for Africa was fast, powerful, and unfair to the people who lived there. But the story does not end in colonialism — as we will see next, Africans never stopped working, hoping, and organizing to win back their freedom."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What was the Berlin Conference of 1884–85 about?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Ending all wars", "European nations agreeing how to divide Africa", "Founding the United Nations", "Building railroads in Europe", "Trading spices with Asia"], "answer": 1, "explain": "At the Berlin Conference, European leaders set rules for dividing Africa among themselves.", "hint": "It was about carving up one whole continent."}, {"q": "How many Africans were invited to help make these decisions at Berlin?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Almost none", "About half the leaders", "All of them", "Only kings", "A thousand"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Almost no Africans were included; outsiders drew the borders of lands where Africans lived.", "hint": "The lesson stresses who was left out."}, {"q": "Which African country famously stayed independent after defeating an invading army at Adwa in 1896?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Egypt", "Ethiopia", "Nigeria", "Kenya", "Ghana"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Ethiopia defeated an invading army at the Battle of Adwa and remained independent.", "hint": "Its capital is Addis Ababa."}, {"q": "Colonialism means one country ruling over another land and its people.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Colonialism is when one country controls and rules another land and its people.", "hint": "Think of one country controlling another."}, {"q": "What did European factories most want from Africa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Snow and ice", "Books", "Tourists", "Ships", "Raw materials like rubber, copper, and gold"], "answer": 4, "explain": "Factories in Europe wanted raw materials such as rubber, copper, gold, and cotton.", "hint": "Think of things factories turn into products."}, {"q": "The borders drawn during the Scramble often ignored real homelands and languages.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Straight lines split some peoples apart and forced others together, ignoring real communities.", "hint": "Think about the straight lines on the map."}, {"q": "Which invention helped Europeans travel deeper into Africa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The telescope", "The printing press", "The steamship", "The compass", "The windmill"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Steamships could travel up rivers, helping Europeans reach inland areas.", "hint": "It runs on steam and floats."}, {"q": "By about 1914, almost the entire continent was claimed by European powers.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. By around 1914, nearly all of Africa was under European control, with only a couple of exceptions.", "hint": "Think 'almost all,' with rare exceptions."}, {"q": "What is a good question to ask about any big decision, according to the Owl tip?", "type": "mc", "options": ["What is for lunch?", "Who was in the room — and who was left out?", "How tall is the building?", "What color is the map?", "How old is the king?"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Asking who was included and who was left out helps you judge whether a decision was fair.", "hint": "It is about voices and fairness."}, {"q": "Many of today's African country borders were set during the colonial period.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Most modern borders were drawn during the Scramble, not by Africans themselves.", "hint": "Think about where those lines came from."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af4", "continent": "africa", "n": 4, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "✊🏿", "title": "Africa Wins Its Independence", "hook": "<b>At midnight on a March night in 1957, a huge crowd cheered as a new flag rose into the sky — and a man declared that his country was \"free forever.\"</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "After decades of colonial rule, the people of Africa stood up and won back their freedom. In just a few amazing years, one country after another raised its own flag and became independent. It is one of the most hopeful chapters in all of history — a story of courage, patient organizing, brilliant leaders, and ordinary people who refused to give up the dream of governing themselves."}, {"t": "p", "html": "By the middle of the 1900s, the world was changing. Two enormous world wars had weakened the European powers and drained their treasuries. Many Africans had served as soldiers in those wars, traveled, studied abroad, and seen the wider world — and they asked a fair question: if we fought for the freedom of others, why are we not free ourselves? A powerful idea spread everywhere: <b>the people who live in a land should rule that land</b>. This idea is called <b>self-determination</b>, and it lit a fire of hope across the whole continent."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Across the continent, leaders, students, workers, and ordinary people organized. They formed political parties, held marches, wrote newspapers, and went on strike. Market women refused to sell goods, farmers withheld their crops, and teachers spread ideas of freedom in classrooms. Some independence movements were peaceful; others involved struggle and conflict. But the goal was shared: to end colonial rule and govern themselves. Leaders also met one another, sharing strategies, so that a victory in one country gave hope and ideas to people in the next."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In 1957, <b>Ghana</b> became the first country south of the Sahara to win independence from European rule. At the stroke of midnight, the old flag came down, the new flag of red, gold, and green rose into the night sky, and enormous crowds wept and cheered with joy. Its leader, <b>Kwame Nkrumah</b>, became a hero across the continent. He famously said that the independence of Ghana was meaningless unless it was linked to the freedom of the entire continent, and he urged other Africans to seek their freedom too. His success showed the world that it could be done — and that gave countless others the courage to try."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "star", "file": "Kwame Nkrumah (JFKWHP-AR6409-A).jpg", "credit": "Photo: White House / Abbie Rowe, Public domain", "caption": "Kwame Nkrumah, first leader of independent Ghana"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Then came a rush. The year <b>1960</b> is often called the \"Year of Africa\" because <b>seventeen</b> African countries became independent in that single year — an astonishing wave of change. Within a couple of decades, almost the whole continent was free of colonial rule. New flags rose, new national anthems were sung, new leaders took office, and millions of people who had been ruled by faraway powers became citizens of their own nations, free to choose their own paths."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In southern Africa, one struggle lasted longer. In South Africa, a cruel system called <b>apartheid</b> separated people by the color of their skin and denied most people their rights — where they could live, work, study, or travel. A leader named <b>Nelson Mandela</b> spent 27 years in prison for opposing it. Around the world, people protested, refused to buy South African goods, and called for change, adding pressure year after year. When Mandela was finally freed in 1990, he chose forgiveness over revenge, and in 1994 South Africa held its first elections where everyone could vote. Mandela became president, a symbol of hope and reconciliation around the world."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> When Nelson Mandela walked out of prison in 1990 after 27 years, he urged peace and forgiveness rather than anger. His choice helped his country avoid a war and inspired people everywhere."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Order these milestones of freedom", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1957", "label": "Ghana becomes independent under Nkrumah"}, {"yr": "1960", "label": "The 'Year of Africa' — 17 countries gain independence"}, {"yr": "1990", "label": "Nelson Mandela is released from prison"}, {"yr": "1994", "label": "South Africa holds its first elections for all"}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Big change rarely comes from one hero alone. Behind every famous leader stood thousands of organizers, teachers, and ordinary people. When you read about a movement, look for the many people whose names you may never hear — they made the change possible too."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Most African nations have now been independent for around 60 to 70 years — younger than many countries elsewhere. Mandela's message of forgiveness over revenge is still studied by peacemakers worldwide. These freedom stories shaped the world we live in today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "From Ghana's midnight flag to South Africa's first free vote, Africans showed extraordinary determination to govern themselves. Winning freedom was a giant achievement — and, as we'll see next, it was also the beginning of a brand-new challenge: building strong nations."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Which country was the first south of the Sahara to win independence from European rule?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Nigeria", "Ghana", "Kenya", "South Africa", "Egypt"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Ghana, led by Kwame Nkrumah, became independent in 1957 and inspired others.", "hint": "Its leader was Kwame Nkrumah."}, {"q": "Why is 1960 called the 'Year of Africa'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A great drought happened", "Seventeen countries became independent that year", "A new ocean was found", "Europe was founded", "All wars ended"], "answer": 1, "explain": "In 1960, seventeen African countries became independent in a single year.", "hint": "It is about a large number of new free countries at once."}, {"q": "'Self-determination' means the people who live in a land should rule it.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Self-determination is the idea that a land's own people should govern themselves.", "hint": "Think 'a people deciding for itself.'"}, {"q": "What was apartheid in South Africa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A type of food", "A system that separated people by skin color and denied rights", "A national holiday", "A mountain range", "A kind of music"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Apartheid was a cruel system that separated people by the color of their skin and denied most their rights.", "hint": "It was an unjust system of separation."}, {"q": "How many years did Nelson Mandela spend in prison?", "type": "mc", "options": ["7 years", "17 years", "27 years", "2 years", "47 years"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Mandela spent 27 years in prison before his release in 1990.", "hint": "It is between 20 and 30 years."}, {"q": "When freed, Mandela chose forgiveness and peace over revenge.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Mandela urged forgiveness and reconciliation, helping his country avoid war.", "hint": "He is remembered for reconciliation."}, {"q": "What helped weaken the European colonial powers in the mid-1900s?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Two enormous world wars", "A new continent appearing", "The invention of the wheel", "A long peace", "Better weather"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Two world wars left European powers weakened, helping open the door to independence movements.", "hint": "Think of major global conflicts."}, {"q": "In 1994, South Africa held its first elections in which everyone could vote.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. In 1994 all South Africans could vote, and Mandela became president.", "hint": "It was the first truly open election."}, {"q": "According to the Owl tip, big change usually comes from what?", "type": "mc", "options": ["One hero alone", "Many organizers and ordinary people together", "Pure luck", "A single king", "No one"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Behind famous leaders stood thousands of organizers and ordinary people who made change possible.", "hint": "It takes more than one person."}, {"q": "Kwame Nkrumah encouraged other Africans to seek their own freedom.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Nkrumah became a hero across the continent and urged others to win independence too.", "hint": "He was a leader who inspired beyond his own country."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af5", "continent": "africa", "n": 5, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🌱", "title": "Building New Nations", "hook": "<b>Winning freedom was just the start. Now came an even harder job: building schools, hospitals, roads, and fair governments for hundreds of millions of people — almost from scratch.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "After independence, Africa's new nations faced a giant question: how do you build a strong, fair, prosperous country from the ground up? Raising a flag is the easy part; building schools, hospitals, roads, courts, and trustworthy governments for millions of people is the hard part. It is one of the great projects of our time, full of real challenges and also of remarkable, inspiring progress."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The new countries inherited some difficult starting conditions. Colonial rulers had often built railroads and ports mainly to carry resources <b>out</b> to the coast for export, not to connect towns and people to one another. Borders drawn in Europe placed many different language groups inside a single country, while splitting others apart. And under colonial rule, very few Africans had been allowed the schooling and training needed to become doctors, engineers, judges, or government officials. So the new nations had to govern, heal, teach, and build all at once — and they had to do it for huge populations spread across vast lands. There was a great deal to build, and not much time."}, {"t": "p", "html": "So the new nations got to work. They opened thousands of <b>schools</b> and universities, often building classrooms in villages that had never had one. They built hospitals and trained doctors and nurses. They created their own money, armies, courts, national anthems, and flags. They chose official languages and wrote new laws. They formed the <b>Organisation of African Unity</b> in 1963 — later the <b>African Union</b> — so countries could cooperate, settle disagreements, and support one another instead of standing alone."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Nairobi skyline.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Mwangi Kirubi, CC BY-SA 4.0", "caption": "Nairobi, a fast-growing modern African city"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Progress has been real and impressive. Far more children go to school today than ever before, and more girls than ever are finishing school and going on to lead. People are living longer and healthier lives as diseases are pushed back. Cities like Lagos, Nairobi, and Accra are bustling centers of business, music, and technology. Africa has become a leader in <b>mobile phone</b> ideas — for example, many people send money by phone, a system invented in Kenya that the whole world now copies. African films, called Nollywood, and African pop music now reach fans on every continent."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Of course, challenges remain. Some countries have faced poverty, conflict, or unfair leaders, and the difficult borders inherited from colonial times sometimes made unity harder to build. Climate change brings droughts and floods that test farmers and cities alike. Building fair governments where power changes peacefully takes time and effort — it took many older countries centuries of struggle to get there. But across the continent, citizens, voters, journalists, and young people keep pushing for honest leadership and a better future, and many countries hold regular, peaceful elections today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Africa is also rich in things money cannot buy: more than two thousand languages, countless musical and artistic traditions, and some of the most spectacular wildlife and landscapes on Earth. From the Sahara's dunes to the rainforests of the Congo, from snow-capped Kilimanjaro to the Great Rift Valley, the continent holds an astonishing variety of nature. And in every country, families are raising children who dream of becoming doctors, coders, farmers, artists, and leaders."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> Africa is the world's youngest continent by age — a very large share of its people are children and teenagers. That means today's young Africans will shape not only their own nations but the whole planet's future."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Then and now", "a": {"title": "Around independence", "items": ["Few schools and trained doctors", "Roads built mainly to export resources", "Brand-new governments finding their feet"]}, "b": {"title": "Today", "items": ["Millions more children in school", "Booming cities and tech innovation", "Citizens pushing for fair, honest government"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Beware of thinking of a whole continent as one single story. Africa has 54 countries, thousands of languages, deserts and rainforests, tiny villages and giant cities. When someone says \"Africa is ___,\" ask, \"Which country? Which place?\" The real picture is always rich and varied."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Why it still matters:</b> Africa is growing faster than any other continent and is expected to have a huge share of the world's young people in the years ahead. Its music, films, fashion, athletes, and inventors are shaping global culture right now. The future of the whole world is tied to Africa's future."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Building a nation is slow, hopeful, everyday work — opening one more school, holding one more fair election, starting one more business. Across 54 countries, hundreds of millions of people are doing exactly that, writing the next chapter of one of the world's most exciting and important stories."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What organization did African nations form in 1963 to cooperate?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The United Nations", "The Organisation of African Unity (later the African Union)", "The European Union", "The World Bank", "The Silk Road League"], "answer": 1, "explain": "In 1963 they founded the Organisation of African Unity, later renamed the African Union.", "hint": "Its modern name is the African Union."}, {"q": "Roads and railways built under colonial rule were often designed mainly to do what?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Connect villages to each other", "Carry resources out of the country", "Bring tourists in", "Move snow", "Reach the moon"], "answer": 1, "explain": "They were often built to carry resources out for export, not to connect people inside the country.", "hint": "Think about exporting raw materials."}, {"q": "Africa is one single country with one language.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Africa is a continent of 54 countries and thousands of languages — hugely varied.", "hint": "Remember the Owl tip about a whole continent."}, {"q": "Which money-by-phone idea, now copied worldwide, started in Kenya?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Paper checks", "Mobile phone money transfers", "Gold coins", "Barter trade", "Stock markets"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Kenya pioneered sending money by mobile phone, an idea the world now copies.", "hint": "It involves a mobile phone."}, {"q": "Africa is the world's youngest continent, with many children and teenagers.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. A very large share of Africa's people are young, which shapes its future.", "hint": "Think about the age of the population."}, {"q": "How many countries make up the continent of Africa today?", "type": "mc", "options": ["5", "12", "27", "54", "100"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Africa has 54 countries, each with its own story.", "hint": "It is more than 50."}, {"q": "Which is an example of real progress since independence?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Fewer schools", "Far more children attending school", "Shorter lives", "No cities", "No flags"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Many more children attend school today, and people live longer, healthier lives.", "hint": "Think about education improving."}, {"q": "Building fair governments where power changes peacefully can take a long time.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. It took many older countries a long time too; it is slow but important work.", "hint": "Think about how long it took elsewhere."}, {"q": "Which of these is a fast-growing modern African city?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Nairobi", "Venice", "Tokyo", "Oslo", "Lima"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Nairobi, in Kenya, is a bustling, fast-growing center of business and technology.", "hint": "It is the capital of Kenya."}, {"q": "According to the lesson, the future of the whole world is connected to Africa's future.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. With its fast growth and young population, Africa's future matters for the entire planet.", "hint": "Think about its growing, young population."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af6", "continent": "africa", "n": 6, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🚀", "title": "Modern Africa: Young, Growing, Rising", "hook": "<b>Half of all the people in Africa are under 19 years old. It is the youngest continent on Earth — a place humming with new ideas, new cities, and new ways of doing old things.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "If you could shrink the world's young people into one giant classroom, a huge share of the front rows would be African. Africa is home to about 1.4 billion people across <b>54 countries</b>, and its median age is around 19 — meaning half of everyone is younger than that. While many parts of the world are growing older, Africa is doing the opposite: it is young, busy, and changing fast."}, {"t": "p", "html": "First, a fact that surprises many people: Africa is <b>not a country</b>. It is a vast continent of 54 independent nations, each with its own flag, government, languages, foods, and music. Nigeria alone has over 200 million people. Tiny Seychelles, a cluster of islands, has fewer than 100,000. Calling 'Africa' one thing is like calling 'Asia' one thing — it hides an enormous amount of variety."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Modern African cities are growing faster than almost anywhere on the planet. <b>Lagos</b>, in Nigeria, is one of the largest cities in the world, packed with markets, music studios, and traffic that locals joke about with great affection. <b>Nairobi</b>, in Kenya, has so many tech start-ups that part of it is nicknamed 'Silicon Savannah.' Cairo, Johannesburg, Accra, and Kinshasa each pulse with their own energy. By 2050, roughly one in four people on Earth is expected to be African."}, {"t": "p", "html": "One of the most remarkable African inventions of recent times started with something almost everyone carries: a mobile phone. In 2007, a Kenyan service called <b>M-Pesa</b> ('M' for mobile, 'pesa' meaning money in Swahili) let people send money to each other using a simple text message — no bank account needed. A fruit seller could be paid by phone. A grandmother in a village could receive money from a child working in the city in seconds."}, {"t": "p", "html": "This mattered because, at the time, many Africans had no nearby bank but did have a phone. M-Pesa let them <b>skip a step the wealthy world took for centuries</b>. Today, hundreds of millions of people across Africa use mobile money for everyday life — buying lunch, paying school fees, running businesses. The rest of the world later copied the idea. It is a clear example of Africa not following, but leading."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> More money moves through mobile-money accounts in sub-Saharan Africa than in any other region on Earth. A continent once told it was 'behind' on banking simply invented a better path."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Nairobi_skyline.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Mutua Matheka, CC BY-SA 4.0", "caption": "Nairobi's skyline, Kenya's tech capital"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Of course, modern Africa also faces real challenges. Some countries struggle with poverty, droughts made worse by climate change, or governments that don't always serve their people well. These problems are honest to name. But they are only part of the picture — and a continent is never just its hardest days. Alongside the struggles are universities, film industries, fashion designers, scientists, and millions of young people building lives and businesses."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The diversity is staggering once you look closely. Africa holds the world's largest hot desert and steaming rainforests, snowy peaks and golden coasts. Its people follow many faiths and speak more than 2,000 languages. A market in Marrakesh, a tech office in Kigali, a fishing village in Senegal, and a vineyard near Cape Town are all 'Africa' — yet each is a world of its own. Holding all of that in mind, instead of one flat picture, is the start of really understanding the continent."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Take Nigeria's film industry, nicknamed <b>'Nollywood.'</b> It produces thousands of movies a year and is one of the busiest film industries in the world. Or think of African musicians like those behind 'Afrobeats,' a sound now topping charts from London to Los Angeles. African creativity is a major export, traveling far beyond the continent's borders."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two pictures of Africa", "a": {"title": "Old stereotype", "items": ["Seen as one place", "Only struggles and aid", "Stuck in the past", "Following others"]}, "b": {"title": "Modern reality", "items": ["54 diverse countries", "Fast-growing cities and business", "Youngest population on Earth", "Inventing mobile money first"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you hear 'Africa,' try asking 'Which part? Which country?' A story about Egypt's deserts tells you nothing about Kenya's tech scene or Ghana's coast. Curiosity grows when you remember how many different places that one word holds."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> The African Union — a group of all 54 countries — launched the African Continental Free Trade Area, one of the largest free-trade zones in the world by number of countries. The goal: let goods, ideas, and people move more easily across borders, so a young entrepreneur in Senegal can sell to customers in Tanzania as easily as next door."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You're describing Africa to a friend", "prompt": "Your friend says, 'Africa is a poor country, right?' What's the most accurate, kind reply?", "opts": [{"label": "'Actually, it's a continent of 54 countries, and it's the youngest, fastest-growing place on Earth — it even invented mobile money.'", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "You correct the mistake gently and add something genuinely interesting. Your friend learns and isn't embarrassed."}, {"label": "'Yeah, basically.'", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "You pass along a wrong idea. The myth that Africa is one poor place keeps spreading."}, {"label": "'It's complicated, never mind.'", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "You dodge it. The misunderstanding survives, and nobody learns anything new."}]}], "quiz": [{"q": "How many countries are in Africa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["12", "27", "40", "54", "100"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Africa is made up of 54 independent countries, each with its own government, flag, and cultures.", "hint": "It's more than 50."}, {"q": "What makes Africa unusual compared to most other continents?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It has the oldest population", "It has the youngest population", "It has no large cities", "It has only one language", "It has no coastline"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Africa's median age is around 19, making it the youngest continent on Earth.", "hint": "Think about age, not size."}, {"q": "What was M-Pesa, launched in Kenya in 2007?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A new airline", "A mobile-money service for sending money by phone", "A type of farm", "A national park", "A music festival"], "answer": 1, "explain": "M-Pesa let people send and receive money using a phone, even without a bank account — a world-leading idea.", "hint": "'Pesa' means money in Swahili."}, {"q": "Africa is a single country.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Africa is a continent of 54 separate countries, not one country."}, {"q": "Which city is nicknamed 'Silicon Savannah' for its tech start-ups?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Cairo", "Lagos", "Nairobi", "Cape Town", "Accra"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Nairobi, Kenya's capital, has so many tech companies that it earned the nickname 'Silicon Savannah.'", "hint": "It's in Kenya."}, {"q": "Mobile money is used more in sub-Saharan Africa than in any other region on Earth.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — Africa leads the world in mobile-money use, having invented and embraced the idea first."}, {"q": "What is 'Nollywood'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A theme park", "Nigeria's huge film industry", "A type of music", "A desert region", "A sports league"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Nollywood is Nigeria's film industry, one of the most productive in the world.", "hint": "Think movies, in Nigeria."}, {"q": "Roughly how many people live in Africa today?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 140 million", "About 400 million", "About 1.4 billion", "About 5 billion", "About 50 million"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Africa is home to around 1.4 billion people, and that number is growing fast.", "hint": "It's over a billion."}, {"q": "Saying 'Africa is one poor place' is accurate.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — Africa is 54 very different countries with cities, industries, and great diversity, not one single thing."}, {"q": "What is the African Continental Free Trade Area meant to do?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Build one giant city", "Make it easier to trade goods and ideas across African borders", "Create a single African language", "Ban all imports", "Stop all travel"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It's one of the world's largest free-trade zones, designed to help people and goods move more easily between African countries.", "hint": "The words 'free trade' are a clue."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af7", "continent": "africa", "n": 7, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🦴", "title": "The Birthplace of Humanity", "hook": "<b>Every human alive today — every grandparent, every friend, every you — has ancestors who once lived in Africa. It is, quite literally, the homeland of our whole species.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Scientists have a striking way of putting it: if you traced your family tree back far enough — past your great-grandparents, past the people who built castles and pyramids, back tens of thousands of generations — every single human line leads to the same place. <b>Africa is the cradle of humankind.</b> This isn't a legend. It's one of the best-supported discoveries in all of science, written in fossils, stones, and even our own DNA."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Much of the story is buried in a place called the <b>Great Rift Valley</b>, a giant crack in the Earth's surface running thousands of kilometers down East Africa, through countries like Ethiopia, Kenya, and Tanzania. Over millions of years, the ground here slowly pulled apart, and layers of rock and ash piled up like pages in a book. Those layers trapped and preserved the bones of ancient creatures — including our earliest relatives."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In 1974, in Ethiopia, scientists uncovered one of the most famous fossils ever found: the skeleton of a small, upright-walking female who lived about <b>3.2 million years ago</b>. They nicknamed her <b>'Lucy.'</b> She wasn't quite a modern human — her species was Australopithecus afarensis — but she walked on two legs, just like you. Lucy showed the world that our ancestors stood upright long before they had large brains."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Another treasure of the Rift Valley is <b>Olduvai Gorge</b> in Tanzania, sometimes called 'the Cradle of Mankind.' There, researchers found some of the oldest stone tools ever made — sharp-edged rocks, shaped by hand nearly two million years ago. These simple tools were a giant leap: they meant early humans could cut, dig, and prepare food in ways no other animal could."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> 'Lucy' got her name because the night she was discovered, the scientists' camp was playing the Beatles song 'Lucy in the Sky with Diamonds.' A 3.2-million-year-old ancestor, named after a pop song."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Our own species, <b>Homo sapiens</b> ('wise human'), appeared in Africa too — the oldest known fossils of people who look like us, found in Morocco, are around 300,000 years old. For most of human history, the only place humans lived was Africa. Everything — language, art, the first campfires, the first stories told under the stars — began on this one continent."}, {"t": "p", "html": "How do scientists feel so sure about all this? They use several kinds of evidence that point the same way. Fossils show the gradual changes in bodies over millions of years. Stone tools reveal growing cleverness. And modern DNA, read from people alive today, traces our family tree backward like a giant detective puzzle — and the trail always leads to Africa. When fossils, tools, and DNA all agree, scientists trust the conclusion. That is how the cradle of humankind was found not by guessing, but by patient, careful study."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Great_Rift_Valley_Kenya.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Sajjad Sherally Fazel, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "Kenya's Great Rift Valley, where humanity began"}, {"t": "p", "html": "So how did humans end up everywhere else? Around 60,000 to 70,000 years ago, small groups of Homo sapiens began walking out of Africa — a journey scientists call the <b>'Out of Africa' migration</b>. They crossed into the Middle East, then spread to Asia, Europe, Australia, and eventually the Americas. They didn't have maps or vehicles. They simply followed food, water, and curiosity, generation after generation, until their descendants had reached nearly every corner of the planet."}, {"t": "order", "title": "The human story, earliest to latest", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "3.2 mya", "label": "'Lucy' walks upright in Ethiopia"}, {"yr": "1.8 mya", "label": "Stone tools made at Olduvai Gorge"}, {"yr": "300,000 ya", "label": "First Homo sapiens appear in Africa"}, {"yr": "60,000 ya", "label": "Humans begin migrating out of Africa"}, {"yr": "15,000 ya", "label": "Humans reach the Americas"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "Here's a wonderful result of this shared origin: scientists can read tiny clues in our DNA, and they find that <b>all humans are remarkably alike</b>. In fact, two chimpanzees from different African forests can be more genetically different from each other than two humans from opposite sides of the planet. Our long shared African childhood as a species left us, deep down, as one large family."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> 'mya' means 'million years ago' and 'ya' means 'years ago' — handy shortcuts scientists use. When a number feels too huge to picture, try this: if all of human history were one day, Lucy would belong to a time long before the day even began."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> New fossils and DNA studies keep refining the story. Discoveries like Homo naledi in South Africa show that several kinds of early humans sometimes lived at the same time. Africa remains the world's richest hunting ground for understanding where we all came from — the past is still being uncovered."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You find an old-looking bone on a hike", "prompt": "It looks like it might be a fossil. What's the wise thing to do?", "opts": [{"label": "Leave it in place, photograph it, and tell a museum or scientist where you found it.", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Fossils mean the most when experts can study exactly where and how deep they were found. You may have helped real science."}, {"label": "Dig it out and take it home as a souvenir.", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Removing it destroys the clues in the surrounding layers — and important fossils belong to everyone, not one collector."}, {"label": "Ignore it and keep walking.", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Understandable, but a quick photo and a note to experts costs nothing and might matter a lot."}]}], "quiz": [{"q": "According to science, where did the human species first appear?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Europe", "Asia", "Africa", "Australia", "The Americas"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Fossils and DNA both show that humans first evolved in Africa, the cradle of humankind.", "hint": "It's the continent this whole lesson is about."}, {"q": "What is 'Lucy'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A famous queen", "A 3.2-million-year-old upright-walking fossil", "A type of stone tool", "A river in Ethiopia", "A modern scientist"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Lucy is a famous fossil skeleton found in Ethiopia in 1974, of an early ancestor who walked on two legs.", "hint": "She was discovered in 1974."}, {"q": "The Great Rift Valley is a giant crack in the Earth running through East Africa.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — the Rift Valley's layers of rock preserved many of our earliest ancestors' fossils."}, {"q": "What was special about Lucy's body?", "type": "mc", "options": ["She had a huge brain", "She walked upright on two legs", "She had wings", "She was three meters tall", "She had no skeleton"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Lucy showed that our ancestors walked upright long before they developed large brains.", "hint": "Think about how you move around."}, {"q": "What was found at Olduvai Gorge in Tanzania?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The first pyramid", "Some of the oldest stone tools", "A buried city", "A gold mine", "A dinosaur egg"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Olduvai Gorge revealed some of the oldest known stone tools, made by early humans nearly two million years ago.", "hint": "It's about early technology made of rock."}, {"q": "What does the name Homo sapiens mean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["'Tall human'", "'Wise human'", "'Fast human'", "'African human'", "'First human'"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Homo sapiens means 'wise human' in Latin — that's our own species.", "hint": "It's a compliment about our minds."}, {"q": "Roughly when did humans begin migrating out of Africa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 500 years ago", "About 5,000 years ago", "About 60,000 years ago", "About 5 million years ago", "Humans never left Africa"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The 'Out of Africa' migration began around 60,000–70,000 years ago, eventually spreading humans worldwide.", "hint": "Tens of thousands of years."}, {"q": "Early humans had maps and vehicles when they spread across the world.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — they traveled on foot over thousands of years, following food, water, and curiosity."}, {"q": "Because of our shared African origin, all humans today are:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Completely unrelated", "Genetically very similar to one another", "From different species", "Unable to be studied", "Mostly different species"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Our shared origin means humans are remarkably alike in our DNA — one big family.", "hint": "Think 'one family.'"}, {"q": "For most of human history, the only continent humans lived on was Africa.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — humans lived only in Africa for most of our species' existence before migrating outward."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af8", "continent": "africa", "n": 8, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🔺", "title": "Ancient Egypt: Pharaohs, Pyramids & the Nile", "hook": "<b>Imagine a kingdom so long-lasting that Cleopatra lived closer in time to the first Moon landing than to the building of the Great Pyramid. That's how astonishingly old Ancient Egypt is.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Stretched along a thin green ribbon in the middle of a vast desert, Ancient Egypt was one of the greatest civilizations the world has ever known. It lasted, in various forms, for around <b>3,000 years</b> — longer than the time between Cleopatra and today. While many empires rose and crumbled in a few centuries, Egypt endured for dozens of generations. The secret to its long life lay in one mighty river."}, {"t": "p", "html": "That river was the <b>Nile</b>, the longest in the world. Egypt sits in the Sahara, where rain almost never falls. Without the Nile, the whole region would be lifeless sand. But every year, the river flooded in a gentle, predictable rhythm, spreading rich black mud across its banks. That mud made the soil so fertile that farmers could grow plenty of grain. The Greek historian Herodotus called Egypt <b>'the gift of the Nile'</b> — and he was right."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Because the floods were so reliable, Egyptians could plan their whole year around them. They invented a calendar, developed math to measure fields, and grew enough food to free up workers for other jobs — building, writing, painting, and worship. A dependable river quietly made an entire civilization possible."}, {"t": "p", "html": "At the top of Egyptian society sat the <b>pharaoh</b>, a ruler believed to be part-human, part-god. The pharaoh was thought to keep the universe in balance and the Nile flowing. Some pharaohs are still famous today: <b>Tutankhamun</b>, the boy-king whose dazzling golden tomb was found nearly intact in 1922; <b>Ramesses II</b>, a great builder; and <b>Hatshepsut</b>, one of the most successful female pharaohs, who ruled as a king in her own right."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The most famous things the Egyptians built are, of course, the <b>pyramids</b>. The Great Pyramid of Giza, built around 4,500 years ago as a tomb for the pharaoh Khufu, was made of over two million blocks of stone, some weighing more than an elephant. It stood as the tallest human-made structure on Earth for almost 4,000 years. And the Egyptians built it without iron tools, wheels for heavy loads, or modern machines — using ramps, ropes, sleds, and the muscle of skilled, organized workers."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> The workers who built the pyramids were not enslaved foreigners, as old movies often show. Archaeologists found their villages, bakeries, and tombs near Giza — they were paid Egyptian laborers, fed bread and beer, and honored when they died."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "pyramids", "file": "Kheops-Pyramid.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Nina Aldin Thune, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "The Great Pyramid of Giza, tomb of Khufu"}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Egyptians also invented one of the world's earliest writing systems: <b>hieroglyphs</b>, a beautiful script using hundreds of little pictures — owls, water ripples, feet, suns. For centuries after Egypt's fall, nobody could read them. Then, in 1799, soldiers found the <b>Rosetta Stone</b>, which carried the same message in hieroglyphs and in Greek. By matching the two, a French scholar named Champollion finally cracked the code, letting the ancient Egyptians 'speak' again."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Egyptians believed deeply in life after death. To prepare a body for the afterlife, they perfected <b>mummification</b> — carefully drying and wrapping the body so it would last for thousands of years. They filled tombs with food, furniture, jewelry, and treasure for the journey ahead. Thanks to the dry desert air and their skill, some mummies survive so well today that scientists can study what ancient Egyptians ate and what illnesses they had."}, {"t": "p", "html": "So why did Egypt last so incredibly long — around 3,000 years? Part of the answer is the Nile's dependable gift of food year after year. Part is the desert on both sides, a natural wall that kept many invaders away. And part is the Egyptians' strong shared beliefs, which held their society together through good times and bad. Few civilizations in history ever matched that staying power. Empires we think of as ancient, like Rome, were newcomers compared to a kingdom that was already thousands of years old when they arrived."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Ancient Egypt, earliest to latest", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~3100 BCE", "label": "Egypt is first united under one ruler"}, {"yr": "~2560 BCE", "label": "Great Pyramid of Giza built for Khufu"}, {"yr": "~1332 BCE", "label": "Tutankhamun becomes pharaoh"}, {"yr": "~30 BCE", "label": "Cleopatra dies; Rome takes over Egypt"}, {"yr": "1922 CE", "label": "Tutankhamun's tomb rediscovered"}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> 'BCE' means 'Before Common Era' and counts backward, so 3100 BCE is older than 30 BCE. 'CE' means 'Common Era' and counts forward to today. When you see BCE, remember: bigger number = longer ago."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> Egypt is a modern country of over 100 million people, with Cairo as its bustling capital. Tourists from all over the world still visit the pyramids, and in 2021 Egypt held a grand parade to move 22 royal mummies to a new museum — ancient kings and queens riding through a modern city to cheering crowds."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You're an Egyptian farmer, 4,000 years ago", "prompt": "The Nile's yearly flood is rising over your fields. What do you do?", "opts": [{"label": "Welcome it — wait for it to drop, then plant in the fresh black mud it leaves behind.", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Exactly right. The flood is a blessing, not a disaster; its mud is what makes your crops grow."}, {"label": "Panic and try to block the river with walls to save your house.", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Fighting the Nile wastes your effort. Egyptians learned to live with the flood, not against it."}, {"label": "Move far into the desert to escape the water.", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "But the desert has no water at all — away from the Nile, nothing grows. The river is your lifeline."}]}], "quiz": [{"q": "Which river made Ancient Egyptian civilization possible?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Amazon", "The Congo", "The Nile", "The Niger", "The Zambezi"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Nile's yearly floods left rich mud that let Egyptians grow food in the middle of a desert.", "hint": "It's the longest river in the world."}, {"q": "Who called Egypt 'the gift of the Nile'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Tutankhamun", "Herodotus", "Cleopatra", "Champollion", "Khufu"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Greek historian Herodotus described Egypt as 'the gift of the Nile,' because the river made everything possible.", "hint": "He was a Greek historian."}, {"q": "Roughly how long did Ancient Egyptian civilization last?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 100 years", "About 500 years", "About 3,000 years", "About 10 years", "About 50 years"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Ancient Egypt lasted around 3,000 years — longer than the time between Cleopatra and today.", "hint": "Thousands, not hundreds."}, {"q": "A pharaoh was believed to be part-human and part-god.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — Egyptians believed the pharaoh kept the universe in balance and the Nile flowing."}, {"q": "What were hieroglyphs?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Egyptian boats", "An early writing system using picture-symbols", "A kind of pyramid", "A type of food", "Royal jewelry"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Hieroglyphs were Egypt's early writing system, using hundreds of little pictures as symbols.", "hint": "Think writing with pictures."}, {"q": "The Rosetta Stone helped scholars finally read hieroglyphs.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — because it showed the same message in hieroglyphs and Greek, scholars could match them and crack the code."}, {"q": "The Great Pyramid of Giza was built as a tomb for which pharaoh?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Tutankhamun", "Ramesses II", "Khufu", "Cleopatra", "Hatshepsut"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Great Pyramid was built around 4,500 years ago as a tomb for the pharaoh Khufu.", "hint": "His name starts with 'Kh.'"}, {"q": "What was mummification for?", "type": "mc", "options": ["To make statues", "To preserve a body for the afterlife", "To build pyramids", "To write messages", "To grow crops"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Egyptians mummified bodies to preserve them for the afterlife, which they believed in deeply.", "hint": "It's about life after death."}, {"q": "The pyramids were built mainly by enslaved foreigners.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — archaeologists found that paid Egyptian workers, who were fed and honored, built the pyramids."}, {"q": "Hatshepsut is remembered as:", "type": "mc", "options": ["A famous scribe", "One of Egypt's most successful female pharaohs", "The builder of the Rosetta Stone", "A Greek historian", "A mummy maker"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Hatshepsut ruled as a king in her own right and was one of Egypt's most successful pharaohs.", "hint": "She was a powerful woman ruler."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af9", "continent": "africa", "n": 9, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🦁", "title": "Deserts, Rivers & Wild Savannas: Africa's Geography & Wildlife", "hook": "<b>From the world's biggest hot desert to steaming rainforests, from the longest river to thundering waterfalls — Africa packs nearly every kind of landscape on Earth into one continent.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Africa is enormous — so big that you could fit the United States, China, India, and most of Europe inside it with room to spare. With that size comes astonishing variety. In a single continent you'll find scorching deserts, dripping jungles, snow-capped mountains near the equator, golden grasslands, and some of the most spectacular wildlife on the planet. Let's take a tour from top to bottom."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Across the north stretches the <b>Sahara</b>, the largest hot desert in the world — roughly the size of the entire United States. It's a land of towering sand dunes, rocky plateaus, and blazing days that turn to cold nights. People have crossed it for thousands of years by camel caravan, trading gold, salt, and ideas. The Sahara is not empty: nomads, oasis towns, and hardy animals all call it home."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Cutting through the deserts of the northeast flows the <b>Nile</b>, the longest river on Earth at over 6,600 kilometers. It begins deep in the heart of Africa and travels north — yes, north — finally emptying into the Mediterranean Sea. Far to the south and west lies the mighty <b>Congo River</b>, which winds through the second-largest rainforest in the world. The Congo Basin is so thick with trees that it's sometimes called 'the second lungs of the Earth,' after the Amazon."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Between the deserts and the rainforests lie the famous African <b>savannas</b> — vast open grasslands dotted with flat-topped acacia trees. This is the Africa many people picture: golden grass rippling under a huge sky, herds of animals as far as the eye can see. The savanna is home to the so-called 'Big Five' — lions, leopards, elephants, rhinos, and buffalo — along with giraffes, zebras, cheetahs, and countless birds."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> Mount Kilimanjaro in Tanzania sits almost on the equator, one of the hottest zones on Earth — yet it's so tall that its summit is capped with ice and snow. You can travel from tropical heat to freezing cold just by climbing up."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Serengeti_lion_running.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Schuyler Shepherd, CC BY-SA 2.5", "caption": "A lion on the Serengeti's open grasslands"}, {"t": "p", "html": "One of the greatest natural events on Earth happens on these grasslands: the <b>Great Migration</b> of the Serengeti. Each year, more than a million wildebeest, along with hundreds of thousands of zebras and gazelles, travel in a giant loop across Tanzania and Kenya, following the rains and fresh grass. Along the way they must cross crocodile-filled rivers and dodge waiting lions. It is the largest movement of land animals anywhere in the world."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Africa's water can be dramatic, too. On the border of Zambia and Zimbabwe lies <b>Victoria Falls</b>, one of the largest waterfalls on the planet. Local people call it <b>'Mosi-oa-Tunya'</b> — 'the smoke that thunders' — because the mist rises so high it can be seen from far away, and the roar of the water can be heard kilometers off. Standing near it, you feel the ground tremble."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two extremes on one continent", "a": {"title": "The Sahara Desert", "items": ["Largest hot desert on Earth", "Almost no rain", "Sand dunes and rock", "Camels and oases"]}, "b": {"title": "The Congo Rainforest", "items": ["Second-largest rainforest", "Rain almost daily", "Dense, dripping jungle", "Gorillas and tropical birds"]}}, {"t": "p", "html": "Why does one continent hold so many different landscapes? A big reason is the equator, which runs right across the middle of Africa. Near it, warm wet air drops heavy rain, growing thick rainforests. Move north or south, and the air dries out, giving grasslands and then deserts like the Sahara. So Africa is almost mirrored: green at the center, drying toward the top and bottom. Mountains, oceans, and great rivers then add even more variety on top of that pattern."}, {"t": "p", "html": "All this incredible wildlife faces real challenges today. Some animals, like rhinos and elephants, have been hunted illegally for their horns and tusks. Forests and grasslands can shrink as more land is needed for farming and cities. But there's hopeful news too: across Africa, huge national parks like the Serengeti, the Maasai Mara, and Kruger protect millions of animals, and local rangers — many of them young Africans — work hard to keep them safe."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> A 'savanna' isn't a desert and isn't a forest — it's grassland with scattered trees, kept open by long dry seasons. When you read about African animals, ask which habitat they live in: a rainforest gorilla and a savanna lion lead totally different lives."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> Conservation in Africa increasingly blends science and technology. Rangers use GPS collars, drones, and even mobile apps to track and protect endangered animals from poachers. Tourism, when done carefully, helps fund this work — visitors pay to see wildlife, and that money helps keep the animals alive and wild."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You're on a savanna safari", "prompt": "Your guide spots a pride of lions resting nearby. What's the responsible thing to do?", "opts": [{"label": "Stay quiet in the vehicle, watch from a respectful distance, and follow the guide's rules.", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Perfect. The animals stay calm and wild, and you get an unforgettable, safe view of real lions."}, {"label": "Climb out for a closer selfie with the lions.", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Extremely dangerous and harmful — wild lions are not pets, and leaving the vehicle can get you or the animals hurt."}, {"label": "Throw food to lure them nearer.", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Feeding wild animals teaches them to depend on humans and can make them aggressive. Never feed wildlife."}]}], "quiz": [{"q": "What is the Sahara?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A rainforest", "The largest hot desert on Earth", "A mountain range", "A river", "A waterfall"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Sahara, across northern Africa, is the world's largest hot desert, roughly the size of the United States.", "hint": "Think sand and heat."}, {"q": "The Nile is the longest river in the world.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — the Nile runs over 6,600 km, flowing north to the Mediterranean Sea."}, {"q": "What is a savanna?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A thick jungle", "Open grassland with scattered trees", "A sandy desert", "A frozen mountain", "A deep ocean"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A savanna is grassland dotted with scattered trees, home to lions, elephants, zebras, and more.", "hint": "Picture golden grass and a few flat-topped trees."}, {"q": "Which animals make up Africa's famous 'Big Five'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Lion, leopard, elephant, rhino, buffalo", "Lion, giraffe, zebra, hippo, ostrich", "Cheetah, gorilla, crocodile, snake, eagle", "Camel, antelope, hyena, baboon, wildebeest", "Tiger, panda, bear, wolf, fox"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The 'Big Five' are the lion, leopard, elephant, rhino, and buffalo.", "hint": "It includes the king of the savanna and the largest land animal."}, {"q": "What is the Great Migration of the Serengeti?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A river that moves", "A yearly journey of over a million wildebeest and other animals", "A type of desert storm", "A city that relocates", "A bird that flies south"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Each year more than a million wildebeest, plus zebras and gazelles, migrate across Tanzania and Kenya following the rains.", "hint": "It's the largest movement of land animals on Earth."}, {"q": "The Congo Basin holds the second-largest rainforest in the world.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — only the Amazon rainforest is larger; the Congo is sometimes called Earth's 'second lungs.'"}, {"q": "What does 'Mosi-oa-Tunya,' the local name for Victoria Falls, mean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["'The great river'", "'The smoke that thunders'", "'The golden water'", "'The endless rain'", "'The quiet pool'"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Local people named it 'the smoke that thunders' for its towering mist and roaring sound.", "hint": "It describes mist and a loud noise."}, {"q": "Mount Kilimanjaro, near the equator, has snow and ice at its summit.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — Kilimanjaro is so tall that its peak stays icy even though it sits in a hot tropical zone."}, {"q": "How do modern rangers help protect African wildlife from poachers?", "type": "mc", "options": ["By using GPS collars, drones, and apps", "By building walls around the whole continent", "By moving all animals to zoos", "By banning all tourists forever", "By feeding the animals daily"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Rangers increasingly use technology like GPS collars and drones to track and protect endangered animals.", "hint": "Think modern gadgets."}, {"q": "Africa contains only one kind of landscape.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — Africa has deserts, rainforests, grasslands, snowy mountains, and more, all on one continent."}]});

  lesson({"id": "af10", "continent": "africa", "n": 10, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🥁", "title": "Rhythm & Story: Africa's Cultures, Languages & Music", "hook": "<b>Every time you hear blues, jazz, rock, or hip-hop, you're hearing echoes of Africa. The rhythms that move the whole world were born on this one continent.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "If you wanted to throw a party for all the languages on Earth, Africa would bring the biggest crowd. The continent is home to more than <b>2,000 languages</b> — about a third of all the languages spoken on the planet. In a single country like Nigeria, people speak over 500 different languages. This astonishing variety reflects thousands of years of distinct peoples, histories, and ways of seeing the world."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Some African languages are spoken by millions across many countries. <b>Swahili</b>, for example, is spoken by over 100 million people in East Africa and is one of the working languages of the African Union. Others, like the click-filled languages of southern Africa, contain sounds found almost nowhere else on Earth. Many Africans grow up speaking three, four, or even more languages — a kind of everyday skill that would amaze people elsewhere."}, {"t": "p", "html": "For much of African history, the most important knowledge wasn't written in books — it was <b>spoken, sung, and remembered</b>. In West Africa, specially trained storytellers called <b>griots</b> (pronounced 'GREE-ohs') served as living libraries. A griot could recite a community's entire history, family trees going back centuries, great battles, and wise sayings — all from memory, often set to music. When a griot performed, the past came alive."}, {"t": "p", "html": "This tradition of <b>oral storytelling</b> kept cultures strong without a single written page. Folktales taught children right from wrong, often through clever animal characters. One of the most beloved is <b>Anansi the spider</b>, a trickster who wins through wit rather than strength. Anansi stories traveled with enslaved Africans across the ocean and survive today in the Caribbean and the Americas — proof that a good story can outlast almost anything."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> The English word 'banjo' likely comes from an African word for a similar string instrument. Enslaved Africans brought their musical traditions to the Americas, and those traditions became the roots of entire new kinds of music."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "star", "file": "African_drummers.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Steve Evans, CC BY 2.0", "caption": "Drummers keeping a community rhythm alive"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Music sits at the very heart of African life — not just for concerts, but for work, worship, weddings, harvests, and celebrations. A key feature is <b>polyrhythm</b>: several different rhythms played at once, layered together so they lock into something rich and danceable. Drums, often a family of them in different sizes, drive the beat, while 'call-and-response' singing lets a leader and a crowd answer each other, line by line."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Here is one of the most important cultural facts in all of world history: when millions of Africans were forcibly carried across the Atlantic during the slave trade, they brought their music in their memories. In the Americas, those African rhythms and the call-and-response style blended with other influences and grew into the <b>blues</b>. From the blues came <b>jazz</b>, then <b>rock and roll</b>, then <b>soul, funk, and hip-hop</b>. Nearly all popular music today carries African roots."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "African roots, global branches", "a": {"title": "African musical traditions", "items": ["Layered polyrhythms", "Call-and-response singing", "Drums of many sizes", "Music for daily life"]}, "b": {"title": "Music it helped create", "items": ["Blues and gospel", "Jazz", "Rock and roll", "Soul, funk, and hip-hop"]}}, {"t": "p", "html": "It's worth pausing on how unfair the old idea was that cultures without writing had 'no history.' A trained griot could carry centuries of names, dates, and events in memory, performing for hours without a single note. Passing knowledge by voice has its own strengths: stories can be shaped to the moment, sung with feeling, and shared with everyone, not just those who can read. Different ways of remembering are not lesser ways — they are simply other doors into the past."}, {"t": "p", "html": "African culture isn't only sound — it's also color and craft. Think of the bright, patterned <b>kente cloth</b> of Ghana, where each pattern carries a meaning; the elaborate beadwork and red robes of the <b>Maasai</b> in Kenya and Tanzania; or the carved <b>masks</b> used in ceremonies across the continent. These masks once amazed European artists like Picasso, who borrowed their bold shapes — another way African creativity reshaped art around the world."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> 'Oral tradition' means knowledge passed down by speaking and singing rather than writing. It's easy to assume that 'no writing' means 'no history' — but a griot's trained memory could hold more detail than many books. Different doesn't mean lesser."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> African music is booming worldwide again. 'Afrobeats' artists from Nigeria and Ghana fill stadiums across the globe, South African 'Amapiano' sets dance floors moving, and African musicians win top international awards. The rhythms that once crossed the ocean in memory now travel the world instantly — and everyone is dancing."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "A griot is performing at a gathering", "prompt": "You're a young person in the community. What's the wisest way to treat this moment?", "opts": [{"label": "Listen closely and remember the stories, so you can pass them on someday.", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "You become part of an ancient chain. Oral tradition only survives when each generation listens and carries it forward."}, {"label": "Assume it doesn't matter because it isn't written in a book.", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "You'd miss real history and wisdom. Spoken knowledge can be every bit as rich as written records."}, {"label": "Record a video to keep but never actually listen.", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Saving it is nice, but the heart of oral tradition is in truly hearing and remembering, not just storing a file."}]}], "quiz": [{"q": "About how many languages are spoken across Africa?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 50", "About 200", "About 500", "More than 2,000", "Just one"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Africa is home to more than 2,000 languages — about a third of all the languages on Earth.", "hint": "It's thousands."}, {"q": "What is a griot?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A type of drum", "A West African storyteller who keeps history by memory", "A kind of mask", "A musical festival", "A king"], "answer": 1, "explain": "A griot is a trained West African storyteller who preserves a community's history, family trees, and wisdom in memory, often with music.", "hint": "Think 'living library.'"}, {"q": "Swahili is spoken by over 100 million people in East Africa.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — Swahili is one of Africa's most widely spoken languages and a working language of the African Union."}, {"q": "Who is Anansi in African folktales?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A powerful king", "A clever trickster spider", "A great river", "A famous drummer", "A type of mask"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Anansi is a beloved trickster spider who wins through cleverness; his stories spread to the Caribbean and Americas.", "hint": "He's a spider known for wit."}, {"q": "What is 'polyrhythm' in African music?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Playing very quietly", "Several different rhythms layered at once", "Singing with no instruments", "Playing only one drum", "Music without any beat"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Polyrhythm means layering several rhythms together at the same time, creating rich, danceable music.", "hint": "'Poly' means many."}, {"q": "Which musical styles grew from African roots brought to the Americas?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Only classical music", "Blues, jazz, rock, soul, and hip-hop", "Only marching bands", "None of them", "Only opera"], "answer": 1, "explain": "African rhythms and call-and-response blended in the Americas to create blues, jazz, rock and roll, soul, funk, and hip-hop.", "hint": "These are some of the most popular music styles in the world."}, {"q": "Because African oral traditions weren't written down, they contained no real history.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — griots and oral traditions preserved detailed history and wisdom, sometimes more than written records."}, {"q": "What is 'call-and-response' in African music?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Two drums fighting", "A leader sings a line and a group answers back", "Playing music backwards", "Singing alone", "A type of dance only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "In call-and-response, a leader sings or plays a line and the group answers, line by line.", "hint": "It's like a musical conversation."}, {"q": "Kente cloth from Ghana is famous because:", "type": "mc", "options": ["It is always plain white", "Its bright patterns each carry meaning", "It is made of metal", "It cannot be worn", "It is used only for fishing"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Ghana's kente cloth is known for bright, patterned designs in which each pattern carries a meaning.", "hint": "Think colorful patterns with significance."}, {"q": "African masks influenced famous modern artists like Picasso.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — the bold shapes of African masks inspired European artists, another way African creativity shaped world art."}]});

  /* ============================================================
     AMERICAS
     ============================================================ */
  cont({
    id: "americas", name: "The Americas", emoji: "🗽", color: "#2e7d54",
    blurb: "Aztecs to modern nations",
    intro: "From mighty Indigenous empires to a “New World” of immigrants, revolutions, and superpowers — the story of two connected continents.",
    badge: { name: "Americas Master", emoji: "🗽" },
    lessons: ["am1", "am2", "am3", "am4", "am5", "am6", "am7", "am8", "am9", "am10", "am11"],
    sectionQuiz: [
      { q: "Which advanced civilization built pyramids in Mexico and had a great capital city on a lake?", type: "mc", options: ["The Aztecs", "The Romans", "The Vikings", "The Egyptians"], answer: 0, explain: "The Aztecs built Tenochtitlan on a lake — now Mexico City." },
      { q: "When Europeans arrived, the biggest killer of Indigenous peoples was…", type: "mc", options: ["Hunger", "New diseases like smallpox", "Cold weather", "Earthquakes"], answer: 1, explain: "Diseases the Indigenous peoples had never faced killed enormous numbers." },
      { q: "The United States declared independence from Britain in…", type: "mc", options: ["1492", "1776", "1865", "1969"], answer: 1, explain: "The Declaration of Independence was signed in 1776." },
      { q: "The US Civil War was fought largely over…", type: "mc", options: ["Tea taxes", "Slavery and whether states could leave the Union", "Gold", "Religion"], answer: 1, explain: "Slavery and the Union's survival were central to the Civil War." },
      { q: "The Inca Empire was located in…", type: "mc", options: ["The Andes Mountains of South America", "Canada", "the Caribbean", "Alaska"], answer: 0, explain: "The Inca ruled a vast Andean empire in western South America." },
      { q: "Millions of immigrants came to the Americas seeking…", type: "mc", options: ["A better life and opportunity", "Colder weather", "Fewer jobs", "War"], answer: 0, explain: "Immigrants sought opportunity, freedom, and a fresh start." },
      { q: "Simón Bolívar is famous for…", type: "mc", options: ["Painting", "Helping free much of South America from Spain", "Inventing the car", "Building pyramids"], answer: 1, explain: "Bolívar led independence movements across South America." },
      { q: "The Maya are especially known for advances in…", type: "mc", options: ["Astronomy, math, and writing", "Steam engines", "Gunpowder", "Sailing ships"], answer: 0, explain: "The Maya had advanced astronomy, math (including zero), and writing." },
      { q: "After WWII, the United States became a global superpower.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "The US emerged from WWII as one of the world's two superpowers." },
      { q: "The Americas today are home to many cultures because…", type: "mc", options: ["No one ever moved there", "Indigenous, European, African, and immigrant peoples all blended", "Only one group lives there", "It was always empty"], answer: 1, explain: "Indigenous, European, African, and later immigrant cultures all mixed." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({"id": "am1", "continent": "americas", "n": 1, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏛️", "title": "Indigenous Empires: Aztec, Maya & Inca", "hook": "<b>Long before any ship arrived from Europe, vast cities glittered across the Americas — with towering pyramids, written words, paved roads, and gardens that seemed to float on water.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Picture a city built on an island in the middle of a lake, linked to the shore by wide stone roads, with a marketplace louder than a stadium and gardens that seemed to float on the water. That city was real. It was <b>Tenochtitlán</b>, the Aztec capital, and in the year 1500 it held perhaps 200,000 people — larger than almost any city in Europe at the time. The Americas were never empty. They were home to thousands of cultures and several powerful empires, each with its own language, science, art, and history."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Three of the best-known empires are the <b>Maya</b>, the <b>Aztec</b>, and the <b>Inca</b>. They did not all live at the same time or place, and it helps to keep them apart in your mind. The Maya rose first, building stone cities across what is now southern Mexico and Central America. The Aztec built their empire much later, in the highlands of central Mexico. And far to the south, threaded along the Andes Mountains of South America, the Inca built the largest empire of all."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The <b>Maya</b> were brilliant thinkers and scientists. They developed one of the very few full writing systems ever invented in the Americas, carving their stories, kings, and battles into stone monuments that we can still read today. Their astronomers watched the night sky so carefully that their calendar was more accurate than the one used in Europe. They also understood and used the number <b>zero</b> centuries before many other cultures did — a powerful idea in mathematics."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The <b>Aztec</b> were master builders, traders, and organizers. On their lake-island capital they created floating garden beds called <b>chinampas</b> — woven from reeds and packed with rich black mud — so they could grow maize, beans, squash, and chili peppers right on the surface of the water. Their great market at Tlatelolco drew tens of thousands of buyers and sellers every single day, trading everything from gold and feathers to cacao beans, which were used as money."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The <b>Inca</b> ruled a mountain empire stretching about 4,000 kilometers down the spine of the Andes. They held it together with an astonishing network of roads — more than 40,000 kilometers of paved paths, with woven rope bridges swinging across deep canyons. Relay runners called <i>chasquis</i> sprinted between rest stations, carrying spoken messages and records stored on knotted, color-coded strings called <b>quipu</b>. To feed millions, the Inca carved <b>terraces</b> like green staircases into steep slopes and freeze-dried potatoes in the cold air to store for years."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "The Inca had no horses, no wheels for transport, and no written alphabet — yet they ran an empire of millions using stone roads, fast runners, terraced farms, and color-coded knotted strings to keep their records straight."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Empires in time", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "250", "label": "Maya cities flourish (Classic period begins)"}, {"yr": "1325", "label": "Aztecs found Tenochtitlán"}, {"yr": "1438", "label": "Inca empire begins rapid expansion"}, {"yr": "1500", "label": "Tenochtitlán among the world's largest cities"}]}, {"t": "scene", "art": "pyramids", "file": "Machu Picchu, Peru (2018).jpg", "credit": "Photo: Diego Delso, CC BY-SA 4.0", "caption": "Machu Picchu, an Inca royal estate in the Andes"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: When you read that a place was \"discovered,\" pause and ask — discovered by whom? Millions of people already lived in the Americas, with their own languages, sciences, and stories. \"First contact\" is a fairer phrase than \"discovery,\" because you cannot discover a home where people already live."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two great capitals", "a": {"title": "Tenochtitlán (Aztec)", "items": ["Built on a lake island", "Floating gardens (chinampas)", "Huge daily marketplace", "Causeways linked it to shore"]}, "b": {"title": "Cusco (Inca)", "items": ["High in the Andes Mountains", "Terraced farming on slopes", "Heart of a 4,000 km empire", "Linked by stone roads and runners"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "These cultures did not vanish into the past. Millions of people today still speak <b>Nahuatl</b> (the Aztec language), <b>Quechua</b> (the Inca language), and many Maya languages. Words you likely use — <i>chocolate</i>, <i>tomato</i>, <i>avocado</i>, <i>chili</i> — all come from Nahuatl. The descendants of these empires still farm the terraces, weave the patterns, and celebrate the festivals of their ancestors across the Americas right now."}, {"t": "p", "html": "It is easy to imagine the distant past as simpler than today, but these were complex societies full of engineers, astronomers, poets, merchants, priests, and farmers solving hard problems every day. Aztec children attended school, Maya scribes trained for years to master their writing, and Inca officials managed vast storehouses of food. Remembering all this helps us see the Americas as they truly were before 1492 — not an empty wilderness waiting to be found, but a world crowded with achievement, invention, debate, and human life, every bit as real, noisy, and busy as our own world is today."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Which empire built its capital on an island in a lake?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Maya", "The Inca", "The Aztec", "The Olmec", "The Inuit"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Aztec built Tenochtitlán on an island in Lake Texcoco, connected to shore by causeways.", "hint": "Think of the floating gardens."}, {"q": "The Inca empire ran mainly along which mountain range?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Rockies", "The Andes", "The Alps", "The Appalachians", "The Himalayas"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Inca empire stretched about 4,000 km down the Andes Mountains of South America.", "hint": "South America's great spine."}, {"q": "What were quipu used for by the Inca?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Cooking food", "Recording information with knotted strings", "Building bridges", "Playing music", "Telling time by the sun"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Quipu were knotted, color-coded strings the Inca used to store records and numbers.", "hint": "It involves strings and knots."}, {"q": "Which culture developed a full writing system and a very accurate calendar?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Aztec", "The Inca", "The Maya", "The Inuit", "The Shoshone"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Maya created one of the Americas' few full writing systems and tracked the stars with great precision.", "hint": "They also understood the number zero."}, {"q": "What were chinampas?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Inca rope bridges", "Aztec floating garden beds", "Maya temples", "Inca message runners", "Aztec war canoes"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Chinampas were floating garden plots the Aztec built to farm on the lake.", "hint": "They helped feed a city on water."}, {"q": "Roughly how long was the Inca road network?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 400 km", "About 4,000 km", "About 40,000 km", "About 400,000 km", "About 40 km"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Inca built over 40,000 km of roads, with relay runners and rope bridges.", "hint": "It was astonishingly large."}, {"q": "Which everyday word comes from the Aztec language Nahuatl?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Sandwich", "Chocolate", "Pizza", "Yogurt", "Cereal"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\"Chocolate,\" \"tomato,\" and \"avocado\" all come from Nahuatl, the Aztec language.", "hint": "It's sweet and brown."}, {"q": "The Americas were mostly empty before Europeans arrived.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Millions of people lived in the Americas, with many cultures and several large empires."}, {"q": "The Inca used terraces to farm on steep mountain slopes.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Terraces were like green staircases that let crops grow on steep land."}, {"q": "The Maya, Aztec, and Inca all lived at the very same time in the same place.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. They lived in different regions and rose to power at different times."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am2", "continent": "americas", "n": 2, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "⛵", "title": "Two Worlds Collide: European Arrival", "hook": "<b>In 1492 three small ships crossed the Atlantic — and two halves of the world that had never met were suddenly, and forever, connected.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "For thousands of years, the people of the Americas and the people of Europe, Africa, and Asia lived without knowing one another existed. Two enormous halves of the world, separated by vast oceans, each with its own crops, animals, languages, and ideas. Then, in 1492, an Italian sailor named <b>Christopher Columbus</b>, paid for by the rulers of Spain, sailed west hoping to reach Asia by a shorter route. He never reached Asia. Instead he landed in the islands of the Caribbean — and from that moment, history changed for everyone on Earth."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Columbus was not actually the first person from across the ocean to reach the Americas. Around the year 1000, Norse sailors — the Vikings — led by <b>Leif Erikson</b> had landed in what is now Canada and built a small settlement. But it did not last long, and the two worlds drifted apart again, each forgetting the other. Columbus's voyage was different because it did not fade away. It began permanent, large-scale contact that pulled the whole planet together. Soon many European nations were sending ships across the Atlantic — <b>Spain</b> and <b>Portugal</b> first, then <b>France</b>, <b>England</b>, and the <b>Netherlands</b> — seeking gold and silver, new land to farm, faster trade routes, and the chance to spread their religion. To the millions already living in the Americas, these arrivals were strangers with unfamiliar tools, strange animals like horses, and intentions that were not always friendly."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The meeting of the two worlds set off an enormous swap of plants, animals, foods, and ideas that historians call the <b>Columbian Exchange</b>. From the Americas came maize, potatoes, tomatoes, chili peppers, chocolate, and rubber — gifts that would reshape cooking everywhere. From Europe, Africa, and Asia came wheat, rice, sugar, and farm animals like horses, cattle, and pigs. This great exchange changed meals, farms, and landscapes on every single continent, and its effects are all around us still."}, {"t": "p", "html": "But the most powerful travelers in this exchange were invisible: <b>germs</b>. Europeans unknowingly carried diseases like smallpox and measles, which had never existed in the Americas. Because Indigenous peoples had never met these germs, their bodies had built up no resistance to them. Over the following century, these diseases spread faster than any army and caused a tremendous loss of life — a quiet tragedy that weakened many communities long before they ever laid eyes on a European."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "The horse, which later became central to many Native nations of the Great Plains, did not exist in the Americas before Europeans brought it. Within a few generations, peoples like the Comanche and the Lakota became some of the finest horse riders in the entire world."}, {"t": "order", "title": "First crossings", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1000", "label": "Norse reach Canada (Vinland)"}, {"yr": "1492", "label": "Columbus lands in the Caribbean"}, {"yr": "1500", "label": "Portugal reaches Brazil"}, {"yr": "1521", "label": "Aztec empire falls to Spain and allies"}]}, {"t": "scene", "art": "ship", "file": "Replica of the Santa María (Columbus's flagship).jpg", "credit": "Photo: Wikimedia Commons contributor, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "A modern replica of a 15th-century caravel"}, {"t": "p", "html": "In Mexico, the Spanish leader <b>Hernán Cortés</b> reached the powerful Aztec empire in 1519. The Aztec ruler <b>Moctezuma II</b> at first welcomed the strangers into his capital. But trust broke down and conflict grew. Cortés found powerful allies among other peoples who resented being ruled and taxed by the Aztec. With those allies, with steel weapons and horses, and with disease ravaging the crowded city, the Spanish toppled the empire by 1521. A strikingly similar story unfolded with the Inca a decade later."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: History is rarely one hero against one villain. The Spanish did not conquer alone — many Indigenous groups, harshly treated under Aztec rule, chose to fight alongside them for reasons of their own. Real events almost always have more than two sides, and good historians try to see them all."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "The Columbian Exchange", "a": {"title": "From the Americas", "items": ["Maize (corn)", "Potatoes", "Tomatoes", "Chocolate & chili peppers"]}, "b": {"title": "To the Americas", "items": ["Horses & cattle", "Wheat & rice", "Sugar cane", "New diseases"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Look at your dinner tonight. Italian tomato sauce, Irish potatoes, Swiss chocolate, Thai chili spice — none of these existed in Europe, Africa, or Asia before 1492. The Columbian Exchange still flavors nearly every meal on the planet, a quiet daily reminder of how deeply and permanently the two halves of the world became connected after that one voyage."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The collision of two worlds brought wonders and new connections, but it also brought conquest, disease, and the loss of independence for millions of people who had governed themselves for centuries. Both of these truths are real at the same time, and neither one erases the other. Holding the wonder and the harm together in our minds — refusing to forget either side — is exactly how we come to understand this enormous turning point honestly, and with genuine care for everyone whose life it changed forever."}], "quiz": [{"q": "In what year did Columbus first cross the Atlantic to the Americas?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1066", "1215", "1492", "1607", "1776"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Columbus reached the Caribbean in 1492, beginning permanent contact between the two worlds.", "hint": "\"In fourteen hundred ninety-two...\""}, {"q": "Who reached the Americas around the year 1000, long before Columbus?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Spanish", "The Norse (Vikings)", "The Portuguese", "The French", "The Dutch"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Norse sailors led by Leif Erikson reached Canada around 1000, but their settlement did not last.", "hint": "Think of longships and sagas."}, {"q": "What is the Columbian Exchange?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A type of money", "A swap of plants, animals, and germs between the worlds", "A peace treaty", "A sailing race", "A kind of ship"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It was the huge transfer of crops, livestock, and diseases between the Americas and the rest of the world.", "hint": "It changed dinner tables everywhere."}, {"q": "Which of these came FROM the Americas to the rest of the world?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Horses", "Wheat", "Potatoes", "Cattle", "Sugar cane"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Potatoes, maize, tomatoes, and chocolate all came from the Americas.", "hint": "Ireland became famous for it."}, {"q": "Why did disease cause such terrible loss among Indigenous peoples?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They refused medicine", "They had no resistance to new germs like smallpox", "The climate was too cold", "They lived too far apart", "They had no doctors"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Diseases like smallpox were new to the Americas, so people had no built-up resistance.", "hint": "The germs had never been there before."}, {"q": "Which leader reached and helped topple the Aztec empire?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Hernán Cortés", "Leif Erikson", "Simón Bolívar", "Christopher Columbus", "Moctezuma II"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Hernán Cortés, allied with rival Indigenous groups, brought down the Aztec empire by 1521.", "hint": "He arrived in Mexico in 1519."}, {"q": "Which animal, central to Plains nations, did NOT exist in the Americas before Europeans came?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The dog", "The bison", "The horse", "The deer", "The eagle"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Horses were brought by Europeans; Plains nations later became expert riders.", "hint": "It is ridden, not hunted."}, {"q": "Columbus was trying to reach the Americas on purpose.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. He was trying to reach Asia by sailing west and landed in the Caribbean instead."}, {"q": "The Spanish defeated the Aztec entirely on their own, with no Indigenous allies.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Many Indigenous groups who resented Aztec rule fought alongside the Spanish."}, {"q": "Tomatoes were eaten in Italy long before 1492.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Tomatoes came from the Americas and only reached Italy after the Columbian Exchange."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am3", "continent": "americas", "n": 3, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🌾", "title": "Slavery in the Americas", "hook": "<b>For over 300 years, millions of African people were carried across the ocean against their will — and through unimaginable hardship, they built families, cultures, and a spirit of freedom that endures to this day.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "This is a hard chapter, and we will tell it with honesty and care, because the people in it deserve nothing less. As Europeans built colonies across the Americas, they wanted workers to grow valuable crops like sugar, tobacco, and cotton on enormous farms called <b>plantations</b>. To get that labor cheaply, they turned to one of the cruelest systems in all of human history: the transatlantic <b>slave trade</b>. Understanding it honestly helps us understand the Americas we live in today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Between the 1500s and the 1800s, traders forced an estimated <b>12 million African people</b> onto ships bound for the Americas. Many were captured far inland, then marched to the coast and sold. They were torn away from their homes, their families, their languages, and everything familiar. The ocean crossing itself, known as the <b>Middle Passage</b>, was a journey of terrible crowding and suffering, and a great many people did not survive it. Every number in this history was once a living person."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Once in the Americas, enslaved people were treated as property under the law — bought, sold, separated from loved ones, and forced to work for life without pay or freedom. They labored on plantations across Brazil, the Caribbean, and what became the southern United States. It is important to say plainly and without flinching: slavery was a profound injustice, and the people who endured it were never, for one moment, less than fully and completely human."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Yet this is not only a story of suffering — it is also, powerfully, a story of <b>resilience</b>. Enslaved people protected their humanity in countless quiet and brave ways. They kept African music, foods, words, and spiritual traditions alive across generations. They built strong family and community bonds even when those bonds were cruelly torn apart. Their songs, called <b>spirituals</b>, carried both deep faith and hidden messages — sometimes even directions toward freedom."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Many people resisted in every way they could. Some worked slowly or quietly broke tools. Some ran away, following secret routes toward free regions or toward hidden communities of people who had escaped. In Haiti, enslaved people led by <b>Toussaint Louverture</b> rose up against their captors and, in 1804, won their freedom and founded a new nation — the first country in the world ever created by people who had freed themselves from slavery by their own hands."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "The <b>Underground Railroad</b> was not underground and was not a railroad. It was a secret network of brave guides and safe houses that helped enslaved people escape to freedom. The famous guide <b>Harriet Tubman</b> escaped slavery herself, then returned again and again to lead others to safety, never losing a single person she guided."}, {"t": "order", "title": "The long road to freedom", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1804", "label": "Haiti wins independence, ending slavery there"}, {"yr": "1833", "label": "Britain abolishes slavery in its empire"}, {"yr": "1865", "label": "Slavery ends in the United States"}, {"yr": "1888", "label": "Brazil abolishes slavery, last in the Americas"}]}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "African Burial Ground National Monument NYC.jpg", "credit": "Photo: National Park Service, Public Domain", "caption": "A memorial honoring enslaved people's lives"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: When studying painful history, look for the people, not just the numbers. \"12 million\" is almost impossible to picture — but every single one of them had a name, a family, a favorite food, a favorite song. History done well never forgets that each number was a whole human life."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two truths held together", "a": {"title": "The hardship", "items": ["Forced from home and family", "Unpaid, unfree labor for life", "The dangerous Middle Passage", "Treated as property by law"]}, "b": {"title": "The resilience", "items": ["Preserved music & traditions", "Built strong communities", "Resisted and escaped to freedom", "Led movements to end slavery"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "The cultures that enslaved people kept alive went on to shape the modern Americas in beautiful and lasting ways. <b>Jazz, blues, gospel, samba, and reggae</b> all grew from African roots planted in American soil. Foods, words, dances, and traditions woven into everyday life today carry that heritage proudly forward — a living testament to people who, against every effort to erase them, refused to be erased."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Slavery did not end on its own. A growing movement of <b>abolitionists</b>, both Black and white, argued that no human being should ever own another, and former captives like <b>Frederick Douglass</b> spoke and wrote so powerfully that the world could no longer look away. We study this history not to feel ashamed, but to honor the truth, remember the people who lived it, and carry forward the courage of their long fight for freedom."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What were the large farms that used enslaved labor called?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Factories", "Plantations", "Markets", "Harbors", "Terraces"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Plantations were large farms growing crops like sugar, tobacco, and cotton using enslaved labor.", "hint": "It starts with 'P'."}, {"q": "What was the Middle Passage?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A road across America", "The ocean crossing enslaved Africans were forced to make", "A trade agreement", "A type of ship", "A river in Brazil"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Middle Passage was the brutal Atlantic voyage that carried enslaved people to the Americas.", "hint": "It happened on the ocean."}, {"q": "Which country, founded in 1804, was created by people who freed themselves from slavery?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Brazil", "Cuba", "Haiti", "Mexico", "Jamaica"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Haiti won independence in 1804, the first nation founded by people who freed themselves from slavery.", "hint": "Toussaint Louverture led the uprising."}, {"q": "Who escaped slavery and returned many times to guide others to freedom?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Harriet Tubman", "Frederick Douglass", "Simón Bolívar", "Toussaint Louverture", "Abraham Lincoln"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Harriet Tubman led many enslaved people to freedom through the Underground Railroad.", "hint": "She is linked to the 'railroad' that wasn't a railroad."}, {"q": "What was the Underground Railroad?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A real train line underground", "A secret network of guides and safe houses for escape", "A mining tunnel", "A type of boat", "A code for trading goods"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It was a secret network helping enslaved people escape to free areas.", "hint": "Not actually a railroad."}, {"q": "What does it mean to 'abolish' slavery?", "type": "mc", "options": ["To expand it", "To officially end it", "To ignore it", "To tax it", "To celebrate it"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Abolitionists worked to end slavery completely.", "hint": "It means to get rid of it."}, {"q": "Which music styles grew from African roots in the Americas?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Jazz and blues", "Polka and waltz", "Opera and ballet", "March and anthem", "None of these"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Jazz, blues, gospel, samba, and reggae all have African roots in the Americas.", "hint": "Think New Orleans and Brazil."}, {"q": "Slavery in the Americas ended quickly and on its own.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. People fought for many years through resistance and the abolitionist movement to end it."}, {"q": "Enslaved people preserved their own music, foods, and traditions.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Preserving culture was one powerful way people protected their humanity."}, {"q": "Brazil was one of the last countries in the Americas to abolish slavery.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Brazil abolished slavery in 1888, the last nation in the Americas to do so."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am4", "continent": "americas", "n": 4, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🗽", "title": "Revolutions: The Americas Become Free", "hook": "<b>In just fifty years, colony after colony across the Americas declared that people should govern themselves — and a great wave of revolutions swept the entire hemisphere.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "By the 1700s, almost all of the Americas was ruled from far across the ocean — by Britain, Spain, Portugal, or France. The people living there, even those born in the colonies, often had little or no say in their own laws, taxes, or trade. They were governed by kings and parliaments thousands of kilometers away who rarely set foot in the lands they ruled. Then, in a single remarkable span of time, a daring idea caught fire across two continents: that ordinary people had the right to rule themselves."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The first great spark came in the thirteen British colonies of North America. Colonists grew angry at being taxed by a government in London in which they had no elected representatives — \"no taxation without representation,\" they argued. In <b>1776</b>, they issued the <b>Declaration of Independence</b>, announcing the birth of the United States of America and declaring boldly that all people are born with rights that no king has the power to take away."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Winning those brave words on the battlefield was a far harder task. The American Revolutionary War dragged on for years, and the outnumbered colonists were helped enormously by <b>France</b>, which sent soldiers, ships, money, and supplies. By 1783 the United States had secured its independence, and soon afterward its leaders wrote a <b>Constitution</b> — a written plan of government, with elected leaders and divided powers, that the country still uses today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The idea of independence spread quickly southward. Across Spanish America, a brilliant and determined leader named <b>Simón Bolívar</b> — often called \"El Libertador,\" the Liberator — led armies that freed a whole string of nations, including Venezuela, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, and Bolivia, which is proudly named after him. Meanwhile, in the far south, <b>José de San Martín</b> led campaigns that helped free Argentina, Chile, and Peru from Spanish rule."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Not every revolution looked the same. Brazil took a quieter path: rather than fighting a long war, it became independent from Portugal in <b>1822</b> when the Portuguese prince living there simply declared Brazil a separate empire. And as we learned earlier, Haiti had already won its freedom back in 1804 — the only one of all these revolutions led by enslaved people fighting for their own liberty. Together, these movements remade the map of an entire hemisphere."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "The famous phrase \"all men are created equal\" inspired people far beyond those who first wrote it. Over the following centuries, many groups — including women, enslaved people, and the poor — pointed straight back at those very words to demand that the promise finally be extended to everyone, not just a few."}, {"t": "order", "title": "A wave of independence", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1776", "label": "United States declares independence"}, {"yr": "1804", "label": "Haiti wins independence"}, {"yr": "1822", "label": "Brazil becomes independent from Portugal"}, {"yr": "1825", "label": "Bolívar's campaigns free Bolivia"}]}, {"t": "scene", "art": "star", "file": "Declaration of Independence (1819), by John Trumbull.jpg", "credit": "Painting: John Trumbull, Public Domain", "caption": "Presenting the Declaration of Independence, 1776"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: A revolution's first promises are often much bigger than its first results. Many brand-new nations declared all people equal, yet still allowed slavery or denied women the vote. Watching how nations slowly grow toward living up to their own stated ideals — over many generations — is one of the most important parts of studying history."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You are a colonist in 1775", "prompt": "Your colony is taxed by a faraway government you cannot vote for. Leaders are debating what to do. What do you argue for?", "opts": [{"label": "Demand a fair say in how you are taxed before anything else", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Reasonable and principled — \"no taxation without representation\" became the rallying cry that united the whole movement."}, {"label": "Refuse all taxes and attack the soldiers immediately", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Acting rashly could spark violence before people are united or ready — many revolutions collapsed exactly this way."}, {"label": "Pay quietly and hope the rules change on their own someday", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Understandable and safe, but change rarely arrives for those who never ask for it. Many people felt this way at first."}]}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Today the Americas hold dozens of independent countries, from Canada in the north to Argentina in the south, most of them governed by leaders the people themselves elect. The once-daring, once-dangerous revolutionary idea that <b>people should choose their own government</b> is now one of the most common and widely shared ideas in the entire world. To a remarkable degree, that global idea began right here in the Americas."}, {"t": "p", "html": "These revolutions did not make everything fair overnight, and we should be honest about that. But they planted a powerful seed that keeps growing: the belief that governments should serve the people, and not the other way around. Generation after generation has worked, argued, and sometimes struggled to make that promise more true — and that hopeful, unfinished project continues right up to today."}], "quiz": [{"q": "In what year did the United States declare independence?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1492", "1620", "1776", "1804", "1822"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Declaration of Independence was issued in 1776.", "hint": "It's celebrated on the Fourth of July."}, {"q": "Which leader is called 'El Libertador' for freeing several South American nations?", "type": "mc", "options": ["George Washington", "Simón Bolívar", "Toussaint Louverture", "José de San Martín", "Hernán Cortés"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Simón Bolívar, the Liberator, freed nations including Venezuela, Colombia, and Bolivia.", "hint": "A country is named after him."}, {"q": "Which country gave major help to the American colonists in their war?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Spain", "Portugal", "France", "Russia", "China"], "answer": 2, "explain": "France sent soldiers, ships, and money, which was crucial to American victory.", "hint": "It later had its own revolution."}, {"q": "How did Brazil become independent in 1822?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Through a long war", "A Portuguese prince declared it a separate empire", "Enslaved people overthrew the king", "Spain freed it", "Britain bought it"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Brazil gained independence peacefully when the Portuguese prince declared it separate from Portugal.", "hint": "It was a quieter path than most."}, {"q": "Which revolution was led by enslaved people fighting for their own freedom?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The United States", "Haiti", "Brazil", "Argentina", "Mexico"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Haiti's revolution, won in 1804, was led by enslaved people seeking their own liberty.", "hint": "It came before most of the others."}, {"q": "The country Bolivia is named after which leader?", "type": "mc", "options": ["José de San Martín", "Simón Bolívar", "Christopher Columbus", "Pedro I", "Benjamin Franklin"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Bolivia is named after Simón Bolívar, the Liberator.", "hint": "Listen to the name closely."}, {"q": "Why did revolutions spread so quickly across the Americas?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Everyone was related", "New ideas about liberty spread, and nations inspired each other", "Kings ordered it", "There was no other choice", "The weather changed"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Ideas about liberty and self-government spread, and successful revolutions encouraged others.", "hint": "Revolutions can be contagious."}, {"q": "Before these revolutions, most of the Americas was ruled by faraway European nations.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Britain, Spain, Portugal, and France ruled most of the Americas before independence."}, {"q": "The new nations instantly made everyone fully equal in practice.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Many still allowed slavery or denied women the vote; equality grew slowly over time."}, {"q": "The American Revolution was won without any foreign help.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. France's soldiers, ships, and money were vital to the colonists' victory."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am5", "continent": "americas", "n": 5, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🚂", "title": "The US: Civil War & Westward Expansion", "hook": "<b>A young nation stretched from one ocean to the other — then nearly tore itself in two over the terrible question of whether one person could own another.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "In the 1800s, the United States grew with breathtaking speed. New land, new railroads, and millions of new arrivals pushed the country steadily westward across the continent. Towns sprang up almost overnight, and the map seemed to change every year. But beneath all that growth ran a deep and dangerous crack: the nation was half free and half built on slavery, and those two halves, pulling in opposite directions, could not hold together forever."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The country spread west in great waves. In the <b>Louisiana Purchase</b> of 1803, it bought a vast stretch of territory from France, roughly doubling the size of the nation overnight. Pioneers in covered wagons, miners chasing gold, and later the railroads all pushed toward the Pacific Ocean. Many Americans called this movement \"westward expansion\" and believed it was the country's destiny to stretch all the way from the Atlantic to the western sea."}, {"t": "p", "html": "But the West was not an empty wilderness waiting to be filled. It was home to many <b>Native American nations</b> who had lived on those lands for countless generations, with their own governments, languages, and ways of life. As settlers poured in, these nations were pushed off their homelands through treaties that were frequently broken and through forced removals like the heartbreaking <b>Trail of Tears</b>. Their story — of deep loss, but also of survival and enduring cultural strength — is a vital part of this history."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Meanwhile, the disagreement over slavery grew unbearable. The economy of the Southern states leaned heavily on enslaved labor, while many Northern states had already ended slavery and wanted to stop it from spreading into the new western lands. When <b>Abraham Lincoln</b> was elected president in 1860, several Southern states broke away to form their own separate country, the Confederacy, and in 1861 the <b>Civil War</b> began. It would become the deadliest war in American history."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The war was fought between the Northern states, called the <b>Union</b>, and the breakaway Southern states, the <b>Confederacy</b>. Hundreds of thousands of soldiers fought and died over four long years, and almost no family in the country was left untouched. In 1863, President Lincoln issued the <b>Emancipation Proclamation</b>, declaring enslaved people in the rebelling states to be free and giving the war a clear moral purpose. Many formerly enslaved men joined the Union army to fight for that freedom. The Union finally won in 1865. The nation stayed whole, and soon afterward slavery was abolished across the entire country, ending a system that had stained it since its founding."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "On the very same day in 1869, a golden spike was hammered into place to join the eastern and western railroad lines, completing the first <b>transcontinental railroad</b>. A journey across the country that once took many dangerous months by wagon could now be made in about a single week by train."}, {"t": "order", "title": "A nation transformed", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1803", "label": "Louisiana Purchase doubles U.S. size"}, {"yr": "1861", "label": "Civil War begins"}, {"yr": "1863", "label": "Emancipation Proclamation"}, {"yr": "1869", "label": "Transcontinental railroad completed"}]}, {"t": "scene", "art": "star", "file": "Abraham Lincoln O-77 matte collodion print.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Alexander Gardner, Public Domain", "caption": "Abraham Lincoln, U.S. president during the Civil War"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: When a war has two sides, ask carefully what each one was fighting for. The Civil War had several causes, but at its very heart sat the question of slavery — whether it would spread, survive, or finally end. Naming the central issue clearly and honestly, without dodging it, is an important part of telling history well."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "A divided nation in 1861", "a": {"title": "The North (Union)", "items": ["More factories and cities", "Slavery mostly ended", "Wanted to keep the nation whole", "Led by President Lincoln"]}, "b": {"title": "The South (Confederacy)", "items": ["Farming and plantation economy", "Depended on enslaved labor", "Broke away to form its own nation", "Wanted slavery to continue"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "The railroad that once stitched the country together still carries goods from coast to coast today, and the Civil War's outcome — one united nation with slavery abolished — shaped the United States we know now. The long work of making the country's founding promise of equality real for everyone continued through the civil rights movement of the 1900s and continues in different forms today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "This era shows a single nation growing and nearly breaking apart at the very same time. It expanded across an entire continent, ended slavery, and managed to hold itself together — but all of it came at a great cost, and with deep injustices, especially toward Native Americans driven from their lands and toward Black Americans whose freedom was finally won yet whose full equality still lay far ahead."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What did the Louisiana Purchase of 1803 do?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Started the Civil War", "Roughly doubled the size of the United States", "Ended slavery", "Built the railroad", "Freed Native lands"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The U.S. bought a huge territory from France, roughly doubling its size.", "hint": "It was a land deal with France."}, {"q": "Who was U.S. president during the Civil War?", "type": "mc", "options": ["George Washington", "Simón Bolívar", "Abraham Lincoln", "Thomas Jefferson", "Frederick Douglass"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Abraham Lincoln led the Union through the Civil War.", "hint": "He issued the Emancipation Proclamation."}, {"q": "The Civil War was mainly fought between which two sides?", "type": "mc", "options": ["North and South", "East and West", "France and Britain", "Settlers and railroads", "City and country"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The Union (North) fought the Confederacy (South).", "hint": "Think of a divided nation by region."}, {"q": "What did the Emancipation Proclamation of 1863 declare?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The war was over", "Enslaved people in rebelling states were free", "A new railroad would be built", "Louisiana was purchased", "The South had won"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It declared enslaved people in the rebelling states to be free.", "hint": "'Emancipation' means freeing."}, {"q": "What was the Trail of Tears?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A railroad route", "A forced removal of Native Americans from their lands", "A Civil War battle", "A river journey west", "A trade road"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It was a tragic forced removal of Native American nations from their homelands.", "hint": "It involved deep loss for Native peoples."}, {"q": "What did the transcontinental railroad, finished in 1869, make possible?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Crossing the country in about a week instead of months", "Ending the Civil War", "Doubling U.S. land", "Freeing enslaved people", "Flying across the country"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The railroad cut a cross-country trip from months to roughly a week.", "hint": "It was about speed of travel."}, {"q": "What was Reconstruction?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Building the railroad", "The period of rebuilding the South and granting rights after the war", "A Native American treaty", "A western settlement", "The start of the war"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Reconstruction was the effort to rebuild the South and extend rights to formerly enslaved people after the war.", "hint": "It came after the war ended."}, {"q": "The American West was empty before settlers arrived.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Many Native American nations had lived there for generations."}, {"q": "The Union (North) won the Civil War, and slavery was abolished.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. The Union won in 1865 and slavery was ended across the country."}, {"q": "Full equality was achieved immediately after the Civil War.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Progress was uneven, and the struggle for equality continued for generations."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am6", "continent": "americas", "n": 6, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏭", "title": "Industry & the Great Wave of Immigration", "hook": "<b>Smokestacks rose, machines roared, and millions of hopeful newcomers sailed into harbor — together they remade the Americas within a single lifetime.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "In the late 1800s and early 1900s, the Americas — and especially the United States — transformed faster than almost any place in history had ever changed before. Factories sprang up by the thousands, cities swelled with people, and a great wave of newcomers arrived from across the seas in search of work and a fresh start. This was the age of <b>industry</b> and <b>immigration</b>, two huge forces sweeping together, and between them they built the modern world we still live in."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The <b>Industrial Revolution</b> had reached the Americas in full force. Instead of making goods slowly by hand, factories now used powerful machines and clever assembly lines to produce them quickly and cheaply. Steel mills, textile factories, and meatpacking plants employed thousands of workers each. A burst of new inventions — the electric light bulb, the telephone, and soon the automobile — changed ordinary daily life so completely that grandparents could barely recognize the world their grandchildren grew up in."}, {"t": "p", "html": "All those roaring factories needed workers, and workers came by the millions. Between roughly 1880 and 1920, more than <b>20 million immigrants</b> arrived in the United States alone — from Italy, Ireland, Poland, Germany, Russia, China, Mexico, and dozens of other places besides. At the same time, millions more poured into Argentina, Brazil, and Canada, all drawn by the same powerful promise of land, jobs, and the chance to build a better life than the one they had left behind."}, {"t": "p", "html": "For many sailing into New York Harbor, the very first thing they glimpsed was the <b>Statue of Liberty</b> — a gift from France — holding her torch high above the water. Most newcomers then passed through <b>Ellis Island</b>, where officials checked their health and carefully wrote down their names. For families who had crossed an entire ocean with everything they owned packed into a single trunk, that moment was filled with hope and fear, exhaustion and excitement, all tangled together at once."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Life for newcomers was rarely easy once they arrived. Many crowded into busy, noisy city neighborhoods, worked long hours for very low pay, and often faced suspicion or unfair treatment from people already living there. Children sometimes worked in dangerous factories instead of going to school. Over time, workers began to organize themselves into <b>labor unions</b> to demand safer conditions, shorter hours, and fairer wages — and they won many of the basic workplace rights we still rely on today."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "Many people believe immigrants' names were changed against their will at Ellis Island, but that is mostly a myth. Officials worked from passenger lists written down back in the home country. Newcomers themselves often chose to adjust or shorten their own names later, hoping to fit in more easily in their new home."}, {"t": "order", "title": "The age of industry", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1876", "label": "Telephone invented"}, {"yr": "1879", "label": "Practical light bulb developed"}, {"yr": "1886", "label": "Statue of Liberty dedicated"}, {"yr": "1892", "label": "Ellis Island opens"}]}, {"t": "scene", "art": "factory", "file": "Immigrants entering the United States through Ellis Island.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Edwin Levick, Public Domain", "caption": "Immigrants arriving at Ellis Island, early 1900s"}, {"t": "guide", "html": "Owl tip: Big numbers like \"20 million immigrants\" can quietly hide individual stories. Behind every one of those numbers stood a real person who said goodbye to home, crossed a vast and frightening ocean, and bravely started life over among total strangers. Whenever you meet a huge number in history, try to picture just one of the people inside it."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You are a new arrival in 1905", "prompt": "You have just reached the city with little money and few contacts. How do you begin to build a new life?", "opts": [{"label": "Settle near others from your homeland and learn from neighbors", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Smart — these tight-knit neighborhoods helped newcomers find jobs, housing, and friendship while they found their feet in a strange new place."}, {"label": "Spend your last savings on a faraway risky venture right away", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Bold but dangerous — without any safety net, a single failure could leave you with nothing in an unfamiliar land."}, {"label": "Take the first low-paying factory job and keep your head down", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "This is what most people did at first. It was hard and tiring, but steady work was often the very first step toward something better."}]}, {"t": "modern", "html": "The Americas today are among the most diverse places anywhere on Earth, shaped by centuries of newcomers arriving and adding something of their own. The food on your plate, the music in your headphones, and many of the words you speak almost certainly carry pieces of many different homelands. That ongoing blending of cultures — sometimes bumpy, often beautiful — remains a defining feature of the modern Americas."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The age of industry and immigration built towering skylines and gleaming railroads, but more importantly it built people — communities of astonishing variety, side by side. In the end it is a story of hard work, hope, struggle, and the simple but powerful wish shared by people everywhere across all of history: the wish to make a better life for yourself and for the children who come after you."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What did factories use to make goods quickly during the Industrial Revolution?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Only hand tools", "Machines and assembly lines", "Horses", "Sailing ships", "Magic"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Factories used machines and assembly lines to produce goods fast and cheaply.", "hint": "It replaced slow handmade work."}, {"q": "Roughly how many immigrants came to the United States between about 1880 and 1920?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 2,000", "About 200,000", "About 2 million", "About 20 million", "About 200 million"], "answer": 3, "explain": "More than 20 million immigrants arrived in the U.S. during this period.", "hint": "It was a truly enormous wave."}, {"q": "What did many immigrants see first when sailing into New York Harbor?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Eiffel Tower", "The Statue of Liberty", "A railroad", "A pyramid", "The White House"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Statue of Liberty, a gift from France, greeted ships entering the harbor.", "hint": "She holds a torch."}, {"q": "What was Ellis Island?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A factory", "An immigration station where arrivals were processed", "A battlefield", "A railroad stop", "A prison"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Ellis Island was where many immigrants were checked and recorded upon arrival.", "hint": "It was the gateway for newcomers."}, {"q": "Why did workers form labor unions?", "type": "mc", "options": ["To build statues", "To demand safer conditions, shorter hours, and fair pay", "To stop immigration", "To start the Industrial Revolution", "To run factories"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Unions organized workers to win safer conditions, shorter hours, and fair wages.", "hint": "It was about workers' rights."}, {"q": "Which invention from this era changed daily life?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The light bulb", "The wheel", "The printing press", "The compass", "The telescope"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The light bulb, telephone, and automobile all transformed daily life in this era.", "hint": "It lights up a room."}, {"q": "Besides the U.S., which countries also drew many immigrants in this era?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Argentina, Brazil, and Canada", "Only Mexico", "No other countries", "Japan and Korea", "Egypt and Greece"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Argentina, Brazil, and Canada also welcomed millions of newcomers.", "hint": "Think north and far south."}, {"q": "The Industrial Revolution made goods slower and more expensive.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Factories and machines made goods faster and cheaper."}, {"q": "Immigration made the Americas more culturally diverse.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Immigrants brought foods, languages, music, and traditions from around the world."}, {"q": "Most immigrants' names were officially changed by officials at Ellis Island.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. That is mostly a myth; officials used ship records, and people often changed names themselves later."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am7", "continent": "americas", "n": 7, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🚀", "title": "Modern Americas: Superpower & Neighbors", "hook": "<b>In 1969, two people from one American country walked on the Moon — and the whole planet watched together.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "The Americas stretch from the icy top of Canada to the windy bottom of Argentina. In the last hundred years, this part of the world became one of the busiest stages in human history — full of invention, music, machines, and big ideas. Let's meet the modern Americas: a powerful neighbourhood of many nations learning to share a hemisphere."}, {"t": "p", "html": "After the year 1900, the <b>United States</b> grew into what people call a <i>superpower</i> — a country whose money, machines, and culture reach almost everywhere. Its factories built cars and aeroplanes; its scientists split atoms and sent rockets to space; its films and songs travelled to every continent. By the middle of the century, choices made in Washington could ripple across the whole world."}, {"t": "p", "html": "But a superpower is only one house on the street. To the north sits <b>Canada</b> — the second-largest country on Earth by area, yet home to fewer people than many single cities. Canada speaks two main languages, English and French, and is famous for vast forests, frozen lakes, and a gentle, careful style of politics."}, {"t": "p", "html": "To the south lies <b>Mexico</b>, where ancient Aztec and Maya roots blend with Spanish history into a vivid modern culture. Mexico City is one of the largest cities on the planet. Beyond it spreads <b>Latin America</b> — dozens of nations from Guatemala to Chile — sharing Spanish or Portuguese languages and deep, mixed traditions."}, {"t": "p", "html": "For much of the 1900s, the world split into two giant teams in a tense rivalry called the <b>Cold War</b> — the United States on one side, the Soviet Union on the other. It was 'cold' because the two never fought each other directly. Instead they competed in science, sport, and especially the race to space."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Apollo_11_first_step.jpg", "credit": "Photo: NASA, public domain", "caption": "Apollo 11 astronaut steps onto the Moon, 1969"}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Wild but true:</b> When Apollo 11 landed on the Moon in 1969, an estimated 600 million people — about one in every six humans alive — watched or listened. It is still one of the most-shared moments in history."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Build the timeline", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1903", "label": "Wright brothers fly the first powered aeroplane"}, {"yr": "1945", "label": "World War II ends; the Cold War begins"}, {"yr": "1969", "label": "Apollo 11 lands humans on the Moon"}, {"yr": "1989", "label": "The Cold War winds down"}, {"yr": "1994", "label": "Canada, the US and Mexico open free trade"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "These neighbours don't just share borders — they share a lot of work. Trucks rumble between Mexico, the United States, and Canada carrying car parts, fruit, and computers. A single car might be designed in Detroit, built partly in Ontario, and assembled with engines from Mexico. The three countries are tied together like links in a chain."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Three neighbours, three flavours", "a": {"title": "United States", "items": ["Huge economy and tech", "English-speaking, very diverse", "Famous for film, music, space"]}, "b": {"title": "Canada & Mexico", "items": ["Canada: bilingual, forests, calm politics", "Mexico: ancient roots, huge cities", "Both: deeply tied to US trade"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> 'Superpower' describes <i>influence</i> — how far a country's choices reach — not whether it is good or bad. Strong neighbours can disagree and still trade, travel, and solve problems together. Power and friendship aren't opposites."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> The modern Americas are knitted together by trade deals, shared rivers, migration, and the internet. People argue about borders and money — that's normal between neighbours — but a banana in a Canadian lunchbox, a song from Mexico topping US charts, and a phone designed across three countries all show how connected this hemisphere has become."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What does it mean to call a country a 'superpower'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Its influence reaches across much of the world", "It has the most mountains", "It has the oldest buildings", "It is the smallest country", "It has no neighbours"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A superpower's money, ideas, and choices ripple far beyond its borders.", "hint": "Think about reach and influence, not size of land."}, {"q": "Why was the Cold War called 'cold'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It happened only in winter", "The two main rivals never fought each other directly", "It was fought in the Arctic", "Nobody cared about it", "It lasted only one year"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The US and Soviet Union competed fiercely but never battled each other head-on.", "hint": "Think about a rivalry without direct fighting."}, {"q": "Canada is famous for speaking which two main languages?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Spanish and Portuguese", "English and French", "French and German", "English and Spanish", "Dutch and English"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Canada is officially bilingual in English and French.", "hint": "One language traces back to settlers from across the Channel from England."}, {"q": "Which event in 1969 was watched by hundreds of millions worldwide?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The first powered flight", "The Apollo 11 Moon landing", "The end of World War II", "The opening of free trade", "The first computer"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Apollo 11 put humans on the Moon, watched by about 600 million people.", "hint": "It involved a rocket and a famous footstep."}, {"q": "Mexico's modern culture blends Spanish history with which ancient roots?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Roman and Greek", "Viking and Celtic", "Aztec and Maya", "Egyptian and Persian", "Inca and Mongol"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Mexico's heritage mixes Aztec and Maya peoples with Spanish influence.", "hint": "These civilisations built great pyramids in Mesoamerica."}, {"q": "What makes the US, Canada and Mexico economically connected?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They share one government", "They trade goods like cars and food across borders", "They use the same money", "They have identical flags", "They speak only one language"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Free trade lets parts and products flow across all three borders.", "hint": "Think about trucks crossing borders with car parts."}, {"q": "Canada is the second-largest country in the world by what measure?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Population", "Number of cities", "Tallest mountains", "Land area", "Number of languages"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Canada is huge in area but has a relatively small population.", "hint": "It's about space, not people."}, {"q": "The Cold War's space race was a competition between the US and the Soviet Union.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Both nations raced to achieve milestones in space, including reaching the Moon."}, {"q": "A superpower can never trade or cooperate with its neighbours.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Strong countries often trade and solve problems with neighbours, even when they disagree."}, {"q": "Mexico City is one of the largest cities on the planet.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Mexico City is among the world's biggest urban areas by population."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am8", "continent": "americas", "n": 8, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🌎", "title": "From the Arctic to the Amazon: The Geography of the Americas", "hook": "<b>One unbroken backbone of mountains runs almost from the North Pole to the bottom of the world.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Imagine walking from frozen Arctic ice, through pine forests, across hot deserts, and into a steaming rainforest — without ever leaving one pair of connected continents. The Americas hold nearly every kind of landscape Earth can make. Pack your boots; we're touring the wildest geography on the planet."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Start with the mountains. Down the western edge runs an enormous spine: the <b>Rocky Mountains</b> in North America and the <b>Andes</b> in South America. The Andes are the longest mountain range on Earth above sea level, stretching about 7,000 kilometres. Many peaks wear snow even though they sit near the warm Equator — because the higher you climb, the colder the air."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Now the rivers. The mighty <b>Amazon</b> in South America carries more water than the next several biggest rivers combined. Around it spreads the <b>Amazon rainforest</b>, a green world so vast it makes a huge share of the planet's oxygen and shelters more kinds of plants and animals than almost anywhere else."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In North America, the <b>Mississippi River</b> drains a giant slice of the continent, gathering water from dozens of smaller rivers before reaching the sea. Near the US–Canada border lie the <b>Great Lakes</b> — five connected lakes holding so much fresh water they look like inland seas. You cannot see across them."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Amazon_Rainforest.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Neil Palmer/CIAT, CC BY-SA 2.0", "caption": "The Amazon rainforest from above"}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Wild but true:</b> The Great Lakes together hold about one-fifth of all the fresh surface water on Earth. If you spread that water over the lower United States, it would cover the whole region about three metres deep."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Americas also stretch through almost every climate zone. At the far north, the <b>Arctic</b> is a land of ice, polar bears, and long dark winters. Near the Equator, rainforests drip with daily downpours. In between sit prairies, deserts like the Atacama (one of the driest places on Earth), and grasslands roamed by wildlife."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two ends of one world", "a": {"title": "The Arctic North", "items": ["Frozen sea ice and tundra", "Polar bears, seals, caribou", "Months of winter darkness"]}, "b": {"title": "The Amazon Tropics", "items": ["Hot, wet rainforest", "Jaguars, monkeys, macaws", "Rain almost every day"]}}, {"t": "p", "html": "Why so much variety? Latitude — how far you are from the Equator — is a big reason. Land near the Equator gets steady, strong sunlight, so it's warm. Land near the poles gets weak, slanted sunlight, so it's cold. Mountains add their own twist: climb high enough anywhere and you'll find winter waiting."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You're a young explorer", "prompt": "You want to see snow but you're standing near the warm Equator in Ecuador. What's the smartest move?", "opts": [{"label": "Climb high into the Andes mountains", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Correct! Altitude brings cold. Even at the Equator, tall peaks stay snowy."}, {"label": "Wait for winter at the beach", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Near the Equator there's no cold winter at sea level — you'd wait forever."}, {"label": "Travel thousands of km north first", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "That works eventually, but the mountains are right beside you — much closer."}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Two things control temperature on a map: <i>latitude</i> (distance from the Equator) and <i>altitude</i> (height above the sea). Remember both, and you can guess the weather of almost any place before you ever pack a bag."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> These landscapes aren't just scenery — they're life support. The Amazon helps balance the planet's air, the Andes feed rivers that millions drink from, and the Great Lakes supply water to huge cities. Geographers, scientists, and local communities now work to protect them, because what happens in one biome can ripple across the whole world."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Which is the longest mountain range above sea level on Earth?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Rocky Mountains", "The Andes", "The Alps", "The Appalachians", "The Himalayas"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Andes run about 7,000 km down western South America.", "hint": "It runs along South America's western edge."}, {"q": "Why can mountains near the Equator still have snow?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Equator is actually cold", "Higher altitude means colder air", "Snow falls only at night there", "They are made of ice", "The Sun avoids them"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Temperature drops as you climb, so tall peaks stay cold even near the Equator.", "hint": "Think about climbing higher into thinner, colder air."}, {"q": "What is special about the Amazon River?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It is the coldest river", "It carries more water than the next several biggest rivers combined", "It flows uphill", "It is entirely frozen", "It is the shortest river"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Amazon's flow is enormous — more than several other giant rivers together.", "hint": "Think about sheer volume of water."}, {"q": "The Great Lakes hold roughly what share of Earth's fresh surface water?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About one-hundredth", "About one-fifth", "All of it", "None of it", "About one-half"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The five Great Lakes hold about a fifth of the planet's fresh surface water.", "hint": "It's a large but not majority fraction."}, {"q": "Which river drains a giant slice of central North America?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Amazon", "The Mississippi", "The Nile", "The Thames", "The Danube"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Mississippi gathers water from many rivers across central North America.", "hint": "It's a North American river, not South American."}, {"q": "The Atacama is famous for being one of the world's ______ places.", "type": "mc", "options": ["wettest", "driest", "coldest", "tallest", "greenest"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Atacama Desert is among the driest places on Earth.", "hint": "Think desert."}, {"q": "Which two factors most control how warm a place is?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Latitude and altitude", "Colour and shape", "Population and roads", "Flags and money", "Day of the week and luck"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Distance from the Equator and height above sea level largely set temperature.", "hint": "One is about north-south position; the other about height."}, {"q": "The Amazon rainforest produces a large share of the planet's oxygen.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Its vast plant life makes the Amazon hugely important for Earth's air."}, {"q": "The Arctic and the Amazon have nearly identical climates.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Arctic is frozen; the Amazon is hot and wet — about as different as climates get."}, {"q": "You can easily see across the Great Lakes to the other side.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "They are so large they look like inland seas — you usually cannot see across them."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am9", "continent": "americas", "n": 9, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🪶", "title": "The First Peoples of North America", "hook": "<b>Long before any ship arrived, hundreds of nations already lived across North America — each with its own language, laws, and stories.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "When we say 'Native Americans,' it's easy to imagine one single group. But North America was home to <i>hundreds</i> of distinct nations, as different from each other as Norway is from Greece. Let's meet a few, and discover a council of nations whose ideas about working together still echo today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "On the wide grasslands of the <b>Great Plains</b> lived nations like the Lakota, Cheyenne, and Comanche. For part of their history they followed the great herds of bison, which gave them food, clothing, tools, and shelter. After horses arrived, some Plains peoples became famously skilled riders, crossing huge distances across the open land."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In the dry southwest, the <b>Pueblo</b> peoples — including the Hopi and Zuni — built homes of stone and sun-dried clay, sometimes stacked several storeys high into cliffs. At <b>Mesa Verde</b>, families lived in cliff dwellings tucked under giant rock overhangs. The Pueblo were skilled farmers who coaxed corn, beans, and squash from thirsty land."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Cliff_Palace_Mesa_Verde.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Andreas F. Borchert, CC BY-SA 4.0", "caption": "Pueblo cliff dwellings at Mesa Verde"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Along the rainy <b>Pacific Northwest</b> coast, nations like the Haida and Tlingit lived among giant cedar forests and salmon-filled rivers. They didn't need to farm — the sea and forest were so rich. They carved towering <b>totem poles</b>: tall cedar logs telling family histories and legends through stacked animal figures."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Wild but true:</b> A totem pole is not worshipped like an idol. It's more like a giant carved storybook or family crest, recording ancestors, clans, and important events for everyone to read at a glance."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In the northeastern woodlands, five nations — the Mohawk, Oneida, Onondaga, Cayuga, and Seneca — did something remarkable. Tired of fighting, they joined into the <b>Iroquois Confederacy</b> (also called the Haudenosaunee), agreeing to settle disputes by talking in a Grand Council instead of by war; later a sixth nation, the Tuscarora, joined. Their system was clever: each nation kept its own affairs, but big decisions affecting everyone went to the Grand Council, where leaders debated until they reached agreement. Clan mothers — respected women — chose and could replace the chiefs. It was one of the oldest lasting examples of nations uniting while keeping their independence."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Different lands, different lives", "a": {"title": "Plains Nations", "items": ["Open grasslands", "Followed bison herds", "Skilled horse riders"]}, "b": {"title": "Pacific Northwest", "items": ["Cedar forests, salmon rivers", "Carved totem poles", "Rich without farming"]}}, {"t": "order", "title": "Order the ideas", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~1100s", "label": "Pueblo cliff dwellings thrive at Mesa Verde"}, {"yr": "before 1500", "label": "Five nations form the Iroquois Confederacy"}, {"yr": "1600s", "label": "Horses spread among Plains nations"}, {"yr": "1722", "label": "The Tuscarora join, making six nations"}, {"yr": "1700s", "label": "Confederacy ideas discussed by American thinkers"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "Why does the Confederacy matter beyond its own people? When thinkers in the young United States debated how to unite separate states into one country, some studied and admired the Haudenosaunee model of independent nations cooperating under a shared council. It was one of several influences on ideas about union and self-government."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you read 'Native Americans,' picture a crowded map of many flags, not one. Each nation had its own language, leaders, and way of life. Lumping them all together is like calling everyone in Europe simply 'European' and stopping there."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> The Haudenosaunee Confederacy still exists, with its own Grand Council. Across the United States and Canada, hundreds of First Nations and tribes keep their languages and ceremonies alive — teaching them in schools, hosting gatherings, and reminding everyone that these cultures are not history museums but living communities."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Roughly how many distinct nations lived in North America before ships arrived?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Exactly one", "A handful", "Hundreds", "None", "Just two"], "answer": 2, "explain": "North America held hundreds of nations with different languages and laws.", "hint": "It was far more than a single group."}, {"q": "Which animal was central to many Great Plains nations?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The bison", "The penguin", "The camel", "The kangaroo", "The elephant"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Bison provided food, clothing, tools, and shelter for Plains peoples.", "hint": "It's a large grazing animal of the grasslands."}, {"q": "What were Pueblo cliff dwellings at Mesa Verde made from?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Ice blocks", "Stone and sun-dried clay", "Steel and glass", "Cedar logs only", "Woven grass"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Pueblo built multi-storey homes of stone and adobe-style clay.", "hint": "Think dry-climate building materials."}, {"q": "A totem pole is best described as what?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A weapon", "A carved record of family history and legends", "A cooking pot", "A boat", "A musical drum"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Totem poles tell family and clan stories through carved figures.", "hint": "It works like a giant carved storybook."}, {"q": "How did the Iroquois Confederacy prefer to settle big disputes?", "type": "mc", "options": ["By war only", "By talking in a Grand Council", "By flipping a coin", "By racing", "By ignoring them"], "answer": 1, "explain": "They debated in a Grand Council until reaching agreement.", "hint": "Think discussion, not battle."}, {"q": "Which role did clan mothers play in the Confederacy?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They were forbidden to speak", "They chose and could replace chiefs", "They had no power", "They led every battle", "They built the totem poles"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Respected clan mothers selected leaders and could remove them.", "hint": "Women held real political authority."}, {"q": "How did the Confederacy influence the young United States?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It supplied its money", "Its model of united-yet-independent nations was studied and admired", "It wrote the US Constitution alone", "It had no influence", "It built the first cities"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Its idea of separate nations cooperating under a shared council was one influence among several.", "hint": "Think about uniting separate parts while keeping independence."}, {"q": "Pacific Northwest nations like the Haida relied heavily on salmon and cedar.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The rich sea and forests meant they thrived without needing to farm."}, {"q": "All Native American nations shared a single language and government.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "There were hundreds of nations, each with its own language and leaders."}, {"q": "The Haudenosaunee Confederacy no longer exists in any form.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It still exists today and keeps its own Grand Council."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am10", "continent": "americas", "n": 10, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "✊", "title": "The Long Road to Equal Rights", "hook": "<b>In 1963, a quarter of a million people gathered in one city to hear four words: 'I have a dream.'</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Some of history's hardest, bravest stories are about people asking a simple question: shouldn't everyone be treated fairly? In the Americas, that question took centuries to answer — and the answering is part of how these nations grew. This is the story of that long, patient road, told as history."}, {"t": "p", "html": "For a long time, a terrible system called <b>slavery</b> existed across the Americas. Millions of Africans were taken from their homes by force and made to work without freedom or pay. People who believed this was deeply wrong began to speak out. They were called <b>abolitionists</b> — because they wanted to abolish, or end, slavery."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Abolitionists came from every background. Some had escaped slavery themselves, like Frederick Douglass and Harriet Tubman, who guided others to freedom; others wrote books, gave speeches, and signed petitions. Over the 1800s, nation by nation, slavery was outlawed across the Americas — in the United States it ended after a painful civil war. But ending slavery did not instantly mean equal treatment. For many years afterward, unfair laws kept Black Americans separated from others — different schools, different seats, different water fountains. This system of forced separation was called <b>segregation</b>, and people knew the promise of fairness was still unfinished."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "star", "file": "Civil_Rights_March_on_Washington,_D.C.jpg", "credit": "Photo: U.S. National Archives, public domain", "caption": "The 1963 March on Washington"}, {"t": "p", "html": "So a new movement grew in the mid-1900s: the <b>Civil Rights Movement</b>. In 1955, a woman named <b>Rosa Parks</b> refused to give up her bus seat, sparking a year-long, peaceful protest. A young minister named <b>Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.</b> became its most famous voice, teaching that change should come through <i>nonviolence</i> — courage without fists."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Wild but true:</b> Dr. King admired Mahatma Gandhi of India, who had used peaceful protest to seek change. So an idea travelled across the world and helped shape one of America's most important movements."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In 1963, about 250,000 people marched on Washington, D.C. There, Dr. King gave his 'I Have a Dream' speech, picturing a future where children would be judged by their character, not their skin. Within a few years, major laws ended legal segregation and protected the right to vote."}, {"t": "order", "title": "The road, step by step", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1800s", "label": "Abolitionists work to end slavery"}, {"yr": "1865", "label": "Slavery is abolished in the United States"}, {"yr": "1920", "label": "American women win the right to vote nationwide"}, {"yr": "1955", "label": "Rosa Parks refuses to give up her bus seat"}, {"yr": "1963", "label": "The March on Washington and 'I Have a Dream'"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "Voting rights tell their own long story. At first, only some men could vote. Over time, the right to vote expanded — to men of all backgrounds, then to women in 1920, then more fully protected for all citizens by laws in the 1960s. Each step came from ordinary people asking, again and again, for a fair share in deciding their future."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two ways people sought change", "a": {"title": "Speaking and writing", "items": ["Speeches and books", "Petitions and newspapers", "Sharing ideas widely"]}, "b": {"title": "Peaceful action", "items": ["Boycotts and marches", "Sit-ins and protests", "Nonviolence under pressure"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> History isn't about blaming people alive today for the past. It's about understanding how rights were won — usually slowly, by brave, patient people — so we can appreciate them and keep them. Curiosity, not shame, is the tool here."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> Across the Americas, the idea that every person deserves equal treatment is written into laws and celebrated in holidays and lessons like this one. People still discuss how to make things fairer — that conversation is part of a healthy society. The road continues, built on the courage of those who walked it first."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What did abolitionists want to do?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Build more factories", "End slavery", "Start new wars", "Lower taxes", "Explore space"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Abolitionists worked to abolish, or end, slavery.", "hint": "The word 'abolish' is hiding inside their name."}, {"q": "Who guided enslaved people to freedom and is remembered as an abolitionist?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Harriet Tubman", "Rosa Parks", "Neil Armstrong", "Christopher Columbus", "Mahatma Gandhi"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Harriet Tubman, who escaped slavery herself, led many others to freedom.", "hint": "She is famous for leading people along escape routes."}, {"q": "What was 'segregation'?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A type of farming", "A system of forced separation by law", "A kind of music", "A sport", "A peace treaty"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Segregation kept people apart through unfair laws even after slavery ended.", "hint": "Think about being kept separate."}, {"q": "What did Rosa Parks do in 1955?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Flew to the Moon", "Refused to give up her bus seat", "Wrote the Constitution", "Won an election", "Built a railroad"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Her refusal sparked a year-long peaceful bus protest.", "hint": "It happened on public transport."}, {"q": "What approach did Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. teach?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Fighting with weapons", "Nonviolence", "Ignoring the problem", "Leaving the country", "Building walls"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Dr. King championed peaceful, nonviolent protest.", "hint": "It means courage without fists."}, {"q": "Whose example of peaceful protest inspired Dr. King?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Mahatma Gandhi", "Julius Caesar", "Genghis Khan", "Napoleon", "Christopher Columbus"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Gandhi of India used peaceful protest, and his ideas influenced King.", "hint": "This leader came from India."}, {"q": "In what year did American women win the right to vote nationwide?", "type": "mc", "options": ["1776", "1865", "1920", "1969", "2000"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Women across the US gained the vote in 1920.", "hint": "It's in the early 20th century."}, {"q": "Slavery in the Americas was ended all at once in a single year everywhere.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Different nations ended slavery at different times across the 1800s."}, {"q": "The 1963 March on Washington drew around a quarter of a million people.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "About 250,000 people gathered to hear speeches including 'I Have a Dream.'"}, {"q": "The right to vote expanded gradually over time rather than being equal from the start.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Voting rights widened step by step over many decades."}]});

  lesson({"id": "am11", "continent": "americas", "n": 11, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "💃", "title": "Latin America Today", "hook": "<b>Stretch one region across two continents, fill it with twenty nations, and you get a place that never stops dancing.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Say 'Latin America' and you've named a region of more than 600 million people spread across Mexico, Central America, the Caribbean, and South America. They share threads — language, faith, football, and rhythm — yet every nation has its own flavour. Let's wander through this vibrant, noisy, colourful world."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Why 'Latin'? Most people here speak <b>Spanish</b> or <b>Portuguese</b> (in Brazil) — languages that grew from Latin, the old tongue of Rome, carried over centuries ago. But these countries blend that European thread with deep <b>Indigenous</b> roots and strong <b>African</b> heritage, creating cultures unlike anywhere else on Earth."}, {"t": "p", "html": "You hear the blend in the music. <b>Salsa</b>, <b>samba</b>, <b>tango</b>, <b>reggaeton</b>, <b>cumbia</b> — these rhythms mix African drums, Indigenous melodies, and European instruments. Music here isn't just for concerts; it spills into streets, kitchens, and festivals. The biggest party of all is <b>Carnival</b> in Rio de Janeiro, Brazil, a dazzling explosion of costumes, dancing, and drums."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Christ_the_Redeemer_-_Cristo_Redentor.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Artyominc, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "Christ the Redeemer above Rio de Janeiro"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Then there's <b>football</b> (what some call soccer). In much of Latin America it's almost a second language. Children play barefoot in alleys dreaming of glory; nations like Brazil and Argentina have produced some of the most famous players in history. When the World Cup arrives, entire countries seem to hold their breath together."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Wild but true:</b> Brazil is the only country to have played in every men's football World Cup ever held, and has won it five times — more than any other nation."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The cities pulse with energy. <b>São Paulo</b> and <b>Buenos Aires</b> are among the largest cities in the world, packed with skyscrapers, markets, and street art. Older cities like <b>Cartagena</b> and <b>Cusco</b> wrap colourful colonial buildings around ancient stone foundations, so you can walk from one century into another in a single block."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two giants, two beats", "a": {"title": "Brazil", "items": ["Speaks Portuguese", "Samba and Carnival", "Amazon rainforest within it"]}, "b": {"title": "Argentina", "items": ["Speaks Spanish", "Tango and steak culture", "Andes mountains along its edge"]}}, {"t": "p", "html": "Life here isn't all festival, of course. Many Latin American nations work to overcome real challenges: gaps between rich and poor, crowded cities, and protecting natural treasures like the Amazon. But across the region you'll also find booming technology hubs, growing universities, and young people inventing new music, art, and businesses."}, {"t": "scenario", "title": "You're visiting a Latin American city", "prompt": "A neighbour invites you to a noisy street festival with drums and dancing. What's the open-minded choice?", "opts": [{"label": "Join in, ask questions, and learn the steps", "tag": "Wise", "outcome": "Wonderful! Festivals are where culture comes alive — and people love sharing it."}, {"label": "Stay inside; it looks unfamiliar", "tag": "Common", "outcome": "Understandable, but you'd miss a warm, generous part of local life."}, {"label": "Assume every country here is exactly the same", "tag": "Risky", "outcome": "Careful — each nation has its own customs. Curiosity beats assumptions."}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> 'Latin America' is a handy label, not a single country. A Mexican taco, a Peruvian flute, and a Brazilian drum are cousins, not twins. The fun is in noticing both what's shared and what's gloriously different."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Today:</b> Latin American culture reaches far beyond the region. Reggaeton tops global music charts, films and TV shows win worldwide audiences, and food like tacos, empanadas, and arepas appears on menus everywhere. This is a young, creative region whose voice grows louder on the world stage every year."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Why is the region called 'Latin' America?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It is very cold", "Most speak languages descended from Latin, like Spanish and Portuguese", "Everyone studies Roman history", "It was named after a person", "It has no connection to language"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Spanish and Portuguese both grew from Latin, the language of ancient Rome.", "hint": "Think about which languages most people speak."}, {"q": "Latin American cultures blend European roots with which other major heritages?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Indigenous and African", "Arctic and Antarctic", "Roman and Greek only", "Chinese and Japanese", "None at all"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Indigenous, African, and European threads mix throughout the region.", "hint": "Think about who lived there first and who was brought there."}, {"q": "Which of these is a famous Latin American music and dance style?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Samba", "Polka", "Yodeling", "Bagpiping", "Opera"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Samba is a famous Brazilian rhythm; salsa and tango are others.", "hint": "It's strongly linked to Brazil and Carnival."}, {"q": "Where is the world-famous Carnival celebration held?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Buenos Aires", "Rio de Janeiro", "Lima", "Bogotá", "Santiago"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Rio de Janeiro's Carnival is a spectacular festival of dance and costume.", "hint": "It's in Brazil, beneath a famous statue."}, {"q": "Which country has played in every men's football World Cup and won five times?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Argentina", "Brazil", "Mexico", "Chile", "Uruguay"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Brazil has appeared in every World Cup and holds five titles.", "hint": "It's the largest country in South America."}, {"q": "Which language is mainly spoken in Brazil?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Spanish", "Portuguese", "French", "Italian", "English"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Brazil is the large Portuguese-speaking nation of South America.", "hint": "It's different from most of its Spanish-speaking neighbours."}, {"q": "What is true about cities like São Paulo and Buenos Aires?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They are tiny villages", "They are among the largest cities in the world", "They have no people", "They are underwater", "They were never built"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Both are huge, busy metropolises with millions of residents.", "hint": "Think big, busy, and crowded."}, {"q": "Latin America is a single country with one government.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It's a region of many nations, each with its own customs and government."}, {"q": "Reggaeton and other Latin styles have reached global music charts.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Latin music now enjoys huge popularity around the world."}, {"q": "Every Latin American country has exactly the same culture and customs.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Each nation has its own distinct traditions, even while sharing some threads."}]});

  /* ============================================================
     MIDDLE EAST  (clean, neutral, evenhanded on sensitive topics)
     ============================================================ */
  cont({
    id: "mideast", name: "Middle East", emoji: "🕌", color: "#8e5a9e",
    blurb: "Where civilization began",
    intro: "The cradle of civilization — birthplace of writing, cities, and three of the world's great religions. A crossroads of continents, ideas, and history.",
    badge: { name: "Crossroads Scholar", emoji: "🕌" },
    lessons: ["me1", "me2", "me3", "me4", "me5", "me6", "me7", "me8", "me9", "me10"],
    sectionQuiz: [
      { q: "The “cradle of civilization,” where the first cities and writing appeared, was…", type: "mc", options: ["Mesopotamia", "Antarctica", "Australia", "Greenland"], answer: 0, explain: "Mesopotamia (modern Iraq) is where civilization first arose." },
      { q: "Three major world religions began in the Middle East:", type: "mc", options: ["Judaism, Christianity, and Islam", "Hinduism, Buddhism, and Shinto", "Only Islam", "None"], answer: 0, explain: "Judaism, Christianity, and Islam all began in this region." },
      { q: "During Europe's Middle Ages, Baghdad was a world center of…", type: "mc", options: ["Ice", "Learning, science, and books", "Car making", "Pyramids"], answer: 1, explain: "Baghdad's House of Wisdom led a golden age of learning." },
      { q: "The resource that made the modern Middle East globally important is…", type: "mc", options: ["Gold", "Oil", "Coal", "Diamonds"], answer: 1, explain: "Vast oil reserves made the region central to the world economy." },
      { q: "The first system of writing was called…", type: "mc", options: ["Cuneiform", "English", "Emoji", "Hieroglyphs"], answer: 0, explain: "Cuneiform, written on clay tablets, was among the first writing systems." },
      { q: "After WWI, the borders of many modern Middle Eastern countries were…", type: "mc", options: ["Ancient and unchanged", "Drawn largely by European powers", "Chosen by a vote", "Random"], answer: 1, explain: "European powers drew many borders after the Ottoman Empire fell." },
      { q: "The state of Israel was established in…", type: "mc", options: ["1776", "1948", "2001", "1900"], answer: 1, explain: "Israel was established in 1948; the region's disputes are complex and ongoing." },
      { q: "The wheel and the first written laws came from the ancient Middle East.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Both the wheel and early law codes (like Hammurabi's) originated here." },
      { q: "The Middle East is a crossroads connecting which continents?", type: "mc", options: ["Asia, Europe, and Africa", "Only Asia", "the Americas", "Antarctica and Australia"], answer: 0, explain: "It sits where three continents meet — a natural crossroads." },
      { q: "Why do many disagreements in the modern Middle East trace back to history?", type: "mc", options: ["They don't", "Borders, religions, and resources from the past still shape the region", "It was always peaceful", "Nobody lives there"], answer: 1, explain: "Old borders, faiths, and resources continue to shape the region." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({"id": "me1", "continent": "mideast", "n": 1, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "📜", "title": "The Cradle of Civilization", "hook": "<b>Imagine a flat, sun-baked land between two great rivers — and on it, the very first cities humans ever built.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Between two rivers — the <b>Tigris</b> and the <b>Euphrates</b> — lies a land the Greeks later called <b>Mesopotamia</b>, meaning \"between the rivers.\" Today this region sits mostly in modern Iraq. Around <b>5,000 years ago</b>, people here did something no humans had ever done before: they built true cities. For this reason, Mesopotamia is often called the <b>Cradle of Civilization</b>."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Why here? The rivers flooded each year and left behind rich, dark mud perfect for farming. With reliable food, villages grew into towns, and towns into cities. The earliest of these belonged to a people called the <b>Sumerians</b>, who lived in southern Mesopotamia. Their cities — such as <b>Ur</b>, <b>Uruk</b>, and <b>Lagash</b> — held tens of thousands of people, with temples, markets, and busy streets."}, {"t": "p", "html": "At the heart of each Sumerian city stood a <b>ziggurat</b>, a giant stepped tower built of mud bricks, rising like a small mountain above the flat plain. People believed their city's god lived at the very top, and priests climbed its great staircases to make offerings. Around it spread crowded workshops where craftspeople hammered metal, threw pottery, and cut jewelry. For the first time in history, not everyone had to farm — when a few families could grow enough food for many, some people were freed to become full-time priests, builders, traders, scribes, or artists. This division of labor is one of the things that makes a true city different from a village."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Running a city meant keeping track of grain, animals, debts, and taxes — and human memory simply wasn't enough. So the Sumerians invented one of the most powerful tools humans ever made: <b>writing</b>. They pressed the tip of a cut reed, called a stylus, into tablets of wet clay, leaving wedge-shaped marks we now call <b>cuneiform</b>. At first these marks recorded plain lists — so many jars of oil, so many sheep — but over time people learned to write stories, letters, contracts, and even poems. One of the oldest stories in the world, the <b>Epic of Gilgamesh</b>, comes to us on these clay tablets, telling of a heroic king and his search for the meaning of life."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Mesopotamians were tireless inventors and problem-solvers. They gave us the <b>wheel</b> — first used flat to shape pottery, then turned on its side and fitted to carts and war chariots. They divided the hour into <b>60 minutes</b> and the circle into <b>360 degrees</b>, a clever base-60 counting system we still use on clocks and compasses today. They mapped the night sky and named patterns of stars, dug long canals to carry river water to dry fields, and sent traders by boat and donkey to distant lands in search of timber, copper, and precious stones their own flat country lacked."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "P1050702 Louvre code Hammurabi face rwk.JPG", "credit": "Photo: Mbzt, CC BY 3.0", "caption": "A stone pillar carved with Hammurabi's laws"}, {"t": "order", "title": "How a civilization grew", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~9000 BC", "label": "Farming begins; villages form"}, {"yr": "~3500 BC", "label": "First cities like Uruk rise"}, {"yr": "~3200 BC", "label": "Cuneiform writing appears"}, {"yr": "~2100 BC", "label": "Great ziggurat of Ur is built"}, {"yr": "~1750 BC", "label": "Hammurabi's law code is carved"}]}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> A single clay cuneiform tablet, if baked or simply left to dry, can survive for thousands of years. Archaeologists have dug up entire \"libraries\" of tablets — including school exercises written by Sumerian children practicing their writing!"}, {"t": "p", "html": "As cities grew larger and busier, so did the need for clear, shared rules. Around <b>1750 BC</b>, a Babylonian king named <b>Hammurabi</b> ordered nearly <b>300 laws</b> carved onto a tall black stone pillar and set up where everyone could see it. <b>Hammurabi's Code</b> covered trade, farming, wages, marriage, and crime, often spelling out an exact penalty for each offense. Some of its punishments seem harsh to us today, and the laws treated rich and poor differently. But the idea behind the code was genuinely powerful and new: laws should be <i>written down and public</i>, so people could know the rules ahead of time rather than being judged by a single ruler's changing mood. That idea — fair warning through written law — still sits at the heart of justice systems around the world."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you hear \"the first\" something — first cities, first writing, first laws — remember these things rarely appeared overnight. They grew slowly, over many lifetimes, as people solved everyday problems like \"How do I remember who owes me grain?\" Big inventions often start small and practical."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Before cities vs. after cities", "a": {"title": "Village life", "items": ["Everyone farms or herds", "Few dozen people", "No writing — memory only", "Trade with close neighbors"]}, "b": {"title": "City life", "items": ["Many specialized jobs", "Tens of thousands of people", "Writing keeps records", "Trade across long distances"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Still with us today:</b> Every time you check a clock, measure an angle, write something down, or roll anything on wheels, you're using ideas first worked out in Mesopotamia. Its ancient sites are still studied by archaeologists worldwide. Mesopotamia reminds us that history isn't only kings and battles — it's also ordinary people inventing the tools, writing, and rules that made the rest of human history possible."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What does the name \"Mesopotamia\" mean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Land of the pyramids", "Between the rivers", "City of gold", "Edge of the desert", "Valley of kings"], "answer": 1, "explain": "\"Mesopotamia\" is Greek for \"between the rivers\" — the Tigris and Euphrates.", "hint": "Think about the two rivers."}, {"q": "Which people built some of the world's first cities in southern Mesopotamia?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Romans", "The Egyptians", "The Sumerians", "The Greeks", "The Vikings"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Sumerians built early cities such as Ur and Uruk.", "hint": "Their city of Ur is famous."}, {"q": "What was cuneiform?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A type of boat", "An early form of writing using wedge marks", "A musical instrument", "A kind of bread", "A board game"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Cuneiform was an early writing system made by pressing a reed stylus into wet clay.", "hint": "It was pressed into clay tablets."}, {"q": "What giant stepped tower stood at the heart of a Sumerian city?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A pyramid", "A lighthouse", "A castle", "A ziggurat", "A windmill"], "answer": 3, "explain": "A ziggurat was a stepped temple-tower believed to be home to the city's god.", "hint": "It starts with 'z'."}, {"q": "Hammurabi is best known for which achievement?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Inventing the wheel", "Building the first ziggurat", "Discovering oil", "Sailing around the world", "Writing a famous code of laws"], "answer": 4, "explain": "Hammurabi had nearly 300 laws carved on a stone pillar for all to see.", "hint": "It involves rules everyone could read."}, {"q": "Which everyday measurement comes from Mesopotamia?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The 60-minute hour", "The metric kilogram", "The Fahrenheit scale", "The light-year", "The decibel"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Mesopotamians used a base-60 system, giving us 60 minutes in an hour and 360 degrees in a circle.", "hint": "Check your clock."}, {"q": "Why was Mesopotamian soil good for farming?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It never rained there", "Yearly river floods left rich mud", "It was made of sand", "Volcanoes fertilized it", "Glaciers covered it"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Tigris and Euphrates flooded each year, leaving behind fertile mud.", "hint": "It has to do with the rivers flooding."}, {"q": "The wheel was first used in Mesopotamia for shaping pottery before it was used on carts.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — potters' wheels came before wheels were put on carts and chariots."}, {"q": "Writing was invented mainly to record poetry and stories first.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — writing began with practical records like lists of grain and goods, then later included stories."}, {"q": "In Mesopotamian cities, everyone still had to farm for food.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — surplus food meant some people could specialize as priests, traders, builders, and artists."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me2", "continent": "mideast", "n": 2, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🕌", "title": "Three Great Religions & a Golden Age", "hook": "<b>From one corner of the world came three of humanity's most widespread religions — and later, a dazzling age of learning.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "The Middle East is the birthplace of three major <b>world religions</b>: <b>Judaism</b>, <b>Christianity</b>, and <b>Islam</b>. Together their followers number in the billions, spread across every continent on Earth. All three are described as <b>monotheistic</b>, meaning they teach belief in one God. This lesson simply describes what each tradition teaches and where it began — with respect and care, never deciding who is right or wrong. Learning about a faith is not the same as joining it; it's a way of understanding the people who hold it dear."}, {"t": "p", "html": "<b>Judaism</b> is the oldest of the three. It traces its roots to the ancient Israelites and to a figure called <b>Abraham</b>, honored as a founding father. Its central text is the <b>Hebrew Bible</b>, whose first part is the <b>Torah</b>. The city of <b>Jerusalem</b> holds deep importance in Jewish tradition, and Jewish life is marked by holy days such as the weekly <b>Sabbath</b> and festivals like Passover. Judaism teaches following God's law, given long ago, as a guide for everyday living."}, {"t": "p", "html": "<b>Christianity</b> grew out of Jewish traditions about 2,000 years ago, centered on the life and teachings of <b>Jesus</b>, whom Christians honor as the Son of God. Its sacred book is the <b>Bible</b>, which includes the Hebrew scriptures (the Old Testament) and the New Testament. Christianity began in the region around Jerusalem and then spread outward — first across the Roman Empire and eventually around the globe — until it became one of the largest religions in the world, with many different branches and customs."}, {"t": "p", "html": "<b>Islam</b> arose in the 600s AD on the <b>Arabian Peninsula</b>, in the cities of <b>Mecca</b> and <b>Medina</b>. Muslims follow the teachings of the Prophet <b>Muhammad</b> and their holy book, the <b>Qur'an</b>, which they believe was revealed to him. Islam shares many figures and stories with the other two traditions, including Abraham, Moses, and Jesus, whom Muslims honor as prophets. Because all three faiths look back to that same figure of Abraham, they are sometimes grouped together as the <b>Abrahamic religions</b>, even though each has its own distinct beliefs and practices."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Dome of the Rock, Jerusalem (1).jpg", "credit": "Photo: Andrew Shiva, CC BY-SA 4.0", "caption": "The golden Dome of the Rock in Jerusalem"}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Three Abrahamic religions", "a": {"title": "Shared threads", "items": ["Belief in one God", "Honor the figure of Abraham", "Roots in the Middle East", "Sacred written scriptures"]}, "b": {"title": "Distinct features", "items": ["Judaism: Hebrew Bible, oldest", "Christianity: centered on Jesus", "Islam: Qur'an and Prophet Muhammad", "Each has its own holy days"]}}, {"t": "p", "html": "A few centuries after Islam began, the Middle East became the world's leading center of <b>learning and science</b> — a period often called the <b>Islamic Golden Age</b> (roughly the 8th to 13th centuries). Cities like <b>Baghdad</b>, <b>Cairo</b>, and <b>Córdoba</b> (in Spain) buzzed with scholars and libraries. In Baghdad, thinkers gathered at a famous center of study often called the <b>House of Wisdom</b>, translating Greek, Persian, and Indian books into Arabic — saving knowledge that might otherwise have been lost — then adding discoveries of their own in mathematics, medicine, and astronomy."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> The word <b>\"algebra\"</b> comes from the Arabic <i>al-jabr</i>, from the title of a book by the mathematician <b>al-Khwarizmi</b> — whose name also gives us the word \"algorithm.\" The numerals you use every day (1, 2, 3...) reached Europe through Arab scholars, which is why we call them \"Arabic numerals.\""}, {"t": "order", "title": "A timeline of beginnings", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~1800 BC", "label": "Traditions trace back to Abraham"}, {"yr": "~30 AD", "label": "Christianity begins around Jesus"}, {"yr": "~610 AD", "label": "Islam begins with Muhammad"}, {"yr": "~800 AD", "label": "House of Wisdom flourishes in Baghdad"}]}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When learning about religions that aren't your own, a good approach is to describe what believers <i>say and do</i> — \"Muslims fast during Ramadan,\" \"Jews observe the Sabbath\" — without deciding who is right. Curiosity and respect can travel together."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Golden Age scholars made real and lasting advances. Doctors like <b>Ibn Sina</b> (known in Europe as Avicenna) wrote vast medical books that were studied in universities for centuries afterward. Astronomers refined star charts, named many stars, and built observatories to track the heavens. Mathematicians developed algebra and helped spread a number system that included a symbol for zero. Travelers and traders linked three continents along land and sea routes, carrying spices, silk, and ideas. Alongside the science, beautiful art, poetry, gardens, and architecture flourished, and great libraries grew so large that some held tens of thousands of books at a time when most of the world had very few."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Still with us today:</b> Hospitals, universities, and the numbers in your math homework all owe something to this era. Many discoveries that later shaped Europe's Renaissance first passed through the libraries of the Middle East. So this one region gave the world not only three of its great faiths but also a treasure-house of knowledge that helped light the path toward modern science."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Which three major religions all began in the Middle East?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Hinduism, Buddhism, Shinto", "Judaism, Christianity, Islam", "Taoism, Sikhism, Jainism", "Zoroastrianism, Bahá'í, Druze", "Confucianism, Shinto, Islam"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Judaism, Christianity, and Islam all trace their origins to the region.", "hint": "They are sometimes called 'Abrahamic.'"}, {"q": "What word describes a religion that teaches belief in one God?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Polytheistic", "Monotheistic", "Atheistic", "Agnostic", "Pantheistic"], "answer": 1, "explain": "'Monotheistic' means belief in a single God — all three of these religions are monotheistic.", "hint": "'Mono' means one."}, {"q": "The three religions are called 'Abrahamic' because they all honor which figure?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Moses", "Abraham", "Alexander", "Hammurabi", "Gilgamesh"], "answer": 1, "explain": "All three look back to Abraham as a founding figure.", "hint": "It's in the word itself."}, {"q": "The holy book of Islam is called the:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Torah", "Iliad", "Vedas", "Qur'an", "Analects"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Muslims follow the Qur'an as their holy book.", "hint": "It begins with 'Q'."}, {"q": "The famous center of learning in Baghdad was often called the:", "type": "mc", "options": ["House of Wisdom", "Great Library of Rome", "Academy of Athens", "Hall of Mirrors", "Temple of Stars"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The House of Wisdom in Baghdad was a great center of translation and study.", "hint": "It suggests a place full of knowledge."}, {"q": "The word 'algebra' comes from a book by which mathematician?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Ibn Sina", "Euclid", "Pythagoras", "Galileo", "Al-Khwarizmi"], "answer": 4, "explain": "Al-Khwarizmi's work gave us both 'algebra' and 'algorithm.'", "hint": "His name also gives us 'algorithm.'"}, {"q": "During the Islamic Golden Age, scholars mainly:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Banned all old books", "Stopped studying science", "Translated and expanded knowledge from many cultures", "Only studied warfare", "Refused to trade with others"], "answer": 2, "explain": "They translated Greek, Persian, and Indian works and added new discoveries of their own.", "hint": "Think about preserving and building on knowledge."}, {"q": "Christianity grew out of Jewish traditions about 2,000 years ago.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — Christianity began within a Jewish context, centered on the life and teachings of Jesus."}, {"q": "The numerals 1, 2, 3 reached Europe through Arab scholars, which is why we call them 'Arabic numerals.'", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — these numerals passed to Europe via the Arab world."}, {"q": "Islam began thousands of years before Judaism and Christianity.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — Judaism is the oldest of the three; Islam began later, in the 600s AD."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me3", "continent": "mideast", "n": 3, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏛️", "title": "The Ottoman Decline & European Interest", "hook": "<b>For 600 years one empire ruled lands across three continents — and the story of how it slowly faded changed the world.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "In the year 1453, a young ruler named <b>Mehmed II</b> captured the great walled city of Constantinople, ending the long <b>Byzantine Empire</b> that had stood for a thousand years. The conquered city became <b>Istanbul</b>, the proud capital of the rising <b>Ottoman Empire</b>. From this moment, over the next several centuries, the Ottomans would grow into one of the largest, richest, and longest-lasting empires in all of human history — a power that European kings watched with both fear and respect."}, {"t": "p", "html": "At its height in the 1500s, under <b>Suleiman the Magnificent</b>, the Ottoman Empire stretched across three continents — parts of <b>Europe, Asia, and Africa</b>. From the gates of central Europe in the north to the deserts of Arabia in the south, and from North Africa in the west to the mountains of the east, it controlled great cities, busy trade routes, and holy sites important to several religions. Within its borders lived a remarkable mix of peoples speaking dozens of languages and following different faiths, all under one sultan. Suleiman himself was known both as a conqueror and as a lawmaker, earning the nickname \"the Lawgiver\" among his own people for the way he organized the empire's rules."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Ottomans were famous for fine architecture, dazzling blue-and-white tilework, and a clever, well-organized system of government. Grand <b>mosques</b> with soaring domes and slender minarets rose over the hills of Istanbul, including masterpieces designed by the architect <b>Sinan</b>, whose buildings still stand today. The empire grew wealthy by controlling and taxing the busy trade that flowed between East and West, and its bazaars overflowed with spices, silks, and goods from across three continents. Within its borders, communities of many faiths and languages were often allowed to govern their own affairs, which helped such a huge and varied empire hold together for so long."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "columns", "file": "Hagia Sophia Mars 2013.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Arild Vågen, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "The domes and minarets of Istanbul's Hagia Sophia"}, {"t": "p", "html": "But no empire stays at its peak forever. Starting in the 1600s, the Ottoman Empire entered a long, slow <b>decline</b> that lasted centuries. There was no single cause. New <b>sea trade routes</b> around Africa meant merchants no longer had to pass through Ottoman lands, so tax money shrank. Meanwhile, European countries were changing fast."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In Europe, the <b>Industrial Revolution</b> brought factories, railways, steamships, and powerful new weapons, allowing European economies to grow at remarkable speed. European armies and navies grew steadily stronger, while the Ottoman military, once the most feared in the world, struggled to keep pace with the new machines and methods. The empire also covered such a vast area, with so many different peoples, that governing it all from a single capital became harder and harder. Distant provinces sometimes drifted away from the center, and the cost of defending so many borders kept rising."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> The Ottoman Empire lasted about <b>600 years</b> — from around 1300 to 1922. That's roughly twice as long as the United States has existed so far, and longer than many other famous empires in history."}, {"t": "order", "title": "The Ottoman story", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~1300", "label": "Ottoman Empire founded"}, {"yr": "1453", "label": "Constantinople becomes Istanbul"}, {"yr": "~1560", "label": "Empire at its height under Suleiman"}, {"yr": "~1700s", "label": "Slow decline takes hold"}, {"yr": "1922", "label": "Empire comes to an end"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "As the empire weakened, European powers grew increasingly interested in its lands — they wanted trade routes, resources, and a path to their faraway colonies. Some European leaders even began calling the Ottoman Empire \"the sick man of Europe,\" and they competed with one another over what might happen to its territory. The Ottomans tried to <b>reform and modernize</b>, building new schools, railways, and a telegraph network and reorganizing their army. These efforts brought real change, but the pressures of a fast-changing world remained great, and the empire grew gradually smaller along its edges through the 1800s."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Why the balance shifted", "a": {"title": "Ottoman challenges", "items": ["Lost income as trade routes moved", "Vast lands hard to govern", "Older military technology", "Less industrial growth"]}, "b": {"title": "European advantages", "items": ["Industrial factories and railways", "Stronger navies and weapons", "New global trade routes", "Competing eagerly for influence"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When an empire \"declines,\" it rarely collapses in a single dramatic moment. Picture it more like a long sunset — gradual changes in money, technology, and neighbors that add up over many decades. Looking for one single cause usually misses the bigger picture."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Still with us today:</b> Modern <b>Turkey</b> grew directly out of the Ottoman heartland, and Istanbul remains one of the world's great cities, sitting where Europe meets Asia. Ottoman food, music, and architecture still shape the region's culture. The empire's long story also sets the stage for the next big chapter: when the old Ottoman world finally ended, the map of the entire Middle East would be redrawn."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What city became the capital of the Ottoman Empire in 1453?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Cairo", "Istanbul (Constantinople)", "Baghdad", "Athens", "Rome"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Mehmed II captured Constantinople in 1453 and it became Istanbul, the Ottoman capital.", "hint": "It bridges Europe and Asia."}, {"q": "Under which ruler did the Ottoman Empire reach its height in the 1500s?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Mehmed II", "Suleiman the Magnificent", "Hammurabi", "Sinan", "Avicenna"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Suleiman the Magnificent ruled during the empire's golden age in the 1500s.", "hint": "His title means 'the Magnificent.'"}, {"q": "Across how many continents did the Ottoman Empire stretch at its height?", "type": "mc", "options": ["One", "Two", "Three", "Four", "Five"], "answer": 2, "explain": "It spanned parts of Europe, Asia, and Africa — three continents.", "hint": "Europe, Asia, and Africa."}, {"q": "Which of these helped cause the Ottoman decline?", "type": "mc", "options": ["New sea trade routes bypassing its lands", "A sudden ice age", "Running out of water completely", "Losing its written language", "Volcanic eruptions"], "answer": 0, "explain": "As merchants found sea routes around Africa, the Ottomans lost valuable trade income.", "hint": "It had to do with where merchants traveled."}, {"q": "What major change made European armies and navies much stronger during this time?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The fall of Rome", "The invention of writing", "The Industrial Revolution", "The first Olympic Games", "The building of pyramids"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Industrial Revolution brought factories, railways, and powerful new weapons.", "hint": "It involved factories and machines."}, {"q": "About how long did the Ottoman Empire last?", "type": "mc", "options": ["About 50 years", "About 600 years", "About 5,000 years", "About 100 years", "About 1,500 years"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The empire lasted roughly from 1300 to 1922 — about 600 years.", "hint": "It's longer than the United States has existed."}, {"q": "The master Ottoman architect famous for grand mosques was named:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Suleiman", "Mehmed", "Ibn Sina", "Avicenna", "Sinan"], "answer": 4, "explain": "Sinan designed many of the empire's most beautiful mosques.", "hint": "His name has two syllables and starts with 'S'."}, {"q": "The Ottoman decline happened suddenly in a single year.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — the decline was a slow process that unfolded over centuries."}, {"q": "The Ottomans tried to modernize by building railways, schools, and a telegraph network.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — the empire attempted real reforms, including new infrastructure and a reorganized army."}, {"q": "Modern Turkey grew out of the Ottoman heartland.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — when the empire ended, modern Turkey emerged from its core territory."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me4", "continent": "mideast", "n": 4, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🗺️", "title": "Drawing the Modern Middle East", "hook": "<b>Look at a map of the Middle East today — many of those borders are barely a hundred years old. Where did they come from?</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "If you look at a modern map of the Middle East, you'll see countries like Iraq, Syria, Jordan, Lebanon, and Saudi Arabia, each with neat borders. Yet many of these lines are surprisingly <b>young</b> — most were drawn in the early 1900s. To understand them, we have to go back to a huge turning point: the end of the <b>Ottoman Empire</b>."}, {"t": "p", "html": "During <b>World War I</b> (1914–1918), the Ottoman Empire fought on the losing side, allied with Germany and Austria-Hungary. The war was enormous and exhausting, and when it finally ended, the old empire — already weakened by its long decline — broke apart for good. Its vast Middle Eastern lands, which had been governed together from Istanbul for centuries, were suddenly without their old rulers. A huge question now hung over the region: what would happen to all this territory, and who would decide its future?"}, {"t": "p", "html": "At the time, two powerful European countries, <b>Britain</b> and <b>France</b>, held great influence in world affairs. After the war, much of the former Ottoman territory was placed under a system called <b>mandates</b>, in which European powers were given responsibility to administer these areas, at least for a time. New lines were drawn on maps to mark out the new territories — sometimes in distant offices in London or Paris, far from the lands and the people they would affect. A map drawn in 1916, even before the war ended, had already sketched out which zones each power hoped to oversee."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "MPK1-426 Sykes Picot Agreement Map signed 8 May 1916.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Royal Geographical Society, Public Domain", "caption": "A 1916 map dividing the region into zones"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Because some of these borders were drawn quickly, and with an eye to European interests, they didn't always match where different communities actually lived. Groups of people who shared a language, religion, or way of life sometimes found themselves split between two new countries, while groups with little in common were sometimes placed inside the same borders. These decisions, made in just a few years, would go on to shape the region for the century that followed — which is why understanding how the lines were drawn helps explain so much about the map today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Out of this same period, many <b>modern nations</b> were born. <b>Iraq</b> and <b>Jordan</b> took shape in the 1920s, each with its own capital and ruler. <b>Saudi Arabia</b> was unified in 1932 under King <b>Abdulaziz Ibn Saud</b>, bringing much of the Arabian Peninsula under one kingdom. <b>Lebanon</b> and <b>Syria</b> became distinct countries with their own identities. Over the following decades, country after country gradually gained full <b>independence</b>, lowering the old flags and taking complete control of its own government and future."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> The country of <b>Turkey</b> took a different path. Rather than being divided up, it formed a new republic in <b>1923</b> under the leader <b>Mustafa Kemal Atatürk</b>, who introduced many reforms to modernize the new nation."}, {"t": "order", "title": "From empire to nations", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1914", "label": "World War I begins"}, {"yr": "1918", "label": "War ends; Ottoman Empire breaks apart"}, {"yr": "1920s", "label": "Borders drawn; Iraq and Jordan form"}, {"yr": "1932", "label": "Saudi Arabia is unified"}, {"yr": "mid-1900s", "label": "More nations gain independence"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "It's worth remembering that the people of the region were never simply bystanders waiting for others to decide their fate. Many leaders, scholars, communities, and popular movements pushed for self-rule, organized, negotiated, and worked hard to shape their own futures. Over the following decades, they built governments, wrote constitutions, founded schools and universities, and forged national identities of their own. The full story of the modern Middle East is therefore one of both outside decisions <i>and</i> determined local efforts to build new nations — a balance worth keeping in mind whenever we study how any country came to be."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Old order vs. new map", "a": {"title": "Before WWI", "items": ["One large Ottoman Empire", "Provinces, not nation-states", "Ruled from Istanbul", "Centuries-old arrangement"]}, "b": {"title": "After WWI", "items": ["Many separate countries", "New national borders", "Local capitals and governments", "Borders only decades old"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Borders on a map can look permanent and natural, as if they were always there. But almost every border was created at some point by people making decisions. Asking \"<i>when</i> and <i>how</i> was this line drawn?\" is a great history question for any map in the world."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Still with us today:</b> The countries created in this era — and the way their borders were drawn — still shape the map of the Middle East you'll find in any atlas. Understanding their origins helps make sense of the region's geography today. In just a few decades, a region governed for centuries as one empire became a patchwork of independent nations — a dramatic example of how quickly the map of the world can change."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Most of the modern Middle East's borders were drawn in which time period?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Ancient Mesopotamia", "The early 1900s", "The year 1453", "Prehistoric times", "The 1700s"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Many borders were drawn in the early 1900s, around the end of World War I.", "hint": "It's tied to a famous 20th-century war."}, {"q": "Which event led to the breakup of the Ottoman Empire's Middle Eastern lands?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Industrial Revolution", "World War I", "The fall of Rome", "The invention of oil drilling", "The Renaissance"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Ottoman Empire fought on the losing side of World War I and broke apart afterward.", "hint": "It was a global war ending in 1918."}, {"q": "Which two European powers held great influence over the region after the war?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Spain and Portugal", "Russia and China", "Italy and Greece", "Britain and France", "Sweden and Norway"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Britain and France held much influence and administered areas under the mandate system.", "hint": "Two neighbors across the English Channel."}, {"q": "What was the 'mandate' system?", "type": "mc", "options": ["A new religion", "An arrangement where European powers administered former Ottoman areas", "A type of money", "A trade route", "A kind of ship"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Under mandates, European powers were set to administer parts of the former Ottoman territory.", "hint": "It involved who would govern the land."}, {"q": "Saudi Arabia was unified in 1932 under which leader?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Atatürk", "Suleiman", "Mehmed II", "Hammurabi", "Abdulaziz Ibn Saud"], "answer": 4, "explain": "King Abdulaziz Ibn Saud unified Saudi Arabia in 1932.", "hint": "The country's name shares part of his name."}, {"q": "Who led the founding of the new Republic of Turkey in 1923?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Mustafa Kemal Atatürk", "Suleiman the Magnificent", "Ibn Saud", "Mehmed II", "Sinan"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Mustafa Kemal Atatürk founded modern Turkey and led major reforms.", "hint": "His surname means 'father of the Turks.'"}, {"q": "Why did some new borders cause difficulties?", "type": "mc", "options": ["They were drawn too small to fit on maps", "They sometimes split communities or grouped different ones together", "They were made of stone walls", "They changed every year", "They had no names"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Borders drawn quickly didn't always match where communities actually lived.", "hint": "Think about the people living on the land."}, {"q": "Before World War I, the region was mostly one large Ottoman Empire rather than many separate countries.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — the area was governed together as Ottoman provinces, not as separate nation-states."}, {"q": "The people of the region had no role in shaping their own futures.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — many local leaders and movements actively pushed for self-rule and helped build new nations."}, {"q": "Turkey was divided into several small countries after WWI.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — Turkey took a different path, forming a single new republic in 1923."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me5", "continent": "mideast", "n": 5, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🛢️", "title": "Oil & a Region at the Center of the World", "hook": "<b>Beneath the deserts of the Middle East lay a hidden treasure that would transform quiet towns into gleaming global cities.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "For most of history, much of the Arabian Peninsula was a land of wide deserts, small ports, and trading towns where people herded camels and goats, fished for pearls in the warm Gulf waters, and crossed the burning sands by camel caravan. Life could be hard, and few outside the region thought of it as wealthy. Then, in the early 1900s, explorers and engineers discovered something deep beneath those sands that would change everything: vast underground reserves of <b>oil</b>, the fuel a fast-modernizing world was about to crave more than almost anything else."}, {"t": "p", "html": "<b>Oil</b> — also called petroleum — is a thick, dark liquid that formed over millions of years from the remains of tiny sea creatures that settled to the bottom of ancient seas and were slowly buried, heated, and squeezed deep underground. Drillers reach it by boring wells far down into the rock. It turned out that the lands around the Persian Gulf held some of the <b>largest oil reserves on Earth</b>. As the world increasingly ran on cars, ships, planes, and factories — all hungry for fuel — demand for oil soared, and the region's once-hidden treasure suddenly became one of the most valuable resources on the planet."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The first big discoveries came in places like <b>Iran</b> in 1908, then <b>Bahrain</b>, <b>Saudi Arabia</b>, and <b>Kuwait</b> in the following decades. Saudi Arabia's enormous desert oil fields, found in the 1930s, proved to be among the richest anywhere on Earth, holding more oil than almost any other place. Suddenly, nations that had been quiet and not wealthy found themselves sitting on a resource that the whole industrializing world urgently needed — and was willing to pay a great deal to buy."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "oil", "file": "Dubai skyline 2015 (cropped).jpg", "credit": "Photo: Tim Reckmann, CC BY-SA 4.0", "caption": "The modern skyline of Dubai at dusk"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Money from oil — often called oil <b>revenue</b> — transformed the <b>Gulf nations</b>. Governments used it to build modern roads, hospitals, schools, universities, ports, and airports, often in just a few decades. Small fishing and trading towns grew into giant cities almost within a single lifetime, so that a grandparent might remember camels and lantern-lit streets where their grandchildren now ride elevators in glass towers. <b>Dubai</b> and <b>Abu Dhabi</b> in the United Arab Emirates, and <b>Doha</b> in Qatar, became famous around the world for gleaming skyscrapers, vast shopping malls, and busy airports that connect travelers across the globe."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Did you know?</b> The <b>Burj Khalifa</b> in Dubai is the tallest building in the world, standing over 828 meters — that's more than half a mile high! Just a few generations earlier, the area around it was largely desert and a modest trading port."}, {"t": "order", "title": "From desert to skyline", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "Early 1900s", "label": "Towns rely on pearls, fishing, trade"}, {"yr": "1908", "label": "Oil found in Iran"}, {"yr": "1930s", "label": "Huge oil fields found in Saudi Arabia"}, {"yr": "Late 1900s", "label": "Gulf cities boom and modernize"}, {"yr": "2010", "label": "Burj Khalifa opens in Dubai"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "Because so much of the world's oil comes from this region, the Middle East became extremely important in <b>global affairs</b>. Cars, trucks, ships, planes, factories, and even the plastics in everyday objects depend on oil, so countries everywhere rely on a steady supply. When oil flows freely, prices stay low; when supplies are disrupted, prices can jump and economies all around the planet feel it. This deep connection to the world's energy needs gave the region a central place on the world stage, far beyond its size on the map."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Before oil vs. after oil", "a": {"title": "Earlier economy", "items": ["Pearling and fishing", "Camel caravan trade", "Small port towns", "Modest incomes"]}, "b": {"title": "Oil-era economy", "items": ["Major oil exports", "Modern cities and airports", "Schools and hospitals", "Global trade hubs"]}}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> A natural resource is only valuable if the world has found a <i>use</i> for it. Oil sat underground for millions of years, ignored. It became precious only once people invented engines that ran on it. Value often comes from a resource <i>and</i> the technology that needs it, together."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Many Gulf nations also realized that oil won't last forever, since it's a <b>non-renewable resource</b> — once it is pumped out and burned, it cannot grow back. So, looking ahead, they began planning carefully for the future by investing their oil wealth in tourism, technology, finance, world-class airlines, and clean energy like solar power, which the region's strong sunshine makes especially promising. The goal is to build broad, modern economies that can keep their people prosperous long after the oil age has passed — turning a single lucky resource into many lasting strengths."}, {"t": "modern", "html": "<b>Still with us today:</b> Gulf cities now host world sporting events, global airlines, and giant universities. Many are racing to develop <b>renewable energy</b> and new industries, hoping to stay prosperous long after oil. The region remains a crossroads connecting Europe, Asia, and Africa. From cuneiform tablets to soaring skyscrapers, the Middle East has spent thousands of years at the center of human history — and, as these five lessons show, its story is still being written today."}], "quiz": [{"q": "What hidden resource transformed the Gulf nations in the 1900s?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Gold", "Oil (petroleum)", "Diamonds", "Coal", "Silver"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Vast oil reserves discovered in the early 1900s transformed the region.", "hint": "Cars and planes run on it."}, {"q": "How did oil (petroleum) originally form?", "type": "mc", "options": ["From volcanic lava", "From the remains of tiny sea creatures over millions of years", "From melted sand", "From rainwater", "From meteor dust"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Oil formed over millions of years from the buried remains of tiny sea creatures.", "hint": "It involves ancient living things and lots of time."}, {"q": "In which country was a major early oil discovery made in 1908?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Iran", "Egypt", "Turkey", "Lebanon", "Israel"], "answer": 0, "explain": "One of the first big Middle Eastern oil discoveries was in Iran in 1908.", "hint": "It's a large country east of Iraq."}, {"q": "Which famous building in Dubai is the tallest in the world?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Burj Khalifa", "The Eiffel Tower", "The Hagia Sophia", "The Empire State Building", "A ziggurat"], "answer": 0, "explain": "The Burj Khalifa stands over 828 meters tall, the tallest building on Earth.", "hint": "Its name starts with 'Burj'."}, {"q": "How did oil money change Gulf nations?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It had no effect", "It made them stop trading", "It caused them to abandon their cities", "It funded modern cities, hospitals, schools, and airports", "It was buried and never used"], "answer": 3, "explain": "Oil revenue paid for roads, hospitals, schools, universities, and gleaming new cities.", "hint": "Think about new buildings and services."}, {"q": "Why is the Middle East so important in global affairs?", "type": "mc", "options": ["It has the only deserts on Earth", "Much of the world's oil comes from there, and the world depends on energy", "It is the largest continent", "It controls all the oceans", "It has the coldest climate"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Because so much oil comes from the region, what happens there can affect the whole world's economy.", "hint": "It connects to energy that everyone uses."}, {"q": "Why are many Gulf nations investing in tourism, technology, and solar power?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Because oil is non-renewable and won't last forever", "Because they dislike oil", "Because the law requires it", "Because oil disappeared overnight", "Because they have no deserts"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Oil is non-renewable, so nations are planning economies that can thrive after the oil age.", "hint": "Think about what happens when a resource runs out."}, {"q": "Before oil, many people in the region made a living from pearling, fishing, and trade.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — pearling, fishing, and caravan trade were important before the oil era."}, {"q": "Oil is a renewable resource that will never run out.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False — oil is non-renewable; once it is used up, it is gone."}, {"q": "Cities like Dubai grew from modest towns into major global hubs within roughly a lifetime.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True — oil wealth allowed remarkably fast growth from small towns to gleaming cities."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me6", "continent": "mideast", "n": 6, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🌆", "title": "The Modern Middle East: Challenge & Change", "hook": "<b>In one lifetime, fishing villages on the Gulf turned into cities of glass towers, driverless metros, and museums shaped like spaceships. How did it happen so fast?</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "The Middle East is one of the world's oldest neighborhoods, yet some of its cities feel like a glimpse of tomorrow. Travel along the Persian Gulf and you'll see skylines that didn't exist when your grandparents were young. The region today is a mix of ancient and brand-new, all in the same view."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Today the Middle East is made up of many independent countries, including Saudi Arabia, Iran, Turkey, Iraq, Egypt, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Syria, Yemen, Oman, and the small but mighty Gulf states: the United Arab Emirates, Qatar, Bahrain, and Kuwait. People here speak Arabic, Persian (Farsi), Turkish, Hebrew, Kurdish, and more. It is a patchwork of languages, faiths, and traditions stitched together by shared history."}, {"t": "p", "html": "A huge part of the modern story is <b>oil and gas</b>. In the 20th century, geologists found enormous reserves of petroleum beneath the deserts and seas. Selling that energy to the world brought sudden wealth to some countries. Leaders used it to build roads, schools, hospitals, airports, and skyscrapers, often in just a few decades, a speed of change few places have ever matched."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Cities like Dubai, Doha, and Abu Dhabi became famous for daring architecture. Dubai built the tallest building on Earth, the Burj Khalifa, soaring over 828 meters. The Gulf also poured money into airlines, universities, and world-class museums, hoping to be known for ideas and culture, not only energy."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Surprising fact:</b> The Middle East is remarkably <b>young</b>. In several countries, more than half the population is under 25. That makes it one of the most youthful regions on the planet, full of students, coders, athletes, and dreamers."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Dubai skyline 2015 (crop).jpg", "credit": "Photo: Tim Reckmann, CC BY-SA 2.0", "caption": "A Gulf skyline rising from the desert"}, {"t": "order", "title": "A century of change", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "1908", "label": "Oil first discovered in the region (Persia)"}, {"yr": "1960s", "label": "Gulf states begin big modern building"}, {"yr": "2010", "label": "Burj Khalifa opens in Dubai"}, {"yr": "2022", "label": "Qatar hosts a global football tournament"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "But oil cannot last forever, and the region knows it. So many countries are working to diversify, meaning they build new kinds of work that don't depend on petroleum. Think technology hubs, tourism, film, finance, solar power, and research labs. Saudi Arabia, for example, is investing in clean-energy projects and new cities in the desert."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Education is booming too. Branch campuses of famous universities have opened in the Gulf, and home-grown schools are training engineers and scientists. Women's participation in universities and work has grown sharply in many countries. The region also reaches space: the United Arab Emirates sent a probe called <b>Hope</b> to orbit Mars in 2021."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you see a shiny new skyline, ask, \"What was here 60 years ago?\" Comparing old maps and photos is a detective's trick for seeing how fast a place has changed, and why."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Then and now on the Gulf", "a": {"title": "Around 1950", "items": ["Small fishing and pearl-diving towns", "Few paved roads", "Travel mostly by boat and camel", "Modest mud-brick houses"]}, "b": {"title": "Today", "items": ["Glass towers and metro lines", "International airports", "Universities and museums", "Millions of residents from around the world"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Modern Middle Eastern cities are global crossroads. In Dubai or Doha, you might hear dozens of languages in one shopping mall, eat food from five continents, and meet workers and students from across Asia, Africa, and Europe. The region's old role as a meeting point of peoples has never really ended; it just grew taller."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Change brings challenges too: keeping cities cool in fierce heat, finding fresh water in dry lands, and making sure progress reaches everyone. These are big puzzles, and the young population growing up now is the generation expected to solve them."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Which resource brought sudden wealth to many Middle Eastern countries in the 20th century?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Gold", "Oil and natural gas", "Diamonds", "Silk", "Coal"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Vast reserves of petroleum and natural gas were discovered beneath the deserts and seas, funding rapid modern development.", "hint": "Think about what fuels cars and planes."}, {"q": "The Burj Khalifa, the world's tallest building, is located in which city?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Doha", "Riyadh", "Dubai", "Cairo", "Tehran"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The Burj Khalifa opened in Dubai in 2010 and stands over 828 meters tall.", "hint": "It's in the United Arab Emirates."}, {"q": "What does it mean for a country to 'diversify' its economy?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Build only oil refineries", "Develop new kinds of work beyond one resource", "Stop trading with the world", "Use only one language", "Move all cities to the coast"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Diversifying means creating many types of industry, like tech, tourism, and research, so the country doesn't depend on a single resource.", "hint": "It's the opposite of putting all your eggs in one basket."}, {"q": "Which country sent the 'Hope' probe to orbit Mars in 2021?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Egypt", "Iran", "The United Arab Emirates", "Turkey", "Jordan"], "answer": 2, "explain": "The UAE's Hope probe reached Mars orbit in 2021, a milestone for the region's space ambitions.", "hint": "A Gulf state famous for futuristic cities."}, {"q": "The Middle East has a notably young population, with many countries having over half their people under 25.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. It is one of the most youthful regions on Earth, full of young students and workers."}, {"q": "Before the oil era, towns along the Persian Gulf were often known for which activity?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Pearl diving and fishing", "Building skyscrapers", "Coal mining", "Making cars", "Growing tea"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Many Gulf towns lived from pearl diving and fishing before oil wealth transformed them.", "hint": "Think small boats and the sea."}, {"q": "Cities like Dubai and Doha are home to people from only one country.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. These cities are global crossroads with residents from across Asia, Africa, and Europe."}, {"q": "Which of these is a real challenge modern Gulf cities work to solve?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Too much snow", "Finding fresh water in dry lands", "Lack of sunlight", "Frozen harbors", "Too many forests"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Water is scarce in these dry regions, so cities invest in technologies like desalination to supply fresh water.", "hint": "The land is famously dry and hot."}, {"q": "Many Middle Eastern countries are investing in clean energy such as solar power.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. With abundant sunshine and an eye on the future, several countries are building large solar projects."}, {"q": "Why do Middle Eastern countries plan for life beyond oil?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Oil is illegal to sell", "Oil reserves will not last forever", "Oil is too cheap to bother with", "They dislike energy", "Oil only exists in Europe"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Petroleum is a finite resource, so countries diversify into other industries to secure their future.", "hint": "Nothing underground lasts forever."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me7", "continent": "mideast", "n": 7, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "👑", "title": "The Persian Empire: Kings, Roads & Tolerance", "hook": "<b>What if a king conquered half the known world, then told the people he ruled to keep their own gods, languages, and customs? That's exactly what Cyrus the Great did.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Around 2,500 years ago, a new power rose on the plateau that is now Iran. Under a leader named Cyrus the Great, the Persians built one of the largest empires the ancient world had ever seen, stretching from the edge of India to the shores of the Mediterranean."}, {"t": "p", "html": "<b>Cyrus the Great</b> founded this empire, called the Achaemenid Empire, around 550 BC. He was a brilliant general, but he is remembered just as much for how he treated the people he conquered. Instead of forcing everyone to follow Persian ways, he often let them keep their own religions, customs, and local rulers. For the ancient world, this was unusually generous."}, {"t": "p", "html": "One famous example: when Cyrus took the great city of Babylon, he allowed people who had been held there far from home to return to their own lands and rebuild their temples. A clay cylinder covered in writing, the <b>Cyrus Cylinder</b>, records some of his decrees and is sometimes called one of the world's earliest statements about treating different peoples fairly."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Surprising fact:</b> The Persian Empire ran a postal-style relay system so good that an ancient writer described the riders as unstoppable by snow, rain, heat, or darkness, a line later echoed by postal services thousands of years later."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "columns", "file": "Persepolis 24.11.2009 11-12-14.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Arad Mojtahedi, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "Stone columns and reliefs at Persepolis"}, {"t": "p", "html": "To govern such a vast land, later kings like Darius the Great organized the empire into provinces called <b>satrapies</b>, each run by a governor called a satrap. To keep them connected, the Persians built the famous <b>Royal Road</b>, a highway stretching roughly 2,500 kilometers. Messengers on horseback could carry news across it in about a week, a journey that would take an ordinary traveler months."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Building an empire", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "550 BC", "label": "Cyrus the Great founds the empire"}, {"yr": "539 BC", "label": "Cyrus takes Babylon and frees captives"}, {"yr": "518 BC", "label": "Darius begins building Persepolis"}, {"yr": "500 BC", "label": "The Royal Road links the empire"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Persians also standardized helpful things across their empire: coins, weights, and an official language for record-keeping. This made trade easier and helped people from many cultures do business together. A merchant could travel for weeks and still find familiar coins and roads."}, {"t": "p", "html": "At the heart of the empire stood <b>Persepolis</b>, a magnificent ceremonial capital built by Darius and his successors. Its great halls had forests of tall stone columns, and its staircases were carved with rows of representatives from many nations bringing gifts, a stone snapshot of how diverse the empire was."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When you read that a ruler was 'tolerant,' look for specific examples, like letting people keep their temples or languages. Specifics turn a label into real understanding."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two ways to rule an empire", "a": {"title": "Force everyone to be the same", "items": ["One required religion", "One forced language", "Local customs banned", "Frequent rebellions"]}, "b": {"title": "The Persian approach (often)", "items": ["Many religions allowed", "Local languages kept", "Local rulers and customs respected", "Easier to govern peacefully"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Persia's legacy lives on in Iran today, where the Persian (Farsi) language, poetry, and the spring festival of Nowruz, the Persian New Year, are still celebrated. Visitors from around the world come to walk among the ruins of Persepolis, now a UNESCO World Heritage Site."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Achaemenid Empire eventually fell to Alexander the Great around 330 BC, but the Persian idea, that a huge empire could hold many peoples together, influenced rulers for centuries afterward."}], "quiz": [{"q": "Who founded the Persian (Achaemenid) Empire around 550 BC?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Darius the Great", "Alexander the Great", "Cyrus the Great", "Xerxes", "Hammurabi"], "answer": 2, "explain": "Cyrus the Great founded the empire and became famous for his unusually fair treatment of conquered peoples.", "hint": "He's remembered for freeing captives in Babylon."}, {"q": "What was unusual about how Cyrus treated the peoples he conquered?", "type": "mc", "options": ["He forced one religion on all", "He often let them keep their religions and customs", "He banned all trade", "He destroyed every city", "He outlawed local languages"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Cyrus frequently allowed conquered peoples to keep their faiths, customs, and local rulers, which was rare for the time.", "hint": "Think tolerance, not force."}, {"q": "The Royal Road was mainly used to do what?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Grow crops", "Carry messages and news quickly across the empire", "Store water", "Hold festivals", "Mine gold"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Royal Road let mounted messengers carry news across thousands of kilometers in about a week.", "hint": "Think of it as an ancient express highway."}, {"q": "What was the magnificent ceremonial capital built by Darius and his successors?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Babylon", "Persepolis", "Athens", "Memphis", "Susa"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Persepolis, with its great columned halls and carved staircases, was the empire's ceremonial capital.", "hint": "Its ruins are in modern Iran."}, {"q": "The Cyrus Cylinder is a clay object recording some of Cyrus's decrees.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. The Cyrus Cylinder is sometimes called an early statement about treating different peoples fairly."}, {"q": "The provinces of the Persian Empire were called what?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Colonies", "Satrapies", "Counties", "Cantons", "Wards"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Each province was a satrapy, governed by an official called a satrap.", "hint": "It starts with 'sat-'."}, {"q": "The Persian Empire standardized things like coins and weights to make trade easier.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Common coins, weights, and roads helped people across many cultures trade smoothly."}, {"q": "Which festival, still celebrated today, is the Persian New Year?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Diwali", "Nowruz", "Hanukkah", "Carnival", "Songkran"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Nowruz marks the Persian New Year at the start of spring and is still celebrated widely.", "hint": "It means 'new day' and arrives in spring."}, {"q": "The Achaemenid Empire eventually fell to which conqueror around 330 BC?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Julius Caesar", "Alexander the Great", "Hannibal", "Genghis Khan", "Attila"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Alexander the Great defeated the Persian Empire around 330 BC, though Persian ideas of empire lived on.", "hint": "A young Macedonian general."}, {"q": "Cyrus the Great forced all conquered peoples to abandon their gods.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. He is remembered for the opposite, often letting people keep their own gods and temples."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me8", "continent": "mideast", "n": 8, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🔬", "title": "Wisdom of the Golden Age: Math, Medicine & Science", "hook": "<b>Every time you solve for x in algebra, you're using a word, and an idea, from a scholar who worked in Baghdad over 1,200 years ago.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Around the 8th to 13th centuries, the Middle East shone as a center of learning. In cities like Baghdad, Cairo, and Cordoba, scholars gathered to study, translate, and discover. This era is often called the Islamic Golden Age, and its ideas still shape your math homework today."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In Baghdad stood a famous center of study sometimes called the <b>House of Wisdom</b>. Scholars there gathered books from Greece, Persia, India, and beyond, translating them into Arabic so knowledge would not be lost. They didn't just copy; they corrected, expanded, and built on what they found."}, {"t": "p", "html": "One of the greatest was <b>al-Khwarizmi</b>, a mathematician of the 9th century. He wrote a book whose title gave us the word <b>algebra</b>. He showed step-by-step methods for solving equations, and his name, passed through Latin, gives us another everyday word: <b>algorithm</b>, the set of steps a computer follows."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Scholars of this age also helped spread the number system we use today, with the digits 0 through 9 and the powerful idea of <b>zero</b> as a placeholder. These numerals came from India and were refined and carried westward through the Middle East, which is why Europeans later called them 'Arabic numerals.'"}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Surprising fact:</b> The scholar <b>Ibn al-Haytham</b> figured out that we see because light bounces off objects and into our eyes, not because our eyes shoot out rays. His careful experiments on light make him a founder of the scientific method of testing ideas."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Astrolabe-Persian-18C.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Andrew Dunn, CC BY-SA 2.0", "caption": "A finely engraved Persian astrolabe"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Medicine flourished too. <b>Ibn Sina</b> (known in Europe as Avicenna) wrote a massive medical encyclopedia, the Canon of Medicine, that was used in universities for hundreds of years, even in Europe. It organized everything known about diseases, treatments, and the human body into one clear reference."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Scholars of the Golden Age", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~825", "label": "Al-Khwarizmi writes his book on algebra"}, {"yr": "~1021", "label": "Ibn al-Haytham completes his Book of Optics"}, {"yr": "~1025", "label": "Ibn Sina finishes the Canon of Medicine"}, {"yr": "~1280", "label": "His works are taught across Europe"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "Astronomers built clever instruments like the <b>astrolabe</b>, a brass disk that could find the time, your position, and the direction of cities by measuring the stars. Sailors, travelers, and timekeepers all relied on it. It was, in a way, an early handheld computer made of metal and math."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Many English science words hide their history. Algebra, algorithm, alcohol, and chemistry all passed through Arabic. Spotting these word-clues is a fun way to trace where ideas traveled."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Two ways to gain knowledge", "a": {"title": "Just believe old books", "items": ["Accept claims without testing", "Never measure", "Copy errors forever", "Hard to improve"]}, "b": {"title": "The Golden Age method", "items": ["Test ideas with experiments", "Measure carefully", "Correct old mistakes", "Build on others' work"]}, "sub": ""}, {"t": "modern", "html": "This knowledge didn't stay in one place. Translated works traveled to Europe and helped spark later scientific progress. Today, mathematicians, doctors, and engineers across the world still build on foundations laid in those bustling medieval libraries."}, {"t": "p", "html": "The Golden Age reminds us that science is a relay race. The Middle East gathered wisdom from many lands, improved it, and passed the torch forward, a gift to everyone who has ever solved an equation or visited a doctor."}], "quiz": [{"q": "The word 'algebra' comes from the title of a book by which scholar?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Ibn Sina", "Al-Khwarizmi", "Ibn al-Haytham", "Aristotle", "Euclid"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Al-Khwarizmi's 9th-century book gave us the word algebra, and his name gave us 'algorithm.'", "hint": "His name also hides inside a computer-science word."}, {"q": "The famous center of learning in Baghdad is often called the:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Hall of Mirrors", "House of Wisdom", "Tower of Babel", "Temple of Stars", "Palace of Books"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The House of Wisdom was a hub where scholars translated and expanded knowledge from many cultures.", "hint": "It's a 'house' of something you gain by learning."}, {"q": "Ibn al-Haytham showed that we see because:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Our eyes shoot out rays", "Light bounces off objects into our eyes", "The sun controls our minds", "Stars send us images", "We imagine everything"], "answer": 1, "explain": "His experiments showed vision works when light reflects off objects and enters the eye, a key step for the scientific method.", "hint": "Think about how light actually travels."}, {"q": "Ibn Sina (Avicenna) is best known for a great work in which field?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Astronomy", "Medicine", "Painting", "Music", "Geography"], "answer": 1, "explain": "His Canon of Medicine was a medical encyclopedia used in universities for centuries.", "hint": "You'd visit this kind of expert when you're sick."}, {"q": "The number system we use, including zero, reached Europe through the Middle East.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. The digits came from India, were refined in the Middle East, and became known in Europe as 'Arabic numerals.'"}, {"q": "An astrolabe was a tool used mainly to:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Cook food", "Measure the stars to find time and direction", "Cut stone", "Weigh gold", "Send letters"], "answer": 1, "explain": "By sighting the stars, an astrolabe could tell the time, your position, and directions, like an early handheld computer.", "hint": "It looks to the sky."}, {"q": "Scholars of the Golden Age translated books only from Arabic into Greek.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. They translated works from Greek, Persian, Indian and other sources into Arabic to preserve and expand them."}, {"q": "Which everyday computer-science word comes from the name al-Khwarizmi?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Pixel", "Algorithm", "Keyboard", "Browser", "Network"], "answer": 1, "explain": "'Algorithm,' a set of step-by-step instructions, comes from his Latinized name.", "hint": "Computers follow these step-by-step."}, {"q": "The idea of zero as a placeholder was important for advanced mathematics.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Zero made it possible to write large numbers clearly and do powerful calculations."}, {"q": "What is one big lesson the Golden Age teaches about science?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Ideas come from only one country", "Knowledge is a relay passed and improved across cultures", "Old books should never be changed", "Experiments are useless", "Only kings can discover things"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Middle East gathered, corrected, and passed on knowledge, showing science as a shared, ongoing effort.", "hint": "Think of a torch handed from runner to runner."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me9", "continent": "mideast", "n": 9, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🏜️", "title": "Deserts, Rivers & the World's Crossroads", "hook": "<b>Stand in the right spot in the Middle East and you could step toward Asia, Africa, or Europe. Few places on Earth connect so many worlds at once.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "The Middle East sits at a remarkable spot on the globe: the meeting point of three continents. To understand its history, you first have to understand its geography, its deserts, its rivers, and the narrow passages that link distant seas."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Much of the region is dry. The vast <b>Arabian Desert</b> covers most of the Arabian Peninsula, with rolling dunes, gravel plains, and a sandy heart called the Rub' al Khali, or 'Empty Quarter,' one of the largest continuous sand deserts on Earth. In such dry lands, water is more precious than gold."}, {"t": "p", "html": "That's why rivers matter so much. The <b>Tigris and Euphrates</b> rivers flow through Iraq, watering a land the ancient Greeks called Mesopotamia, meaning 'between the rivers.' Their floods left rich soil, and on that soil some of the world's first cities, writing, and laws were born. Without these rivers, history would look very different."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Surprising fact:</b> The Rub' al Khali desert is so large and empty that some of its dunes rise higher than 250 meters, taller than many skyscrapers, and a person could travel for days without seeing a single town."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "globe", "file": "Suez Canal, Egypt (cropped).jpg", "credit": "Photo: Axelspace Corporation, CC BY-SA 4.0", "caption": "Ships crossing the Suez Canal in Egypt"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Along the region's western edge run other famous waters. The <b>Jordan River</b> flows into the very salty Dead Sea, the lowest point on Earth's land surface, where the water is so dense that swimmers float easily. Nearby, the mighty <b>Nile</b> brings life to Egypt, its green ribbon of farmland cutting through desert on both sides."}, {"t": "p", "html": "One human-made waterway changed the world: the <b>Suez Canal</b> in Egypt, opened in 1869. By cutting through a narrow strip of land, it connected the Mediterranean Sea to the Red Sea, letting ships travel between Europe and Asia without sailing all the way around Africa. It remains one of the busiest shipping routes on the planet."}, {"t": "order", "title": "Waters that shaped a region", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "~3500 BC", "label": "First cities rise between the Tigris and Euphrates"}, {"yr": "~3000 BC", "label": "Egypt flourishes along the Nile"}, {"yr": "1869", "label": "The Suez Canal opens"}, {"yr": "Today", "label": "Suez remains a key world shipping route"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "Because it links three continents, the Middle East has always been a <b>crossroads</b>. Traders, travelers, armies, and ideas passed through it for thousands of years. Spices from India, silk from China, gold from Africa, and goods from Europe all met in its markets and ports. To control these routes was to hold a key to world trade."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> When a place is called a 'crossroads,' look at a map and trace what it connects. Geography often explains why certain cities became rich, powerful, or famous."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "Desert versus river valley", "a": {"title": "The open desert", "items": ["Very little rainfall", "Few permanent settlements", "Travel by camel caravans", "Oases as precious rest stops"]}, "b": {"title": "A river valley", "items": ["Reliable water and rich soil", "Crowded cities and farms", "Boats for transport", "Birthplace of early civilizations"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Geography still rules daily life. Modern countries build pipelines and canals, and the Suez Canal carries a large share of the world's trade. Meanwhile, engineers tackle the old challenge of fresh water using desalination plants that turn seawater into drinking water for desert cities."}, {"t": "p", "html": "From empty dunes to crowded canals, the Middle East shows how land and water shape human life. Its position as a bridge between continents made it a meeting place of peoples, and that's a big part of why its story is so rich."}], "quiz": [{"q": "The Middle East is famous as a meeting point of how many continents?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Two", "Three", "Four", "Five", "Six"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It links Asia, Africa, and Europe, making it a true crossroads of the world.", "hint": "Asia, Africa, and one more."}, {"q": "The Tigris and Euphrates rivers flow mainly through which modern country?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Egypt", "Iraq", "Turkey only", "Saudi Arabia", "Iran"], "answer": 1, "explain": "They run through Iraq, the heart of ancient Mesopotamia, 'the land between the rivers.'", "hint": "Ancient Mesopotamia is here."}, {"q": "What does 'Mesopotamia' mean?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Land of gold", "Between the rivers", "City of the sun", "Edge of the desert", "Place of kings"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Mesopotamia is Greek for 'between the rivers,' referring to the Tigris and Euphrates.", "hint": "Think about the two rivers."}, {"q": "The Suez Canal connects which two bodies of water?", "type": "mc", "options": ["The Atlantic and Pacific", "The Mediterranean and Red Seas", "The Caspian and Black Seas", "The Persian Gulf and Indian Ocean", "The Dead Sea and Nile"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Opened in 1869, the Suez Canal links the Mediterranean Sea to the Red Sea, shortening trips between Europe and Asia.", "hint": "It lets ships skip sailing around Africa."}, {"q": "The Dead Sea is so salty that people float in it easily.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Its very high salt content makes the water dense, so swimmers float on the surface."}, {"q": "The Rub' al Khali, or 'Empty Quarter,' is best described as:", "type": "mc", "options": ["A rainforest", "A huge sand desert", "A frozen plain", "A crowded city", "A coral reef"], "answer": 1, "explain": "It is one of the largest continuous sand deserts on Earth, with enormous dunes and few settlements.", "hint": "Its nickname means 'empty.'"}, {"q": "The Nile River brings life to which country in the region's western edge?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Iraq", "Egypt", "Oman", "Lebanon", "Yemen"], "answer": 1, "explain": "The Nile's green valley supports farms and cities through the deserts of Egypt.", "hint": "Think pyramids."}, {"q": "Because it is dry, fresh water has always been precious in much of the Middle East.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. With large deserts and little rain, water shaped where people could live and farm."}, {"q": "In the open desert, long-distance travel was traditionally done by:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Camel caravans", "Steam trains", "Sailboats", "Bicycles", "Subways"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Camel caravans crossed the deserts, stopping at oases for water and rest.", "hint": "This animal is called the 'ship of the desert.'"}, {"q": "The Suez Canal is mostly unused today and carries little world trade.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. It remains one of the busiest and most important shipping routes on the planet."}]});

  lesson({"id": "me10", "continent": "mideast", "n": 10, "minutes": 10, "emoji": "🕌", "title": "Bazaars, Food & Everyday Life", "hook": "<b>Imagine a market so old and so vast you could wander its covered lanes for hours, past mountains of spices, glowing lamps, and the smell of fresh bread. Welcome to the bazaar.</b>", "beats": [{"t": "lead", "html": "Empires and inventions are exciting, but the real heartbeat of any place is everyday life: what people eat, how they greet guests, and where they shop. In the Middle East, much of that life has long flowed through the bustling market."}, {"t": "p", "html": "A traditional Middle Eastern market is called a <b>souk</b> (in Arabic) or a <b>bazaar</b> (in Persian and Turkish). Many are covered to give shade from the sun, with twisting lanes grouped by trade: one alley for spices, another for gold, another for carpets or copper pots. Some, like the Grand Bazaar in Istanbul, have thousands of shops under one roof."}, {"t": "p", "html": "In the souk you'll find foods that have flavored the region for thousands of years. <b>Bread</b> is daily and sacred, often flat and freshly baked. <b>Dates</b>, sweet and sticky, have nourished desert travelers for ages. And <b>spices</b>, like cumin, saffron, cardamom, and cinnamon, were once so valuable that whole trade routes were built around them."}, {"t": "fact", "html": "<b>Surprising fact:</b> Saffron, the world's most expensive spice, comes from the tiny threads inside a crocus flower. It takes around 150 flowers to make just one gram, which is why a pinch can cost more than its weight in silver."}, {"t": "scene", "art": "scroll", "file": "Grand Bazaar Shop Istanbul 2007.jpg", "credit": "Photo: Maderibeyza, CC BY-SA 3.0", "caption": "A colorful shop in Istanbul's Grand Bazaar"}, {"t": "p", "html": "Hospitality is a deeply honored value across the region. Welcoming a guest, even a stranger, with food and drink is a point of pride. Offering tea or coffee, often spiced or sweet, is a warm ritual. In many homes, refusing to share a meal with a visitor would be unthinkable; the guest is treated almost like family."}, {"t": "p", "html": "Art here often follows beautiful patterns rather than pictures of people. <b>Calligraphy</b>, the art of elegant writing, turns words into flowing decoration on walls, books, and tiles. Alongside it, dazzling <b>geometric patterns</b>, repeating stars and interlocking shapes, cover mosques and palaces. These designs can be stunningly complex, all built from simple math."}, {"t": "order", "title": "A spice's long journey", "sub": "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.", "items": [{"yr": "Field", "label": "Saffron crocus flowers are picked by hand"}, {"yr": "Drying", "label": "The red threads are dried with care"}, {"yr": "Bazaar", "label": "Spices are sold in the souk"}, {"yr": "Kitchen", "label": "A cook adds a pinch to a festive dish"}]}, {"t": "p", "html": "Mealtimes are social. Dishes are often shared from the center of the table: warm flatbreads for scooping, dips like hummus, grilled meats, rice studded with nuts, and sweets soaked in honey or rosewater. Eating together, slowly and with conversation, matters as much as the food itself."}, {"t": "guide", "html": "<b>Owl tip:</b> Look closely at a geometric tile pattern and try to find the smallest piece that repeats. Spotting that 'unit' is exactly how artists, and mathematicians, build these dazzling designs."}, {"t": "compare", "title": "A supermarket versus a souk", "a": {"title": "A modern supermarket", "items": ["Fixed prices on labels", "Quiet, packaged goods", "In and out quickly", "Little conversation"]}, "b": {"title": "A traditional souk", "items": ["Friendly bargaining over prices", "Open sacks of fragrant spices", "A place to meet and chat", "Crafts made by hand nearby"]}}, {"t": "modern", "html": "Today, gleaming shopping malls stand beside ancient souks, and you can order shawarma by app. Yet the old markets thrive, drawing both locals and curious travelers. Calligraphy and geometric art appear on everything from museum walls to sneaker designs, proof that old traditions can feel fresh."}, {"t": "p", "html": "From a shared loaf of bread to a star-shaped tile, everyday Middle Eastern culture is full of warmth, beauty, and welcome. It's a reminder that history isn't only about kings and battles; it's also about the meals and patterns that make daily life rich."}], "quiz": [{"q": "A traditional covered Middle Eastern market is called a souk or a:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Plaza", "Bazaar", "Stadium", "Harbor", "Forum"], "answer": 1, "explain": "'Souk' is Arabic and 'bazaar' is Persian and Turkish; both name the region's bustling markets.", "hint": "The Grand one is in Istanbul."}, {"q": "Which spice, made from tiny flower threads, is famously the world's most expensive?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Pepper", "Saffron", "Cinnamon", "Cumin", "Salt"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Saffron comes from crocus flowers and takes around 150 blooms per gram, making it extremely valuable.", "hint": "It gives food a golden color."}, {"q": "What food has long nourished desert travelers and is sweet and sticky?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Dates", "Ice cream", "Apples", "Corn", "Cheese"], "answer": 0, "explain": "Dates are sweet, energy-rich, and have sustained travelers across the deserts for ages.", "hint": "It grows on palm trees."}, {"q": "Calligraphy is the art of:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Cooking meat", "Elegant, decorative writing", "Weaving carpets", "Building domes", "Carving wood"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Calligraphy turns beautiful writing into decoration on walls, books, and tiles.", "hint": "It's all about letters and words."}, {"q": "Hospitality and welcoming guests with food and drink is highly valued in the region.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Offering tea, coffee, or a meal to guests, even strangers, is a deep point of pride."}, {"q": "Much traditional Islamic art uses which kind of design especially?", "type": "mc", "options": ["Realistic portraits of kings", "Repeating geometric patterns", "Photographs", "Cartoon animals", "Maps of the stars only"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Geometric patterns and calligraphy, rather than lifelike pictures of people, decorate many mosques and palaces.", "hint": "Think interlocking stars and shapes."}, {"q": "In a traditional souk, prices are always fixed and printed on labels.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 1, "explain": "False. Friendly bargaining over prices is a normal and expected part of shopping in the souk."}, {"q": "Bread in the Middle East is often described as:", "type": "mc", "options": ["Rare and disliked", "Flat, fresh, and an everyday staple", "Only eaten on holidays", "Made from rice", "Always frozen"], "answer": 1, "explain": "Flatbread is freshly baked and eaten daily, even used to scoop up dips and stews.", "hint": "You might tear it to scoop hummus."}, {"q": "Meals in the region are often shared from the center of the table.", "type": "tf", "options": ["True", "False"], "answer": 0, "explain": "True. Sharing dishes and eating together with conversation is an important part of the culture."}, {"q": "How do many artists and mathematicians build a complex geometric pattern?", "type": "mc", "options": ["By repeating a small unit shape", "By painting random blobs", "By copying photographs", "By using only one color", "By avoiding any straight lines"], "answer": 0, "explain": "A small repeating 'unit' is multiplied and arranged to create dazzling, intricate designs.", "hint": "Find the smallest piece that repeats."}]});

  /* ============================================================
     OCEANIA & PACIFIC
     ============================================================ */
  cont({
    id: "oceania", name: "Oceania & Pacific", emoji: "🏝️", color: "#1597a5",
    blurb: "Ancient voyagers & island worlds",
    intro: "The world's smallest continent and its largest ocean — home to history's greatest sea-voyagers, the planet's oldest living cultures, astonishing wildlife, and thousands of islands now on the front line of a changing climate.",
    badge: { name: "Pacific Voyager", emoji: "🏝️" },
    lessons: ["oc1", "oc2", "oc3", "oc4", "oc5", "oc6", "oc7", "oc8", "oc9", "oc10"],
    sectionQuiz: [
      { q: "Aboriginal Australians have one of the world's…", type: "mc", options: ["Newest cultures", "Oldest continuous living cultures", "Smallest", "Only written cultures"], answer: 1, explain: "Aboriginal cultures stretch back over 60,000 years." },
      { q: "Pacific Islanders navigated vast oceans using…", type: "mc", options: ["GPS", "Stars, waves, and birds", "Engines", "Maps from Europe"], answer: 1, explain: "They were master navigators using nature itself." },
      { q: "Which European explorer mapped much of the Pacific and eastern Australia in the 1700s?", type: "mc", options: ["Captain James Cook", "Christopher Columbus", "Marco Polo", "Magellan"], answer: 0, explain: "Captain Cook charted much of the region in the 1700s." },
      { q: "The Indigenous people of New Zealand are the…", type: "mc", options: ["Maori", "Inca", "Zulu", "Inuit"], answer: 0, explain: "The Maori are New Zealand's Indigenous people." },
      { q: "The Pacific Ocean is the world's largest ocean.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "It's the biggest ocean — bigger than all the land on Earth combined." },
      { q: "Australia is famous for marsupials and egg-laying mammals called…", type: "mc", options: ["monotremes", "reptiles", "amphibians", "primates"], answer: 0, explain: "The platypus and echidna are monotremes — mammals that lay eggs." },
      { q: "Australia and New Zealand were colonized mainly by…", type: "mc", options: ["Britain", "Spain", "France", "China"], answer: 0, explain: "Both became British colonies, then independent nations." },
      { q: "A big challenge facing low-lying Pacific islands today is…", type: "mc", options: ["Too much snow", "Rising seas from climate change", "Volcanoes only", "Too many cars"], answer: 1, explain: "Rising sea levels threaten low islands — a major climate concern." },
      { q: "The Treaty of Waitangi (1840) is famous partly because…", type: "mc", options: ["it was never signed", "its English and Maori versions said different things", "it ended World War II", "it created the Pacific Ocean"], answer: 1, explain: "The two versions used different words, and the disagreement still matters today." },
      { q: "Why are Pacific Islanders called some of history's greatest explorers?", type: "mc", options: ["They had the best ships from Europe", "They crossed vast open oceans using only nature to navigate", "They never left home", "They used satellites"], answer: 1, explain: "They mastered the open ocean long before compasses or maps." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc1", continent: "oceania", n: 1, minutes: 10, emoji: "🛶",
    title: "Master Voyagers of the Pacific",
    hook: "Long before Europe built ocean ships, Pacific islanders crossed thousands of miles of open sea in canoes — and settled a third of the planet using only the stars, the waves, and the birds.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Spread across the world's largest ocean are thousands of islands, and reaching almost every one of them is one of the greatest adventures in human history. Geographers group these islands into three regions whose names are worth knowing: <b>Melanesia</b> (“black islands,” including New Guinea and Fiji), <b>Micronesia</b> (“tiny islands” north of the equator), and <b>Polynesia</b> (“many islands,” the huge triangle stretching from Hawaii to New Zealand to remote Easter Island). The people who settled them were not lost wanderers blown off course. They were the most skilled ocean navigators the world had ever seen." },
      { t: "p", html: "Their story began thousands of years ago with seafarers archaeologists call the <b>Lapita</b> people, who pushed out from the islands of Southeast Asia roughly <b>3,000 years ago</b>, carrying their distinctive pottery, their crops, and their animals from island to island. Their descendants, the <b>Polynesians</b>, then did something almost unimaginable. Over centuries they sailed ever further east into emptier and emptier ocean, reaching Hawaii, Easter Island, and finally New Zealand — the last large landmass on Earth to be settled by humans, only about <b>700 years ago</b>." },
      { t: "p", html: "What makes this so remarkable is <i>how</i> they did it. They had no compass, no clock, no map, and no metal at all. Instead they built powerful <b>double-hulled voyaging canoes</b> — two long hulls joined by a deck, carrying a sail, dozens of people, and enough food, water, and live animals to start a brand-new colony. Because these canoes were fast, stable, and could carry settlers and supplies together, a single successful voyage could plant a whole community on an island no human had ever touched." },
      { t: "scene", art: "ship", file: "Hokule'aSailing2009.jpg", credit: "Photo: Phil Uhl, CC BY-SA 3.0", caption: "Double-hulled voyaging canoes carried whole communities across the open Pacific." },
      { t: "p", html: "The real magic was <b>wayfinding</b> — navigating by reading nature itself. A master navigator memorized a “star compass” of dozens of stars that rose and set at fixed points on the horizon, and steered by them all night long. By day, when the stars were gone, they read the <b>ocean swells</b>, feeling in the hull how waves bent around unseen islands far over the horizon. They watched the flight paths of <b>seabirds</b> at dawn and dusk, noticed the greenish glow that distant lagoons cast onto the underside of clouds, and tracked floating leaves and the color of the water. The whole ocean became a kind of living instrument they could read." },
      { t: "hotmap", map: "oceania", title: "The Polynesian Triangle", sub: "Tap each point of the great voyaging world.",
        spots: [
          { x: 300, y: 60, label: "Hawaii", text: "The northern tip of Polynesia, settled by voyagers around 1,000 years ago." },
          { x: 250, y: 175, label: "New Zealand (Aotearoa)", text: "The last large landmass on Earth settled by humans, about 700 years ago." },
          { x: 200, y: 120, label: "Open Pacific", text: "Navigators crossed thousands of miles of this empty ocean using only nature." },
        ] },
      { t: "p", html: "It took a lifetime to learn, and because the knowledge lived only inside the minds of expert navigators, it was fragile. After Europeans arrived with compasses and charts, traditional wayfinding faded and very nearly died out completely. For a while, some outsiders even doubted the islands had been settled on purpose at all, suggesting the voyagers must have simply drifted by luck — a claim that quietly insulted one of humanity's greatest achievements." },
      { t: "order", title: "Settling the Pacific", sub: "Drag these into order, earliest to latest.",
        items: [
          { yr: "~1500 BC", label: "Lapita seafarers spread across Melanesia" },
          { yr: "~1000 BC", label: "They reach western Polynesia (Tonga, Samoa)" },
          { yr: "~1000 AD", label: "Voyagers settle Hawaii and Easter Island" },
          { yr: "~1300 AD", label: "Polynesians reach New Zealand, the last big land" },
          { yr: "1976 AD", label: "The Hokulea revives traditional wayfinding" },
        ] },
      { t: "fact", html: "In <b>1976</b>, a double-hulled canoe called the <b>Hokulea</b> sailed from Hawaii to Tahiti with no instruments at all, guided by a master navigator named <b>Mau Piailug</b>. It proved beyond doubt that the old voyagers had crossed the ocean by skill, not by accident — and it relaunched the art for a new generation." },
      { t: "fact", html: "The voyaging canoes carried a traveling pantry of plants and animals — taro, breadfruit, bananas, pigs, dogs, and chickens — so that the moment a new island was found, the settlers could start farming. They didn't just find islands; they brought everything needed to <b>live</b> on them." },
      { t: "p", html: "Could these epic voyages really have been planned, not accidental? The evidence is overwhelming. Navigators often deliberately sailed <b>into the wind</b> first, reasoning that if they found no land they could turn and ride the wind safely home — a clever insurance policy no lost drifter would ever use. They timed departures to the seasons, packed weeks of food and water, and carried breeding animals and seed crops. In Micronesia, navigators even built <b>“stick charts”</b> — lattices of palm ribs and shells that mapped how ocean swells curl around islands, the only ocean maps of their kind anywhere on Earth." },
      { t: "fact", html: "Knowledge this precious had to be taught with great care. Young navigators trained for years, memorizing star paths as <b>chanted songs</b> and practicing by feeling the swells while lying in the bottom of a canoe. A single master might carry the safe routes to dozens of islands entirely in his head — a living library that took a lifetime to fill, and could be lost in a single generation." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Notice what this story overturns: “advanced” doesn't have to mean machines and metal. The Polynesians built a sophisticated science of the sea entirely out of observation and memory. Real intelligence is about how carefully you read the world — not how much equipment you own." },
      { t: "modern", html: "Today, traditional wayfinding is proudly alive again. The Hokulea has since sailed all the way around the world the ancient way, and young navigators across the Pacific are learning the star compass once more. It still matters because it reminds everyone that there is more than one way to be brilliant — and that knowledge worth keeping has to be passed, carefully, from one generation to the next or it can vanish in a single lifetime." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "The three island regions of the Pacific are Melanesia, Micronesia, and…", type: "mc", options: ["Polynesia", "Indonesia", "Australasia", "Patagonia"], answer: 0, explain: "Polynesia means “many islands” — the huge triangle from Hawaii to NZ to Easter Island.", hint: "It means “many islands.”" },
      { q: "The skill of navigating by stars, swells, and birds is called…", type: "mc", options: ["wayfinding", "farming", "weaving", "mining"], answer: 0, explain: "Wayfinding turned the whole ocean into a readable instrument." },
      { q: "Pacific voyagers crossed the ocean using…", type: "mc", options: ["GPS and engines", "stars, ocean swells, winds, and birds", "European maps", "luck alone"], answer: 1, explain: "They read nature itself — no compass or chart needed." },
      { q: "What kind of boat did Polynesians use for long voyages?", type: "mc", options: ["double-hulled voyaging canoes", "steel steamships", "submarines", "rubber rafts"], answer: 0, explain: "Two hulls joined by a deck made them fast, stable, and able to carry settlers and supplies." },
      { q: "New Zealand was the last large landmass on Earth settled by humans.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Polynesians reached it only about 700 years ago." },
      { q: "Voyaging canoes carried plants and animals because…", type: "mc", options: ["they were pets only", "settlers needed to start farming on a new island", "they were for trade in Europe", "the law required it"], answer: 1, explain: "Taro, pigs, and chickens let a new colony survive from day one." },
      { q: "The Lapita people began spreading across the Pacific about…", type: "mc", options: ["3,000 years ago", "300 years ago", "last century", "50 years ago"], answer: 0, explain: "Their voyages, around 1500 BC, began the great Pacific settlement." },
      { q: "The 1976 canoe that revived wayfinding was named…", type: "mc", options: ["the Hokulea", "the Titanic", "the Mayflower", "the Endeavour"], answer: 0, explain: "The Hokulea sailed Hawaii to Tahiti with no instruments." },
      { q: "A navigator could sense a hidden island by…", type: "mc", options: ["feeling how ocean swells bent around it", "calling it on the radio", "reading a paper map", "using sonar"], answer: 0, explain: "Swells wrapping around distant land could be felt in the canoe's hull." },
      { q: "The main lesson of the master voyagers is that…", type: "mc", options: ["only machines make people advanced", "careful observation of nature can be a sophisticated science", "the ocean is easy to cross", "maps are useless"], answer: 1, explain: "They built a real science of the sea from memory and observation alone." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc2", continent: "oceania", n: 2, minutes: 10, emoji: "⛵",
    title: "European Explorers Reach the Pacific",
    hook: "To Europeans, the Pacific was the last great blank space on the map. When they finally crossed it in the 1700s, the islands were changed forever.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "For centuries, European mapmakers stared at a huge blank space at the bottom of the world. They were so sure a vast unknown <b>“southern land”</b> must be there — a continent heavy enough to “balance” the lands of the north — that they named it before anyone had seen it: <i>Terra Australis</i>, Latin for “southern land,” which is where the name <b>Australia</b> comes from. The trouble was, the Pacific is so enormous that finding anything in it was like searching for a few coins scattered across a football field in the dark." },
      { t: "p", html: "The ocean even got its name from a European. In <b>1521</b>, the explorer <b>Ferdinand Magellan</b> sailed into it after a stormy passage around South America, found the water calm, and called it the <i>Mar Pacífico</i> — the “peaceful sea.” Over the next two centuries a trickle of European ships crossed it. The Dutch sailor <b>Abel Tasman</b> reached Tasmania and New Zealand in the 1640s, but it was one British captain who would map the Pacific more thoroughly than anyone before him." },
      { t: "p", html: "That captain was <b>James Cook</b>. On three great voyages between 1768 and 1779, he charted the coast of New Zealand, the entire eastern coast of Australia, and dozens of islands with such accuracy that some of his maps were still used more than a century later. What set Cook apart was that he sailed with <b>scientists and artists</b> — botanists collecting plants, astronomers measuring the heavens, painters recording everything they saw — so his ships came home loaded not just with charts but with a flood of new knowledge about the natural world." },
      { t: "scene", art: "ship", file: "Captainjamescookportrait.jpg", credit: "Public domain", caption: "Captain James Cook charted much of the Pacific in the 1700s." },
      { t: "p", html: "It is important to be honest about a word here. Europeans often said they “discovered” these lands, but of course people already lived on them and had navigated these waters for thousands of years. What truly changed was that the Pacific was now <b>connected to Europe</b> — and that connection carried enormous consequences, both wonderful and terrible. New metal tools, crops, and animals arrived and transformed island life. But so did European <b>diseases</b> like measles and smallpox, which the islanders had never met before and had no resistance to. In some places these illnesses killed a heartbreaking share of the population, just as they had in the Americas." },
      { t: "compare", title: "What contact brought",
        a: { title: "Arrived from Europe", items: ["Accurate maps and charts", "Metal tools, cloth, and new crops", "Missionaries and the written word", "Whalers, traders, and settlers"] },
        b: { title: "The heavy cost", items: ["Deadly new diseases", "Loss of land and freedom", "Pressure to abandon old ways", "The end of the islands' long isolation"] } },
      { t: "p", html: "Because Cook's maps showed exactly where these lands lay and how to reach them, they opened the door for Britain to plant <b>colonies</b>. The first British colony in Australia was founded in <b>1788</b> — partly as a faraway prison settlement, sending convicts to the other side of the planet. From that moment the long isolation of the Pacific was over, and the lives of Aboriginal Australians, Maori, and Pacific Islanders would never be the same." },
      { t: "fact", html: "When Cook's crew first saw a strange hopping animal and asked local Aboriginal people what it was, the word they heard became its English name: <b>kangaroo</b>." },
      { t: "fact", html: "Cook also quietly defeated one of the great killers of long voyages: <b>scurvy</b>, a disease caused by a lack of vitamin C. By forcing his crews to eat pickled cabbage and other fresh foods, he kept his sailors far healthier than was normal — saving lives even before doctors fully understood why it worked." },
      { t: "p", html: "Cook was not the first European to reach these waters, only the most thorough. A century earlier the Dutch sailor <b>Abel Tasman</b> had bumped into Tasmania and New Zealand but sailed away without grasping what he'd found, and Spanish ships had long crossed the Pacific for trade. What set Cook apart was patience and method: he mapped <i>carefully</i>, came back to check his work, and wrote down everything he saw." },
      { t: "p", html: "After the explorers came the <b>traders, whalers, and missionaries</b>, and they reshaped island life as much as any map. Whaling ships turned quiet bays into busy ports; missionaries brought writing and schools, but also pressed islanders to abandon ancestral customs, dress, and dances. Within a few generations, societies thousands of years old were transformed — sometimes welcoming the change, often given little choice in it." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Maps are never just maps. When Cook charted a coastline he wasn't only recording where land was — he was making it possible for ships, settlers, and whole empires to follow. A single accurate map can redirect the course of history." },
      { t: "modern", html: "Cook's voyages connected the Pacific to the rest of the world, which is exactly why his name still sparks debate. To some he was a brilliant navigator and scientist; to many Indigenous peoples his arrival marked the start of losing their lands, and that pain is real and remembered. Both things are true at once. Understanding history honestly means holding the achievement and the harm together, instead of pretending only one of them happened." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "The name “Australia” comes from the idea of a…", type: "mc", options: ["northern land", "southern land (Terra Australis)", "lost city", "river"], answer: 1, explain: "Europeans imagined a great “southern land” long before they found it.", hint: "Think about direction — Latin for “southern.”" },
      { q: "Who named the Pacific the “peaceful sea” in 1521?", type: "mc", options: ["Magellan", "Cook", "Tasman", "Columbus"], answer: 0, explain: "Magellan found the water calm and called it Mar Pacífico." },
      { q: "Which captain mapped New Zealand and eastern Australia in the 1700s?", type: "mc", options: ["James Cook", "Marco Polo", "Abel Tasman", "Magellan"], answer: 0, explain: "Cook charted the region on three voyages.", hint: "He shares his name with a kitchen job." },
      { q: "What made Cook's voyages special compared to most?", type: "mc", options: ["he carried scientists and artists", "he sailed alone", "he used engines", "he never made maps"], answer: 0, explain: "His ships brought home new science, art, and accurate charts." },
      { q: "European contact brought diseases that devastated Indigenous peoples.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Measles and smallpox were deadly to people with no resistance." },
      { q: "Britain began colonizing Australia in…", type: "mc", options: ["1492", "1788", "1900", "1945"], answer: 1, explain: "The first British colony — partly a convict settlement — began in 1788." },
      { q: "Saying Europeans “discovered” these islands is misleading because…", type: "mc", options: ["the islands didn't exist", "people had lived there for thousands of years", "Europeans never arrived", "they were underwater"], answer: 1, explain: "The islands were long inhabited and well known to their peoples." },
      { q: "Cook helped prevent scurvy by making his crews…", type: "mc", options: ["eat fresh and pickled foods", "drink only rum", "sleep more", "row faster"], answer: 0, explain: "Foods with vitamin C kept scurvy away, even before the science was understood." },
      { q: "Besides disease, contact also brought islanders…", type: "mc", options: ["metal tools, new crops, and writing", "nothing at all", "their first canoes", "the Pacific Ocean"], answer: 0, explain: "New tools, crops, animals, and the written word arrived too." },
      { q: "Why is Cook's legacy debated today?", type: "mc", options: ["he was both a great navigator and the start of colonization's harms", "he never existed", "he was only a cook", "he discovered Europe"], answer: 0, explain: "Honest history holds his achievements and the harm to Indigenous peoples together." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc3", continent: "oceania", n: 3, minutes: 10, emoji: "🇦🇺",
    title: "Australia & New Zealand Grow Up",
    hook: "Two far-flung British colonies grew into wealthy, modern democracies — while slowly learning to face the cost their success had imposed on the peoples who were there first.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "<b>Australia</b> and <b>New Zealand</b> both began as distant British colonies on the far side of the world, founded in the late 1700s and early 1800s. Over the next century they grew from rough frontier settlements into prosperous, self-governing nations with their own parliaments, economies, and proud identities — yet they kept close ties to Britain and to each other. Their story is one of building bold new societies, and then, much more slowly, learning to reckon honestly with what those societies had cost." },
      { t: "p", html: "A surprising thing helped make them rich: <b>distance and good land</b>. Both countries had huge open spaces and mild climates, so they became giants of farming and herding. New Zealand alone has long had far more <b>sheep</b> than people. There was one big problem, though — their best customers were on the other side of the planet, and meat and butter rotted on the long sea voyage to Britain. The answer arrived in <b>1882</b>, when the first ship fitted with <b>refrigeration</b> carried frozen New Zealand lamb all the way to London still fresh. Because food could now be frozen and shipped across the world, distant farms suddenly had a global market, and both nations boomed." },
      { t: "p", html: "They also became surprising pioneers of <b>democracy</b>. In <b>1893</b>, New Zealand became the first self-governing country in the world where <b>women won the right to vote</b>, and Australia followed soon after — decades ahead of Britain or the United States. Gold rushes in the 1850s drew waves of hopeful migrants, towns swelled into cities, and in <b>1901</b> Australia's separate colonies joined together into one federated nation. Step by step, two colonies were turning into modern countries." },
      { t: "scene", art: "star", file: "Treaty House at Waitangi Treaty Grounds.jpg", credit: "Photo: Wikimedia Commons, CC BY-SA", caption: "The historic Treaty House at Waitangi, New Zealand." },
      { t: "p", html: "National pride was forged partly in war. In <b>1915</b>, during World War I, Australian and New Zealand soldiers — the <b>ANZACs</b> — fought a costly, doomed campaign at <b>Gallipoli</b> in Turkey. The battle was a military failure, but the courage and mateship the soldiers showed became a powerful part of how both nations saw themselves, and <b>ANZAC Day</b> is still solemnly remembered every year. It was one of the moments these young countries stopped feeling like colonies and started feeling like nations." },
      { t: "order", title: "Becoming nations", sub: "Earliest to latest.",
        items: [
          { yr: "1840", label: "Treaty of Waitangi signed in New Zealand" },
          { yr: "1850s", label: "Gold rushes draw migrants and build cities" },
          { yr: "1882", label: "First frozen-meat ship reaches Britain" },
          { yr: "1893", label: "New Zealand: women win the vote (a world first)" },
          { yr: "1901", label: "Australia's colonies federate into one nation" },
        ] },
      { t: "p", html: "But there is a hard truth at the center of this success. The prosperity was built on land taken from <b>Indigenous peoples</b> — Aboriginal Australians and the Maori — and for a long time their cultures were pushed aside, their children sometimes taken from their families, and newcomers from outside Europe were kept out by unfair laws. None of the wealth or the democracy erased that injustice. Facing it honestly is part of what it has meant for these countries to truly grow up." },
      { t: "fact", html: "New Zealand still has roughly <b>five sheep for every person</b> — one of the highest ratios on Earth. Wool and lamb helped build the whole country's wealth." },
      { t: "fact", html: "Australia and New Zealand share a friendly rivalry over who invented the fluffy dessert called <b>pavlova</b> — and over the perfect flat white coffee. Sometimes growing up as neighbors means arguing happily over dessert forever." },
      { t: "p", html: "The <b>gold rushes</b> of the 1850s changed everything. News of gold drew a flood of hopeful migrants from Britain, Europe, China, and beyond, and sleepy colonies swelled with people, money, and bustling new cities almost overnight. But that prosperity came wrapped in prejudice: from 1901, Australia's harsh <b>“White Australia” policy</b> deliberately shut out non-European migrants for decades." },
      { t: "p", html: "Only in the 1960s and 70s did that policy finally crumble, and both nations chose a new path — opening their doors to people from Asia and the Pacific and remaking themselves as proudly <b>multicultural</b> societies. The two countries also forged a deep bond with each other, sealed in the shared sacrifice of the ANZACs, that survives today as one of the world's friendliest international friendships — the “trans-Tasman” family." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Notice the pattern: a country can be genuinely admirable — democratic, prosperous, generous — and still owe a real debt to the people it displaced. Growing up, for a nation just like for a person, often means finding the courage to admit a wrong and try to make it right." },
      { t: "modern", html: "Today both nations work openly to recognize past wrongs and to celebrate Indigenous cultures rather than hide them — an unfinished journey often called <b>reconciliation</b>. Maori traditions in New Zealand and Aboriginal art and heritage in Australia are increasingly honored as national treasures. It still matters because these countries offer the rest of the world a real-life model for how a nation can be honest about a painful past without losing pride in what it has become." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Australia and New Zealand began as colonies of…", type: "mc", options: ["Britain", "Spain", "France", "Japan"], answer: 0, explain: "Both were British colonies before becoming independent nations.", hint: "The same country that colonized India." },
      { q: "What invention let their farms sell food to far-off Britain?", type: "mc", options: ["refrigerated (frozen) shipping", "the telephone", "the airplane", "the printing press"], answer: 0, explain: "From 1882, frozen meat could survive the long sea voyage to London." },
      { q: "New Zealand was the first self-governing country to give women the vote.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Women gained the vote there in 1893 — a genuine world first." },
      { q: "Australia's separate colonies joined into one nation in…", type: "mc", options: ["1788", "1901", "1945", "2000"], answer: 1, explain: "Federation united the colonies into the nation of Australia in 1901." },
      { q: "The ANZACs are remembered for their World War I campaign at…", type: "mc", options: ["Gallipoli", "Waterloo", "Normandy", "Midway"], answer: 0, explain: "Gallipoli (1915) became central to both nations' identities." },
      { q: "Both countries grew wealthy mainly from…", type: "mc", options: ["farming, herding, mining, and gold", "oil only", "the Silk Road", "pyramids"], answer: 0, explain: "Sheep, gold, minerals, and farming built their early wealth." },
      { q: "A hard truth behind their success is that…", type: "mc", options: ["it was built on land taken from Indigenous peoples", "they had no people at all", "they were never colonies", "they invented the Pacific"], answer: 0, explain: "Prosperity came at a real cost to Aboriginal and Maori peoples." },
      { q: "The slow work of recognizing past wrongs is often called…", type: "mc", options: ["reconciliation", "federation", "navigation", "industrialization"], answer: 0, explain: "Reconciliation means honestly facing the past and trying to repair it." },
      { q: "Roughly how many sheep does New Zealand have per person?", type: "mc", options: ["about five", "none", "a hundred", "exactly one"], answer: 0, explain: "Around five sheep per person — among the highest ratios anywhere." },
      { q: "The main lesson of this story is that a nation can be…", type: "mc", options: ["both admirable and still owe a debt to those it displaced", "perfect with no flaws", "only good or only bad", "never prosperous"], answer: 0, explain: "Growing up means holding pride and honesty together." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc4", continent: "oceania", n: 4, minutes: 10, emoji: "🌊",
    title: "The Pacific in World War II & Independence",
    hook: "For most of history the Pacific was one of the most peaceful places on Earth. World War II turned it into a vast battlefield — and afterward, a wave of new island nations was born.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "For thousands of years the remote islands of the Pacific had been some of the calmest, most isolated places on the planet. That changed with shocking speed when <b>World War II</b> exploded across the ocean. In December <b>1941</b>, Japan attacked the American naval base at <b>Pearl Harbor</b> in Hawaii, pulling the United States into the war and turning the “peaceful sea” into the largest battlefield in human history." },
      { t: "p", html: "The fighting stretched across thousands of miles of water, and both sides used a clever strategy the Allies called <b>“island-hopping.”</b> Instead of trying to capture every single island — which would have taken forever and cost countless lives — the Allies seized only the most important ones, the islands with <b>airfields and harbors</b>, and simply bypassed the rest, cutting them off from supplies until they withered. Because whoever controlled these tiny specks of land controlled the air and the supply routes across the whole ocean, islands most people had never heard of suddenly decided the fate of millions." },
      { t: "p", html: "Some of the war's most famous turning points happened here. At the <b>Battle of Midway</b> in 1942, the United States won a stunning naval victory that changed the course of the Pacific war. At <b>Guadalcanal</b>, soldiers fought for months in brutal jungle heat. For Pacific Islanders, the war arrived uninvited on their shores; many served as scouts, carriers, and coastwatchers, and some islands were scarred by fighting that had nothing to do with them. The Pacific war finally ended in <b>1945</b>." },
      { t: "scene", art: "globe", file: "Raising the Flag on Iwo Jima by Joe Rosenthal.jpg", credit: "Public domain", caption: "US Marines raise the flag at Iwo Jima, 1945 — a fierce Pacific battle." },
      { t: "p", html: "When peace returned, the map of the Pacific began to change in a different way. For decades these islands had been ruled by faraway empires — British, French, American, Australian, and others. But in the decades after the war, one by one, island peoples won their <b>independence</b>. Western Samoa led the way in <b>1962</b>, followed by Fiji, Tonga, Papua New Guinea, and many more. Because the age of empires was ending all over the world, the Pacific filled with proud new nations — small in land, but each carrying cultures and languages thousands of years old." },
      { t: "p", html: "These new countries faced a real puzzle: how does a tiny nation make its voice heard in a world of giants? Their answer was to <b>work together</b>. They formed groups like the Pacific Islands Forum, where leaders meet to speak with one combined voice on the issues that matter most to them. A single island might be easy to ignore; a whole ocean of islands, speaking as one, is much harder to overlook." },
      { t: "fact", html: "Some Pacific islands are so spread out that a nation's land might be tiny while its <b>ocean territory</b> is enormous. The island country of Kiribati is mostly water — its scattered islands are sprinkled across an area of sea larger than India." },
      { t: "fact", html: "After the war, several Pacific atolls were used by larger countries to test powerful new weapons. Places like <b>Bikini Atoll</b> were so affected that some communities had to leave their home islands — a reminder that even the most remote places can be caught up in the decisions of distant powers." },
      { t: "p", html: "The war struck close to home, too. In 1942 Japanese planes <b>bombed the Australian city of Darwin</b>, and the <b>Battle of the Coral Sea</b> — fought entirely by aircraft from ships that never even saw each other — helped shield Australia from invasion. For the first time, a world war had reached the region's own shores, and it changed how these nations saw their place in the world." },
      { t: "p", html: "After 1945, the Pacific entered an uneasy new age. Larger powers tested <b>nuclear weapons</b> on remote atolls, forcing some communities from their homes, even as the old empires withdrew and proud new nations rose. Today those nations punch above their weight through cooperation: the <b>Pacific Islands Forum</b> lets them negotiate as a bloc on fishing, security, and climate — proving once more that unity is a small country's greatest strength." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Watch the strategy in island-hopping: you don't need to win everywhere to win overall — you take the few points that truly matter and let the rest fall. That idea of focusing your effort on the decisive spots, instead of spreading it thin, shows up far beyond war." },
      { t: "modern", html: "From the battles of WWII to the birth of a dozen new nations, the Pacific shows how even the world's most remote places are tied to global events — and how small countries can punch above their weight by uniting. It still matters today, because those same island nations now lead the world on a new front line: protecting the planet's climate, the subject of a later lesson." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What event pulled the United States into the Pacific war in 1941?", type: "mc", options: ["the attack on Pearl Harbor", "the fall of Rome", "the sinking of the Titanic", "the Treaty of Waitangi"], answer: 0, explain: "Japan's attack on Pearl Harbor brought the US into WWII.", hint: "It happened at a US naval base in Hawaii." },
      { q: "The strategy of capturing only the key islands was called…", type: "mc", options: ["island-hopping", "trench warfare", "wayfinding", "the Silk Road"], answer: 0, explain: "Island-hopping seized the islands with airfields and harbors and bypassed the rest." },
      { q: "Which 1942 battle was a major turning point in the Pacific?", type: "mc", options: ["Midway", "Gallipoli", "Waterloo", "Hastings"], answer: 0, explain: "The US victory at Midway changed the course of the Pacific war." },
      { q: "The Pacific war ended in…", type: "mc", options: ["1918", "1945", "1962", "2001"], answer: 1, explain: "World War II ended in 1945." },
      { q: "After the war, many Pacific islands gained their…", type: "mc", options: ["independence from faraway empires", "first human settlers", "first oceans", "membership in Europe"], answer: 0, explain: "A wave of new island nations was born in the decades after 1945." },
      { q: "Which nation led the way to independence in 1962?", type: "mc", options: ["Western Samoa", "France", "Japan", "Canada"], answer: 0, explain: "Western Samoa was among the first Pacific nations to gain independence." },
      { q: "How do tiny Pacific nations make their voices heard?", type: "mc", options: ["by working together in groups like the Pacific Islands Forum", "by staying silent", "by fighting wars", "by leaving the Pacific"], answer: 0, explain: "Speaking with one combined voice is harder to ignore." },
      { q: "Island-hopping worked because…", type: "mc", options: ["whoever held key islands controlled the air and supply routes", "every island was equally important", "the islands were empty", "ships couldn't sail"], answer: 0, explain: "Controlling the airfields and harbors controlled the whole ocean." },
      { q: "A Pacific nation can have tiny land but a huge ocean territory.", type: "tf", options: ["True", "False"], answer: 0, explain: "Kiribati, for example, spreads across a sea area larger than India." },
      { q: "One lasting lesson of the Pacific war is that…", type: "mc", options: ["small, focused efforts on decisive points can win", "remote places never matter", "big armies always win everywhere", "oceans cannot be crossed"], answer: 0, explain: "Focusing effort on the decisive spots — not spreading thin — was the key." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc5", continent: "oceania", n: 5, minutes: 10, emoji: "🏝️",
    title: "A World of Islands: The Geography of Oceania",
    hook: "One giant dry continent, two restless islands sitting on a ring of volcanoes, and thousands of tiny specks scattered across the planet's largest ocean — welcome to the strangest geography on Earth.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "<b>Oceania</b> is unlike any other region on the map. It isn't one solid landmass at all, but a scattering of land across the immense <b>Pacific Ocean</b> — the largest single feature on the whole planet, covering roughly a third of Earth's surface. Geographers usually divide Oceania into the continent of <b>Australia</b>, the islands of <b>New Zealand</b>, and the three great island groups of <b>Melanesia, Micronesia, and Polynesia</b>. Together they add up to the world's smallest continent by land but, by ocean, the largest realm of all." },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Australia</b> is the odd giant at the center. It is the <b>flattest, driest inhabited continent on Earth</b> — most of its middle is a vast, sun-baked semi-desert that Australians simply call the <b>Outback</b>. Because so little rain reaches the interior, the great majority of Australians live squeezed along the green coastal edges, especially the wetter east and southeast. A long, worn mountain chain called the <b>Great Dividing Range</b> runs down that eastern coast, and the country's most important river, the <b>Murray</b>, drains the farmland of the southeast." },
      { t: "p", html: "The islands come in two very different flavors, and the difference shapes everything about life on them. <b>“High islands”</b> are the tops of <b>volcanoes</b> poking out of the sea — tall, green, and rugged, with rich soil, fresh streams, and room to farm. <b>“Low islands,”</b> by contrast, are <b>coral atolls</b>: thin rings of sand and reef, often rising only a meter or two above the waves, with little soil and no rivers at all. Because high islands have land and water to spare while low islands have almost none, the two kinds of island grew very different ways of life — and, as we'll see later, very different futures in a warming world." },
      { t: "compare", title: "Two kinds of Pacific island",
        a: { title: "High islands (volcanic)", items: ["Tall, green, and mountainous", "Rich soil and fresh streams", "Room to farm and grow", "Example: Hawaii, Fiji's big islands"] },
        b: { title: "Low islands (coral atolls)", items: ["Flat rings of sand and reef", "Only a meter or two above the sea", "Little soil, no rivers", "Example: Tuvalu, the Marshall Islands"] } },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>New Zealand</b> is a world of its own. It sits right on the <b>Ring of Fire</b>, the great belt of earthquakes and volcanoes that circles the Pacific, where two of Earth's tectonic plates grind together. That collision pushed up the dramatic <b>Southern Alps</b>, carved deep coastal <b>fiords</b>, and left the country dotted with volcanoes, hot springs, and geysers. It is a land still actively being built and reshaped by the forces deep underground." },
      { t: "scene", art: "island", file: "Bora Bora ISS006.jpg", credit: "Public domain (NASA)", caption: "A Pacific island ringed by coral reef and a turquoise lagoon." },
      { t: "p", html: "Off Australia's northeast coast lies one of the natural wonders of the world: the <b>Great Barrier Reef</b>, the largest living structure on the planet, stretching more than 2,300 kilometers. It wasn't built by engineers but by countless tiny coral animals over millions of years — so big that it can be seen from space. Reefs like it are the rainforests of the sea, sheltering a dazzling share of all ocean life, and protecting the islands behind them from storms." },
      { t: "fact", html: "Australia is slowly <b>drifting north</b> by about 7 centimeters every year — roughly the speed your fingernails grow. Over a human lifetime the whole continent shifts by several meters, enough that mapmakers occasionally have to update the country's official coordinates." },
      { t: "fact", html: "Many Pacific nations are mostly <b>ocean</b>. A country might have only a few square kilometers of land but control a stretch of sea larger than a big European country — which means their “territory” is mostly water, fish, and waves." },
      { t: "p", html: "How does a flat coral ring end up alone in the deep ocean, with no land beneath it? The answer is a beautiful piece of science first worked out by <b>Charles Darwin</b>. A reef starts growing in the shallow water around a volcanic island. Over millions of years the volcano slowly <b>sinks</b> and erodes away — but the coral keeps building upward toward the light, until the island has vanished and only a ring of reef, an <b>atoll</b>, is left encircling an empty lagoon." },
      { t: "p", html: "Australia alone spans a whole sweep of climates. Its tropical <b>north</b> is hot and wet, with monsoon rains and rainforest; its <b>southeast and southwest</b> are mild and green, which is exactly why most people and farms cluster there; and its vast <b>center</b> is dry red desert. New Zealand, far to the south and cooler, adds snowy peaks and misty rainforests — so within Oceania you can find nearly every climate on Earth." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Here's a habit of a good geographer: ask how the <i>land itself</i> shapes the people. Australia's dryness pushed its cities to the coast; an atoll's flatness puts it at the mercy of the sea. Again and again, where people can live and how they live is written first in the rock, the rain, and the reef." },
      { t: "modern", html: "Understanding Oceania's geography isn't just trivia — it's the key to its biggest modern story. Because so many of its nations are low coral islands with no high ground to retreat to, the shape of the land is exactly what makes climate change such an urgent threat here. Geography, it turns out, is destiny: the same flatness that makes an atoll a paradise also makes it fragile." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Oceania is centered on which ocean?", type: "mc", options: ["the Pacific", "the Atlantic", "the Arctic", "the Indian"], answer: 0, explain: "The Pacific is the largest feature on Earth, covering about a third of the planet.", hint: "It's the world's largest ocean." },
      { q: "Australia is the world's…", type: "mc", options: ["wettest continent", "flattest and driest inhabited continent", "coldest continent", "most mountainous continent"], answer: 1, explain: "Its dry interior, the Outback, makes it the driest inhabited continent." },
      { q: "Most Australians live…", type: "mc", options: ["in the desert interior", "along the green coastal edges", "on boats", "in the mountains"], answer: 1, explain: "The dry Outback pushes people to the wetter coasts, especially the southeast." },
      { q: "A flat ring of sand and reef rising barely above the sea is called…", type: "mc", options: ["a coral atoll (low island)", "a volcano", "a fiord", "a glacier"], answer: 0, explain: "Low islands are coral atolls — little soil, no rivers, just a meter or two high." },
      { q: "“High islands” are usually the tops of…", type: "mc", options: ["volcanoes", "coral reefs", "sandbars", "icebergs"], answer: 0, explain: "Volcanic high islands are tall and green, with rich soil and fresh water." },
      { q: "New Zealand sits on the Pacific's belt of volcanoes and earthquakes called the…", type: "mc", options: ["Ring of Fire", "Great Barrier", "Outback", "Silk Road"], answer: 0, explain: "Two tectonic plates collide there, building the Southern Alps and volcanoes." },
      { q: "The Great Barrier Reef was built by…", type: "mc", options: ["tiny coral animals over millions of years", "engineers", "volcanoes overnight", "rivers"], answer: 0, explain: "It's the largest living structure on Earth — visible even from space." },
      { q: "Australia drifts north by about how much each year?", type: "mc", options: ["7 centimeters", "7 meters", "7 kilometers", "not at all"], answer: 0, explain: "About 7 cm a year — roughly the speed your fingernails grow." },
      { q: "Reefs are sometimes called the “rainforests of the sea” because they…", type: "mc", options: ["shelter a huge share of ocean life", "are made of trees", "are always cold", "have no animals"], answer: 0, explain: "Reefs are bursting with life and also protect islands from storms." },
      { q: "Why does geography make climate change especially dangerous for many Pacific nations?", type: "mc", options: ["they are low, flat islands with no high ground", "they are tall mountains", "they have no people", "they are far from any ocean"], answer: 0, explain: "Flat coral atolls have nowhere to retreat as the sea rises." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc6", continent: "oceania", n: 6, minutes: 10, emoji: "🦘",
    title: "Australia's Amazing Wildlife",
    hook: "Mammals that carry babies in pouches, a mammal that lays eggs and hunts with electricity, and animals found nowhere else on Earth — Australia is a living laboratory of evolution.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "If you wanted to design the strangest, most wonderful collection of animals on the planet, you might just end up with <b>Australia</b>. Around four out of every five mammals, reptiles, and frogs that live there are found <b>nowhere else in the world</b>. The reason isn't magic — it's <b>isolation</b>. For tens of millions of years, Australia drifted alone as an island continent, cut off from the rest of the world, and its animals quietly evolved down their own separate path while the rest of the planet went a different way." },
      { t: "p", html: "The most famous Australians are the <b>marsupials</b> — mammals that give birth to tiny, jellybean-sized babies which then finish growing inside a cozy <b>pouch</b>. The bounding <b>kangaroo</b>, the sleepy tree-hugging <b>koala</b>, the burrowing <b>wombat</b>, and the fierce little <b>Tasmanian devil</b> are all marsupials. In most of the world, pouched mammals lost out long ago to the placental mammals (the group that includes us). But because Australia was sealed off, its marsupials faced no such rivals and flourished into an astonishing variety found almost nowhere else." },
      { t: "scene", art: "kangaroo", file: "Kangaroo and joey05.jpg", credit: "Photo: Wikimedia Commons, CC BY-SA", caption: "The kangaroo — a marsupial that carries its young in a pouch — is found only in Australia and nearby." },
      { t: "photo", art: "kangaroo", file: "Koala clinging onto a Eucalyptus tree.jpg", credit: "Photo: Wikimedia Commons, CC BY-SA", caption: "A koala dozes in a eucalyptus tree — it is not a bear, but a marsupial." },
      { t: "photo", art: "kangaroo", file: "Duck-billed platypus (Ornithorhynchus anatinus) Scottsdale.jpg", credit: "Photo: Klaus, CC BY-SA 2.0", caption: "The platypus — a furry, egg-laying mammal with a duck-like bill." },
      { t: "p", html: "Stranger still are the <b>monotremes</b> — mammals that <b>lay eggs</b>. There are only a handful of egg-laying mammals left on Earth, and Australia has them all: the spiny <b>echidna</b> and the almost unbelievable <b>platypus</b>. The platypus has a duck-like bill, a beaver-like tail, webbed feet, and it hunts underwater with its eyes shut — sensing the faint electric signals given off by its prey, like a living metal detector. The males even have a venomous spur. When the first platypus specimen reached British scientists, they were sure it was a hoax, with a duck's bill sewn onto an animal's body." },
      { t: "p", html: "The wonders don't stop at mammals. Australia has flightless birds like the towering <b>emu</b> and the dangerous <b>cassowary</b>, the laughing <b>kookaburra</b>, and forests of <b>eucalyptus</b> (gum) trees so full of oil that they actually depend on <b>fire</b> — many of their seeds only sprout after a blaze sweeps through. Life here has adapted not just to isolation but to a harsh land of drought, heat, and flame." },
      { t: "scenario", title: "You're an early settler with a problem", prompt: "Rabbits you brought from Europe are breeding out of control and eating the crops. A friend suggests releasing a foreign toad to eat the beetles too. What's the wise move?",
        opts: [
          { label: "Release the toad — more help is better", tag: "Watch out", outcome: "This actually happened: cane toads were released in 1935 and became a disaster, poisoning native animals and spreading everywhere. Adding a new foreign species often makes things worse." },
          { label: "Stop and study the local food web first", tag: "Wise", outcome: "Exactly. On an isolated continent, native animals have no defenses against newcomers. Careful study before acting is the whole lesson Australia learned the hard way." },
          { label: "Do nothing and hope it sorts itself out", tag: "Risky", outcome: "Invasive species rarely fix themselves — the rabbits kept multiplying. But at least doing nothing avoids creating a brand-new problem on top of the old one." },
        ] },
      { t: "p", html: "That same isolation that created such wonders also made Australia's wildlife <b>fragile</b>. Because native animals evolved with no defense against outsiders, species brought in by humans — <b>rabbits, foxes, cats, and cane toads</b> — have caused enormous damage, and Australia has sadly lost more mammal species to extinction in modern times than any other country. Protecting what remains is now a national mission." },
      { t: "fact", html: "<b>Koalas</b> sleep up to <b>20 hours a day</b>. Their diet of eucalyptus leaves is so low in energy and so mildly toxic that they have to rest almost constantly just to digest it." },
      { t: "fact", html: "The <b>platypus</b> doesn't have a stomach — its gullet connects almost straight to its intestines. It also glows a faint blue-green under ultraviolet light, for reasons scientists still don't fully understand." },
      { t: "p", html: "Why was Australia so isolated in the first place? Long ago it was part of a giant southern supercontinent called <b>Gondwana</b>, joined to South America, Africa, India, and Antarctica. As Gondwana slowly broke apart, Australia drifted off on its own tens of millions of years ago and became a kind of giant ark, sailing alone through deep time while its passengers evolved into forms found nowhere else." },
      { t: "p", html: "That long solitude produced strange <b>plants</b> as well as strange animals — and many learned to live with fire. Eucalyptus forests almost invite flame, their oily leaves burning fast and many of their seeds bursting open only in the heat. This makes Australia one of the most fire-prone places on Earth, as the terrible <b>bushfires of 2019–2020</b> showed, when vast areas burned and scientists estimate billions of animals were affected — a stark warning of how a warming climate sharpens an ancient danger." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Here's the big idea: <b>isolation breeds uniqueness</b>. Cut a population off from the rest of the world — on an island, a continent, a mountaintop — and over enough time it evolves into something found nowhere else. The flip side is that unique island life is also the easiest to wipe out, because it never learned to defend against strangers." },
      { t: "modern", html: "Australia's wildlife is a living lesson in how evolution works and how easily it can be undone. As habitats shrink and bushfires grow fiercer, scientists and ordinary Australians are racing to protect creatures that exist nowhere else on Earth. It still matters because once a unique species is gone, no other place can ever bring it back — it's lost from the whole planet, forever." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Why does Australia have so many animals found nowhere else?", type: "mc", options: ["it was isolated for millions of years", "it is very small", "it has no water", "people invented them"], answer: 0, explain: "Long isolation let its animals evolve down their own separate path.", hint: "Think about being cut off from the rest of the world." },
      { q: "Mammals that carry their young in a pouch are called…", type: "mc", options: ["marsupials", "monotremes", "reptiles", "amphibians"], answer: 0, explain: "Kangaroos, koalas, and wombats are all marsupials." },
      { q: "Mammals that lay eggs are called…", type: "mc", options: ["monotremes", "marsupials", "birds", "fish"], answer: 0, explain: "The platypus and echidna are monotremes — egg-laying mammals." },
      { q: "How does a platypus hunt underwater?", type: "mc", options: ["by sensing the electric signals of its prey", "by smell only", "with sharp eyes", "by sound alone"], answer: 0, explain: "It hunts with eyes shut, detecting faint electric signals like a metal detector." },
      { q: "Many eucalyptus trees actually depend on…", type: "mc", options: ["fire to sprout their seeds", "snow", "ocean salt", "darkness"], answer: 0, explain: "Their seeds often sprout only after a fire sweeps through." },
      { q: "Releasing cane toads in 1935 turned out to be…", type: "mc", options: ["a disaster that harmed native animals", "a huge success", "completely harmless", "illegal everywhere"], answer: 0, explain: "The toads poisoned native predators and spread out of control." },
      { q: "Australia's native wildlife is fragile mainly because…", type: "mc", options: ["it has no defenses against introduced species", "it is too large", "it lives only in cities", "it cannot reproduce"], answer: 0, explain: "Isolated species never evolved defenses against newcomers like cats and foxes." },
      { q: "Koalas sleep so much because…", type: "mc", options: ["their eucalyptus diet gives little energy", "they are nocturnal hunters", "they hibernate all year", "they are sick"], answer: 0, explain: "Low-energy, mildly toxic leaves force them to rest up to 20 hours a day." },
      { q: "Early scientists thought the first platypus was…", type: "mc", options: ["a fake stitched together from other animals", "a kind of fish", "a dinosaur", "a bird"], answer: 0, explain: "Its duck bill and odd body made them suspect a hoax." },
      { q: "The big idea “isolation breeds uniqueness” means…", type: "mc", options: ["cut-off populations evolve into one-of-a-kind forms", "islands have no animals", "all animals are the same everywhere", "isolation stops evolution"], answer: 0, explain: "But that same uniqueness is also the easiest to lose forever." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc7", continent: "oceania", n: 7, minutes: 10, emoji: "🪃",
    title: "The First Australians: Aboriginal Culture & the Dreaming",
    hook: "For more than 60,000 years — longer than any other culture on Earth — Aboriginal Australians have lived on, cared for, and remembered their land. This is the world's oldest living story.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "<b>Aboriginal Australians</b> have one of the <b>oldest continuous living cultures on Earth</b>, stretching back more than <b>60,000 years</b> — older than the pyramids, older than farming, older than written language anywhere. For all that almost unimaginable time, hundreds of distinct peoples lived across the continent, speaking more than <b>250 different languages</b>, each group bound to its own particular stretch of land, which they call <b>Country</b>. To say this culture is “ancient” is true, but it can mislead: it is not a thing of the past. It is alive right now." },
      { t: "p", html: "At the heart of Aboriginal life is a profound idea that Europeans translated, imperfectly, as <b>the Dreaming</b> (or Dreamtime). The Dreaming is not just a set of myths. It is the deep account of how ancestral beings created the land, the animals, the people, and the law — and it is also a guide to how to live well and care for Country today. Because the Dreaming ties the land, the rules of life, and the story of creation into one connected whole, for Aboriginal peoples the landscape itself is a kind of sacred history book, where every hill, river, and rock holds meaning." },
      { t: "scene", art: "boomerang", file: "Uluru, helicopter view, cropped.jpg", credit: "Photo: Corey Leopold, CC BY 2.0", caption: "Uluru, a sacred place at the heart of Aboriginal Australia." },
      { t: "p", html: "One of the most astonishing achievements is the <b>songline</b>. Because Aboriginal peoples did not use writing, they stored vast knowledge inside <b>songs, stories, dance, and art</b>. A songline is a sung map: a journey across the land, described in a song, where the verses name waterholes, landmarks, and safe routes in their correct order. By singing the song, a traveler could find their way across hundreds of kilometers of country they had never seen. In this way, an entire continent's geography was carried in memory and melody — one of the greatest feats of human memory ever known." },
      { t: "p", html: "This was not a people who simply wandered a wild land; they actively <b>managed</b> it. Aboriginal groups used careful, deliberate <b>“fire-stick farming,”</b> setting small, controlled burns to clear underbrush, encourage fresh growth, and attract animals to hunt. Because these gentle fires prevented the build-up of fuel, they also reduced the giant, destructive bushfires that can rage when the land is left unmanaged — a piece of ancient wisdom that modern Australia is now, at last, beginning to learn from again." },
      { t: "p", html: "Aboriginal memory reaches almost incomprehensibly far back. Some stories accurately describe coastlines and islands that vanished beneath <b>rising seas at the end of the last Ice Age, more than 7,000 years ago</b> — meaning real events were remembered, by voice alone, across roughly three hundred generations. (The peoples of the <b>Torres Strait</b> islands, between Australia and New Guinea, are a separate Indigenous group with their own distinct cultures and seafaring traditions.)" },
      { t: "fact", html: "Some Aboriginal <b>rock art</b> is among the oldest art in the world. Certain painted shelters have been used and repainted for tens of thousands of years — galleries far, far older than anything in Europe's famous museums." },
      { t: "fact", html: "The huge red rock at the heart of Australia is best known by its Aboriginal name, <b>Uluru</b>, used by the local Anangu people for countless generations. It is a deeply sacred place, and its true meaning lives in the Dreaming stories tied to it." },
      { t: "p", html: "When British colonization began in 1788, it brought terrible hardship: Aboriginal peoples lost much of their land, were struck by new diseases, and for much of the 1900s, children were even taken from their families in a policy whose pain is still felt today. Yet Aboriginal cultures <b>survived</b>. In recent decades a powerful revival has taken hold — in 1992 a famous court case brought by <b>Eddie Mabo</b> finally recognized that Indigenous peoples had rights to their traditional land, overturning the cruel old lie that the continent had belonged to no one." },
      { t: "p", html: "Aboriginal peoples were also brilliant <b>toolmakers and scientists of the bush</b>. They ground some of the world's earliest known edge-polished <b>axes</b>, shaped spear-throwers called <b>woomeras</b> that hurled spears with astonishing force, and knew which of thousands of plants could heal a wound, settle a stomach, or be safely eaten in each season. This was hard-won knowledge, tested and refined over hundreds of generations." },
      { t: "p", html: "Colonization's wounds ran deep. For much of the 1900s, Aboriginal children were forcibly taken from their families — a tragedy now called the <b>Stolen Generations</b> — and Aboriginal people were not even fully counted as citizens until a landmark national vote in 1967. Healing has been slow but real: in 2008 the country formally <b>apologized</b>, sacred Uluru was handed back to its traditional owners, and today the yearly <b>NAIDOC</b> celebrations and a thriving Aboriginal art movement carry the culture proudly forward." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Hold onto this: there is more than one way to <i>know</i> a place. A geologist might map a region with instruments; an Aboriginal elder might hold its rivers, seasons, and dangers inside a song learned over a lifetime. Both are real, rigorous knowledge. Respecting that is the heart of true world awareness." },
      { t: "modern", html: "Today, Aboriginal art is celebrated around the globe, Indigenous languages are being revived, and Aboriginal land management is studied by scientists fighting bushfires and protecting nature. It still matters because the First Australians prove something hopeful and humbling at once: that human beings can live with a place — really know it, care for it, and remember it — for tens of thousands of years, if they choose to listen to it closely enough." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Aboriginal Australians have one of the world's…", type: "mc", options: ["newest cultures", "oldest continuous living cultures", "only written cultures", "smallest territories"], answer: 1, explain: "Their culture stretches back more than 60,000 years.", hint: "Think older than the pyramids." },
      { q: "Aboriginal peoples call the land they are bound to…", type: "mc", options: ["Country", "the Outback", "the colony", "the reef"], answer: 0, explain: "“Country” means a people's own sacred stretch of land." },
      { q: "The Dreaming is best described as…", type: "mc", options: ["the deep story of creation, law, and how to care for the land", "a kind of sleep", "a European invention", "a type of canoe"], answer: 0, explain: "It ties creation, law, and land into one connected whole." },
      { q: "A “songline” is…", type: "mc", options: ["a sung map that guides travelers across the land", "a musical instrument", "a type of dance only", "a written book"], answer: 0, explain: "Verses name landmarks in order, storing a continent's geography in memory." },
      { q: "Aboriginal peoples managed the land using…", type: "mc", options: ["careful controlled burning (fire-stick farming)", "giant dams", "factories", "no methods at all"], answer: 0, explain: "Small, deliberate fires renewed the land and prevented huge bushfires." },
      { q: "How was vast knowledge stored without writing?", type: "mc", options: ["in songs, stories, dance, and art", "in books", "on computers", "it wasn't stored"], answer: 0, explain: "Memory, song, and art carried knowledge across generations." },
      { q: "Some Aboriginal stories accurately remember events from…", type: "mc", options: ["over 7,000 years ago", "last year", "the 1900s only", "the future"], answer: 0, explain: "They describe coastlines lost to rising seas after the Ice Age." },
      { q: "The Torres Strait Islanders are…", type: "mc", options: ["a separate Indigenous people with their own cultures", "the same as all Aboriginal groups", "European settlers", "a Maori tribe"], answer: 0, explain: "They are a distinct Indigenous group with their own seafaring traditions." },
      { q: "The 1992 Mabo court case was important because it…", type: "mc", options: ["recognized Indigenous rights to traditional land", "started World War II", "banned all art", "created Australia"], answer: 0, explain: "It overturned the false idea that the land had belonged to no one." },
      { q: "The lesson “there is more than one way to know a place” means…", type: "mc", options: ["song-and-memory knowledge can be as real as instrument knowledge", "only science counts", "maps are useless", "the land cannot be known"], answer: 0, explain: "Respecting different kinds of real knowledge is the heart of world awareness." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc8", continent: "oceania", n: 8, minutes: 10, emoji: "🌿",
    title: "Maori New Zealand: Aotearoa, the Haka & the Treaty",
    hook: "The last Polynesian voyagers found a cool green land they named Aotearoa. The culture they built there — and a single, disputed treaty — still shape New Zealand today.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Around <b>700 years ago</b>, the great Polynesian voyages reached their final destination: two large, cool, green islands far to the south, unlike any tropical home they had known. The settlers named the new land <b>Aotearoa</b>, often translated as “the land of the long white cloud,” and over the centuries they grew into a distinct people: the <b>Maori</b>. Cut off at the very edge of the Polynesian world, they developed their own language, arts, and traditions, while never forgetting they were children of the ocean voyagers." },
      { t: "p", html: "Maori society was built around family and belonging. People belonged to a <b>whanau</b> (extended family), which was part of a <b>hapu</b> (a larger clan), which belonged to an <b>iwi</b> (a tribe), all traced through <b>whakapapa</b> — a carefully remembered line of ancestors reaching back to the very canoes that first arrived. At the center of community life stood the <b>marae</b>, a sacred meeting ground with a beautifully carved meeting house, where people gather to this day for ceremonies, debates, welcomes, and farewells." },
      { t: "scene", art: "marae", file: "Ardie Savea Haka 2018.jpg", credit: "Photo: Wikimedia Commons, CC BY-SA", caption: "A Māori haka — a powerful ceremonial dance and welcome." },
      { t: "p", html: "Maori culture is rich with powerful art forms. The <b>haka</b> is a thunderous ceremonial dance of stamping feet, slapping chests, and fierce chanted words — performed to welcome honored guests, to mark great occasions, and, famously, by New Zealand's rugby team before a match. There is the spiraling <b>ta moko</b> (traditional tattoo), which records a person's ancestry and status right on their skin, and the intricate carving and weaving that cover the meeting houses. Each art form carries <b>mana</b> — a deep idea of honor, authority, and spiritual power that a person or place can hold and must be respected." },
      { t: "p", html: "Everything changed with the arrival of Europeans, and the turning point was a single document: the <b>Treaty of Waitangi</b>, signed in <b>1840</b> between the British Crown and many Maori chiefs. It was meant to set out how the two peoples would live together — but it became one of history's most famously <b>disputed</b> agreements, for a fascinating and important reason hidden inside the translation." },
      { t: "compare", title: "Why the Treaty is still argued over",
        a: { title: "The English version said…", items: ["Maori gave Britain full <b>sovereignty</b>", "The Crown would rule over everything", "Britain held the ultimate power"] },
        b: { title: "The Maori version said…", items: ["Maori gave Britain <i>kawanatanga</i> — “governance”", "Chiefs kept <i>rangatiratanga</i> — full chiefly authority", "Maori believed they kept control of their lands and treasures"] } },
      { t: "p", html: "Because the two versions promised genuinely different things, Maori and the British walked away believing they had agreed to two different deals — and as settlers poured in and took land, that gap erupted into the <b>New Zealand Wars</b> of the mid-1800s and into grievances that lasted generations. The Treaty was both a founding promise and a broken one, and learning to honor it properly has been a central task of New Zealand ever since." },
      { t: "fact", html: "The most famous haka, <b>“Ka Mate,”</b> was composed by a Maori chief around 1820. When the All Blacks perform it before games, they share a piece of living Maori culture with millions of people around the world." },
      { t: "fact", html: "The Maori language, <b>te reo Maori</b>, nearly died out — but a determined revival, including “language nests” where elders teach toddlers, helped bring it back. It became an <b>official language</b> of New Zealand in 1987, and Maori place names are used proudly across the country." },
      { t: "p", html: "Maori tradition remembers the explorer <b>Kupe</b> as the first to find Aotearoa, sailing home to Polynesia with directions that later canoes followed south. Arriving in a land far colder than the tropics, the settlers adapted ingeniously: they learned to grow the <b>kumara</b> (sweet potato) in the cool climate, hunted the giant flightless <b>moa</b> bird, and built fortified hilltop villages called <b>pa</b> to protect their communities." },
      { t: "p", html: "After the Treaty, broken promises and land grabs erupted into the <b>New Zealand Wars</b> of the mid-1800s, and huge areas of Maori land were confiscated. The grief of those losses lasted for generations. But Maori never stopped pressing for their rights, and from the 1970s a powerful revival took hold: the <b>Waitangi Tribunal</b> was created in 1975 to hear old grievances, and “language nests” began teaching te reo Maori to a brand-new generation of children." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Notice the deep lesson buried in the Treaty: <b>translation matters enormously</b>. A single word — “sovereignty” versus “governance” — set two peoples on a collision course for over a century. When cultures meet, being truly understood is just as important as being heard." },
      { t: "modern", html: "Today a remarkable <b>Maori renaissance</b> is underway: the language is taught in schools, a special tribunal works to address old Treaty injustices, and Maori art, the haka, and traditions are celebrated as the proud heart of New Zealand's identity. It still matters because New Zealand is showing the world, in real time, how two peoples can keep working — imperfectly but honestly — to honor a promise made long ago." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What did the Polynesian settlers name New Zealand?", type: "mc", options: ["Aotearoa", "Australia", "Hawaii", "Atlantis"], answer: 0, explain: "Aotearoa is often translated “land of the long white cloud.”", hint: "It starts with “A” and means a land of cloud." },
      { q: "The Indigenous people of New Zealand are the…", type: "mc", options: ["Maori", "Aboriginal Australians", "Inca", "Inuit"], answer: 0, explain: "The Maori descend from Polynesian voyagers who arrived around 700 years ago." },
      { q: "A marae is…", type: "mc", options: ["a sacred meeting ground with a carved meeting house", "a type of canoe", "a mountain", "a kind of food"], answer: 0, explain: "The marae is the heart of Maori community life." },
      { q: "The haka is a…", type: "mc", options: ["powerful ceremonial dance and chant", "written law", "musical instrument", "board game"], answer: 0, explain: "It welcomes guests and marks great occasions — famously before rugby games." },
      { q: "Whakapapa refers to…", type: "mc", options: ["a remembered line of ancestors", "a weapon", "a dance", "a treaty"], answer: 0, explain: "Whakapapa traces ancestry back to the first canoes." },
      { q: "The Treaty of Waitangi was signed in…", type: "mc", options: ["1840", "1492", "1945", "2000"], answer: 0, explain: "It was signed in 1840 between the British Crown and many Maori chiefs." },
      { q: "Why is the Treaty so famously disputed?", type: "mc", options: ["its English and Maori versions promised different things", "no one ever signed it", "it was written in Latin", "it was never translated"], answer: 0, explain: "“Sovereignty” in English vs “governance” in Maori meant two different deals." },
      { q: "The English version claimed Britain gained sovereignty; the Maori version said chiefs kept…", type: "mc", options: ["their full chiefly authority (rangatiratanga)", "nothing at all", "only the oceans", "the right to leave"], answer: 0, explain: "Maori believed they kept rangatiratanga — authority over their lands and treasures." },
      { q: "Te reo Maori, the Maori language, today is…", type: "mc", options: ["an official language being revived", "completely extinct", "spoken only in Europe", "banned"], answer: 0, explain: "It became an official language in 1987 and is taught in schools." },
      { q: "The big lesson hidden in the Treaty is that…", type: "mc", options: ["translation and being truly understood matter enormously", "treaties are pointless", "language never matters", "wars are unavoidable"], answer: 0, explain: "A single mistranslated word shaped a century of history." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc9", continent: "oceania", n: 9, minutes: 10, emoji: "🌊",
    title: "Vanishing Shores: Oceania & a Changing Climate",
    hook: "The nations that did the least to cause climate change are among the first to feel it. For low-lying Pacific islands, the rising sea is not a distant worry — it is at the door.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "Across the Pacific, thousands of people live on <b>coral atolls</b> — those thin, flat rings of land that rise only a meter or two above the ocean. For these communities, the slow rise of the sea is not a far-off scientific prediction. It is a daily reality already lapping at their doorsteps, threatening homes, farms, and the very ground their ancestors have lived on for thousands of years. To understand why, we have to follow a clear chain of cause and effect." },
      { t: "p", html: "It begins with a warming planet. As people burn coal, oil, and gas, heat-trapping gases build up in the air and Earth slowly warms. That warming raises the sea in two ways: first, warm water <b>expands</b> and takes up more space; and second, great sheets of <b>ice</b> on Greenland and Antarctica melt and add more water to the oceans. The rise is only millimeters a year — tiny anywhere else. But on an island that is barely a meter above the waves, a small rise is the difference between a home and a flood." },
      { t: "scene", art: "island", file: "Aerial view of Tuvalu’s capital, Funafuti, 2011. Tuvalu is a remote country of low lying atolls, making it vulnerable to climate change. Photo- Lily-Anne Homasi - DFAT (12779656093).jpg", credit: "Photo: Lily-Anne Homasi / DFAT, CC BY 2.0", caption: "On a low atoll, even a small rise in the sea can swallow homes and poison the soil." },
      { t: "p", html: "The danger comes in several forms. <b>“King tides,”</b> the highest tides of the year, now push saltwater straight into villages. That salt seeps into the soil and ruins crops, and it poisons the thin layer of <b>fresh groundwater</b> that islanders depend on for drinking. Out at sea, warmer water causes <b>coral bleaching</b> — the reefs that feed the islands and shield them from storms turn ghostly white and can die. And warmer oceans fuel stronger <b>cyclones</b>. Because the islands are low, flat, and surrounded by sea on every side, each of these threats hits harder here than almost anywhere on Earth." },
      { t: "scenario", title: "You advise a Pacific island nation", prompt: "Your low-lying country faces a rising sea. With limited money, what should leaders focus on?",
        opts: [
          { label: "Demand the whole world cut emissions, and do nothing at home", tag: "Incomplete", outcome: "Global action is essential — but it's slow, and the sea is rising now. Waiting alone leaves your people exposed in the meantime." },
          { label: "Build defenses and speak out globally — both at once", tag: "Wise", outcome: "Exactly what Pacific nations actually do: restore reefs and mangroves, build sea walls, AND become the world's loudest moral voice for cutting emissions." },
          { label: "Just move everyone away immediately", tag: "Last resort", outcome: "Leaving means losing a homeland and culture thousands of years old. Most islanders fight to stay first, and treat migration as a final option." },
        ] },
      { t: "p", html: "Faced with this, Pacific peoples have refused to be victims. They have become some of the world's <b>clearest and most powerful voices</b> for protecting the climate, traveling to global summits with a simple, unforgettable message: <i>“1.5 to stay alive”</i> — meaning the world must limit warming to 1.5°C or their countries will drown. There is a deep <b>fairness</b> question here too: the islands produce almost none of the pollution causing the problem, yet they suffer its effects first and worst. That is exactly why their voices carry such moral weight." },
      { t: "fact", html: "The tiny nation of <b>Tuvalu</b> is so threatened that it began building a <b>digital version of itself</b> — recreating its islands, culture, and records online, so its identity can survive even if the land is lost beneath the sea." },
      { t: "fact", html: "Islanders are fighting back with clever <b>adaptation</b>: replanting protective <b>mangrove</b> forests, restoring coral reefs that break the waves, building sea walls, and even raising land higher. Some leaders have also bought land on higher islands as a backup home, just in case." },
      { t: "p", html: "The threat reaches under the water, too. Healthy <b>coral reefs</b> are the supermarkets and the seawalls of island life at once — they shelter the fish that families eat, and they break the force of storm waves before they reach the shore. So when warming seas bleach and kill those reefs, islanders lose their food and their protection together, a double blow that makes every other danger worse." },
      { t: "p", html: "Because some islands may one day become unlivable, the world is now wrestling with hard new questions of <b>fairness</b>. Should wealthy, high-polluting nations help pay for the “loss and damage” their emissions cause far away? Some islanders are already preparing for the worst: the nation of <b>Kiribati</b> once bought land in Fiji as a possible future refuge. These are wrenching questions about justice that the whole world is only beginning to face." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Trace the cause and effect one more time: warming → expanding, melting oceans → higher seas → flooding on flat islands. Now notice the injustice layered on top — the people harmed first did the least to cause it. Real world awareness means seeing both the science <i>and</i> the fairness in a single problem." },
      { t: "modern", html: "The story of the vanishing shores is really the whole world's story, told first on its smallest stages. It still matters because the Pacific islands are a warning and a conscience for everyone: what happens to a tiny atoll today reveals where larger coasts and cities may head tomorrow — and reminds us that the planet's choices are shared, whether we live by the sea or far from it." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Why are coral atolls so threatened by rising seas?", type: "mc", options: ["they rise only a meter or two above the ocean", "they are very tall", "they have no people", "they are made of ice"], answer: 0, explain: "Low, flat islands have no high ground to retreat to.", hint: "Think about how high above the water they sit." },
      { q: "A warming planet raises the sea by warm water expanding and by…", type: "mc", options: ["ice sheets melting", "rivers drying up", "more rain only", "the moon moving"], answer: 0, explain: "Melting Greenland and Antarctic ice adds water to the oceans." },
      { q: "“King tides” are dangerous to islands because they…", type: "mc", options: ["push saltwater into villages and soil", "bring heavy snow", "cool the planet", "create new land"], answer: 0, explain: "Salt ruins crops and poisons the fresh groundwater islanders drink." },
      { q: "When reefs overheat and turn white, it's called…", type: "mc", options: ["coral bleaching", "a king tide", "an atoll", "a cyclone"], answer: 0, explain: "Bleached reefs can die, removing food and storm protection." },
      { q: "The Pacific slogan “1.5 to stay alive” refers to…", type: "mc", options: ["limiting global warming to 1.5°C", "a sports score", "1.5 meters of sea wall", "1.5 islands"], answer: 0, explain: "Islanders warn that more than 1.5°C of warming could drown their nations." },
      { q: "What makes the islands' situation especially unfair?", type: "mc", options: ["they cause little pollution but suffer the effects first", "they pollute the most", "they refuse all help", "they have no culture"], answer: 0, explain: "The least responsible are hit first and hardest — a core fairness issue." },
      { q: "Tuvalu responded to the threat by…", type: "mc", options: ["building a digital version of itself", "ignoring it", "moving to Europe", "stopping the tides"], answer: 0, explain: "It is preserving its islands and culture online in case the land is lost." },
      { q: "Pacific nations have mostly chosen to…", type: "mc", options: ["adapt at home AND speak out globally", "stay silent", "do nothing", "blame each other"], answer: 0, explain: "They restore reefs and build defenses while leading the global climate call." },
      { q: "Restoring mangroves and reefs helps because they…", type: "mc", options: ["break the waves and protect the shore", "raise the temperature", "cause flooding", "use up fresh water"], answer: 0, explain: "Natural barriers shield islands from storms and erosion." },
      { q: "The deeper point of this lesson is to see…", type: "mc", options: ["both the science and the fairness of one problem", "only the science", "only the politics", "that islands don't matter"], answer: 0, explain: "World awareness means holding the cause-and-effect and the justice together." },
    ],
  });

  lesson({
    id: "oc10", continent: "oceania", n: 10, minutes: 10, emoji: "🏉",
    title: "Modern Oceania: Sport, People & Culture Today",
    hook: "From the biggest Polynesian city on Earth to a rugby team feared worldwide, modern Oceania is small in population but mighty in culture.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "The Oceania of today is young, diverse, and surprisingly influential for a region with so few people. Once-isolated British colonies have become some of the world's most <b>multicultural</b> societies. After World War II, Australia and New Zealand opened their doors — first to migrants from across Europe, then increasingly to people from Asia and the Pacific Islands — and that mixing has reshaped the food, the music, the sport, and the streets of both nations into something new and lively." },
      { t: "p", html: "Nowhere shows this better than the <b>Pacific connection</b>. So many Islanders have moved to New Zealand for work and study that <b>Auckland</b> is now the <b>largest Polynesian city in the world</b> — home to more Pacific people than any island. These communities have brought their languages, churches, foods, and especially their <b>music and sport</b>, weaving Pacific culture deep into the identity of modern New Zealand and Australia alike." },
      { t: "p", html: "If there is one thing that unites the region, it might be a near-religious love of <b>sport</b>. New Zealand's <b>All Blacks</b> are among the most successful teams in the history of any sport, and their pre-game <b>haka</b> is recognized around the globe. Australians are passionate about cricket, their own homegrown game of <b>Australian Rules football</b>, rugby, and netball. Pacific Islanders, pound for pound, produce a remarkable number of the world's best rugby players. And out on the water, the region dominates <b>surfing</b> and <b>sailing</b> — little New Zealand has repeatedly won the America's Cup, sailing's greatest prize, against far larger nations." },
      { t: "scene", art: "star", file: "Sydney Opera House.JPG", credit: "Photo: Wikimedia Commons, CC BY-SA", caption: "The Sydney Opera House — a symbol of modern Australia." },
      { t: "p", html: "The region's culture reaches the world in other ways too. New Zealand's spectacular landscapes have made it a global <b>film capital</b> — the <i>Lord of the Rings</i> and <i>Hobbit</i> movies were filmed among its mountains, earning it the nickname “Hollywood of the South.” Indigenous culture is increasingly center stage, with Maori and Aboriginal musicians, actors, and artists celebrated nationally and abroad, and ancient instruments like the Aboriginal <b>didgeridoo</b> heard in modern songs worldwide." },
      { t: "p", html: "Economically, the region runs on a modern mix. Australia is a mining powerhouse, digging up iron, coal, and gold for the world, especially for Asia's booming factories. Both Australia and New Zealand export vast amounts of <b>food</b> — meat, dairy, wine, and fruit — and both draw millions of <b>tourists</b> to their reefs, mountains, and beaches. The result is some of the highest standards of living anywhere on Earth, though the region still works on real challenges: caring for the environment, closing gaps faced by Indigenous communities, and finding its place between its old ties to Britain and its growing links with Asia." },
      { t: "fact", html: "Australia and New Zealand carry on a cheerful, never-ending rivalry over who invented the meringue dessert called <b>pavlova</b> — and over which country a beloved actor or singer “really” belongs to. Neighborly bragging is practically a national sport of its own." },
      { t: "fact", html: "The <b>didgeridoo</b>, a long wooden wind instrument from northern Australia, is one of the world's oldest instruments — and playing it well requires “circular breathing,” a technique that lets a player blow out and breathe in at the same time." },
      { t: "p", html: "Walk through a city like Sydney, Melbourne, or Auckland today and you'll hear dozens of languages and smell food from every continent. Wave after wave of newcomers — Greeks and Italians after the war, then Vietnamese, Chinese, Indian, and Pacific families — have made these among the most <b>multicultural cities on Earth</b>, where a single street might offer dumplings, kebabs, sushi, and a flat white all in a row." },
      { t: "p", html: "Underneath the easygoing lifestyle sits a modern, trade-driven economy. Australia sells iron and coal to Asia's factories; both nations export food and welcome millions of tourists. More and more, the region looks <b>north to Asia</b> for its future, even as it keeps its old ties to Britain. Real challenges remain — protecting the environment and closing the gaps still faced by Indigenous communities — but few places on Earth enjoy a higher quality of life." },
      { t: "guide", html: "Here's the takeaway about Oceania today: a place doesn't need a huge population to have a huge influence. Through sport, film, music, and food, a handful of small nations have planted their culture all over the world. Impact isn't only about size — it's about what you share and how boldly you share it." },
      { t: "modern", html: "Modern Oceania shows how far-flung, multicultural island nations can shape global culture far beyond their size — while still honoring the ancient peoples who came first. It still matters because the region is a small, vivid model of the whole planet's future: many cultures living together, proud of where they came from, and figuring out, day by day, how to share one home." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Since World War II, Australia and New Zealand have become…", type: "mc", options: ["highly multicultural societies", "completely isolated", "part of Asia", "uninhabited"], answer: 0, explain: "Waves of migration reshaped their food, music, sport, and identity.", hint: "Think about many cultures mixing together." },
      { q: "Which city is the largest Polynesian city in the world?", type: "mc", options: ["Auckland", "London", "Tokyo", "Sydney"], answer: 0, explain: "More Pacific people live in Auckland than in any island." },
      { q: "New Zealand's famous rugby team is the…", type: "mc", options: ["All Blacks", "Red Sox", "Lakers", "Yankees"], answer: 0, explain: "The All Blacks are among the most successful teams in any sport." },
      { q: "Australian Rules football is…", type: "mc", options: ["a homegrown Australian game", "a Maori dance", "a type of food", "a sailing race"], answer: 0, explain: "Aussie Rules is one of Australia's most beloved sports." },
      { q: "Tiny New Zealand has repeatedly won sailing's greatest prize, the…", type: "mc", options: ["America's Cup", "World Cup", "Stanley Cup", "Ashes"], answer: 0, explain: "It has beaten far larger nations in the America's Cup." },
      { q: "Which film series was famously shot in New Zealand?", type: "mc", options: ["The Lord of the Rings", "Star Wars", "Harry Potter", "Frozen"], answer: 0, explain: "Its landscapes earned it the nickname “Hollywood of the South.”" },
      { q: "The didgeridoo is…", type: "mc", options: ["an ancient Aboriginal wind instrument", "a New Zealand sport", "a Pacific canoe", "a kind of fish"], answer: 0, explain: "Playing it well requires circular breathing." },
      { q: "Australia's economy includes a major role for…", type: "mc", options: ["mining and food exports", "oil only", "the Silk Road", "whaling only"], answer: 0, explain: "It exports iron, coal, gold, meat, dairy, wine, and more." },
      { q: "What friendly thing do Australia and New Zealand argue about?", type: "mc", options: ["who invented pavlova and who owns famous stars", "who has more volcanoes", "who is closer to Europe", "who has the bigger army"], answer: 0, explain: "Neighborly bragging over dessert and celebrities is half the fun." },
      { q: "The big lesson of modern Oceania is that…", type: "mc", options: ["a small population can still have a huge global influence", "only big countries matter", "culture can't travel", "islands are all the same"], answer: 0, explain: "Through sport, film, music, and food, small nations shaped the world." },
    ],
  });

